<L>Can clepe watte as wel as can &thorn;e pope</L>
<L N="644">But who so cou&thorn;e in o&thorn;er &thorn;ing him grope</L>
<L>Than hadde he spent al his philosophie</L>
<L>Ay questio quid Iuris wolde he crye</L>
<L>He was a gentil harlot and a kynde</L>
<L N="648">A bettre felaw schulde men not fynde</L>
<L>He wolde suffre for a quart of wyn<MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A good felawe to haue his concubyn</L>
<L>A twelf moneth and excuse him atte fulle /</L>
<L N="652">fful priuely eek a fynch cou&thorn;e he pulle /</L>
<L>And if he fond owher a good felawe</L>
<L>He wolde techen him to han non awe</L>
<L>In such caas of &thorn;e Erchedeknes curs</L>
<L N="656">But if mannes soule were in his purs</L>
<L>ffor in his purs he scholde punyssched be</L>
<L>Purs is &thorn;e Erchedeknes helle seide he</L>
<L>But wel I wot he lyhede right in dede</L>
<L N="660">Of cursyng ought eche gilty man him drede</L>
<L>ffor curs wil sle right as assoylyng sauith</L>
<L>And also war him of a Significauith</L>
<L>In daunger hadde he at his owne gyse</L>
<L N="664">The yonge gerles of &thorn;e diocise</L>
<L>And knew here counseil and what was al here rede</L>
<L>A garland hadde he sette vpon his heede</L>
<L>As gret as it were for an ale stake</L>
<L N="668">A bokeler hadde he made him of a cake /</L>
<L>With him &thorn;er rood a gentill pardoner</L>
<L>Of Rouncyuall his frend and his comper</L>
<L>That streight was comen fro &thorn;e court of Rome</L>
<L N="672">fful lowe he song come hider loue tome</L>
<L>This Somnour bar to him a stif burdoun
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>Was neuer trompe of half so gret a soun</L>
<L>This pardoner hadde her as yelow as wax</L>
<L N="676">But smothe it heng as doth a strik of flax.</L>
<L>By ounces heng his lokkes &thorn;at he hadde /</L>
<L>And &thorn;er with he his schuldres ouer spradde</L>
<L>But &thorn;inne it lay by culpons on and oon</L>
<L N="680">But hood for Iolite werede he noon</L>
<L>ffor it was trussed vp in his walet</L>
<L>Him &thorn;oughte he rood al of the newe get</L>
<L>Discheuele saf his cappe he rood al bare</L>
<L N="684">Swich glaryng yghen hadde he as an hare</L>
<L>A vernicle hadde he sewid on his cappe<MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His walet [lay] biforn him in his lappe /</L>
<L>Bret ful of pardon comen fro Rome al hoot</L>
<L N="688">A voys he hadde as smal as a goot</L>
<L>No berd ne hadde he ne neuer schulde haue</L>
<L>As smothe it was as it ware late schaue</L>
<L>I trowe he were a geldyng or a mare</L>
<L N="692">But of his craft fro Berwik in to ware</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;er such ano&thorn;er pardoner</L>
<L>ffor in his male he hadde a pilewber</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at he sayde was oure lady veyle</L>
<L N="696">He seide he hadde a gobet of &thorn;e seyle</L>
<L>That seint petir hadde whan &thorn;at he wente</L>
<L>Vpon the see til ihesu crist him hente</L>
<L>He hadde a Croys of laton ful of stones</L>
<L N="700">And in a glas he hadde pigges boones</L>
<L>But with &thorn;ese reliqes whan &thorn;at he fonde</L>
<L>A poure person dwellyng vpon londe /</L>
<L>Vpon a day he gat him more moneye</L>
<L N="704">Than &thorn;at &thorn;e person gat in mon&thorn;es tweye</L>
<L>And &thorn;us with feyned flatering and Iapes</L>
<L>He made &thorn;e person and &thorn;e poeple his apes</L>
<L>But trewely to tellen atte &thorn;e laste</L>
<L N="708">He was in chirche a noble ecclesiaste</L>
<L>Wel cou&thorn;e he rede a lessonn or a story
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>But al&thorn;er best he song an offertory</L>
<L>ffor wel he wiste whan &thorn;at song was songe</L>
<L N="712">He moste preche and wel affile his tonge</L>
<L>To wynne seluer as he [right] wel cowde</L>
<L>Ther fore he song so meriely and lowde /</L>
<L>Now haue I told &yogh;ow so&thorn;ly in a clause</L>
<L N="716">The estat . the array &thorn;e nombre and eeke &thorn;e cause</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at assembled was &thorn;is companie</L>
<L>In Suthwerk at &thorn;is gentil hostelrie /</L>
<L>That highte &thorn;e Tabbard faste by &thorn;e belle</L>
<L N="720">But now is tyme to yow for to telle /</L>
<L>How &thorn;at we beeren vs &thorn;at ilke night<MILESTONE N="11a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan we were in &thorn;at Osterie alight</L>
<L>And after wol I telle of oure viage</L>
<L N="724">And all the remenant of our pilgrimage</L>
<L>But ferst I pray &yogh;ow of your curtesie</L>
<L>The &yogh;e ne rette it nought my vilenye</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at I pleinly speke in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L N="728">To telle &yogh;ow here wordes and here cheere</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ough I speke here wordes propurly</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is &yogh;e knowen as wel as I</L>
<L>Who so schal telle a tale after a man</L>
<L N="732">He mot reherse as neyh as euer he can</L>
<L>Euerich a word if it be in his charge</L>
<L>Al speke he neuer so rudely and large</L>
<L>Or elles he moot telle his tale vntrewe</L>
<L N="736">Or feyne &thorn;inges or fynde wordes newe</L>
<L>He may nought spare al &thorn;ough he were his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>He moot als wel seie o word as ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>Crist spak himself ful brode in holy writte</L>
<L N="740">And wel &yogh;e wot no vilenye is itte</L>
<L>Ek Plato seith who so can him rede</L>
<L>The wordes mot be cosyn to &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>Also I prey&yogh;e &yogh;ow for&yogh;iue it me</L>
<L N="744">Al haue I not set folk in here degre</L>
<L>Heer in &thorn;is tale as &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholden stonde
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>My witt is schort &yogh;e may wel vnderstonde</L>
<L>Gret cheere maad oure ost vs euerychon</L>
<L N="748">And to &thorn;e souper sette he vs anon</L>
<L>He serued vs with vitailles atte beste</L>
<L>Strong was &thorn;e wyn and wel drynken vs leste</L>
<L>A semly man our hoste he was with alle</L>
<L N="752">ffor to ben a marchall in an halle</L>
<L>A large man he was with ey&yogh;en stepe</L>
<L>A fairer burgeys is &thorn;er non in Chepe</L>
<L>Bold of his speche and wys and wel y-taught</L>
<L N="756">And of manhode him lakkede right naught</L>
<L>Ek &thorn;er to he was right a merie man<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And after soper pleyen he bigan</L>
<L>And spak of mer&thorn;e amonges o&thorn;er &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="760">Whan &thorn;at he hadde maad our rikenynges</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;us Now lordynges trewely</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben to me welcome right hertely</L>
<L>ffor by my trouthe if &thorn;at I schal not lye</L>
<L N="764">I seyh not &thorn;is yer so mery a companye</L>
<L>At oones in &thorn;is herberw as is now</L>
<L>ffayn wold I don &yogh;ou merthe wist I how</L>
<L>And of a mer&thorn;e I am right now bi&thorn;ought</L>
<L N="768">To don you eese and it schal coste nought</L>
<L>ye gon to Caunturbury god yow speede</L>
<L>The blisful martir quyte &yogh;ou &yogh;our meede</L>
<L>And wel I woot as &yogh;e gon by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L N="772">ye schapen &yogh;ou to talen and to pleye</L>
<L>ffor trewely confort ne mer&thorn;e is non</L>
<L>To riden by &thorn;e wey domb as a ston</L>
<L>And &thorn;er for wol I make you disport</L>
<L N="776">As I seide erst and do you som confort</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ou like&thorn; all by on assent</L>
<L>ffor to stonden at my Iuggement</L>
<L>And for to werken as I schal &yogh;ou seie</L>
<L N="780">To morwe whan &yogh;e riden by &thorn;e weie /</L>
<L>Now by my fader soule &thorn;at is deed
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>But &yogh;e be merye I wil &yogh;eue &yogh;ow myn heed</L>
<L>Hold vp &yogh;our hond wi&thorn;oute more speche /</L>
<L N="784">Our counseil was not longe for to seche /</L>
<L>vs &thorn;ought it was not wor&thorn; to make it wys</L>
<L>And graunted him wi&thorn;oute more avys</L>
<L>And bad him seye his verdit as him leste</L>
<L N="788">Lordynges quod he / now herkne&thorn; for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>But take it nought I prey &yogh;ow in disdeigne</L>
<L>This is &thorn;e poynt to speke schort and pleigne</L>
<L>That ech of &yogh;ou to schorte with &yogh;our weye</L>
<L N="792">In &thorn;is viage schal telle tales tweie</L>
<L>To Caunturbury-ward I mene it so<MILESTONE N="12a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And homward he schal tellen o&thorn;er tuo</L>
<L>Of auentures &thorn;at whilom haue bifall</L>
<L N="796">And which of yow &thorn;at beri&thorn; him best of all</L>
<L>That is to sein that telle&thorn; in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>Tales of best sentence and most solas ./</L>
<L>Schal haue a souper at our al&thorn;er cost</L>
<L N="800">Her in &thorn;is place sittynge by &thorn;is post</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at we comen a&yogh;ein fro Canturbury</L>
<L>And for to make &yogh;ou &thorn;e more mury</L>
<L>I wil my seluen goodly with &yogh;ou ryde</L>
<L N="804">Right at myn owne cost and be &yogh;our gyde</L>
<L>And who so wol my Iuggement wi&thorn; seye</L>
<L>Schal paye al &thorn;at we spende by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>And if &yogh;e vouche saf &thorn;at it be so</L>
<L N="808">Tel me anon wi&thorn;outen wordes moo</L>
<L>And I wol erly schape me &thorn;er fore</L>
<L>This &thorn;ing was graunted and our o&thorn;es swore</L>
<L>With ful glad herte and prey&yogh;en him also</L>
<L N="812">That he wolde vouche saf for to do so</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wolde ben our gouernour</L>
<L>And of oure tales Iugge and reportour</L>
<L>And sette a souper at a certein pris</L>
<L N="816">And we wiln rewled ben at his deuys /</L>
<L>In heighe and lowe and &thorn;us by oon assent
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>We ben accorded to &thorn;e Iuggement</L>
<L>And &thorn;er vpon &thorn;e wyn was fet anon</L>
<L N="820">We dronken and to reste went echon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen eny lenger taryyng</L>
<L>A morwe whan &thorn;e day bigan to spryng</L>
<L>vp ros oure oost and was our al&thorn;er cok</L>
<L N="824">And gadered vs to gider all in a flok</L>
<L>And for&thorn; we riden a litel more &thorn;an paas</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e wateryng of seint Thomas</L>
<L>And &thorn;er our oost gan his hors areste</L>
<L N="828">And seide lordes herkne&thorn; if you leste /</L>
<L>&YOGH;e wot &yogh;our forward and I it &yogh;ou recorde<MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If euynsong and morwesong acorde</L>
<L>lat see now who schal telle &thorn;e firste tale</L>
<L N="832">As euer mote I drynke wyn of ale</L>
<L>Who so be rebel to my Iuggement /</L>
<L>Schal paie for all that by &thorn;e weie is spent</L>
<L>Now drawe&thorn; Cut or &thorn;at we fer&thorn;er twynne</L>
<L N="836">he which &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e schortest schal bigynne</L>
<L>&para; Sir knight quod he my maister and my lord</L>
<L>Now drawe&thorn; Cut for &thorn;at is myn acord</L>
<L>Come&thorn; nerre quod he my lady prioresse</L>
<L N="840">And &yogh;e sir clerk let be &yogh;our schamfastnesse</L>
<L>Ne studie&thorn; nought lay hond to euery man</L>
<L>Anon to drawe euery wight bygan</L>
<L>And schortly for to tellen as it was /</L>
<L N="844">Were it by auenture or sort or cas</L>
<L>The so&thorn; is &thorn;is the Cut fel to &thorn;e knight</L>
<L>Of which ful bli&thorn;e and glad was euery wight</L>
<L>And telle he moste his tale as it was resoun</L>
<L N="848">By forward and by composicioun</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd what nede&thorn; wordes mo</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is good man saugh &thorn;at it was so</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at wys was and obedient</L>
<L N="852">To keepe his forward by his free assent</L>
<L>He seide si&thorn;&thorn;e I schal begynne &thorn;e game
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>What welcome be &thorn;e Cutte a goddes name</L>
<L>Now lat vs ride and herkne&thorn; what I seye</L>
<L N="856">And with &thorn;at word we riden for&thorn; oure weye</L>
<L>And he bigan with right a merye cheere</L>
<L>His tale anon and seyde as &yogh;e may heere
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000054.tif" N="26">
<HEAD>Iam que domos patrias scitice post aspera gentis Prelia laurigero etc.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom was as olde stories tellen vs</L>
<L N="860">Ther was a Duk that highte Theseus /</L>
<L>Of Athenes he was / lord and gouernour</L>
<L>And in his tyme such a Conquerour</L>
<L>That grettere was non vnder &thorn;e sonne<MILESTONE N="13a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="864">fful many a riche Contre hadde he wonne</L>
<L>What with his wisdam and his chiuallerie</L>
<L>He conquered all &thorn;e regne of ffeminie</L>
<L>That whilom was I-cleped Scithia</L>
<L N="868">And weddede &thorn;e queen ypolita</L>
<L>And brought hir hom wi&thorn; him in his contre</L>
<L>With muche glorie and gret solempnite</L>
<L>And eek hir &yogh;onge suster Emelye</L>
<L N="872">And &thorn;us with victorie and with melodie<NOTE PLACE="marg">[line erased here, apparently the previous one repeated.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Late I &thorn;is noble duk to Athenes ride</L>
<L>And all his host in armes him bisyde</L>
<L>And certes if it nere to long to heere</L>
<L N="876">I wolde haue tolde fully &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>how wonnen was &thorn;e regne of ffeminie</L>
<L>By Theseus and by his Chiualrie</L>
<L>And of the grete bataille for &thorn;e noones</L>
<L N="880">Bitwixen athenes and Amazones</L>
<L>And how asseged was Ipolita</L>
<L>The faire hardy quene of Scithia</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e fest &thorn;at was at hir weddyng</L>
<L N="884">And of &thorn;e tempest at hir hom comyng</L>
<L>But al &thorn;at &thorn;ing I moot as now forbere /</L>
<L>I haue god wot a large feeld to ere</L>
<L>And weyke ben &thorn;e oxen in my plough</L>
<L N="888">The remnant of &thorn;e tale is long ynough</L>
<L>I wol not letten eek noon of &thorn;is route
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Lat euery felawe telle his tale aboute</L>
<L>And lat se now who schal &thorn;e souper wynne</L>
<L N="892">And &thorn;er I lafte I wil a&yogh;ein bigynne</L>
<L>This Duk of whom I make mencioun</L>
<L>Whan he was comen almost to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>In all his wele and his moste pryde</L>
<L N="896">He was war as he cast his eyhe asyde</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at &thorn;er kneled in &thorn;e heighe weye</L>
<L>A company of ladies tweye and tweye<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Eche after o&thorn;er cladde in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L N="900">But such a cry and such a woo &thorn;ei make</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is world is creature lyuynge</L>
<L>That herde such ano&thorn;er weymentynge</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is cry &thorn;ey nolde neuer stente</L>
<L N="904">Til &thorn;ei &thorn;e Reynes of his bridel hente</L>
<L>What folk ben &yogh;e &thorn;at at myn hom comynge</L>
<L>Pertourbe so my feste wi&thorn; cryinge</L>
<L>Quod Theseus haue &yogh;e so gret enuye</L>
<L N="908">Of myn honour that &thorn;us compleigne and crie</L>
<L>Or who ha&thorn; &yogh;ou mysboden or offended</L>
<L>And telle&thorn; me if it may ben amended</L>
<L>And whi &thorn;at &yogh;e ben clo&thorn;ed thus in blak</L>
<L N="912">The eldest lady of hem alle spak</L>
<L>Whan sche had swouned with a dedly cheere</L>
<L>That it was routhe for to seen and heere</L>
<L>&para; Sche seide lord to whom fortune ha&thorn; yiuen</L>
<L N="916">Victorie and as a conquerour to lyuen</L>
<L>Not greue&thorn; ous &yogh;oure gloire and your honour</L>
<L>But we beseke mercy and socour</L>
<L>Haue mercy on our woo and our distresse</L>
<L N="920">Som drope of pite &thorn;urgh &thorn;i gentilesse /</L>
<L>vpon vs wrecched wommen let &yogh;e fall</L>
<L>ffor certes lord &thorn;er is non of vs all</L>
<L>That sche nath ben a duchesse or a queene</L>
<L N="924">Now be we Caytifs as it is wel seene</L>
<L>Thanked be fortune and hir false whiel
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>That non estat ensureth for to ben wel</L>
<L>Now certes lord to abyde &yogh;oure presence /</L>
<L N="928">Here in &thorn;is temple of the goddesse Clemence</L>
<L>We haue be waytinge al &thorn;is fourte night</L>
<L>Helpe vs lord si&thorn; it is in &thorn;y might</L>
<L>&para; I wrecche which &thorn;at weepe and weile &thorn;us</L>
<L N="932">Was whilom wyf of king Cappaneus</L>
<L>That starf at Thebes cursed be &thorn;at day</L>
<L>And alle we &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is array<MILESTONE N="14a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And maken al &thorn;is lamentacioun</L>
<L N="936">We losten all our housbondes at &thorn;at toun</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at &thorn;assege &thorn;er aboute lay</L>
<L>And yet now &thorn;e olde Creon weiloway</L>
<L>That lord is now of Thebes &thorn;e Cite</L>
<L N="940">ffulfild of Ire and of Iniquite</L>
<L>He for despite and for his Tyrannie</L>
<L>To don &thorn;e deede bodies vilenye</L>
<L>Of all oure lordes whiche &thorn;at ben slawe</L>
<L N="944">Ha&thorn; all &thorn;e bodies on an heep y-drawe</L>
<L>And wol nought suffre hem by non assent</L>
<L>Neither to ben y-buried no&thorn;er y-brent</L>
<L>But make&thorn; houndes ete hem in despyt</L>
<L N="948">And with &thorn;at word wi&thorn;oute more respit</L>
<L>Thei fellen gruf and cryden pitously</L>
<L>Haue on vs wrecchede wommen som mercy</L>
<L>And lat our sorwe synken in &thorn;in herte</L>
<L N="952">This gentil duk doun from his courser sterte</L>
<L>With herte pitous whan he herde hem speke</L>
<L>Him &thorn;oughte &thorn;at his herte wolde breke</L>
<L>Whan he saugh hem so pite and so mate</L>
<L N="956">That whilom were of so gret astate</L>
<L>And in his armes he hem all vp hente</L>
<L>And hem conforte&thorn; in ful good entente</L>
<L>And swor his oth as he was trewe knight</L>
<L N="960">He wolde don so ferfor&thorn;ly his might</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e tyrant hem to wreke
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>That all &thorn;e poeple of grece scholde speke</L>
<L>How Creon was of Theseus y-serued</L>
<L N="964">As he &thorn;at hadde his de&thorn; ful wel deserued</L>
<L>And right anon wi&thorn;outen more abod</L>
<L>His baner he displaied and forth rood</L>
<L>To Thebes-ward and al his host biside</L>
