<L>His speche no&thorn;er his voys &thorn;ough men it herde</L>
<L N="1372">And in his gere for al &thorn;e world he ferde /</L>
<L>Not comly lyk to louers maladye</L>
<L>Of heres but ra&thorn;er lik manye</L>
<L>Engendred of humour malencolik</L>
<L N="1376">Biforn his celle fantastik</L>
<L>And schortly torned was al vp and doun</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e habite and disposicioun</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;is woful louere daun arcite</L>
<L N="1380">What scholde I alday of his woo endite</L>
<L>Whan he endured hadde a &yogh;eer or tuo</L>
<L>This cruel torment and &thorn;is peyne and woo</L>
<L>At Thebes in his contre as I seyde</L>
<L N="1384">Vpon a night in sleep as he him leyde</L>
<L>Him &thorn;oughte &thorn;at &thorn;e wengede god mercurie</L>
<L>Biforn him stood and bad him to be merie</L>
<L>His sleepy &yogh;erde in honde he bar vpright</L>
<L N="1388">An hatte he wered vppon his heeres bright
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>Arrayed was &thorn;is god as he took keepe</L>
<L>As he was whan &thorn;at argus took his sleepe</L>
<L>And seyde him &thorn;us to Athenes schalt &thorn;ou wende</L>
<L N="1392">Ther is &thorn;e schapen of &thorn;i wo an ende</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word arcite wook and sterte</L>
<L>Now trewely how sore &thorn;at me smerte</L>
<L>Quod he to Athenes right now wol I fare</L>
<L N="1396">Ne for &thorn;e drede of de&thorn; schal I nought spare</L>
<L>To see my lady &thorn;at I loue and serue /</L>
<L>In hire presence I ne recche nou&yogh;t to sterue /</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word he caughte a gret mirour</L>
<L N="1400">And saugh &thorn;at chaunged was al his colour</L>
<L>And saugh his visage al in ano&thorn;er kinde</L>
<L>And right anon it ran him in his mynde<MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Than si&thorn;en his face was so disfigured</L>
<L N="1404">Of maladie &thorn;e which he hadde endured</L>
<L>He mighte wel if &thorn;at he bar him lowe</L>
<L>Lyue in Athenes eueremore vnknowe /</L>
<L>And seen his lady wel neigh day by day</L>
<L N="1408">And right anon he changed his array</L>
<L>And cladde him as a poure laborer</L>
<L>And al allone saf oonly a squier</L>
<L>That knew his priuete and al &thorn;e caas</L>
<L N="1412">Which was desgised pouerly as he was</L>
<L>To Athenes is he gon &thorn;e nexte way</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e courte he wente vpon a day</L>
<L>And atte gate he profred his seruise</L>
<L N="1416">To drugge and drawe what so men wol deuise</L>
<L>And schortly of &thorn;is matier for to sein</L>
<L>He fille in office with a chamburlein /</L>
<L>The which &thorn;at was dwellyng with Emelye</L>
<L N="1420">ffor he was wys and sone cou&thorn;e aspye</L>
<L>Of euery seruant which &thorn;at serue&thorn; here</L>
<L>Wel cou&thorn;e he hewen woode and water bere</L>
<L>ffor he was yong and mighty for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="1424">And &thorn;erto he was strong and bigge of bones
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>To doon &thorn;at eny wight him can deuyse</L>
<L>A yeer or tuo he was in &thorn;is seruise</L>
<L>Page of &thorn;e Chambre of Emelye &thorn;e brighte</L>
<L N="1428">And Philostrat he seyde &thorn;at he highte</L>
<L>&para; But half so wel byloued aman as he</L>
<L>Ne was &thorn;er neuer in court of his degre</L>
<L>He was so gentil of condicioun</L>
<L N="1432">That &thorn;urgh out al the court was his renoun</L>
<L>Thei seide &thorn;at it were a charite</L>
<L>That Theseus wolde enhaunce his degre</L>
