<L>As whan a &thorn;ing is schape it schal be</L>
<L>That sone after &thorn;e mydnyght Palamon</L>
<L N="1468">By helpyng of a frende brak prison</L>
<L>And fle&thorn; &thorn;e cite faste as he may goo</L>
<L>ffor hadde yeue his gailler drunke soo</L>
<L>Of a clarre maad of a certeyn wyn</L>
<L N="1472">With nercotiks and opie of Thebes fyn</L>
<L>That al &thorn;at night &thorn;ough &thorn;at men wolde him schake</L>
<L>Tbe gailler sleep he mighte not awake<MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he fleeth as fast as euer he may</L>
<L N="1476">The night was schort and faste by &thorn;e day</L>
<L>That needes cost he most himseluen hyde</L>
<L>And til a groue faste &thorn;er bisyde</L>
<L>With dredful foot &thorn;an stalke&thorn; Palamon</L>
<L N="1480">ffor schortly &thorn;is was his opinion</L>
<L>That in &thorn;at groue he wolde him hide alday</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e night &thorn;an wolde he take his way</L>
<L>To Thebes-ward his frendes for to pray</L>
<L N="1484">On Theseus to helpe him to werray</L>
<L>And schortly ou&thorn;er he wolde leese his lif</L>
<L>Or wynnen Emely to his louely wif /</L>
<L>This is &thorn;effecte and his entente playn</L>
<L N="1488">&para; Now wol I torne vnto arcite agayn</L>
<L>That litel wiste how neih &thorn;at was his care</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at fortune hadde kaught him in his snare</L>
<L>The besy larke messanger of day</L>
<L N="1492">Salueth in hir song &thorn;e morwe gray</L>
<L>And fyry phebus rise&thorn; vp so bright</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e orient laugheth of &thorn;e light</L>
<L>And with his streemes drieth in &thorn;e greues</L>
<L N="1496">The seluir dropes hangyng in &thorn;e leeues
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="44"></L>
<L>And Arcita in &thorn;e court roial</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Theseus his squier principal</L>
<L>Is rysen and loke&thorn; on &thorn;e mery day</L>
<L N="1500">And for to doon his obseruance to may</L>
<L>Remembryng on &thorn;e poynt of his desir</L>
<L>He on his courser stertyng as &thorn;e fir</L>
<L>Is riden in to &thorn;e feeldes him to pleye</L>
<L N="1504">Out of &thorn;e court were it a myle or tweye</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e groue of which &thorn;at I &yogh;ou tolde</L>
<L>By auenture his weye he gan to holde /</L>
<L>To maken him a garland of &thorn;e greues</L>
<L N="1508">Were it of woodebynde or hawethorne leeues</L>
<L>And loude he song a&yogh;ein &thorn;e sonne scheene /</L>
<L>May with all &thorn;i floures whit and grene<MILESTONE N="22a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Welcome be &thorn;ou faire freisshe may</L>
<L N="1512">I hope &thorn;at I som grene gete may</L>
<L>And from his courser with a lusty herte</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e groue ful hastily he sterte</L>
<L>And in a path he rometh vp and doun</L>
<L N="1516">Ther as by auenture of &thorn;is Palamon</L>
<L>Was in a busshe &thorn;at no man might him see</L>
<L>fful sore aferd of his deth was he</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing ne knewe he &thorn;at it was arcite</L>
<L N="1520">God wot he wolde haue trowed it ful lite</L>
<L>But so&thorn; is seide go si&thorn;&thorn;en many &yogh;eeres</L>
<L>That feeld ha&thorn; yhen and &thorn;e woode ha&thorn; eeres</L>
<L>It is ful fair a man to bere him euene /</L>
<L N="1524">ffor alday meete&thorn; men at vnsett steuene</L>
<L>fful litel woot arcite of his felawe</L>
<L>That was so neigh to herken of his sawe</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e busshe he sitte&thorn; now ful stille</L>
