<L>Toward &thorn;e groue as &yogh;e schul after heere</L>
<L>The noblest of &thorn;e Greekes &thorn;at &thorn;er were</L>
<L N="2900">vpon here schuldres carieden &thorn;e beere</L>
<L>With slake paas and eighen reede and wete</L>
<L>&THORN;urghout &thorn;e Cite by &thorn;e maistre streete /</L>
<L>That sprad was al with blak and wonder highe</L>
<L N="2904">Right of &thorn;e same is &thorn;e same is &thorn;e street y-wrye</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e right hond went olde Egeus</L>
<L>And on &thorn;at other syde duk Theseus</L>
<L>With vessels in here hand of gold ful fyne</L>
<L N="2908">As ful of hony melk and blood and wyne</L>
<L>Ek Palaman with ful gret companye</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at com woful Emelye</L>
<L>With fire in honde as was &thorn;at tyme &thorn;e gyse</L>
<L N="2912">To do &thorn;office of funeral seruise</L>
<L>Heigh labour and ful gret apparaillyng</L>
<L>Was atte seruise and &thorn;e fir makyng<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That wi&thorn; his greene top &thorn;e heuene raughte</L>
<L N="2916">And twenty fadme of brede &thorn;e armes straughte /</L>
<L>This is to sein &thorn;e bowes were so brode</L>
<L>Of stree first &thorn;er was leyd many a loode</L>
<L>But how &thorn;e fir was maked vp on heighte</L>
<L N="2920">Ne eek &thorn;e names how &thorn;e trees highte</L>
<L>As Ok. fir. birch. asp. Alder. holm. popeler</L>
<L>Willow. Elm. plane. Assh. box. chesteyn lynde laurer.</L>
<L>Mapel. &thorn;orn. beech. hasill. ew. whipiltre</L>
<L N="2924">how &thorn;ey were felde schal not be told for me</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e goddes ronnen vp and doun</L>
<L>Disherited of here habitacioun</L>
<L>In which &thorn;ei woneden in reste and pees</L>
<L N="2928">Nymphes ffawnes and amadries /</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e beestes and &thorn;e briddes alle</L>
<L>ffledden for feered whan &thorn;e woode was falle /
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e ground agast was of &thorn;e light</L>
<L N="2932">That was not wont to see &thorn;e sonne bright</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e fyr was couched first with stree /</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne with drye stockes clouen a &thorn;re</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne with greene woode and spicerie</L>
<L N="2936">And &thorn;anne with cloth of gold and wi&thorn; Perrye</L>
<L>And garlandes hangyng with ful many a flour</L>
<L>The mirre &thorn;encens with al so sweete odour</L>
<L>Ne how arcite lay among al &thorn;is</L>
<L N="2940">Ne what richesse aboute his body is</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;at Emelye as was &thorn;e gyse</L>
<L>Putte in &thorn;e fyre of funeral seruise /</L>
<L>Ne how sche swounede whan maad was &thorn;e fire</L>
<L N="2944">Ne what sche spak ne what was hire desire</L>
<L>Ne what Iuwels men in &thorn;e fyre cast</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e fyr was greet and brende fast</L>
<L>Ne how som cast hir scheeld and som hire spere</L>
<L N="2948">And of here vestimentz whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ey were</L>
<L>And coppes full of melk and wyn and blood</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e fyr &thorn;at brente as it were wood<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;e Grekes with an huge route</L>
<L N="2952">Thries ryden al &thorn;e fir aboute</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e left hond with a bowe schotynge</L>
<L>And &thorn;ries with here speres claterynge</L>
<L>And &thorn;ries how &thorn;e ladyes gon to crye</L>
<L N="2956">Ne how &thorn;at lad was homward Emelye</L>
<L>Ne how arcite is brent to aisshes colde</L>
<L>Ne how &thorn;at liche-wake was y-holde</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ilke nyght ne how &thorn;e greekes play</L>
<L N="2960">The wake-pleyes ne kepe I nought to say</L>
<L>Who wrastele&thorn; best naked with oyle anoynt</L>
<L>Ne who &thorn;at bar him best in no disioynt</L>
<L>I wol not tellen alle how &thorn;ey goon</L>
<L N="2964">hom til athenes whan &thorn;e play was don</L>
<L>But schortly to &thorn;e poynt &thorn;an wol I wende</L>
<L>And maken of my longe tale an ende
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>&para; By proces and of lengthe of certeyn &yogh;eeres</L>
<L N="2968">Al stynt is &thorn;e mournyng and &thorn;e teeres</L>
<L>Of grekes by on general assent</L>
<L>Than semede &thorn;er was a parlement</L>
<L>At atthenes vpon a certein point and caas</L>
<L N="2972">Among &thorn;e whiche poyntes y-spoken was</L>
<L>To haue with certain contrees alliance</L>
<L>And haue fully of Thebane obeissance</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;is noble Theseus anon</L>
<L N="2976">leet seende after gentil Palamon</L>
<L>vnwist of him what was &thorn;e cause and why</L>
<L>But in his blake clo&thorn;es sorwfully</L>
<L>he com at his comandement in hye</L>
<L N="2980">Tho sente Theseus for Emelye</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ey were sette and huyst was in &thorn;e place /</L>
<L>An Theseus abyden ha&thorn; a space</L>
<L>Or eny word com fro his wise breste</L>
<L N="2984">his ey&yogh;en sette he &thorn;er as was his leste /</L>
<L>And with a sad visage he siked stille /</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at right &thorn;us he seyde his wille<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The ferste maner of &thorn;e cause aboue</L>
<L N="2988">Whan he ferst maade &thorn;e faire cheine of loue</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;effect and heigh was his entente</L>
<L>Wel wist he why and what &thorn;er of he mente</L>
<L>ffor with &thorn;at faire cheyne of loue he bonde</L>
<L N="2992">The fyr. &thorn;e aier. the water and &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>In certeyn boundes &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not flee /</L>
<L>That same prince and &thorn;at same mouer quod he</L>
<L>ha&thorn; stablissed in &thorn;is wrecchede world a-doun</L>
<L N="2996">Certeine daies and dominacioun</L>
<L>To all &thorn;at be&thorn; engendred in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e whiche day &thorn;ay may not pace</L>
<L>Alle mowe &thorn;ey yet &thorn;o dayes abregge</L>
<L N="3000">Ther neede&thorn; nought non auctorite to legge</L>
<L>ffor it is proeued by experience</L>
<L>But &thorn;at me list to declaren my sentence /
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Than may men wel by &thorn;is ordre discerne</L>
<L N="3004">That &thorn;ilke mouere stable is and eterne</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe but it be a foole</L>
<L>That euery partie darreyned from his hoole</L>
<L>ffor nature ha&thorn; nat taken his bygynnyng</L>
<L N="3008">Of no partye nor of cantel of a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But of a &thorn;ing &thorn;at parfyt is and stable</L>
<L>Descendyng so til it be corumpable</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore for his wise purueance</L>
<L N="3012">he ha&thorn; so wel byset his ordinance</L>
<L>That specie of &thorn;inges and progressions</L>
<L>Schullen endure by successions</L>
<L>And nought eterne wi&thorn;outen any lye</L>
<L N="3016">This maystow vnderstonden and seen at yhe</L>
<L>Loo &thorn;e Ok &thorn;at ha&thorn; so long a norshing</L>
<L>ffro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at it first bygynne&thorn; to spring</L>
<L>And hath so long a lijf as &yogh;e may see</L>
<L N="3020">Yet atte laste wasted is &thorn;e tree /</L>
<L>Considere&thorn; eek how &thorn;at &thorn;e harde ston</L>
<L>vnder oure foot on which we trede and goon<MILESTONE N="43a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yet waste&thorn; it as it li&thorn; by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L N="3024">The brode ryuer som tyme wexe&thorn; dreye</L>
<L>The grete townes see we wane and wende</L>
<L>&THORN;an &yogh;e see &thorn;at all &thorn;is &thorn;ing ha&thorn; ende</L>
<L>Of man and woman se we wel also</L>
<L N="3028">That needeth in oon of &thorn;e termes tuo</L>
<L>That is to sein in &yogh;ou&thorn;e or elles age</L>
<L>He moot be deed &thorn;e king as schal &thorn;e page</L>
<L>Sum in his bedd. som in &thorn;e deepe see</L>
<L N="3032">Som in the large feeld as &yogh;e may see /</L>
<L>Ther helpe&thorn; nought al go&thorn; &thorn;at ilke weye</L>
<L>Than may I sein that al &thorn;is &thorn;ing moot deye</L>
<L>What maketh &thorn;is but Iuppiter &thorn;e king</L>
<L N="3036">That is Prince and cause of alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Conuertyng alle vnto his propre wille</L>
<L>ffrom which it is darreyned so&thorn; to tille
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>And heer agayns no creature on lyue</L>
<L N="3040">Of no degree auaille&thorn; for to stryue</L>
<L>Thanne is it wisdom as it &thorn;enke&thorn; me</L>
<L>To make vertue of necessite /</L>
<L>And take it wel &thorn;at we may not eschewe</L>
<L N="3044">And nameliche &thorn;at to vs alle is dewe</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">[No gap: line left out.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And rebell is to him &thorn;at all may gye</L>
<L>And certeinly a man ha&thorn; most honour</L>
<L N="3048">To deyen in his excellence and flour</L>
<L>Whan he is siker of his goode name</L>
<L>Than ha&thorn; he doon his freendes ne him no schame</L>
<L>And gladder oughte his frendes ben of his de&thorn;</L>
<L N="3052">Whan wi&thorn; honour y-yolden is vp &thorn;e bre&thorn;</L>
<L>Than whan his name apalled is for age</L>
<L>ffor al forgeten is his vessellage</L>
<L>Than is the beste as for a wor&thorn;y fame</L>
<L N="3056">To deyen whan he is best of name</L>
<L>The contrarie of alle &thorn;is is wilfulnesse</L>
<L>Why grucchen we why haue we heuynesse</L>
<L>That goode Arcite of Chiuallerie &thorn;e flour<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3060">Departed is wi&thorn; duete and with honour</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is foule prison of &thorn;is lyf</L>
<L>Why grucche&thorn; heere his cosyn and his wyf</L>
<L>Of his welfare &thorn;at loue&thorn; him so wel</L>
<L N="3064">Kan he hem &thorn;ank nay god woot neuer a deel</L>
<L>That bo&thorn;en his soule and eek him offende /</L>
<L>And yet &thorn;ei mowe her lustes nought amende</L>
<L>What may conclude of &thorn;is longe serie</L>
<L N="3068">But after wo I rede vs to be merye</L>
<L>And &thorn;anken Iupiter of all his grace</L>
<L>And er we departen from &thorn;is place</L>
<L>I rede we make of oure sorwes tuo</L>
<L N="3072">O parfyt ioye lastyng euer mo</L>
<L>And loke&thorn; now where most sorwe is Inne</L>
<L>Ther wol I ferst amenden and bygynne
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>Suster quod he &thorn;is is my ful assent</L>
<L N="3076">Wi&thorn; all &thorn;auys heere of my parlement /</L>
<L>That gentil Palamon &yogh;oure oughne knight</L>
<L>That serueth &yogh;ou with wille and herte and might /</L>
<L>And euer ha&thorn; don si&thorn;en ye ferst him knewe</L>
<L N="3080">That &yogh;e schull of &yogh;our grace vpon him rewe</L>
<L>And taken him for housbond and for lord</L>
<L>Lene me your hond for &thorn;is is oure acord</L>
<L>Lat see now of your wommanly pite</L>
<L N="3084">he is a kinges bro&thorn;er sone parde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough he were a pore Bachiller</L>
<L>Syn he ha&thorn; serued you so many a yeer</L>
<L>And had for &yogh;ou so gret aduersite /</L>
<L N="3088">It moste ben considered leeue&thorn; me</L>
<L>ffor gentil mercy oughte to passen right</L>
<L>Than seide he &thorn;us to Palamon &thorn;e knight</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;er neede&thorn; litel sermonyng</L>
<L N="3092">To make you assented to &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Come nere and take &yogh;oure lady by &thorn;e hond</L>
<L>Bitwixen hem was maad anon &thorn;e bond</L>
<L>That highte matrimoigne or mariage<MILESTONE N="44a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3096">By all &thorn;e counsail and &thorn;e baronage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us wi&thorn; alle blisse and melodye</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; Palamon y-wedded Emelye</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at al &thorn;is world ha&thorn; wrought</L>
<L N="3100">Sende him his loue &thorn;at ha&thorn; it deere bought</L>
<L>ffor now is Palamon in alle wele</L>
<L>Lyuyng in blisse in richesse and in hele</L>
<L>And Emely him loueth so tendrely</L>
<L N="3104">And he hir serue&thorn; so gentilly</L>
<L>That was &thorn;er no word hem betweene /</L>
<L>Of Ialousie or ony o&thorn;er teene</L>
<L>Thus endeth Palamon and Emelye /</L>
<L N="3108">And god saue all &thorn;is faire companye
</L>
</LG>

