<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000117.tif" N="89">
<HEAD>&para; The Millewardes tale/<NOTE PLACE="head">[no gap in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e knight had &thorn;us his tale y-told</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e companye nas &thorn;er &yogh;ong ne old</L>
<L>That he ne seyde it / was a noble storye</L>
<L N="3112">And wor&thorn;i for to drawen in memorie</L>
<L>And nameliche &thorn;e gentils euerych oon</L>
<L>Oure Oost lough and swor so mot I gon</L>
<L>This go&thorn; aright vnbokeled is &thorn;e male/</L>
<L N="3116">lat se now who schal telle ano&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>ffor trewely &thorn;e game is wel bygonne</L>
<L>Now telle&thorn; &yogh;e sire monk if &yogh;e kunne</L>
<L>Somwhat to quyte with &thorn;e knightes tale</L>
<L N="3120">The meller &thorn;at for-drunken was al pale</L>
<L>So &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e vpon his hors he sat</L>
<L>he nolde aualen ney&thorn;er hood ne hat</L>
<L>Ne abide noman for his curtesie/</L>
<L N="3124">But in Pilates vois he gan to crye</L>
<L>And swor by armes and by blood and bones</L>
<L>I can a noble tale for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; which I wol now quite &thorn;e knightes tale</L>
<L N="3128">Oure oost saugh &thorn;at he was drunken of ale</L>
<L>And seyde abyde Robyn leeue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Som bettre man schal telle vs ferst ano&thorn;er<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Abyd and lat vs werken &thorn;riftily</L>
<L N="3132">By goddes soule quod he &thorn;at wol nat I</L>
<L>ffor I wol speken or elles go my weye</L>
<L>Oure oost answerde /telle on a deuelleweye</L>
<L>Thou art a fool &thorn;i witte is ouercome</L>
<L N="3136">Now herkne&thorn; quo&thorn; &thorn;e meller alle and some</L>
<L>But first I make a protestacioun</L>
<L>That I am dronke I knowe it by my soun</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore if I speke or mys say</L>
<L N="3140">Wite &yogh;e it &thorn;e ale of Suthwerk I &yogh;ou pray
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>ffor I wol telle a legende and a lyf</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of a Carpenter and of his wijf /</L>
<L>how &thorn;at a clerk ha&thorn; sett &thorn;e wrightes cappe</L>
<L N="3144">The Reeue answerde and seyde stynt &thorn;y clappe</L>
<L>lat be &thorn;i lewed dronken harlotrie</L>
<L>It is a synne and eeke gret folye</L>
<L>To apeiren eny man or diffame</L>
<L N="3148">And eek to bringe wyfes in such fame</L>
<L>Thou maist ynough of o&thorn;er &thorn;inges sain</L>
<L>This dronken meller spak ful soone agayn</L>
<L>And seyde leeue bro&thorn;er Osewold /</L>
<L N="3152">Who has no wyf he is no Cokewold</L>
<L>But I seye nought &thorn;erfore &thorn;at &thorn;ou art oon</L>
<L>Ther been ful goode wyfes many on</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="3156">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Why art &thorn;ou angry wi&thorn; my tale now</L>
<L>I haue a wif parde as wel as &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Yet nolde I not for &thorn;e Oxen in my plough</L>
<L N="3160">Take vpon me more &thorn;an ynough</L>
<L>As demen on my self &thorn;at I were oon</L>
<L>I wil bileeue &thorn;at I am noon</L>
<L>And housbonde schal not ben Inquysitif</L>
<L N="3164">Of goddes priuetees ne of his wijf</L>
<L>So he may fynde goddes foyson &thorn;ere/</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e remenant neede&thorn; nought to enquere</L>
<L>What scholde I more sayn but &thorn;is Mellere</L>
<L>he nolde his wordes for no man forbere<MILESTONE N="45a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But tolde his cherles tale in his manere</L>
<L>Me a&thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at I schal reherce hem heere</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore euery gentil wight I preye</L>
<L N="3172">Deme&thorn; nought for goddes loue &thorn;at I seye</L>
<L>Of yuel entent but for &thorn;at I moot reherse</L>
<L>Here tales alle be &thorn;ei bettre or worse</L>
<L>Or elles falsen som of my matiere</L>
<L N="3176">And &thorn;er-fore who so list it nought to heere
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>Torne ouer &thorn;e leef and chees ano&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e schulle fynde ynowe grete and smale</L>
<L>Of storial &thorn;ing &thorn;at touche&thorn; gentilesse</L>
<L N="3180">And eek moralite and holynesse</L>
<L>Blame&thorn; not me if &thorn;at &yogh;e cheese amys</L>
<L>The meller is a cherl &yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;is</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e Reeue eek and o&thorn;er mo</L>
<L N="3184">And harlotrie &thorn;ey tolden bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>Auise&thorn; &yogh;ou and putte&thorn; me out of blame</L>
<L>And eek men schal not make ernest of game<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="92">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was dwellyng at Oxenfoord</L>
<L N="3188">A Riche gnoffe &thorn;at gestes heeld to boorde</L>
<L>And of his crafte he was a Carpunter</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;er was dwellyng a pouer scoler</L>
<L>hadde lerned art but all his fantasye</L>
<L N="3192">Was torned for to lerne astrologie/</L>
<L>And cou&thorn;e a certein of conclusions</L>
<L>To demen by interrogacions</L>
<L>If &thorn;at men axed him in certeyn houres</L>
<L N="3196">Whan men schuld haue drought or elles schoures</L>
<L>Or if men axed him what schal bifalle</L>
<L>Of euery &thorn;ing I may nought reknen alle</L>
<L>This clerk was cleped heende Nicholas</L>
<L N="3200">Of derne loue he cou&thorn;e and of Solas</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to he was sleigh and ful priue</L>
<L>And like a mayde meeke for to see</L>
<L>A chambre hadde he in &thorn;at hostellerie</L>
<L>Allone wi&thorn;outen eny companye<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>fful fetisly dight wi&thorn; herbes soote</L>
<L>And he himself as sweete as is &thorn;e roote</L>
<L>Of licoris or any Settewale</L>
<L N="3208">his almagist and bokes grete and smale</L>
<L>his astrelabre longyng for his art</L>
<L>his augrym stones' layen faire a part</L>
<L>On schelfes couched at his beddes heede</L>
