<L>At &thorn;ilke tyme &thorn;an all his we&thorn;eres blake
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>That sche hadde a schip hir self allon</L>
<L N="3544">And &thorn;er-fore wost &thorn;ou what is best to doon</L>
<L>This axe&thorn; haste and of an hastyf &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Men may nought preche or make tarying</L>
<L>Anon go gete vs faste in to &thorn;is Inne</L>
<L N="3548">A knedyng trough or elles a kemelynne</L>
<L>ffor ech of vs but look &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben large</L>
<L>In which men mowe swymme as in a barge</L>
<L>And han &thorn;er vitailles suffisaunt</L>
<L N="3552">But for a day fy on &thorn;e remenaunt</L>
<L>The water schal aslake and gon a way</L>
<L>Aboute prime vpon &thorn;e nexte day</L>
<L>But Robyn may not wite of &thorn;is &thorn;i knaue/</L>
<L N="3556">Ne eek &thorn;y mayde gylle I may nought saue/</L>
<L>Axe nought why for &thorn;ough &thorn;ou axe me</L>
<L>I wol nought tellen goddes priuite</L>
<L>Suffice&thorn; &thorn;e but if &thorn;i wittes madde</L>
<L N="3560">To haue as gret a grace as noe hadde</L>
<L>Thi wif schal I wel sauen out of doute</L>
<L>Go now &thorn;i wey and speed &thorn;e heer aboute/</L>
<L>But when &thorn;ou hast for hire and &thorn;e and me</L>
<L>Y-geten vs &thorn;ese knedyng tubbes &thorn;re<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Than schalt &thorn;ou hang hem in &thorn;e rof ful hye</L>
<L>That noman of oure purueance espye</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ou &thorn;us hast don as I haue seyd</L>
<L N="3568">And hast oure vitailes faire in hem y-leyde</L>
<L>And eek an ax to smyte &thorn;e corde a tuo</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e water come&thorn; &thorn;at we may go</L>
<L>And broke an hole an heigh vpon &thorn;e gable</L>
<L N="3572">vnto &thorn;e gardeynward ouer &thorn;e stable</L>
<L>That we may freely passen for&thorn; oure wey</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e grete schour is gon a wey</L>
<L>Thanne schalt &thorn;ou swymme as mery I vndertake</L>
<L N="3576">As do&thorn; &thorn;e white doke after his drake</L>
<L>Than wol I clepe how alison how Ioon</L>
<L>Be merie for &thorn;e flood wol passe anon
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wolt sein haill maister Nicholay</L>
<L N="3580">Goode morwen I see &thorn;e wel for it is day</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne schal we be lordes all oure lif</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e world as Noe and his wijf</L>
<L>But &thorn;at of oo &thorn;ing I warne &thorn;e ful right</L>
<L N="3584">Be wel auysed on &thorn;at ilke night</L>
<L>That we ben entred in to &thorn;e schippes boord</L>
<L>That noon of vs ne speke nought a word</L>
<L>Ne clepe ne crye but been in his preyere</L>
<L N="3588">ffor it is goddes oughne heeste deere</L>
<L>Thy wijf and &thorn;ou mot hange fer atwynne</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at betwixe &yogh;ou schal be no synne</L>
<L>No more in lokyng &thorn;an &thorn;er schal in dede</L>
<L N="3592">This ordinance is seid go god &thorn;e speede</L>
<L>To morwe at night whan men ben all on sleepe</L>
<L>In to our knedyn tubbes wil we creepe</L>
<L>And sitten &thorn;er abidyng goddes grace</L>
<L N="3596">Go now &thorn;y wey I haue no lenger space</L>
<L>To make of &thorn;is no lenger sermonyng</L>
<L>Men sein &thorn;us sende &thorn;e wise and sey no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art so wys it neede&thorn; &thorn;e nought to teche</L>
<L>Go saue oure lijf and &thorn;at I &thorn;e beseche<MILESTONE N="51a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; This seely Carpunter go&thorn; for&thorn; his wey</L>
<L>fful ofte he seyde allas and weylawey</L>
<L>And to his wijf he tolde his priuitee</L>
<L N="3604">And sche was warr and knew it bet &thorn;an he</L>
<L>What al &thorn;is queynte cast was for to seye</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles sche ferde as sche wolde deye</L>
<L>And seyde allas go for&thorn; &thorn;i weie anon</L>
<L N="3608">help vs to scape or we ben deede echon</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i trewe verray wedded wijf</L>
<L>Go deere spouse and help to saue oure lijf</L>
<L>&para; lo which a gret &thorn;ing is affection</L>
<L N="3612">Men may dye of ymaginacion</L>
<L>So deepe may impressions be take</L>
<L>This seely Carponter bygynne&thorn; quake
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>him &thorn;enketh verraily &thorn;at he may se</L>
<L N="3616">Noe flood come walkyng as &thorn;e see</L>
<L>To drenchen alison his hony deere</L>
<L>he weepe&thorn; waille&thorn; maketh sory cheere/</L>
<L>he syke&thorn; wi&thorn; ful many a sory swogh</L>
<L N="3620">And go&thorn; and gete&thorn; him a knedyng trough</L>
<L>And after a tubbe and a kemelyn</L>
<L>And priuily he sent hem to his In</L>
<L>And hyng hem in &thorn;e roof in priuite</L>
<L N="3624">his oughne hond he made eek leddres &thorn;re</L>
<L>To clymben by &thorn;e ronges and &thorn;e stalkes</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e tubbes hangyng in &thorn;e balkes</L>
<L>And hem vitailled bo&thorn;e trough and tubbe</L>
<L N="3628">Wi&thorn; bred and cheese and good ale in a Iubbe/</L>
<L>Suffisyng right ynough as for a day</L>
<L>But ar &thorn;at he hadde maad al &thorn;is array</L>
<L>he sent his knaue and eek his wenche also</L>
<L N="3632">vpon his neede to london for to go</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e monday whan it drough to night</L>
<L>he schette his dore wi&thorn;oute candel light</L>
<L>And dressed all &thorn;ing as it scholde be/</L>
<L>And schortly clomben vp all &thorn;re/<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thei setten stille wel a forlong way</L>
<L>Now pater noster clum seide Nicholay</L>
<L>And Clum quod Iohn and Clum seide alison</L>
<L N="3640">This Carpunter seide his deuocion</L>
<L>And stille he sitte and bidde&thorn; his prayere</L>
<L>Awaityng on the rayn if he it heere</L>
<L>The deth sleepe for wery bysynesse</L>
<L N="3644">ffil on &thorn;is Carpunter right as I gesse</L>
<L>Aboute corfew tyme or litel more</L>
<L>ffor trauaille of his gost he grone&thorn; sore</L>
<L>And eft he route&thorn; for his heed myslay</L>
<L N="3648">Doun of &thorn;e laddre stalke&thorn; Nicholay</L>
<L>And alison ful softe a doun sche spedde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen wordes mo &thorn;ey gon to bedde
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>Ther as &thorn;e carpunter is wont to lye</L>
<L N="3652">Ther was &thorn;e reuel and &thorn;e melodye/</L>
<L>And &thorn;us lith alison and Nicholas</L>
<L>In busynesse of mer&thorn;e and of solas</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e belle of laudes gan to rynge</L>
<L N="3656">And the freres in &thorn;e chauncell gonne synge/</L>
<L>This parische clerk &thorn;is amorous absolon</L>
<L>That is for loue alwey so wo bigon</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e monday was at Osenay</L>
<L N="3660">With compaignie him to desport and play</L>
<L>And axed vpon caas a cloisterer</L>
<L>fful priuily after Iohn &thorn;e Carpunter</L>
<L>And he drough him a part out of &thorn;e chirche</L>
<L N="3664">And seyde I not I saugh him heere nought werche</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;e Saturday I trowe &thorn;at he be went</L>
<L>ffor tymber &thorn;ere oure abbot ha&thorn; him sent</L>
<L>ffor he is wont for tymber for to go</L>
<L N="3668">And dwelle atte graunge a day or tuo</L>
<L>Or elles he is at his hous certeyn</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at he be I can nought so&thorn;ly sein</L>
<L>This absolon ful ioly was and light</L>
<L>And &thorn;oughte now is tyme to wake al nyght<MILESTONE N="52a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor sikerly I saugh him nought styryng</L>
<L>Aboute his dore syn day bigan to spring</L>
<L>So mote I &thorn;riue I schal at cokkes crowe</L>
<L N="3676">fful priuily knokken as his wyndowe</L>
<L>That stant ful lowe vpon his boures walle</L>
<L>To alison now wol I tellen alle</L>
<L>My loue longyng for &yogh;it I schal not misse</L>
<L N="3680">That atte laste wey I schal hir kisse</L>
<L>Som maner comfort schal I haue par fay</L>
<L>My mou&thorn; ha&thorn; icched al &thorn;is longe day</L>
<L>That is a signe of kissyng atte leste</L>
<L N="3684">Al night me mette eek I was at a feeste</L>
<L>Therfore I wol go sleepe an our or tweye</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e night &thorn;an wol I wol I wake and pleye
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e ferste cok ha&thorn; crowe anon</L>
<L N="3688">vp rist &thorn;is Ioly louer absolon</L>
<L>And him arraye&thorn; gay and poynt/ deuyse</L>
<L>But ferst he chewe&thorn; grayn and likorise</L>
<L>To smellen swoote or he hadde kempt his here</L>
<L N="3692">vnder his tonge a trewe loue he beere/</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er-by wende he to be gracious</L>
<L>he rowmeth to &thorn;e carpenteres hous</L>
<L>And stille he stant vnder &thorn;e schot wyndowe</L>
<L N="3696">vnto his brest it raught it was so lowe/</L>
<L>And softe he coughed wi&thorn; a semy soun</L>
<L>What do &yogh;e hony combe swete alisoun</L>
<L>My faire brid my sweete synamome/</L>
<L N="3700">Awaketh lemman myn and speke&thorn; to me</L>
<L>We[l] litel &thorn;enken &yogh;e vpon my woo</L>
<L>That for &yogh;oure loue I swete as I go</L>
<L>No wonder is &thorn;ough &thorn;at I swelte and swete</L>
<L N="3704">I morne as do&thorn; &thorn;e lambe after &thorn;e teete</L>
<L>I-wys lemman I haue such loue longyng</L>
<L>That lik a turtel trewe is my moornyng</L>
<L>I may not ete namore &thorn;an a mayde/</L>
<L>Go fro &thorn;e wyndow Iakke fool sche sayde<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As help me god it wil not be com pame/</L>
<L>I loue ano&thorn;er and elles I were to blame/</L>
<L>Wel bette &thorn;an &thorn;e by Ihesu absolon</L>
<L N="3712">Go for&thorn; &thorn;i wey or I wil caste a stoon</L>
<L>And lete me slepe a twenty deuel way</L>
<L>Allas quod absolon and weyloway</L>
<L>That trewe loue was euer so yuel besette/</L>
<L N="3716">Than kisse me syn it may be no bette/</L>
<L>ffor ihesus loue and for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L>Wolt &thorn;ou &thorn;an go &thorn;i way &thorn;er-with quod sche</L>
<L>Ye certes lemman quod &thorn;is absolon</L>
<L N="3720">Than make &thorn;e redy quod sche I come anon</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>This absolon doun sette him on his knees
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="107"></L>
<L N="3724">And saide I am a lord at alle degrees</L>
<L>ffor after &thorn;is I hope &thorn;er come&thorn; more</L>
<L>lemman &thorn;i grace and sweete brid &thorn;in ore</L>
<L>The wyndow sche vndo&thorn; and &thorn;at in hast/</L>
<L N="3728">haue do quod sche com of and speed &thorn;e faste</L>
<L>lest &thorn;at our neighebore &thorn;e espie</L>
<L>This absolon gan wipe his mou&thorn; ful drye</L>
<L>Derk was &thorn;e night as piche or as &thorn;e cole</L>
<L N="3732">And at the wyndow out sche putte hire hole</L>
<L>And absolon him fil no bet ne wers</L>
<L>But wi&thorn; his mou&thorn; he kiste hire naked ers/</L>
<L>fful sauorly er he were war of &thorn;is/</L>
<L N="3736">A bak he stert and &thorn;ought it was amys/</L>
<L>ffor wel he wiste a womman ha&thorn; no berd</L>
<L>he felt a &thorn;ing al rough and longe y-hered</L>
<L>And sayde fy allas what haue I do</L>
<L N="3740">Tehe quod sche and clapt &thorn;e wyndow to</L>
<L>And absolon go&thorn; for&thorn; a sory pas</L>
<L>A berde a berd seide heende Nicholas</L>
<L>By goddes corpus &thorn;is goth faire and wel</L>
<L N="3744">This sely absolon herde it euery del</L>
<L>And on his lippe he gan for anger byte</L>
<L>And to himself he seyde I schal &thorn;e quyte<MILESTONE N="53a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Who rubbe&thorn; now who frote&thorn; now his lippes</L>
<L>With dust with sond wi&thorn; straw with clo&thorn; wi&thorn; chippes</L>
<L>But absolon &thorn;at seith ful ofte allas/</L>
<L>My soule bitake I to Saternas/</L>
<L>But me were leuere &thorn;an al &thorn;is toun quod he/</L>
<L N="3752">Of &thorn;is despite awroken for to be</L>
<L>Allas quo&thorn; he allas I ne hadde y-bleynt</L>
<L>his hote loue is cold and al yqueynt</L>
<L>ffor fro &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he hadde kest hire ers</L>
<L N="3756">Of paramours he sette not a kers/</L>
<L>ffor he was heled of his maladie/</L>
<L>fful ofte paramoures he gan diffie</L>
<L>And weepe as do&thorn; a child &thorn;at is y-bete/</L>
<L N="3760">A softe paas he wente ouer &thorn;e strete/
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>vntil a Smyth men clepen daun Geruays</L>
<L>That in his forge smythie&thorn; plough harnays</L>
<L>he scharpe&thorn; scharre and Culter bisyly.</L>
<L N="3764">This absolon knokke&thorn; al Esely</L>
<L>And sayde vnto Geruays and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>What who art &thorn;ou it am I absolon</L>
<L>What absolon for cristes swete tree</L>
<L N="3768">Why ryse so ra&thorn;e benedicite</L>
<L>What eyle&thorn; &yogh;ou som gay gerl god it woot</L>
<L>ha&thorn; brought &yogh;ou &thorn;us vpon &thorn;e viritoot</L>
<L>By seinte note &yogh;e wot wel what I me[ne]</L>
<L N="3772">This absolon ne roughte nat a bene</L>
<L>Of all his pley no word a-gayn he gaf</L>
<L>he hadde more tow on his distaf</L>
<L>Than Geruays knew and sayde frend so deere</L>
<L N="3776">The hoote Culter in &thorn;e Chemenye heere</L>
<L>As lene it me I haue &thorn;er-wi&thorn; to done/</L>
<L>I wol bringe it agayn ful soone</L>
<L>Geruais answerde certes were it gold</L>
<L N="3780">Or in a poke nobles all vntold</L>
<L>Thou scholdest haue as I am trewe smith</L>
<L>Ey cristes foo what wol &yogh;e don &thorn;er-with<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ther-of quod absolon be as be may</L>
<L N="3784">I schal wel telle it &thorn;e to morwe day</L>
<L>And caughte &thorn;e culter by &thorn;e colde stele</L>
<L>fful softe out a&thorn; &thorn;e dore he gan to stele</L>
<L>And went vnto &thorn;e Carpenteres wal</L>
<L N="3788">he koughede ferst and knokkede &thorn;er wi&thorn; al</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e wyndow right as he dede ere/</L>
<L>This alison answerde who is &thorn;ere</L>
<L>That knokke&thorn; as I warant it a &thorn;eef</L>
<L N="3792">Why nay quod he god woot my sweete leef</L>
<L>I am &thorn;in absolon &thorn;i dereling</L>
<L>Of gold quod he I haue &thorn;e brought a ryng</L>
<L>My moder yaf it me so god me saue/</L>
<L N="3796">fful fyn it is and &thorn;er-to wel y-graue
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>This wol I yiuen &thorn;e if &thorn;ou me kisse</L>
<L>This Nicholas was risen for to pisse/</L>
<L>And &thorn;ought he wolde amenden al &thorn;e Iape/</L>
<L N="3800">he schulde kisse his ers or &thorn;at he scape</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;e wyndow dide he hastily</L>
<L>And out his ers he putte priuily</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e buttok to &thorn;e haunche bon</L>
<L N="3804">And &thorn;er-wi&thorn; spak &thorn;is clerk &thorn;is absolon</L>
<L>Spek swete brid I not wher &thorn;ou art</L>
<L>This Nicholas anon leet flee a fart</L>
<L>As gret as it hadde ben a &thorn;onder dent</L>
<L N="3808">That wi&thorn; &thorn;e strook he was almost y-blent</L>
<L>And he was redy wi&thorn; his Iren hoot</L>
<L>And Nicholas in &thorn;e ers he smoot</L>
<L>Of go&thorn; &thorn;e skyn an hande brood aboute/</L>
<L N="3812">The hoote culter brenned so his toute/</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e smerte he wende for to dye</L>
<L>As he were wood for woo he gan to crye/</L>
<L>help water water help for goddes herte</L>
<L N="3816">This Carpunter out of his slomber sterte</L>
<L>And herde on cryen watir as he were wood</L>
<L>And &thorn;ought allas now come&thorn; Noweles flood<MILESTONE N="54a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And sette him vppe wi&thorn;oute wordes mo</L>
<L N="3820">And wi&thorn; an ax he smot &thorn;e corde a tuo</L>
<L>And doun go&thorn; al he fond ney&thorn;er to selle/</L>
<L>No breed nor ale til he com to &thorn;e selle/</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e floor and &thorn;er a swowen he lay</L>
<L N="3824">vp sterte hire alison and Nicholay</L>
<L>and cried out and harrow in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>The neigheboures bo&thorn;e smale and grete</L>
<L>In ronnen for to gauren on &thorn;is man</L>
<L N="3828">That a swowen lay bo&thorn;e pale and wan</L>
<L>ffor with &thorn;at falle he brosten ha&thorn; his arm</L>
<L>But stonde he moste vnto his oughne harm</L>
<L>ffor whan he spak he was anon bore doun</L>
<L N="3832">With heende Nicholas and alisoun
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>They tolden euery man &thorn;at he was wood</L>
<L>he was a-gast so of &thorn;e Nowels flood</L>
<L>Thurgh fantasie &thorn;at of his vanite</L>
<L N="3836">he hadde y-bought him knedyng tubbes &thorn;re</L>
<L>And hadde hem hanged in &thorn;e roof aboue</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he preyed him for goddes loue</L>
<L>To sitten in &thorn;e roof par companye</L>
<L N="3840">The folk gan laughen at his fantasie</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e roof &thorn;ay loken and &thorn;ei cape</L>
<L>And torned all his harm vnto a Iape</L>
<L>ffor what so &thorn;is Carpenter answerde</L>
<L N="3844">It was for nought no men his reson herde</L>
<L>With o&thorn;es grete he was so sworn a doun</L>
<L>That he was holden wood in all &thorn;at toun</L>
<L>ffor euery clerk anon right heeld with o&thorn;er</L>
<L N="3848">They seyde &thorn;e man is wood my leeue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>And euery wight gan laughen at his strif</L>
<L>Thus swyued was &thorn;e Carpunteres wijf</L>
<L>ffor all his keepyng and his Ialousye/</L>
<L N="3852">And absolon ha&thorn; kist hir ne&thorn;er yhe</L>
<L>And Nicholas is scalded in his toute//</L>
<L>This tale is don and god saue al &thorn;e route<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
