<HEAD>&para; Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Reeues tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan folk han laughen at &thorn;is nyce cas</L>
<L>Of absolon and heende Nicholas<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; C<SUP>o</SUP>. iij<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Diuerse folk diuersely &thorn;ey seyde</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e more part &thorn;ei lough and pleyde</L>
<L>Ne at &thorn;is tale I saugh noman him greeue</L>
<L N="3860">But it were oonly Osewold &thorn;e Reeue</L>
<L>By cause he was of Carpenteres craft</L>
<L>A litel Ire is in his herte laft</L>
<L>he gan to grucche and blamen it a lite</L>
<L N="3864">So &thorn;e ik quod he ful wel cou&thorn;e I &thorn;e quyte</L>
<L>With bleryng of a proud melleres ye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at me liste to speke of Ribaudie</L>
<L>But yk am old me list not pley for age</L>
<L N="3868">Gras tyme is don my fodder is forage/</L>
<L>This white top write&thorn; myn olde &yogh;eres</L>
<L>myn herte is also mouled as myn heeres</L>
<L>But if I fare as do&thorn; an open ers</L>
<L N="3872">That ilke fruyt is euer lengere &thorn;e wers</L>
<L>Til it be roten in mullok or in stree/</L>
<L>We olde men I drede so fare we</L>
<L>Til we be roten can we nought be ripe</L>
<L N="3876">We hoppen alwey whil &thorn;e world wil pipe</L>
<L>ffor in oure wille &thorn;er stike&thorn; euer a naile</L>
<L>To haue an hoor heer and a greene taile</L>
<L>As ha&thorn; a leek for &thorn;ough oure might be gon</L>
<L N="3880">Oure wille desire&thorn; folie euer in oon</L>
<L>ffor whan we may nought doon &thorn;an wole we speke</L>
<L>yet in oure asschen olde is fyr y-reke</L>
<L>ffoure gleedes han we whiche I schal deuyse/</L>
<L N="3884">Auauntyng lyuyng anger couetyse</L>
<L>This foure sparkes longe&thorn; vnto eelde</L>
<L>Oure olde lymes now wel ben vnwelde
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>But wil ne schal nat failen &thorn;at is so&thorn;</L>
<L>And yet haue I alway a Coltes to&thorn;<MILESTONE N="55a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As many a &yogh;eer as it is passen henne</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at my tappe of lif bygan to renne</L>
<L>ffor sikerly whan I was born anoon</L>
<L N="3892">De&thorn; drough &thorn;e tappe of lijf and leet it goon</L>
<L>And euer si&thorn;en ha&thorn; so &thorn;e tappe y-ronne</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at almost al empty is &thorn;e tonne</L>
<L>The streem of lijf now droppe&thorn; on &thorn;e chimbe.</L>
<L N="3896">The sely tonge may wel rynge and chymbe.</L>
<L>Of wrecchedenesse &thorn;at passed is ful yore</L>
<L>With old folk saue dotage is nomore/</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at oure oost hadde herde &thorn;is sermonyng</L>
<L N="3900">he gan to speken as loodly as a king</L>
<L>he seyde what amounte&thorn; all &thorn;is witte</L>
<L>What schal we speke alday of holy writte</L>
<L>The deuel maade a reeue for to preche</L>
<L N="3904">Or of a Soutere schipman or a leche</L>
<L>Sey for&thorn; &thorn;i tale and tarie nought &thorn;e tyme</L>
<L>lo deppeford and it is halfwey prime</L>
<L>lo Grenewich &thorn;at many a schrewe is Inne</L>
<L N="3908">It were al tyme &thorn;i tale for to begynne</L>
<L>Now sires quod &thorn;is Osewold &thorn;e Reeue</L>
<L>I pray you alle &thorn;at ye nought &yogh;ou greeue</L>
<L>Thou I answere and somdel sette his houve</L>
<L N="3912">ffor leueful it is with force force of schouve</L>
<L>This dronken mellere ha&thorn; y-told vs heere</L>
<L>how &thorn;at bygyled was a Carpuntere/</L>
<L>Perauenture in scorn for I am oon</L>
<L N="3916">And by youre leeue I schal him quyte anoon</L>
<L>Right in his cherles termes wil I speke/</L>
<L>I preye to god his nekke mote tobreke</L>
<L>he can wel in myn &yogh;e sen a stalke</L>
<L>But in his owne he can nought seen a balke/<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; ffabula</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="113">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Trumpyngton nought fer fro Cantabregge</L>
<L>Ther go&thorn; a brook and ouer &thorn;at a bregge</L>
<L N="3923">vppon &thorn;e whiche brook &thorn;er stant a Melle</L>
<L>And &thorn;is is verray so&thorn; &thorn;at I &yogh;ou telle<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A meller was &thorn;er duellyng many a day</L>
<L>As any pecok he was proud and gay</L>
<L>Pype he cou&thorn;e and fissche and nettes beete</L>
<L N="3928">And torne coppes and wel wrastle and scheete/</L>
<L>Ay by his belt he bar a long Panade</L>
<L>And of a swerd ful trenchant was &thorn;e blade/</L>
<L>A Ioly popper bar he in his pouche</L>
<L N="3932">Ther was noman for peril durste him touche/</L>
<L>A scheffeld thwitel bar he in his hose</L>
<L>Round was his face and Camuse was his nose/</L>
<L>As pyled as an ape was his sculle</L>
<L N="3936">he was a market betere atte fulle</L>
<L>Ther was no wight &thorn;at dorst hand on him legge</L>
<L>But if he swor he scholde anon abegge</L>
<L>A &thorn;eef he was forso&thorn;e of corn and mele</L>
<L N="3940">And &thorn;at a sleigh and vsaunt for to stele</L>
<L>his name was hoote deynous Symkyn</L>
<L>A wijf he hadde come of noble kyn</L>
<L>The parsoun of &thorn;e toun hir fader was/</L>
<L N="3944">With hire he yaf ful many a panne of bras</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at Symkyn scholde in his blood allye</L>
<L>Sche was y-fostred in a Nonnerie/</L>
<L>ffor symkyn wolde no wyf as he sayde</L>
<L N="3948">But sche were wel ynorissched and a mayde/</L>
<L>To sauen his estate of yomanrie/</L>
<L>And sche was proud and pert as is a pye</L>
<L>A ful fair sight was it vppon hem tuo</L>
<L N="3952">On halidayes biforn hire wolde he go
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his typet wounden aboute his heede/</L>
<L>And sche cam after in a gyte of reede/</L>
<L>And Symkyn hadde hosen of &thorn;e same</L>
<L N="3956">Ther dorste no wight clepen hire but dame</L>
<L>Was non so hardy &thorn;at wente by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; hire dorste or ones rage or play</L>
<L>But if he wolde be slain of Symkyn</L>
<L>With panade or with knyf or boydekyn<MILESTONE N="56a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor Ielous folk ben perilous eueremo</L>
<L>Algate &thorn;ei wolde here wyues wenden so</L>
<L>And eek for sche was somdel smoterlich</L>
<L N="3964">Sche was as digne as water in a dich</L>
<L>As ful of hoker and of bisemare</L>
<L>hire &thorn;oughte &thorn;at a lady schulde hir spare</L>
<L>What for hire kynrede and hire nortelrie</L>
<L N="3968">That sche hadde lerned in &thorn;e nonnerie</L>
<L>A doughter hadde &thorn;e betwixe hem tuo</L>
<L>Of twenty &yogh;er wi&thorn;outen eny moo</L>
<L>Sauyng a childe &thorn;at was of half &yogh;eer age</L>
<L N="3972">In cradel it lay it was a proper page/</L>
<L>This wenche &thorn;ikke and wel ygrowen was</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Camoys nose and eyen grey as glas</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; buttokes brode and brestes rounde and hye</L>
<L N="3976">But right fair was hire heer I wol nought lye</L>
<L>&para; The parson of &thorn;e toun for sche was fair</L>
<L>In purpos was to maken hire his hair</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of his catel and his mesuage</L>
<L N="3980">And strange he made it/ of hire mariage</L>
<L>his purpos was for to bistowe hire hye</L>
<L>In to som wor&thorn;i blood of auncetrie/</L>
<L>ffor holy chirches good moot ben dispended</L>
<L N="3984">On holy cherche blood &thorn;at is descended</L>
<L>Therfore he wolde his holy blood honoure/</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at &thorn;e holy chirche scholde deuoure</L>
<L>Gret soken ha&thorn; &thorn;is meller out of doute</L>
<L N="3988">Wi&thorn; whete and malt of all &thorn;e land aboute/
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>And nameliche &thorn;er was a gret collegge</L>
<L>Men clepe&thorn; &thorn;e Soler halle of Cantabregge</L>
<L>&THORN;ere was here whete and eek here malt y-grounde</L>
<L N="3992">And on a day it happe&thorn; in a stounde</L>
<L>Syk lay &thorn;e manciple on a maladie/</L>
<L>Men wenden wisly &thorn;at he schulde dye</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;is mellere stal bo&thorn;e mele and corn</L>
<L>An hundred tyme more &thorn;anne biforn<MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er biforn he stal but curteysly</L>
<L>But now he was a theef outrageously</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e wardein chidde and made fare/</L>
<L N="4000">But &thorn;er-of sette &thorn;e meller nought a tare/</L>
<L>he crakede bost and swor it was nought so/</L>
<L>Thanne were &thorn;ere &yogh;onge scoleres tuo</L>
<L>That dwelten in &thorn;e halle of which I seye</L>
<L N="4004">Testyf &thorn;ey were and lusty for to pleye</L>
<L>And oonly for here mirthe and reuerye</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e wardein bisily &thorn;ei crye</L>
<L>To &yogh;if hem leue but a litel stounde</L>
<L N="4008">To go to melle and seen here corn y-grounde</L>
<L>And hardily &thorn;ei dorste leye here nekke</L>
<L>The mellere schulde nat stele hem half a pekke/</L>
<L>Of corn ne by sleight ne by force hem Reue</L>
<L N="4012">And atte laste &thorn;e wardeyn yaf hem leue</L>
<L>Iohn hight &thorn;at oon and alayn hight &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Of oo toun were &thorn;ei born &thorn;at highte strother</L>
<L>ffer in the North I can not telle where</L>
<L N="4016">This alayn make&thorn; redy all his gere</L>
<L>And on an hors &thorn;e sak he cast anon</L>
<L>ffor&thorn; go&thorn; alayn &thorn;e clerk and also Iohn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good swerd and wi&thorn; bokeler by his syde</L>
<L N="4020">Iohn knew &thorn;e wey him needede no guyde/</L>
<L>And atte melle &thorn;e sak a doun he layth</L>
<L>Alain spak first . alhail Symon in fai&thorn;</L>
<L>how fares &thorn;i faire doughter and &thorn;i wyf</L>
<L N="4024">Alayn welcome quod Symkyn by my lyf
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>And Iohn also how now what do &yogh;e heere</L>
<L>By god quod Iohn Symond neede ha&thorn; no peere</L>
<L>him bihoues serue himself &thorn;at has na swayn</L>
<L N="4028">Or elles he is a folt as clerkes sayn</L>
<L>Oure manciple I hope he wil be deed</L>
<L>Swa werkes him ay &thorn;e wanges in his heed</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore is I come and eek alayn</L>
<L>To grynde oure corn and carie it ham agayn<MILESTONE N="57a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I pray you speedes vs heithen &thorn;at &yogh;e may</L>
<L>It schal be don quod Symkyn by my fay</L>
<L>What wil &yogh;e doon whil &thorn;at it is in hande</L>
<L N="4036">By god right by &thorn;e hoper wil I stande</L>
<L>Quo&thorn; Iohan and se how gates &thorn;e corn gas Inne</L>
<L>&YOGH;it saugh I neuer by my fader kynne</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e hoper wagged til and fra</L>
<L N="4040">Alayn answerde Iohn and wiltow swa</L>
<L>Than wil I be byne&thorn;e by my croune</L>
<L>And se how gates &thorn;e mele falles a doune</L>
<L>In-til &thorn;e trough &thorn;at sal be my disporte</L>
<L N="4044">Quod Iohn in faath I may ben of &yogh;our sorte</L>
<L>I is as ille a melle as ere &yogh;e</L>
<L>This mellere smylede at here nycete</L>
<L>And &thorn;ought al &thorn;is nys don but for a wile</L>
<L N="4048">They wene &thorn;at no man hem may begyle</L>
<L>But by my &thorn;rift yit schal I blere here ye</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e sleight in here philosophie</L>
<L>The more queinte crekes &thorn;at &thorn;ay make/</L>
<L N="4052">The more wol I stele whan I take</L>
<L>In stede of flour &yogh;it wol I yeue hem brenne/</L>
<L>The grettest clerkes ben nought &thorn;e wisest menne</L>
<L>As whilom to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;us spak &thorn;e mare</L>
<L N="4056">Of all here arte counte I nou&yogh;t a tare/</L>
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;e dore he go&thorn; ful priuely</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he saugh his time softely</L>
<L>he loke&thorn; vp and doun til he ha&thorn; founde</L>
<L N="4060">The clerkes hors &thorn;er as it stood ybounde
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>Behynde &thorn;e mille vnder a leuesel</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hors he go&thorn; him faire and wel</L>
<L>he strepe&thorn; of &thorn;e bridel right anoon</L>
<L N="4064">And whan &thorn;e hors was laus he gynne&thorn; goon</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fen &thorn;are wilde mares renne/</L>
<L>And forth with wehe &thorn;orugh &thorn;ikke and &thorn;orugh &thorn;enne</L>
<L>This meller go&thorn; agayn no word he sayde</L>
<L>But do&thorn; his note and wi&thorn; hise clerkes pleyde<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Til &thorn;at hire corn was faire and wel y-grounde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e mele is sakked and y-bounde</L>
<L>This Iohn go&thorn; out and fynt his hors away</L>
<L N="4072">And gan to crye harrow and weylaway</L>
<L>Oure hors is lost Alayn for goddes banes</L>
<L>Steppe on &thorn;i feet com of man al at anes</L>
<L>Allas oure wardein has his palfray lorn</L>
<L N="4076">This aleyn al forgat bo&thorn;e mele and corn</L>
<L>Al was out of his mynde his housbondrye</L>
<L>What whilk wey is he gon he gan to crye</L>
<L>The wyf cam leepyng inward at a ren</L>
<L N="4080">Sche seyde allas &yogh;our hors goth in &thorn;e fen</L>
<L>With wilde mares as faste as he may goo</L>
<L>Vnthank come on his hand &thorn;at bond him so</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at bettre scholde haue knyt &thorn;e reyne</L>
<L N="4084">Allas quod Iohn Alayn for cristes peyne</L>
<L>lay doun &thorn;i swerd and I wol myn alswa</L>
<L>I is ful swift god wat as is a Ra</L>
<L>By goddes harte he sal nou&yogh;t scape vs ba&thorn;e</L>
<L N="4088">Why ne had &thorn;ou put &thorn;e caple in &thorn;e lathe</L>
<L>Ilhaille by godde alayn &thorn;ou is a fonne</L>
<L>Thise sely clerkes han fulfaste y-ronne</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fen bo&thorn;e alayn and eek Iohn</L>
<L N="4092">And whan &thorn;e Mellere seigh &thorn;at &thorn;ei were gon</L>
<L>he half a buisschel of here corn ha&thorn; take</L>
<L>And bad his wijf go knede it in a cake</L>
<L>And seide I trowe &thorn;e clerkes weren aferd</L>
<L N="4096">Yet kan a mellere make a clerkes berd
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>ffor all his art yet lat hem gon here weye</L>
<L>Lo where he go&thorn; ye lat &thorn;e children pleye</L>
<L>They gete him nought so lightly by my croun</L>
<L N="4100">Thise seely clerkes rennen vp and doun</L>
<L>With keep. keep. stand. stand. iossa. warderere /</L>
<L>Ga whistel &thorn;ou and I schal keepe him heere</L>
<L>But schortly til it was verray night</L>
<L>They cou&thorn;e nought &thorn;ough &thorn;ei dede all here might<MILESTONE N="58a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>here capel cacche he ran alwey so faste</L>
<L>Til in a diche &thorn;ei caught him atte laste</L>
<L>Wery and wet as beest is in &thorn;e rayn</L>
<L N="4108">Come&thorn; seely Iohn and with him com&thorn; alayn</L>
<L>&para; Allas quod Iohn &thorn;e day &thorn;at I was born</L>
<L>Now ere we dryuen til hething and til scorn</L>
<L>Oure corn is stole men wil vs fooles calle</L>
<L N="4112">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e wardein and oure felawes alle</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;e meller weylawey</L>
<L>Thus pleyne&thorn; Iohan as he go&thorn; by &thorn;e wey</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e melle and bayard in his hond</L>
<L N="4116">The meller sittyng by &thorn;e fyr he fond</L>
<L>ffor it was nyght and fer&thorn;er might he nought</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e loue of god &thorn;ei him bisought</L>
<L>Of herberwe and of eese as for here peny</L>
<L N="4120">The mellere seyde agayn if &thorn;er be eny</L>
<L>Such as if is &yogh;it schal &yogh;e haue &yogh;oure part</L>
<L>Myn hous is streit but &yogh;e han lerned art</L>
<L>&YOGH;e can by argumentes make a place</L>
<L N="4124">A myle brood of twenty foote of space</L>
<L>lat se now if &thorn;is place mow suffise</L>
<L>Or make it rowmere with speche as is &yogh;oure gyse</L>
<L>Now Symond seyde &thorn;is Iohn by seint Cuthberd</L>
<L N="4128">As is &thorn;ou mery and &thorn;at is faire answerd</L>
<L>I haue herd say men sal take of tua &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Swilk as he fyndes or take swilk as he brynges/</L>
<L>But specially I pray &thorn;e ooste deere</L>
<L N="4132">Gete vs som mete and drynk and mak vs cheere
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>And we wol payen trewly atte fulle</L>
<L>With empty handes men may naan haukes tulle</L>
<L>Lo heer oure siluer reedy for til spende</L>
<L N="4136">This meller to &thorn;e toun his doughter sende</L>
<L>ffor ale and breed and rosted hem a goos</L>
<L>And boond here hors it scholde namore go loos</L>
<L>And in his owne chambre he made a bedde</L>
<L>With scheetes and wi&thorn; chalons faire y-spredde<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nought from his oughne bed ten foote or twelue/</L>
<L>his doughter hadde a bed al by hir selue/</L>
<L>Right in &thorn;e same chambre by and by</L>
<L N="4144">It mighte be no bette and cause why</L>
<L>Ther was no romer herberwe in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>&thorn;ey soupen and &thorn;ey speken hem of solace</L>
<L>And drynken euere strong ale atte beste</L>
<L N="4148">A-boute mydnyght wente &thorn;ei to reste</L>
<L>Wel ha&thorn; &thorn;e mellere vernysshed his heed</L>
<L>fful pale he was for-drunken and nou&yogh;t reed</L>
<L>he yexeth and he speke&thorn; &thorn;urgh &thorn;e nose/</L>
<L N="4152">As he were on &thorn;e quakke or on &thorn;e pose/</L>
<L>To bedde he go&thorn; and with him go&thorn; his wijf</L>
<L>As eny Iay he light was and Iolif</L>
<L>So was hire Ioly whistel wel y-wette</L>
<L N="4156">The cradell at hire beddes feet is sette/</L>
<L>To rokken and yeue &thorn;e childe to souke</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at dronken was al in &thorn;e crouke</L>
<L>To bedde wente &thorn;e doughter right anoon</L>
<L N="4160">To bedde go&thorn; Alayn and also Iohn</L>
<L>Ther was nomore &thorn;em needede no dwale</L>
<L>This meller ha&thorn; so wisely bibbed ale</L>
<L>That as an hors he snorte&thorn; in his slepe</L>
<L N="4164">Ne of his tayl behynde he took no keepe</L>
<L>his wijf bar him a burdon a ful strong</L>
<L>Men mighten heere here routyng a furlong</L>
<L>The wenche route&thorn; eek par compaignie</L>
<L N="4168">Alayn &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at herde &thorn;is melodye
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>he pokede Iohn and seyde sleepist &thorn;ou</L>
<L>herdestow euer slik a sang ar now</L>
<L>lo swilk a couplyng is bitwixe hem alle</L>
<L N="4172">A wilde fyr on &thorn;air bodies falle</L>
<L>ho herkned euer slik a ferly &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Ye &thorn;ai sall haue &thorn;e flour of yll endyng</L>
<L>This lange night &thorn;er tydes me na reste/</L>
<L>But &yogh;it na force al schal be for &thorn;e beste<MILESTONE N="59a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor Iohn seide als euer mote I &thorn;riue</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I may yon wenche wol I swyue</L>
<L>Som esement ha&thorn; lawe schapen vs</L>
<L N="4180">ffor Iohn &thorn;er is a lawe &thorn;at seith &thorn;us</L>
<L>That if a man in a poynt be agreeued</L>
<L>That in ano&thorn;er he schal be releeued</L>
<L>Oure corn is stolen so&thorn;ly it is no nay</L>
<L N="4184">And we han had an ylle fitte to day</L>
<L>And syn I schal haue noon amendement</L>
<L>Agayn my losse I wol haue esement</L>
<L>By goddes sale it sal nan o&thorn;ir be</L>
<L N="4188">This Iohn answerde Alayn so mot I &thorn;e</L>
<L>The meller is a perilous man he sayde</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he out of his slape abrayde</L>
<L>he mighte don vs bo&thorn;e a vilanye</L>
<L N="4192">Alayn answerde I counte him nought a flye</L>
<L>And vp he rist and by &thorn;e wenche he crepte</L>
<L>This wenche lay vpright and faste slepte</L>
<L>Til he so neigh was or sche mighte spye</L>
<L N="4196">That it hadde been to late for to crye</L>
<L>And schortly for to seyn &thorn;ey were at oon</L>
<L>Now play alayn for I wol speke of Ioon</L>
<L>This Iohn li&thorn; stille a forlong wey or tuo</L>
<L N="4200">And to himself he make&thorn; rou&thorn;e and wo</L>
<L>Allas quod he &thorn;is is a wikke Iape</L>
<L>Now may I sayn &thorn;at I is but an ape</L>
<L>&YOGH;et ha&thorn; my felaw somwhat for his harm</L>
<L N="4204">he has &thorn;e myllers doughter in his arm
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>he auntred him and ha&thorn; his needes spedde</L>
<L>And I lye as a draf sak in my bedde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is Iape is told ano&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="4208">I schal be holde a daffe a Cokenay</L>
<L>I wol arise and aunter it by my faith</L>
<L>vnhardy is vnseely as men saith</L>
<L>And vp he ros and softely he went</L>
<L N="4212">vnto &thorn;e cradill and in his hand it hent<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And bar it softe vnto his beddes feet</L>
<L>Sone after . &thorn;e wif hire routyng leet</L>
<L>And gan to wake and went hire out to pisse</L>
<L N="4216">And com agayn and gan hir cradel mysse</L>
<L>And groped heer and &thorn;er but sche fond noon</L>
<L>Allas quod sche I hadde almost mys goon</L>
<L>I hadde almost goon to &thorn;e clerkes bedde</L>
<L N="4220">Ey benedicite &thorn;an hadde I foule y-spedde</L>
<L>And for&thorn; sche go&thorn; til sche &thorn;e cradil fond</L>
<L>Sche grope&thorn; alwey for&thorn;er with hire hond</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;e bed and &thorn;oughte nought but good</L>
<L N="4224">By cause &thorn;at &thorn;e cradel by it stood</L>
<L>And nyste wher sche was for it was derk</L>
<L>But faire and wel sche crepe in to &thorn;e clerk</L>
<L>And lith ful stille and wolde haue caught a slepe</L>
<L N="4228">With-Inne a while &thorn;is Iohn &thorn;e clerk vp lepe</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is goode wijf he lei&thorn; on sore</L>
<L>So mery a fitte ne hadde sche not ful yore</L>
<L>he prike&thorn; harde and deepe as he were madde</L>
<L N="4232">This Ioly lyf han &thorn;ise tuo clerkes ladde</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ridde cok bygan to synge</L>
<L>Aleyn wax wery in &thorn;e dawenynge</L>
<L>ffor he hadde swonken all &thorn;e longe nyght</L>
<L N="4236">And sayde far wel Malyn sweete wight</L>
<L>The day is come I may no lenger byde</L>
<L>But euermoo wher so I go or ryde</L>
<L>I am &thorn;in oughne clerk so haue I hele</L>
<L N="4240">Now deere lemman quod sche go far wele
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>But or &thorn;ou go oo &thorn;ing I wol &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou wendest homward by &thorn;e melle</L>
<L>Right at &thorn;e entre of &thorn;e dore behynde</L>
<L N="4244">Thou schalt a cake of half a busshel fynde</L>
<L>That was y-maked of &thorn;in oughne mele</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at I hilpe my sire for to stele</L>
<L>And goode lemman god &thorn;e saue and keepe/</L>
<L N="4248">And with &thorn;at word almost sche gan to weepe<MILESTONE N="60a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Alayn vprist and &thorn;ought or &thorn;at it dawe/</L>
<L>I wol go creepen in by my felawe/</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;e cradel wi&thorn; his hond anon</L>
<L N="4252">By god &thorn;ought he al wrang I haue mysgon</L>
<L>Myn heed is toty of my swynk/ to nyght</L>
<L>That make&thorn; me &thorn;at I go nought aright</L>
<L>I wot wel by &thorn;e cradel I haue mysgo</L>
<L N="4256">here lith &thorn;e meller and his wijf also</L>
<L>And forth he go&thorn; on twenty deuelway</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e bed &thorn;er as &thorn;e meller lay</L>
<L>he wende haue cropen by his felawe Iohn</L>
<L N="4260">And by &thorn;e mellere in he creep anoon</L>
<L>And caught him by &thorn;e necke and softe he spak</L>
<L>he seyde &thorn;ou Iohn &thorn;ou swyneshed awak</L>
<L>ffor cristes sawle and heer a noble game/</L>
<L N="4264">ffor by &thorn;at lord &thorn;at called is saint Iame</L>
<L>As I haue &thorn;ries in &thorn;is schorte night</L>
<L>Swyued &thorn;e mellers doughter bolt vprigh[t]</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;ou hast as a coward ben agast</L>
<L N="4268">&thorn;e false harlot quod &thorn;e meller hast</L>
<L>A fals traitour false clerk quod he</L>
<L>&thorn;ou schalt be ded by goddes dignite</L>
<L>Who durste be so bolde to disparage</L>
<L N="4272">My doughter &thorn;at is comen of such lynage</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e &thorn;rote bolle he caught alayn</L>
<L>And he hent him dispitously agayn</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e nose he smot him with his fiste/</L>
<L N="4276">Doun ran &thorn;e bloody streen vpon his briste
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e floor with nose and mouth to-broke</L>
<L>&thorn;ei walwe as do&thorn; tuo pigges in a poke</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ai gon and doun a-gayn anoon</L>
<L N="4280">Til &thorn;at &thorn;e meller spurned at a stoon</L>
<L>And doun he fel bakward vpon his wijf</L>
<L>That wiste no&thorn;ing of &thorn;is nyce strijf</L>
<L>ffor sche was falle a sleepe a litel wight</L>
<L>With Iohn &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at waked hadde al &thorn;e night<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with &thorn;e falle out of hir sleep sche brayde</L>
<L>help holy cros of bromeholm sche sayde/</L>
<L>In manus tuas lord to &thorn;e I calle</L>
<L N="4288">Awake Symond &thorn;e feend is on me falle</L>
<L>Myn herte is broken help I nam but ded</L>
<L>Ther li&thorn; on vp my wombe and vp myn heed</L>
<L>help Symkyn for &thorn;e false clerkes fighte</L>
<L N="4292">This Iohn starte vp as fast as euer he mighte</L>
<L>And grasped by &thorn;e walles to and fro</L>
<L>To fynde a staf and sche stert vp also</L>
<L>And knew &thorn;e estris bet &thorn;an did &thorn;at Iohn</L>
<L N="4296">And by &thorn;e wal a staf sche fond anon</L>
<L>And saugh a litel schymeryng of a light/</L>
<L>ffor at an hole in schoon &thorn;e moone bright</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at light sche saugh hem bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L N="4300">But sikerly sche nyste who was who</L>
<L>But as sche saugh a whit &thorn;ing in hir eye</L>
<L>And whan sche gan &thorn;is white &thorn;ing aspye</L>
<L>Sche wende &thorn;e clerk had wered a voluper</L>
<L N="4304">And wi&thorn; &thorn;e staf sche drough ay ner and ner</L>
<L>And wende han hitte &thorn;is alayn atte fulle</L>
<L>And smot &thorn;e meller on &thorn;e pilede skulle</L>
<L>That doun he goth and cryed harrow I dye</L>
<L N="4308">This clerkes beet him weel and leet him lye</L>
<L>And grey&thorn;en hem and tooke here hors anon</L>
<L>And eek here mele and on here wey &thorn;ey goon</L>
<L>And atte Mille yet &thorn;ai toke here cake/</L>
<L N="4312">Of half a busschel flour ful wel y-bake
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>Thus is &thorn;e proude Meller wel y-bete</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; y-lost &thorn;e gryndyng of &thorn;e whete</L>
<L>And payed for &thorn;e soper euery dele/</L>
<L N="4316">Of Alayn and of Iohn &thorn;at bette him weel</L>
<L>his wyf is swyued and his doughter als/</L>
<L>lo swich it is a mellere to be fals</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore &thorn;is prouerbe is seyd ful soth</L>
<L N="4320">him &thorn;ar nat weene wel &thorn;at yuel do&thorn;<MILESTONE N="61a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A gilour schal himself begyled be/</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at sitte&thorn; highe in mageste/</L>
<L>Saue all &thorn;is companye grete and smale</L>
<L N="4324">Thus haue I quytte &thorn;e meller in my tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="125">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Cook of london whil &thorn;e Reue spak</L>
<L>ffor ioye he &thorn;oughte he clawed him on &thorn;e bak</L>
<L>ha ha quod he for cristes passioun</L>
<L N="4328">This meller ha&thorn; a scharp conclusioun</L>
<L>vpon his argument of herbergage</L>
<L>We[l] seide Salamon in his langage/</L>
<L>Ne bryng nat euery man in to &thorn;in hous</L>
<L N="4332">ffor herberwyng be night is perilous</L>
<L>Wel oughte a man auysed for to be</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at he broughte in to his priuite</L>
<L>I praie to god so yeue me sorwe and care</L>
<L N="4336">If euere sithen I highte hogge of of ware</L>
<L>herde I mellere bettre y-set a werke</L>
<L>he hadde a Iape of malice in &thorn;e derke/</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e vouche sauf to heere/</L>
<L N="4340">But god forbede &thorn;at we stynte heere</L>
<L>A tale of me &thorn;at am a pouere man</L>
<L>I wol yow telle as wel as euer I can</L>
<L>A litel Iape &thorn;at fil in oure Citee</L>
<L N="4344">Oure oost answerde and seide I graunte it &thorn;e</L>
<L>Now telle on Roger loke &thorn;at it be good</L>
<L>ffor many a paste hast &thorn;ou latyn blood</L>
<L>And many a Iakke of Douer hast &thorn;ou sold</L>
<L N="4348">That ha&thorn; ben twyes hoot and twyes cold</L>
<L>Of many pilgrym hastow cristes curs</L>
<L>ffor of &thorn;y persely &yogh;it &thorn;ey fare &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei haue eten wi&thorn; &thorn;e stubbul goos</L>
<L N="4352">ffor in &thorn;y schoppe is many a flye loos</L>
<L>Now tel on gentil Roger by &thorn;i name</L>
<L>But yet I preye &thorn;e be not wro&thorn; for game</L>
<L>A man may say ful soth in game and play</L>
<L N="4356">Thou seist ful so&thorn; quod Roger by my fay<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>But so&thorn; play quad play as &thorn;e flemyng seith</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore herry baillyf by &thorn;i feith</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t wroth or we departen heere</L>
<L N="4360">Though &thorn;at my tale be of an Ostelleere</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I wol not tellen it &yogh;it</L>
<L>But or we parte I-wys &thorn;ou schalt be quyt</L>
<L>And &thorn;er wi&thorn; al he lough and made cheere/</L>
<L N="4364">And saide his tale as &yogh;e schal after heere<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="127">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP>. iiij<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Prentys whilom dwelled in oure Citee</L>
<L>And of a craft of vitaillers was he</L>
<L>Gaillard he was as goldfynch in &thorn;e schawe</L>
<L N="4368">Broun as a berye a propur schort felawe/</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; lokkes blake y-kempt ful fetysly</L>
<L>Daunce he couthe so wel and Iolyly</L>
<L>That he was cleped Perkyn Reuolour</L>
<L N="4372">he was as ful of loue paramour</L>
<L>As is &thorn;e hyue ful of hony sweete</L>
<L>Wel was &thorn;e wenche with him mighte meete</L>
<L>At euery brydale wolde he synge and hoppe</L>
<L N="4376">he louede bet &thorn;e tauerne &thorn;an &thorn;e schoppe</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;er any rydyng was in chepe</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e schoppe &thorn;ider wolde he leepe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he hadde al &thorn;e sight y-seyn</L>
<L N="4380">And daunced wel wolde he not come ageyn</L>
<L>And gadered him a meyne of his sorte</L>
<L>To hoppe and synge and maken such desporte</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ei setten steuene for to mete</L>
<L N="4384">To pleyen atte dys in such a streete</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e toun nas &thorn;er no prentys</L>
<L>That fairere cou&thorn;e caste a paire of dys:</L>
<L>Than Perkyn cou&thorn;e and &thorn;er-to he was fre</L>
<L N="4388">Of his dispense in place of priuite/</L>
<L>That fond his maister wel in his chaffare/</L>
<L>ffor ofte tyme he fond his box ful bare</L>
<L>ffor sikerly a prentys Reuelour<MILESTONE N="62a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4392">That haunte&thorn; dys ryot or paramour</L>
<L>his maister schal it in his schoppe abeye</L>
<L>Al haue he not part of &thorn;e menstralcye</L>
<L>ffor theft and riot &thorn;ei ben conuertible</L>
<L N="4396">Al conne he play on gyterne or Rubible
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Reuel and trouthe as in a lough degre</L>
<L>&thorn;ey been ful wro&thorn;e alday as men may se</L>
<L>This Iolif prentys with his maister bood</L>
<L N="4400">Til he were neigh out of his prentyshood</L>
<L>Al were he snybbed bo&thorn;e erly and late</L>
<L>And som tyme lad with Reuel to Newgate</L>
<L>But atte last his mayster him bi&thorn;oughte</L>
<L N="4404">vpon a day whan he his paper soughte</L>
<L>Of a prouerbe &thorn;at sei&thorn; &thorn;is same word</L>
<L>Wel bette is roten appul out of hord</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;at it rotye al &thorn;e remenant</L>
<L N="4408">So fare&thorn; it by &thorn;e riotous seruant</L>
<L>It is ful lasse harm to late it pace</L>
<L>&thorn;anne he schende all &thorn;e seruant&yogh; in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Therfore his mayster &yogh;af him a quitance</L>
<L N="4412">And bad him go with sorwe and with meschance</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;is Ioly prentys hadde his leue</L>
<L>Now lat him riote al &thorn;e night or leue</L>
<L>And for &thorn;er nys no &thorn;eef wi&thorn;outen a lowke</L>
<L N="4416">That helpe&thorn; him to wasten and to sowke/</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he brybe can or borwe may</L>
<L>Anon he sente his bedde and his array</L>
<L>vnto a Coupere of his owne sorte</L>
<L N="4420">That louede dys and Reuel and disporte</L>
<L>And hadde a wyf &thorn;at heeld for contynance/</L>
<L>A schoppe / and swyued for hire sustynance.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="129">
<HEAD>APPENDIX TO GROUP A.</HEAD>
<HEAD>[THE SPURIOUS TALE OF GAMELYN.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>Incipit ffabula/</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LIthen &amp; lestene&thorn; and herkene&thorn; aright</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schulle heeren of a doughty knight</L>
<L>Sire Iohn of Boundys was his name</L>
<L N="4">he cou&thorn;e of norture and mochil of game.</L>
<L>Thre sones &thorn;e knight hadde and with his body he hem wan<MILESTONE N="62a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The eldest was a moche schrewe and sone he bigan</L>
<L>his bre&thorn;eren loued wel here fader and of him were agast</L>
<L N="8">The eldest deserue&thorn; his faderes curs &amp; hadde it atte last</L>
<L>The goode knight his fader lyued so yore</L>
<L>That de&thorn; was comen him to and handlid him ful sore/</L>
<L>The goode knight cared sore sik &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L N="12">how hise children schulde lyuen after his day</L>
<L>he hadde ben wyde wher but non housbond he was</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e lond &thorn;at he hadde it was verrey purchas</L>
<L>ffayn he wolde it were dressed among hem alle</L>
<L N="16">That eche of hem hadde his part as it mighte falle</L>
<L>Tho sente he in to contre after wise knightes</L>
<L>To helpen delen his londes and dressen hem to rightes</L>
<L>he sent hem word by lettres &thorn;ey scholden hy&yogh;e blyue</L>
<L N="20">If &thorn;ey wolde speke wi&thorn; him whil he was on lyue
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>Tho &thorn;e knightes herden seek &thorn;at he lay</L>
<L>hadde &thorn;ei no reste nei&thorn;er night ne day</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei comen to him &thorn;er he lay stille</L>
<L N="24">On his de&thorn; bedde to abyde goddes wille</L>
<L>Thanne seyd &thorn;e goode knight syk &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>lordes I &yogh;ou warne for so&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen nay</L>
<L>I may no lengere lyuen heer in &thorn;is stounde</L>
<L N="28">ffor &thorn;orugh goddes wille deth drawe&thorn; me to grounde/</L>
<L>Ther nas noon of hem all &thorn;at herde him aright</L>
<L>That &thorn;ay hadden reu&thorn;e of &thorn;at ilke knight</L>
<L>And seyde sire for goddes loue dismaye &yogh;ou nought</L>
<L N="32">God may don boote of bale &thorn;at is now y-wrought</L>
<L>Than spak &thorn;e goode knight sike &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>Boote of bale god may sende I wot it is no nay</L>
<L>But I beseke &yogh;ou knightes for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L N="36">Go&thorn; and dresseth my lond among my sones &thorn;re</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of god dele&thorn; hem nat amys</L>
<L>And for&yogh;ete&thorn; nought Gamelyn my &yogh;onge sone &thorn;at is</L>
<L>Take&thorn; heede to &thorn;at oon as wel as to &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L N="40">Seelde &yogh;e see ony heir helpen his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Tho leeten &thorn;ey &thorn;e knight lyen &thorn;at was not in hele<MILESTONE N="63a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wenten in to counseill his londes for to dele/</L>
<L>ffor to delen hem all to oon was here &thorn;ought</L>
<L N="44">And for gamelyn was yongest he scholde haue nought</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e lond &thorn;at &thorn;er was &thorn;ai dalten it it tuo</L>
