<L>And so schal we alle may &thorn;er noman flee</L>
<L>God bring vs to &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at euer schal be AmeN pour charite<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="155">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="129">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&alpha;. FRAGMENT II.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> MAN OF LAW'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>CORPUS MS.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owre oost saugh wel &thorn;at by &thorn;e brighte sonne<NOTE PLACE="marg">.C<SUP>m</SUP>.v<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>The ark of his artificial day hadde ronne</L>
<L>The fer&thorn;e part of half an hour and moore</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough he were nought deepe expert in lore<MILESTONE N="74a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he wist it was &thorn;e xviij.<SUP>e</SUP> day</L>
<L>Of Aprille &thorn;at is messager to May</L>
<L>And saugh wel &thorn;at &thorn;e schadwe of euery tree</L>
<L N="8">Was as in leng&thorn;e &thorn;e same quantite</L>
<L>That was &thorn;e body erect &thorn;at caused it</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by &thorn;e schadewe he took his wit</L>
<L>That Phebus which &thorn;at schon so cler and bright</L>
<L N="12">Degrees was xlv clombe on hight</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at day as in &thorn;at latitude</L>
<L>It was ten atte clokke he gan conclude</L>
<L>And sodeinly he plight his hors aboute</L>
<L N="16">lordynges quod he I warne &yogh;ou alle &thorn;is route</L>
<L>The fer&thorn;e party of &thorn;is day is gon</L>
<L>Now for &thorn;e loue of god and of seint Iohn</L>
<L>lese&thorn; no tyme as ferforth as ye may</L>
<L N="20">Lordinges &thorn;e time it waste&thorn; night and day</L>
<L>And stele&thorn; from vs what priuely slepyng</L>
<L>And what &thorn;urgh necligence in oure waking</L>
<L>As doth &thorn;e streem &thorn;at turne&thorn; neuer agayn</L>
<L N="24">Descendyng from &thorn;e mountayn in to playn</L>
<L>Wel can senek and many a Philosophre</L>
<L>Biweilen tyme more &thorn;an gold in cophre</L>
<L>ffor los of catelle may recouered be</L>
<L N="28">But los of tyme schende&thorn; vs quod he
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="156"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="130"></L>
<L>It wil nought come agayn wi&thorn;outen drede</L>
<L>Namore &thorn;an wile Malkyns maydenhede</L>
<L>Whan sche ha&thorn; lost it / in hir wantonnesse</L>
<L N="32">lat vs nought mowlen &thorn;us in ydelnesse</L>
<L>Sire Man of lawe quod he saue &yogh;e blis</L>
<L>Tel vs a tale anon as forward is</L>
<L>ye be submitted &thorn;urgh your free assent</L>
<L N="36">To stonde in &thorn;is cas of my Iuggement</L>
<L>Aquite&thorn; &yogh;ow now of &yogh;oure beheste</L>
<L>Thanne haue &yogh;e doon your deuer atte leste</L>
<L>Oost quod he depardeux ich assente</L>
<L>To breke forward is nought myn entente<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Biheste is dette and I wil holde fayn</L>
<L>Al my biheste I can no bettre sain</L>
<L>ffor swich lawe as a man yeue&thorn; ano&thorn;er wight</L>
<L N="44">he schulde himself vsen it by right</L>
<L>Thus wile oure text but na&thorn;eles certein</L>
<L>I can right now no &thorn;rifty tale sein</L>
<L>That Chaucer &thorn;ough he can but lewedly</L>
<L N="48">On metris and in rymyng craftily</L>
<L>ha&thorn; sayd hem in such englissh as he can</L>
<L>Of olde tyme as knowe&thorn; many a man</L>
<L>And if he haue nought seyd hem leeue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="52">In o book / he ha&thorn; seyd hem in ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor he ha&thorn; told of louers vp and don</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;an Ovide made mencion</L>
<L>In his Epistles &thorn;at been ful olde</L>
<L N="56">What scholde I tellen hem sen &thorn;ei ben tolde</L>
<L>In you&thorn;e he made of Ceys and alcione</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;en ha&thorn; he spoke of euerychone</L>
<L>Thise noble wyfes and &thorn;ese louers eeke</L>
<L N="60">Who so &thorn;at wile his large volom seeke</L>
<L>Cleped &thorn;e seintes legende of Cupide</L>
<L>Ther may he seen &thorn;e large woundes wyde</L>
<L>Of lucresse &amp; of Babilan Tisbe</L>
<L N="64">The swerd of Dido for &thorn;e fals Ene
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="157"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="131"></L>
<L>The tree of Phillis for hire Demephon</L>
<L>The pleynt of Dyanyre and of Ermion</L>
<L>Of Adriane and of ysyphile</L>
<L N="68">The barayne ysle stondyng in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>The dreynt leander for his Erro</L>
<L>The teeres of helyne and eek &thorn;e woo</L>
<L>Of Brixseyde and of &thorn;e ladomya</L>
<L N="72">&thorn;e cruelte of queen medea</L>
<L>The litel children hangyng by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e Iason &thorn;at was of loue so fals</L>
<L>Of ypmistra Penolope Alceste</L>
<L>youre wifhode he comendeth wi&thorn; &thorn;e beste<MILESTONE N="75a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But certeinly no word ne write&thorn; he</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ikke wicke ensample of Canace</L>
<L>That loued hir owne brother synfully</L>
<L N="80">Of suche cursed stories I sei fy</L>
<L>Or elles of Tyro Appoloneus</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e cursed king Antiochus</L>
<L>Biraft his doughter of hir maydenhede</L>
<L N="84">That is so horrible a tale for to rede</L>
<L>Whan he hir &thorn;rew &thorn;orugh &thorn;e pament</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore he of ful auisement</L>
<L>Nolde neuer write in none of his sermons</L>
<L N="88">Of which vnkynde abhominacions</L>
<L>Ne I ne wil not reherce if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>But of my tale how schal I don &thorn;is day</L>
<L>Me were lo&thorn; be likned douteles</L>
<L N="92">To muses &thorn;at men clepen pieriedes</L>
<L>Methamorphoseos wot what I mene</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I recche nought a bene</L>
<L>Though I come after him with hawe bake</L>
<L N="96">I speke in prose and lat him Rimes make</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at word he with a sobre chere</L>
<L>Bigan his tale as &yogh;e schal after heere.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000186.tif" N="158"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="132">
<HEAD>[PROLOGUE OF THE MAN OF LAW'S TALE.] &para; Incipit ffabula.<NOTE PLACE="head">[There are no breaks in the MS between stanzas or Parts.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Hateful harm condicion of pouert</L>
<L>With thurst with cold with hunger he confoundeth</L>
<L>To asken helpe &thorn;e schame&thorn; in &thorn;in hert</L>
<L N="102">If &thorn;ou now axe wi&thorn; neede art &thorn;ou so wounded</L>
<L>That verray neede vnwrappeth al &thorn;i wounde hid</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;in heed &thorn;ou most for Indigence</L>
<L N="105">Or stele or begge or borwe &thorn;i dispence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thou blamest crist and seist ful bitterly</L>
<L>he mys departe&thorn; richesse temporal</L>
<L>Thy neyghebour &thorn;ou witest synfully</L>
<L N="109">And seist &thorn;ou hast to litel and he ha&thorn; al</L>
<L>Par fey seistow somtyme he rekene schal</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his tail schal brennen in &thorn;e gleede</L>
<L>ffor he nought helpe&thorn; needeful in here neede<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Herkne what is &thorn;e menyng of &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Bet is to deyen &thorn;an haue Indigence</L>
<L>This self neighebore wile &thorn;e dispise</L>
<L N="116">If &thorn;ou be pouer far wel &thorn;i reuerence</L>
<L>yet of &thorn;e wise man tak &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e dayes of pore men ben wikke</L>
<L N="119">Be war &thorn;erfore or &thorn;ou come in &thorn;at prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; If &thorn;ou be pouere &thorn;i bro&thorn;er hate&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;i freendes fleen fro &thorn;e allas</L>
<L>O Riche marchantz ful of wele be</L>
<L N="123">O noble prudent folk as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>youre bagges ben nought filled with ambes aas</L>
<L>But with Sis Cynk &thorn;at renne&thorn; for &yogh;our chance</L>
<L N="126">At Cristes masse merye may &yogh;e daunce
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="159"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ye seeken lond and see for &yogh;our wynnynges</L>
<L>As wys folk &thorn;at knowen alle thestat</L>
<L>Of regnes &yogh;e ben fadres of ty&thorn;inges</L>
<L N="130">And tales bothen of pees and of debat</L>
<L>I were right now of tales desolat</L>
<L>Nere &thorn;at a marchant gon is many a yere</L>
<L N="133">Me taught a tale which as ye schal heere
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000188.tif" N="160"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="134">
<HEAD>[PART I.]<NOTE PLACE="head">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In Surrye whilom dwelt a companye</L>
<L>Of Chapmen riche and &thorn;er-to sad and trewe</L>
<L>That wyde where sente here spicerie</L>
<L N="137">Clo&thorn;es of gold and Satyn riche of hewe</L>
<L>here chaffare was so thrifty and so newe</L>
<L>That euery wight ha&thorn; deynte to chaffare</L>
<L N="140">With hem and eek to sellen hem here ware</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now fil it &thorn;at &thorn;e maistres of &thorn;at sort</L>
<L>han schapen hem to Rome for to wende</L>
<L>Were it fo chapmanhode or for disport</L>
<L N="144">Non o&thorn;er message wolde &thorn;ey &thorn;ider sende</L>
<L>But comen hemself to Rome &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>And in swich place as &thorn;ought hem auantage</L>
<L N="147">ffor here entente &thorn;ei take here herbergage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Soiorned han &thorn;ise marchantez in &thorn;at toun<MILESTONE N="76a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A certein tyme as felle to hire plesance</L>
<L>But so felle &thorn;at &thorn;e excellent renoun</L>
<L N="151">Of &thorn;e Emperour doughter dame Custance</L>
<L>Reported was with euery circumstance</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;ise Surrien marchantz in swich wise</L>
<L N="154">ffro day to day as I schal you deuyse/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This was &thorn;e comone voys of euery man</L>
<L>Oure emperour of Rome god him see</L>
<L>A doughter he ha&thorn; &thorn;at syn &thorn;e world bigan</L>
<L N="158">To rekne as wel hir goodnesse as beaute</L>
<L>Nas neuer such ano&thorn;er as is sche</L>
<L>I pray to god in honour hir sustene</L>
<L N="161">And wolde sche were of alle Europe &thorn;e queene
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="161"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In hire is heigh beaute wi&thorn;oute pride<NOTE PLACE="marg">Europia est <I>tercia</I> pars mundi.</NOTE></L>
<L>you&thorn;e wi&thorn;oute greenehod of folye</L>
<L>To alle hire werkes vertu is hire guyde</L>
<L N="165">humblesse ha&thorn; slayn in hire al tyrannye</L>
<L>Sche is a merour of alle curtesye</L>
<L>hire herte is verray chambre of holynesse</L>
<L N="168">hire hand ministre of fredam for almesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And al &thorn;is voys is so&thorn; as god is trewe</L>
<L>But now to purpos lat vs turne again</L>
<L>Thise marchantz han doon fraught here schippes newe</L>
<L N="172">And whan &thorn;ay haue &thorn;is blisful mayde sain</L>
<L>hom to Surrey be&thorn; &thorn;ei went agayn</L>
<L>And don here needes as &thorn;ey han don yore</L>
<L N="175">And lyuen in wele I can seye yow nomore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now fil it &thorn;at &thorn;is marchantz stoden in grace</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at was &thorn;e Sowdon of Surrie</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;ei came from eny strange place</L>
<L N="179">he wolde of his benigne curtesie/</L>
<L>Make hem good chere and besily aspie</L>
<L>Tythynges of sundy Remes for to leere</L>
<L N="182">The wondres &thorn;at &thorn;ey mighte seen or heere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amonges o&thorn;er &thorn;inges specially</L>
<L>Thise marchantz han him told of Dame Custance<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So gret noblesse in ernest ceriously</L>
<L N="186">That &thorn;is Sowdan ha&thorn; caught so gret/ plesance</L>
<L>To han hire figure in his remembrance</L>
<L>And alle his lust and alle his besy cure</L>
<L N="189">Was for to loue hire whil his lijf may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Parauenture in &thorn;ilke large book</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;ei cleped &thorn;e heuen write was</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sterres whan &thorn;at he his bir&thorn;e took</L>
<L N="193">That he for loue schulde han his de&thorn; allas
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="162"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="136"></L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e sterres clerer &thorn;an is &thorn;e glas</L>
<L>Is writen god wot / who so cowde it rede/</L>
<L N="196">The de&thorn; of euery man wi&thorn;outen drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In sterres many a wynter &thorn;er biforn</L>
<L>Was write &thorn;e deth of Ector Achilles<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ceptra pharonei fratrum discordia Thebe flamma pnetontis deucalionis aque in stellis priami species audacia turni sensus vlixeu herculeus que vigor.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Pompe Iulius or &thorn;ei were born</L>
<L N="200">The stryf of Thebes and of hercules/</L>
<L>Of Sampson Turnus and of Socrates</L>
<L>The deth/ but mennes wittes ben so dulle</L>
<L N="203">That no wight can wel rede it atte fulle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Sowdon for his priuey counseil sente</L>
<L>And schortly of &thorn;is mater for to pace</L>
<L>he ha&thorn; to hem declared his entente</L>
<L N="207">And seide hem certein but if he might haue grace</L>
<L>To haue Custance wi&thorn;inne a litel space</L>
<L>he nas but ded and charged hem in hye</L>
<L N="210">To schapen for his lyf som remedye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Diuerse men diuerse &thorn;inges seiden</L>
<L>The argumentes casten vp and doun</L>
<L>Many a sotil reson for&thorn; &thorn;ey leyden</L>
<L N="214">They speken of Magique and abusion</L>
<L>But fynally as in conclusion</L>
<L>They can not seen in &thorn;at non auantage</L>
<L N="217">Ne in non o&thorn;er weye saf mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Than saugh &thorn;ey &thorn;er in such difficulte</L>
<L>By way of reson for to speke al playn</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at &thorn;er was such diuersite<MILESTONE N="77a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="221">Bitwen here bo&thorn;e lawes &thorn;at &thorn;ei sayn</L>
<L>They trowe &thorn;at no cristne prince wolde fain</L>
<L>Wedde his child vnder oure lawes so sweete</L>
<L N="224">That vs was taught by mahon oure prophete
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="163"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And he answerde ra&thorn;er &thorn;an I leese</L>
<L>Custance I wol be cristned douteles</L>
<L>I mot ben hires I may non o&thorn;er cheese</L>
<L N="228">I pray &yogh;ow holde&thorn; &yogh;our argumentz in pees</L>
<L>Saue&thorn; my lif and be&thorn; nought Recheles</L>
<L>To geten hire &thorn;at ha&thorn; my lif in cure</L>
<L N="231">ffor in this woo I may not longe endure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What nede&thorn; grettere dilatacion</L>
<L>I seie by tretys and embassadrie/</L>
<L>And by &thorn;e popes mediacion</L>
<L N="235">And alle &thorn;e chirche and alle &thorn;e chiualrie</L>
<L>That in distruction of mawmattrie</L>
<L>And in encres of cristes lawe deere</L>
<L N="238">They ben accorded so as &yogh;e schal heere/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; how &thorn;at &thorn;e Sowdan and his Baronage</L>
<L>And alle his lieges schold y-cristened be/</L>
<L>And he schal han Custance in mariage</L>
<L N="242">And certein gold y not what quantite</L>
<L>And herto founden sufficeant seurte</L>
<L>This same accord was sworn in either syde</L>
<L N="245">Now faire Custance almighty god &thorn;e gyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wolde sommen waiten as I gesse/</L>
<L>That I schulde tellen al &thorn;e purueance</L>
<L>That &thorn;e Emperour of his noblesse</L>
<L N="249">hath schapen for his doughter dame Custance</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe &thorn;at so gret ordinance</L>
<L>May noman tellen in a litel clause</L>
<L N="252">As was arrayed for so heigh a cause</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bisschoppes ben schapen wi&thorn; hire for to wende</L>
<L>lordes ladies knightes of renoun</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er folk ynowe &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>And notified is &thorn;urgh out &thorn;e toun<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="164"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="138"></L>
<L>That euery wight wi&thorn; gret deuocion</L>
<L>Scholde preye crist &thorn;at he &thorn;is mariage</L>
<L N="259">Resceyue in gree. and speede &thorn;is viage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The day is come of hir departyng</L>
<L>I sey &thorn;e woful lady<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so]</NOTE> fatal is come</L>
<L>That &thorn;er may be no lenger tarying</L>
<L N="263">But for&thorn;ward &thorn;ey hem dressen alle &amp; some</L>
<L>Custance &thorn;at with sorw is al ouercome</L>
<L>fful pale arist and dresse&thorn; hire to wende</L>
<L N="266">ffor wel sche seeth &thorn;er is non o&thorn;er ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas what wonder is it &thorn;ough sche wepte</L>
<L>That schal be sent to strange nacion</L>
<L>ffro freendes &thorn;at so tendrely hire kepte</L>
<L N="270">And to be bounden vnder subiection</L>
<L>Of oon sche knoweth not his condicion</L>
<L>housbondes ben alle goode and han ben yore</L>
<L N="273">That knowen wyfes I dar say &yogh;ou namore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffader sche sayde &thorn;i wrecchede child Custaunce</L>
<L>Thy yonge doughter fostred vp so softe</L>
<L>And ye my mooder my souereigne plesance</L>
<L N="277">Ouer alle &thorn;ing out taken crist a lofte</L>
<L>Custance youre child hir recomande&thorn; ofte</L>
<L>vnto your grace for I schal to Surrie</L>
<L N="280">Ne schal I neuer seen &yogh;ou more with ye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas vnto &thorn;e Barbarie nacion</L>
<L>I moste anon si&thorn;&thorn;en it is your wille</L>
<L>But crist &thorn;at starf for oure Redempcion</L>
<L N="284">So yeue me grace his hestes to fulfille</L>
<L>I wrecche womman no fors &thorn;ough I spille</L>
<L>Wommen are born to thraldom and penance</L>
<L N="287">And to ben vnder mannes gouernance
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="165"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I trowe at Troye whan Purrus brak &thorn;e walle</L>
<L>Or ylion &thorn;at brende Thebes &thorn;at Citee</L>
<L>Not Rome for the harme thurgh hanybal</L>
<L N="291">That Romayns ha&thorn; venquissed tymes &thorn;re</L>
<L>Nas herde such tendre weepyng for pite<MILESTONE N="78a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As in &thorn;e Chambre for hire departyng</L>
<L N="294">But for&thorn; sche moot wher so sche weepe or syng<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Vnde P[t]holomeus libro j<SUP>o</SUP>, Capitulo g<SUP>o</SUP> primi motus celi duo sunt quorum vnus est qui mouet totum semper ab oriente in occidentem vno modo super orbes &amp; cetera. Item aliter vero motus est qui mouet orbem stellarum currencium. Contra motum primum videlicet ab occidente in orientem super alios duos polos &amp; cetera. Omnes enim concordati sunt quod electiones sint debiles nisi in di|uitibus, habent enim isti licet debilitentur eorum electiones radicem .i. natiuitates eorum que confortat omnem planetam debilem in itinere. huc. philosophus.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O ferste moeuyng cruel firmament</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;y diuinal sweigh that crowdest ay</L>
<L>And hurlest alle fro Est to Occident</L>
<L N="298">That naturelly wolde holde ano&thorn;er way</L>
<L>Thy crowdyng sett &thorn;e heuen in such array</L>
<L>Atte bygynnyng of &thorn;is fiers viage</L>
<L N="301">That cruel mars ha&thorn; slain &thorn;is mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Infortunat ascendent tortuous</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e lord is helples falle allas</L>
<L>Out of his angle in to &thorn;e derkest hous</L>
<L N="305">O. mars .o. ata&yogh;ir as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>O fieble moone vnhappy been &thorn;y paas</L>
<L>Thou knettest &thorn;e &thorn;er &thorn;ou nart nought receyued</L>
<L N="308">There &thorn;ou were wel fro &thorn;ens now art &thorn;ou weyued</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Imprudent Emperour of Rome allas</L>
<L>Was &thorn;er no Philosophre in al &thorn;i toun</L>
<L>Is no tyme bet &thorn;an o&thorn;er in such caas</L>
<L N="312">Of viage is &thorn;er non election</L>
<L>Namly to folk of heigh condicion</L>
<L>Nat whan a roote is of a burthe y-knowe</L>
<L N="315">Allas &yogh;e ben to lewed or to slowe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The schip is brought &thorn;is woful faire mayde</L>
<L>Solempnely wi&thorn; euery circumstance</L>
<L>Now Ihesu crist be with &yogh;ou alle sche sayde</L>
<L N="319">Ther nys nomore but far wel faire Custance
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="166"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="140"></L>
<L>Sche peyne&thorn; hire to make good contynance</L>
<L>And for&thorn; I lete hire saile in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L N="322">And torne I wille again to my matiere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The mooder of &thorn;e Sowdon welle of vices</L>
<L>Espied ha&thorn; hir sones pleyne entent</L>
<L>how he wol lete his olde Sacrifices</L>
<L N="326">And right anon sche for hire counseil sent</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei ben come to knowe what sche ment</L>
<L>And whan assembled was &thorn;is folk in feere<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="329">Sche sette hire doun and seide as ye schal heere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; lordes quo&thorn; sche &yogh;e knowen euerych on</L>
<L>how &thorn;at my sone in poynt is for to lete</L>
<L>The holy lawes of oure alkaron</L>
<L N="333">yeuen by goddes messager Makomete</L>
<L>But oon avow to grete god I hete</L>
<L>The lyf schal rather out of my body sterte</L>
<L N="336">Or makometis lawe out of myn herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What scholde vs tyden of &thorn;is newe lawe</L>
<L>But &thorn;raldam to oure bodyes and penance</L>
<L>And afterward in helle to ben drawe</L>
<L N="340">ffor we reneyed mahon oure creance</L>
<L>But lordes wol ye maken assurance</L>
<L>As I schal sein assentyng to my lore</L>
<L N="343">And I schal make vs sauf for eueremore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; They sworen and assenten euery man</L>
<L>To lyue with hire and dye and by hire stonde</L>
<L>And euerich in &thorn;e beste wise he can</L>
<L N="347">To streng&thorn;en hire schal alle his frendes fonde</L>
<L>And sche ha&thorn; &thorn;is emprise take on honde</L>
<L>Which &yogh;e schal here &thorn;at I schal deuyse</L>
<L N="350">And to hem alle sche spak in &thorn;is wise
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="167"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="141"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; We schulle ferst feyne vs cristendom to take/</L>
<L>Cold water schal not greue vs but a lite</L>
<L>And I schal swich a reuel and feste maken</L>
<L N="354">That as I trowe I schal &thorn;e soudon quite</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough his wijf be cristened neuer so white</L>
<L>Sche schal haue neede to waissche a-way &thorn;e reede</L>
<L N="357">Though sche a ffonte ful of water wi&thorn; hire leede/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O soudanesse roote of Iniquite</L>
<L>Virago &thorn;ou Semyram &thorn;e secounde</L>
<L>O. serpent vnder femeninete</L>
<L N="361">lik to &thorn;e serpent deepe in helle y-bounde</L>
<L>O feyned womman al &thorn;at may confounde</L>
<L>Vertu and Innocence &thorn;orgh &thorn;y malice</L>
<L>Is bredd in &thorn;e as nest of euery vice<MILESTONE N="79a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O Sathan envious syn &thorn;ilke day</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou were chased fro oure heritage</L>
<L>Wel knewestow to wommen &thorn;e olde way</L>
<L N="368">Thow madest Eua to bringen in seruage</L>
<L>Thow wilt fordon cristene mariage</L>
<L>Thin Instrument so weylowey &thorn;e while</L>
<L N="371">Makest &thorn;ou of wommen whan &thorn;ou wilt begile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Sowdanesse whom I &thorn;us blame and warie</L>
<L>leet priuely hire counseil gon here way</L>
<L>What schulde I in &thorn;is tale lenger tarye</L>
<L N="375">Sche rideth to &thorn;e Sowdan on a day</L>
<L>And seide him &thorn;at sche wolde reneye hir lay</L>
<L>And cristendom of prestes handes fonge</L>
<L N="378">Repentynge sche he&thorn;ene was so longe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Besekyng him to doon hire &thorn;at honour</L>
<L>That sche most han &thorn;e cristne folk to feste</L>
<L>To plesen hem I wol do my labour</L>
<L N="382">The Sowdan seith I wil don at your heste
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="168"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="142"></L>
<L>And knelyng &thorn;anketh hire of &thorn;at requeste</L>
<L>So glad he was he nyste what to seye</L>
<L N="385">Sche kiste hir sone and hom sche go&thorn; hir weye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART II.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Arryued been &thorn;ise cristene folk to londe</L>
<L>In Surrie with a gret solempne route</L>
<L>And hastiliche &thorn;is sowdan sent his sonde</L>
<L N="389">ffirst to his mooder and alle &thorn;e regne aboute</L>
<L>And saide his wijf was come out of doute</L>
<L>And preyde hir for to ryde agein &thorn;e queene</L>
<L N="392">The honour of his regne to susteene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gret was &thorn;e prees and riche was &thorn;array</L>
<L>Of Surriens and Ramains met y feere</L>
<L>The mooder of &thorn;e Soudan riche and gay</L>
<L N="396">Receyued hire with also glad a cheere</L>
<L>As any mooder might hir doughter deere</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e nexte Citee &thorn;er bisyde</L>
<L N="399">A softe paas solempnely &thorn;ei ryde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Naught trowe I &thorn;e tryumphe of Iulius<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of which &thorn;at lukan make&thorn; such a bost</L>
<L>Was riallere ne more curious</L>
<L N="403">Than was thassemble of &thorn;is blisful oost</L>
<L>But &thorn;is scorpion this wikkede goost</L>
<L>The Sowdanesse for alle hir flateringe</L>
<L N="406">Caste vnder &thorn;is ful mortally to stynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Sowdan come&thorn; himself sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L>So really that wonder is to telle</L>
<L>he welcome&thorn; hire with alle ioye and blis</L>
<L N="410">And &thorn;us in merthe and Ioye I lete hem dwelle
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="169"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="143"></L>
<L>The fruyt of &thorn;is matiere &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>Whan tyme come men &thorn;ought it for &thorn;e best</L>
<L N="413">That Reuel stynte and men gon to here Rest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The tyme com &thorn;is olde Sowdanesse</L>
<L>Ordeyned ha&thorn; &thorn;is feeste of which I tolde</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e feste cristene folk hem dresse</L>
<L N="417">In general bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde</L>
<L>here may men feste and rialte biholde</L>
<L>And deyntees mo &thorn;an I can &yogh;ou deuyse</L>
<L N="420">But all to deere &thorn;ei bought it ar &thorn;ey ryse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O sodein woo &thorn;at euer art Successour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Semper mundane leticie tristicia repentina succedit. Mundana ergo felicitas multis amaritudinibus est respersa. Extre|ma gaudij luctus occupat audi ergo salubre consilium in die bonorum ne immemor sis malorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To worldly blysse spreynd is with bitternesse</L>
<L>The ende of &thorn;e ioye of oure worldly laboure</L>
<L N="424">Wo occupieth &thorn;e fyn of oure gladnesse</L>
<L>herk &thorn;is counseille for &thorn;i sikernesse</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;i glade day haue in thy mynde</L>
<L N="427">The vnwar wo or harm &thorn;at comth behynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor schortly for to tellen at oo word</L>
<L>The Sowdan and &thorn;e cristene euerychone</L>
<L>Ben al to-hewe and stiked atte bord</L>
<L N="431">But it were oonly dame Custance allone</L>
<L>This olde Sowdanesse cursede crone</L>
<L>ha&thorn; with hire freendes doon &thorn;is cursede dede</L>
<L N="434">ffor sche hir self wolde alle &thorn;e contre lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ne &thorn;er nas Surrian non &thorn;at was conuerted</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e counseil of &thorn;e Sowdan wot<MILESTONE N="80a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That he nas al to-hewe or he asterted</L>
<L N="438">And circumstance han &thorn;ei take anon foot hoot</L>
<L>And in a Schippe al steereles god woot</L>
<L>Thay han hire sette and bidden hire lerne sayle</L>
<L N="441">Out of Surrie agaynward to ytaile
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="170"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="144"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A certein tresour &thorn;at sche &thorn;ider ladde</L>
<L>And so&thorn; to sain vitaile gret plente</L>
<L>They han hire yeuen and clo&thorn;es eek sche hadde</L>
<L N="445">And for&thorn; sche saile&thorn; in &thorn;e Salte see</L>
<L>O my Custance ful of benignite</L>
<L>O emperoures yonge doughter deere</L>
<L N="448">he &thorn;at is lord ouer fortune be &thorn;y steere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche blisse&thorn; &amp; with ful pitous vois</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e croys of crist &thorn;us seyde sche</L>
<L>O cler o welful auter holy croys</L>
<L N="452">Rede of &thorn;i lambes blood ful of pite</L>
<L>That wisshe &thorn;e world fro &thorn;e olde iniquite</L>
<L>Me fro &thorn;e feend and fro his clawes keepe</L>
<L N="455">That day &thorn;at I schal drenchen in &thorn;e deepe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; victorious tree proteccion of trewe</L>
<L>That oonly wor&thorn;i were for to bere</L>
<L>The king of heuene with his woundes newe</L>
<L N="459">The white lambe &thorn;at hurt was with a spere</L>
<L>ffleemer of feendes out of him and here</L>
<L>On whych &thorn;i lymes feithfully entenden</L>
<L N="462">Me keepe and yef me might my lijf tamenden</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; yeeres and dayes fleet &thorn;is creature</L>
<L>Thurgh out &thorn;e see of grece vnto &thorn;e strayte</L>
<L>Of Marrok as it was hire auenture</L>
<L N="466">O many a sory meel now may sche bayte</L>
<L>After hire de&thorn; fulofte may sche wayte</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &thorn;e wilde wawes wil hir dryue</L>
<L N="469">vnto &thorn;e place &thorn;er sche schal arryue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Men mighten [aske] whi sche nas nat slayn</L>
<L>Eke atte feste who might hir body saue</L>
<L>I answere to &thorn;at demande agayn<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="473">he saued daniel in &thorn;e horrible caue
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="171"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="145"></L>
<L>Ther euery wight saue he maister or knaue</L>
<L>Was wi&thorn; &thorn;e leon frete or asterte</L>
<L N="476">No wight but god &thorn;at he bar in his herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; God list to schewe his wonderful myracle</L>
<L>In hire. for sche scholde seen his mighty werkes</L>
<L>Crist which &thorn;at is to euery harm triacle</L>
<L N="480">By certein menes oft as knowen clerkes</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &thorn;ing for certein ende &thorn;at ful derk is</L>
<L>To mannes wit &thorn;at for oure ignorance</L>
<L N="483">Ne konne nought knowe his prudent purueance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now si&thorn; sche was not atte feste y-slawe</L>
<L>Who kept hir fro &thorn;e drenching in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>Who kepte Ionas in &thorn;e fisshes mawe</L>
<L N="487">Til he was spouted vp at Nyniue</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe it was no wight but he</L>
<L>That kepte pepul ebraik from here drenchyng</L>
<L N="490">With drye feet &thorn;urgh out &thorn;e see passyng</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who bad &thorn;e foure spiritz of tempest</L>
<L>That power han bo&thorn;e to annoyen lond and see</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e north and south and also west and est</L>
<L N="494">Anoye&thorn; ney&thorn;er see ne lond ne tree</L>
<L>So&thorn;ly &thorn;e comandour of &thorn;at was he</L>
<L>That fro &thorn;e tempest ay &thorn;is womman kepte</L>
<L N="497">As wel whan sche wook as whan sche slepte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wher might &thorn;is womman mete and drynke haue</L>
<L>Three &yogh;eer and moore how laste&thorn; hire vitaille</L>
<L>Who fedde &thorn;e Egipcien marie in the Caue</L>
<L N="501">Or in desert no wight but crist sanz faille</L>
<L>v. &thorn;ousand folk it was a gret meruaille</L>
<L>With loues fyue and fisshes tuo to feede</L>
<L N="504">God sent his foyson at hire grete neede
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="172"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche driue&thorn; for&thorn; in to oure Occean</L>
<L>&thorn;urghout oure wilde see til atte last</L>
<L>vnder an hold &thorn;at nempnen I ne can</L>
<L>ffor in Northumburland &thorn;e wawe hir cast<MILESTONE N="81a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e sond hir schippe stiked so fast</L>
<L>That &thorn;ennes wold it nought of alle a tyde</L>
<L N="511">The wille of crist was &thorn;at sche scholde abyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Constable of &thorn;e castelle doun is fare</L>
<L>To seen &thorn;is wrak and alle &thorn;e schippe he sought</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;is wery womman ful of care</L>
<L N="515">he fond also &thorn;e tresow &thorn;at sche brought</L>
<L>In hire langage mercy sche bisought</L>
<L>The lyf out of hir body for to twynne</L>
<L N="518">hire to deliuere of wo &thorn;at sche was Inne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A maner latyn corupt was hire speche</L>
<L>But algates &thorn;er by was sche vnderstonde</L>
<L>The constable whan him list no lengere seche</L>
<L N="522">This woful womman brought he to &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>Sche kneeleth doun and &thorn;anke&thorn; goddes sonde</L>
<L>But what sche was sche wolde no man seye</L>
<L N="525">ffor foul ne fair &thorn;ough &thorn;at sche scholde deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche seyde sche was so mased in &thorn;e see/</L>
<L>That sche foryat hire mynde by hire trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>The constable of hire ha&thorn; so gret pite</L>
<L N="529">And eek his wyf &thorn;at &thorn;ei weepen for rou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Sche was so diligent wi&thorn;outen slou&thorn;e</L>
<L>To serue and plese euerich in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="532">That alle hire louen &thorn;at loken on hire face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The constable and dame hermengheld his wif</L>
<L>Were payens and &thorn;at contray euery where</L>
<L>But hermyngeld loued hir right as hire lijf</L>
<L N="536">And Custance ha&thorn; so longe soiorned &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="173"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="147"></L>
<L>In orisons wi&thorn; many a bitter teere</L>
<L>Til Ihesu ha&thorn; conuerted &thorn;urgh his grace</L>
<L N="539">Dame hermyngeld constablesse of &thorn;ilke place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In alle &thorn;at land durste no cristene route</L>
<L>Alle cristene folk ben fled from &thorn;at contre</L>
<L>Thurgh payens &thorn;at conquereden heer aboute</L>
<L N="543">The plages of &thorn;e north by land &amp; see</L>
<L>To wales fledde &thorn;e cristianite/<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of olde britons dwellyng in &thorn;is Isle/</L>
<L N="546">There was hire refut / for &thorn;e meene while</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But yit nas neuer cristene britons so exiled</L>
<L>That &thorn;er nas somme in here priuyte</L>
<L>honourede crist/ and hethen folk bygiled</L>
<L N="550">And neygh &thorn;e castelle swich &thorn;er dwelden &thorn;re</L>
<L>That oon of hem was blynd and might not se</L>
<L>But it were wi&thorn; &thorn;ilk eyen of his mynde</L>
<L N="553">With whiche men seen after &thorn;at &thorn;ai ben blynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Bright was &thorn;e sonne as in &thorn;at Someres day</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e Constable and his wyf also</L>
<L>And Custance han y-take &thorn;e righte way</L>
<L N="557">Toward &thorn;e see a forlong weye or two</L>
<L>To pleyen and to Romen to and fro</L>
<L>And in here walk &thorn;re blynde men &thorn;ey mette</L>
<L N="560">Crokede and olde with fast eyen y-schette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In the name of crist criede &thorn;is blynde breton</L>
<L>dame hermyngild yeue me sight agayn</L>
<L>This lady wax affrayed of &thorn;e soun</L>
<L N="564">lyst &thorn;at hir housbond schortly for to sein</L>
<L>Wolde hire for ihesu cristes loue haue slain</L>
<L>Til Custance made hire bold and made hire werche</L>
<L N="567">The wille of crist as doughter of his cherch
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="174"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="148"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Constable wax abaisshed of &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>And sayde what amounte&thorn; al &thorn;is fare</L>
<L>Custance answerde sire it is cristes might</L>
<L N="571">That helpe&thorn; folk out of &thorn;e feendes snare</L>
<L>And so ferforth sche gan oure lay declare</L>
<L>That sche &thorn;e Constable or &thorn;at it was eue</L>
<L N="574">Conuerte&thorn; and on cryst made him bileeue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Constable was no&thorn;ing lord of &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Of which I speke &thorn;ere he Custance fond</L>
<L>But kepte it strongly many a wynter space</L>
<L N="578">vnder .alla. kyng of all Northumberlond</L>
<L>&thorn;at was ful wys and wor&thorn;y of his hond</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e Scottes as men may wel heere<MILESTONE N="82a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="581">But torne I wil again to my mateere/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sathan &thorn;at euer vs wayteth to begile</L>
<L>Saugh of Custance al hire perfection</L>
<L>And cast anon how he might quite her while</L>
<L N="585">And made a yong knight &thorn;at dwelte in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>loue hire so hoot of fowl affection</L>
<L>That verraily him &thorn;ought he schulde spill</L>
<L N="588">But he of hire might ones haue his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; he woweth hire but it auaile&thorn; nought</L>
<L>Sche wolde do no synne by no weye</L>
<L>And for dispit he compassed in his &thorn;ought</L>
<L N="592">To make hir on schameful de&thorn; to deye</L>
<L>he wayte&thorn; whan &thorn;e Constable was aweye</L>
<L>And priuyly vpon a night he crept</L>
<L N="595">In hermyngildes chambre whil sche slept</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wery for-waked in his orisons</L>
<L>Slepeth Custance and hermenghild also</L>
<L>This knight &thorn;urgh Sathanas temptacions</L>
<L N="599">Al softely is to &thorn;e bedde I-go
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="175"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="149"></L>
<L>And kutte &thorn;e &thorn;rote of hermengild a tuo</L>
<L>And leyde &thorn;e blody knyf by dame Custance</L>
<L N="602">And wente his wey &thorn;er god yeue him meschance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sone after comth &thorn;is constable hom a gayn</L>
<L>And eek Alla &thorn;at king was of &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>And saugh his wyf dispitousliche slain</L>
<L N="606">ffor which ful ofte he wepte and wrong his hond</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e bed &thorn;e bloody knyf he fond</L>
<L>By dame Custance allas what might sche seye</L>
<L N="609">ffo verray woo hir witte was alle aweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To king Alla was told al &thorn;is meschance</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;e tyme and wher and in what wise</L>
<L>That in a schip was founde &thorn;is Custance</L>
<L N="613">As heer biforn &yogh;e han herd eer deuise</L>
<L>The kinges herte of pite gan agrise</L>
<L>Whan he seih so benigne a creature</L>
<L>ffalle in disese and in mysauenture<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor as &thorn;e lomb toward his deth is brought</L>
<L>So stant &thorn;is Innocent bifore &thorn;e king</L>
<L>This false knight &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;is trayson wrought</L>
<L N="620">Bere&thorn; hire an hand &thorn;at sche ha&thorn; do &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles &thorn;er was gret mornyng</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e poeple and seye &thorn;ay can not gesse</L>
<L N="623">That sche hadde don so gret a wickednesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor &thorn;ey han sein hir euer so vertuous</L>
<L>And louyng hermynghild right as hire lif</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is bar witnesse euerich in &thorn;at hous</L>
<L N="627">Sauf he &thorn;at hermegild slough wi&thorn; his knif</L>
<L>This gentil king ha&thorn; caught a gret motyf</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is witnesse and &thorn;ought he wolde enquere</L>
<L N="630">Deppere in &thorn;is cas a trouthe for to lere
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="176"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="150"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Allas Custance &thorn;ou nast no champion</L>
<L>Ne fighte canst &thorn;ou nought so weyloway</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at for oure redempcion</L>
<L N="634">And bond Sathan and lith yet &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>So be &thorn;y stronge champion &thorn;is day</L>
<L>ffor but vpon &thorn;e miracle kithe</L>
<L N="637">Wi&thorn;outen gilt &thorn;ou schalt ben slayn as swithe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche sitte hir doun on knees and &thorn;us sche sayde</L>
<L>Immortal god &thorn;at sauedest Susanne</L>
<L>ffro false blame and &thorn;ou merciful mayde</L>
<L N="641">Marie I mene doughter to seint Anne</L>
<L>Biforn whos child aungelis synge Osanne</L>
<L>If I be gilteles of &thorn;is felonie</L>
<L N="644">My socour be for elles schalt I dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; haue ye not sein som tyme a pale face/</L>
<L>Among a prees of him &thorn;at ha&thorn; be lad</L>
<L>Toward his deth wher as him get no grace/</L>
<L N="648">And swich a colour in his face ha&thorn; had</L>
<L>Men mighte knowe his face &thorn;at was bystad</L>
<L>Amonges alle &thorn;e faces in &thorn;at route</L>
<L N="651">So stant Custance and loketh hire aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O queenes lyuynge in prosperite<MILESTONE N="83a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Duchesses and &yogh;e ladies euerichone</L>
<L>haue som routhe on hir aduersite</L>
<L N="655">An emperoures doughter stant allone</L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn; no wight to whom to make hir moone</L>
<L>O blood real &thorn;at stondest in &thorn;is drede/</L>
<L N="658">ffer been &thorn;i freendes at &thorn;y grete neede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This alla king ha&thorn; such compassion</L>
<L>As gentil herte is fulfild of pite</L>
<L>That from his eyhen ran &thorn;e water don</L>
<L N="662">Now hastilich do fecche a book quod he
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="177"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="151"></L>
<L>And if &thorn;is knight wol swere how &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>This womman slough &yogh;it wol we vs auyse /</L>
<L N="665">Whom &thorn;at we wolde &thorn;at schal be oure Iustise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A briton book y-writen with euaungiles</L>
<L>Was fette and on &thorn;is book he swor anon</L>
<L>Sche giltif was in &thorn;e mene whiles</L>
<L N="669">An hand him smot vpon &thorn;e nekke bon</L>
<L>That doun he felle at ones as a stoon</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e his eyen brust out of his face/</L>
<L N="672">In sight of euery body in &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A vois was herd in general audience</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;ou hast disclandred gilteles</L>
<L>The doughter of holy chirche in heigh presence</L>
<L N="676">Thus hast &thorn;ou doon and &yogh;et I moot holde my pees</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is merueyle agast was alle &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>As m[a]zed folk &thorn;ei stooden euerychone</L>
<L N="679">ffor drede of wreche saue Custance allone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gret was &thorn;e drede and eek &thorn;e repentance</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at hadden wrong suspecion</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;is seely Innocent Custance</L>
<L N="683">And for &thorn;is miracle in conclusion</L>
<L>And by Custance mediacion</L>
<L>The king and many ano&thorn;er in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="686">Conuerted was &thorn;anked be goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This false knight was slain for his vntrouthe</L>
<L>By Iuggement of. alla. hastily<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And yet Custance ha&thorn; of his deth gret rou&thorn;e</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is ihesus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS ihc]</NOTE> of his mercy</L>
<L>Made Alla wedden ful solempnely</L>
<L>This holy mayden &thorn;at is so bright and scheene</L>
<L N="693">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; Crist made Custance a queene
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="178"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="152"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But who was woful if I schul nat lye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wedding but Donegilde and nomo</L>
<L>The kinges mooder ful of tyrannye</L>
<L N="697">hir &thorn;ought hir cursed herte barst/ a two</L>
<L>Sche wolde nought hir sone hadde don so</L>
<L>hir &thorn;ought a despit &thorn;at he schulde take</L>
<L N="700">So strange a creature vnto his make</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Me list nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e chaf ne of &thorn;e stre</L>
<L>Make so long a tale as of &thorn;e corn</L>
<L>What schulde I tellen of &thorn;e realte</L>
<L N="704">Of mariage or which cours go&thorn; biforn</L>
<L>Who blowe&thorn; in a trompe or in an horn</L>
<L>The fruyt of euery tale is for to seie/</L>
<L N="707">Thei ete and drynke and daunce and synge and pleye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>They gon to bedde as it was skile and right</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough &thorn;at wyfes ben ful holy &thorn;inges</L>
<L>They moste take a pacience a night</L>
<L N="711">Such manere necessaries as ben plesynges</L>
<L>To folk &thorn;at han y-wedded hem wi&thorn; rynges</L>
<L>And leye a litel here holynesse asyde</L>
<L N="714">As for &thorn;e time it may non o&thorn;er betyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; On hire he gat a knaue child anon</L>
<L>And to a bisshope and his counseil eeke</L>
<L>he took his wijf to kepe whan he is goon</L>
<L N="718">To Scotland ward his fomen for to seeke</L>
<L>Now faire Custance &thorn;at is so humble and meeke</L>
<L>So longe is gon wi&thorn; childe til &thorn;at stille</L>
<L N="721">Sche halt hir chambre abydyng at cristes wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The tyme is come a knaue child sche beer</L>
<L>Mauricius atte font ston &thorn;ei him calle</L>
<L>This Constable do&thorn; for&thorn; come a messagere<MILESTONE N="84a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="725">And wrot to his king &thorn;at cleped was alle.
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="179"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="153"></L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;is blisful tyding is bifalle</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er tydynges spedful for to seye</L>
<L N="728">he take&thorn; &thorn;e lettre and forth he go&thorn; his weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This messager to don his auantage/</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e kinges moder ride&thorn; swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>And salueth hire ful faire in his langage</L>
<L N="732">Ma dame quo&thorn; he &yogh;e may be glad and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>And thanke god an hundred &thorn;ousand si&thorn;e</L>
<L>My lady queen ha&thorn; child wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
<L N="735">To Ioye and blisse of alle &thorn;is regne aboute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; lo here &thorn;e lettres seled of &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That I mot bere with al &thorn;e haste I may</L>
<L>If ye wole aught vnto your sone &thorn;e king</L>
<L N="739">I am your seruant bo&thorn;e night and day</L>
<L>Dongyld answerd as now at &thorn;is tyme nay</L>
<L>But heer al night I wole &thorn;ou take &thorn;i rest</L>
<L N="742">Tomorwe wil I seie what me lest</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This messager drank sadly ale and wyn</L>
<L>And stolen weren his lettres priuyly</L>
<L>Out of his box whil he sleep as a swyn</L>
<L N="746">And counterfeted was ful subtilly</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er lettre wrought ful synfully</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e king direct of &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L N="749">ffro his Conestable as &yogh;e schal after heere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The lettre spak &thorn;e queen deliuered was</L>
<L>Of so horrible a feendlich creature</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e Castelle non so hardy was</L>
<L N="753">That ony while dorste &thorn;erinne endure</L>
<L>The mooder was an elf by auenture</L>
<L>ycome by charmes or by sorcerie</L>
<L N="756">And euery wight hate&thorn; hire companye
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="180"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wo was &thorn;is king whan he &thorn;is lettre hadde seyn</L>
<L>But to no wight he tolde his sorwes sore</L>
<L>But of his oughne hond he wrot ageyn</L>
<L>Welcome &thorn;e sonde of crist for eueremore<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To me &thorn;at am now lerned in his lore</L>
<L>lord welcome be &thorn;i lust and &thorn;i plesance</L>
<L N="763">My lust is put al in &thorn;in ordinance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; kepeth &thorn;is child al be it foul or faire</L>
<L>And eek my wif vnto myn hom comyng</L>
<L>Crist whan him list may sende me an haire</L>
<L N="767">More agreable &thorn;an &thorn;is is to my liking</L>
<L>This lettre he sele&thorn; priuyly wepyng</L>
<L>Which to &thorn;e messager was take sone</L>
<L N="770">And forth he go&thorn; &thorn;er is nomore to doone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O messager fulfild of dronkenesse /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Quid turpius ebrioso cui fetor in ore tremor in corpore qui promit stulta prodit occulta cui mens alienatur facies trans|formatur nullum enim latet secretum vbi regnat ebrietas.</NOTE></L>
<L>Strong is &thorn;i bre&thorn; &thorn;i lymes faltren ay</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou biwreyest alle sikernesse /</L>
<L N="774">Thy mynde is lorn &thorn;ou iangelest as a Iay</L>
<L>Thy face is torned in a newe aray</L>
<L>Ther dronkenesse regne&thorn; in ony route</L>
<L N="777">Ther nys no counseil hid wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O donegild I haue non englissh digne</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;y malice and &thorn;y tyrannye</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore to &thorn;e feend I &thorn;e resigne /</L>
<L N="781">lat him enditen of &thorn;i traiterie /</L>
<L>ffy mannyssh fy o nay by god I lye</L>
<L>ffy feendlich spirit for I dar wel telle</L>
<L N="784">Though &thorn;ou here walke &thorn;y spirit is in helle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This messager com&thorn; fro &thorn;e king agayn</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e kinges moodres court he light</L>
<L>And sche was of &thorn;is messager ful fain</L>
<L N="788">And plesed him in al &thorn;at euer sche might
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="181"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="155"></L>
<L>he drank and wel his gerdel vnderpight</L>
<L>he sleepe&thorn; and he snorte&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS fn . . .]</NOTE> in his gyse</L>
<L N="791">Al night til &thorn;e sonne gan arise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Eft were his lettres stolen euerich on</L>
<L>And countrefeted lettres in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>The king comande&thorn; his constable anon</L>
<L N="795">vp peyne of hangyng on a heih Iuyse</L>
<L>That he ne schulde suffre in no wise/<MILESTONE N="85a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Custance in with his Regne for tabide</L>
<L N="798">Thre dayes and a quarter of a tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But in &thorn;e same schip as he hire fond</L>
<L>hire and hire &yogh;onge sone and alle hir gere</L>
<L>he schulde putte and croude fro &thorn;e londe</L>
<L N="802">And charge hire &thorn;at sche neuer eft come &thorn;ere</L>
<L>O my Custance wel may &thorn;i goost haue feere/</L>
<L>And sleping in &thorn;i drem ben in penaunce/</L>
<L N="805">Whan Donegild caste al &thorn;is ordinance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This messager on morwe whan he wook</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e castel halt &thorn;e nexte way</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Constable he &thorn;e lettre took</L>
<L N="809">And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;is pitous lettre say</L>
<L>fful ofte he seyde allas and weylaway</L>
<L>&para; lord crist quod he how may &thorn;is lettre endure</L>
<L N="812">So ful of synne is many a creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O mighty god if &thorn;at it be &thorn;i wille</L>
<L>Sith &thorn;ou art rightful Iuge how may it be</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou wolt suffren Innocentz to spille</L>
<L N="816">And wikke folk regnen in prosperite</L>
<L>&para; O goode Custance allas so wo is me</L>
<L>That I moot be &thorn;i tormentour or deye</L>
<L N="819">On schames de&thorn; &thorn;er is non o&thorn;er weye
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="182"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wepen bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde in al &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e king &thorn;is cursede lettre sente</L>
<L>And Custance with a dedly pale face</L>
<L N="823">The fer&thorn;e day toward hir schip sche wente</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles sche take&thorn; in good entente</L>
<L>The wille of crist and knelyng in &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="826">Sche seyde lord ay welcome be &thorn;i sonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he &thorn;at me kepte fro &thorn;e false blame</L>
<L>Whil I was on &thorn;e lond amonges yow /</L>
<L>he kan me kepe from harm and eek fro schame</L>
<L N="830">In salte see al &thorn;ough I se not how</L>
<L>As strong as euer he was he is right now /</L>
<L>In him trust I and in his mooder deere<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="833">That is to me my sail and eek my steere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hir litel child lay weepyng in hire arm</L>
<L>And knelyng pitously to him sche seide</L>
<L>Pees litel sone I wol do &thorn;e non harm</L>
<L N="837">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at hir couerchef of hir heed sche breyde</L>
<L>And ouer his litel ey&yogh;en sche it leyde/</L>
<L>And in hir arm sche lulleth it ful faste /</L>
<L N="840">And in to heuen hir yhen vp sche caste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Moder quod sche and mayde bright marie</L>
<L>Soth is &thorn;at &thorn;urgh wommannes eggement</L>
<L>Mankynde was lorn and dampned ay to deye</L>
<L N="844">ffor which &thorn;i child was on a croys y-rent</L>
<L>Thy blisful eighen saugh al his torment</L>
<L>Than is &thorn;er no comparison bitwene</L>
<L N="847">Thy wo and any wo man may sustene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thou saugh &thorn;i sone y-slayn biforn &thorn;in eyen</L>
<L>And &yogh;it now lyue&thorn; my litel child par fay</L>
<L>Now lady bright to whom alle woful cryen</L>
<L N="851">Thow glorie of wommanhod &thorn;ou faire may
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="183"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="157"></L>
<L>Thou hauen of refut brighte sterre of day</L>
<L>Rewe on my child &thorn;at of &thorn;i gentilesse</L>
<L N="854">Rewest on euery rewful in distresse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O litel child allas what is &thorn;i gilt</L>
<L>That neuer wroughtest synne as &yogh;it par de</L>
<L>Why wil &thorn;in harde fader haue &thorn;e spilt</L>
<L N="858">O mercy deere Conestable quod sche</L>
<L>As lat my litel child dwelle heer with &thorn;e</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou darst nought sauen him for blame</L>
<L N="861">So kisse him ones in his fadres name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ther with sche loke&thorn; bakward to &thorn;e lond</L>
<L>And sayde farewel housbonde routheles</L>
<L>And vp sche rist and walketh doun &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="865">Toward &thorn;e schip hir folwe&thorn; alle &thorn;e prees</L>
<L>And euer sche preie&thorn; hir child to holde his pees</L>
<L>And take&thorn; hire leeue and with an holy entent</L>
<L>Sche blisse&thorn; hire and in to schip sche wente<MILESTONE N="86a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>vitailled was &thorn;e schip it is no drede</L>
<L>habundauntly for hire ful longe space</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er necessaries &thorn;at scholden neede</L>
<L N="872">Sche hadde ynough heried be goddes grace</L>
<L>ffor wynd and weder almighty god purchace</L>
<L>And brynge hir home I can no better sey</L>
<L N="875">But in &thorn;e see sche dryue&thorn; for&thorn; hir wey</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART III.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alla &thorn;e king com&thorn; hom sone after &thorn;is /</L>
<L>vnto his castelle of &thorn;e which I tolde</L>
<L>And axe&thorn; wher his wyf and his child is</L>
<L N="879">The Constable gan aboute his herte colde
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="184"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="158"></L>
<L>And pleynly al &thorn;e maner he him tolde</L>
<L>As ye han herd I can telle it no bettre</L>
<L N="882">And scheweth &thorn;e king his seal and his lettre</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seyde lord as &yogh;e comaunded me</L>
<L>vp peyne of deth so haue I don certein</L>
<L>This messager tormented was til he</L>
<L N="886">Moste biknowen and tellen plat and plein</L>
<L>ffrom night to night in what place he hadde leyn</L>
<L>And &thorn;us by witt and subtil enqueryng</L>
<L N="889">ymagined was by whom &thorn;is harm gan spring</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The hond was knowe &thorn;at &thorn;e lettre wrot</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e venym of &thorn;e cursed dede</L>
<L>But in what wise certeinly I not</L>
<L N="893">The effect is &thorn;is &thorn;at alla out of drede</L>
<L>his mooder slough &thorn;at many men pleynly reede</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at sche traitour was to hire ligeance /</L>
<L N="896">Thus ende&thorn; olde Donegild wi&thorn; meschance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The sorwe &thorn;at &thorn;is Alla night and day</L>
<L>Make&thorn; for his wyf and for his child</L>
<L>Ther is no tonge &thorn;at it telle may</L>
<L N="900">But now wol I vnto Custance go</L>
<L>That fleete&thorn; in &thorn;e see in peyne and wo</L>
<L>.v. yeer and more as likede cristes sonde</L>
<L N="903">Ar &thorn;at hire schip approched vnto londe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vnder an he&thorn;en castelle atte laste<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e name in my text nou&yogh;t I fynde</L>
<L>Custance and eek hir childe &thorn;e see vp caste</L>
<L N="907">Almighty god &thorn;at saue&thorn; al mankynde</L>
<L>haue on Custance and hir child som mynde</L>
<L>That fallen is in hethene hond eft sone</L>
<L N="910">In poynt to spille as I schal telle yow soone
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="185"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Doun fro &thorn;e Castelle com&thorn; &thorn;er many a wight</L>
<L>To gawren on &thorn;is schip and on Custance</L>
<L>But schortly fro &thorn;e castel on a night</L>
<L N="914">The lordes styward god yeue him meschance</L>
<L>A theef &thorn;at hadde renyed oure creance /</L>
<L>Com in to schip allone and seide he scholde</L>
<L N="917">hir lemman be wher so sche wolde or nolde/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wo was &thorn;is wrecchede womman &thorn;o bigon</L>
<L>hir child cryede and sche cried pitously</L>
<L>But blisful marie halp hir right anoon</L>
<L N="921">ffor with hir strogelyn wel and mightily</L>
<L>The theef fel ouer bord al sodeinly</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e see he dreynte for vengance</L>
<L N="924">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; crist / vnwemmed kept Custance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O foule lust of luxurie lo &thorn;in ende<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; O extrema libidinis turpitudo que non solum mentem effeminat sed eciam corpus eneruat semper sequntur dolor &amp; peni|tencia post &amp; cetera.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nought / oonly &thorn;at &thorn;ou fayntest mannes mynde</L>
<L>But verreyly &thorn;ou wolt his body schende</L>
<L N="928">The ende of &thorn;i werk or of &thorn;i lustes blynde</L>
<L>Is compleynyng how many oon may men fynde</L>
<L>That nought for werk somtyme but for &thorn;entent</L>
<L N="931">To don &thorn;is synne ben ey&thorn;er slayn or schent</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; how may &thorn;is weyke womman han &thorn;e streng&thorn;e</L>
<L>hire to defende ageyn &thorn;is renegat</L>
<L>O. golyas vnmesurable of leng&thorn;e</L>
<L N="935">how mighte Dauid make &thorn;e so mat</L>
<L>So yonge and of armure so desolat</L>
<L>how dorst he loke vpon &thorn;i dredful face</L>
<L N="938">Wel may men sen it was but goddes grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who yaf Iudith corage or hardynesse</L>
<L>To slen him Olefernus in his tent<MILESTONE N="87a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And to delyueren out of wrecchednesse</L>
<L N="942">The poeple of god. I sey for &thorn;is entent
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="186"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="160"></L>
<L>&thorn;at right as god spirit and vigor sent</L>
<L>To hem and saued hem out of meschance</L>
<L N="945">So sent he might and vigor to Custance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor&thorn; go&thorn; hir schip for&thorn; on &thorn;e narwe mouth</L>
<L>Of Iubaltar and Septe dryuyng ay</L>
<L>Somtyme west and som tyme north and south</L>
<L N="949">And som tyme est ful many a wery day</L>
<L>Til cristes mooder blissed be sche ay</L>
<L>ha&thorn; schapen &thorn;urgh hir endeles goodnesse</L>
<L N="952">To make an ende of alle hir heuynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now lat vs stynte of Custance but a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>And speke we of &thorn;e Romeyn Emperour</L>
<L>That out of Surrie ha&thorn; &thorn;e lettres knowe</L>
<L N="956">The slaughtere of cristene folk and deshonour</L>
<L>Don to his doughter by a fals traytour</L>
<L>I mene &thorn;e cursede wickede Sowdonesse</L>
<L N="959">That at &thorn;e feste let slen bo&thorn;e more and lesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffor which &thorn;is Emperour ha&thorn; sent anon</L>
<L>his senatour wi&thorn; real ordinance</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lordes god wot many on</L>
<L N="963">On Surriens to taken his vengance</L>
<L>They brennen sleen and bringen hem to mesch&amacr;nce</L>
<L>fful many a day but schortly &thorn;is is &thorn;ende</L>
<L N="966">homward to Rome &thorn;ei schapen hem to wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Senatour repaireth with victorie</L>
<L>To Romeward saylinge really</L>
<L>And mette &thorn;e schip dryuyng as sei&thorn; &thorn;e storie</L>
<L N="970">In which Custance sitte ful pitously</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing ne knew he what sche was ne why</L>
<L>Sche was in swich aray ne sche nyl seye</L>
<L N="973">Of hire astate &thorn;ough sche scholde deye
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="187"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="161"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he bringe&thorn; hire to Rome and to his wijf</L>
<L>he yaf hire and hire &yogh;onge sone also</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e Senatour sche ladde hir lyf<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="977">Thus kan oure lady bringen out of woo</L>
<L>Woful Custance and many ano&thorn;er mo</L>
<L>And long tyme dwelled sche in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="980">In holy werkes euere as was hir grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Senatoures wijf hir aunte was</L>
<L>But for al &thorn;at sche knew hir neuer &thorn;e more</L>
<L>I wil no lenger tarien in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L N="984">But to king Alla which I spak of yore</L>
<L>That for his wyf wepe&thorn; and sike&thorn; sore /</L>
<L>I wol retorne and lete I wil Custance</L>
<L N="987">vnder &thorn;e Cenatoures gouernance /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; kyng Alla which &thorn;at hadde his moder slayn</L>
<L>vpon a day fil in such repentance</L>
<L>That if I schortly tellen schal and playn</L>
<L N="991">To Rome he come&thorn; to receyuen his penance</L>
<L>And put him in &thorn;e popes ordinance</L>
<L>In heigh and low and Ihesu crist besoughte</L>
<L N="994">fforyeue his wikkede werkes &thorn;at he wroughte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The fame ano &thorn;urgh Rome toun is born</L>
<L>how Alla king schal comen in pilgrinage</L>
<L>By herberiours &thorn;at wenten him biforn</L>
<L N="998">ffor which &thorn;e Senatour as was vsage</L>
<L>Rood him agayn and many of his lynage</L>
<L>As wel to schewen his hie magnificence</L>
<L N="1001">As to don any king a reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gret cheere doth &thorn;is noble Senatour</L>
<L>To king Alla and he to him also</L>
<L>Euerich of hem do&thorn; o&thorn;er gret honour</L>
<L N="1005">And so bifille &thorn;at in a day or tuo
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="188"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="162"></L>
<L>This Senatour is to king alla go</L>
<L>To feeste and schortly if I schal not lye</L>
<L N="1008">Custance sone is in his companye /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Som men wolde seyn atte requeste of Custance</L>
<L>This Senatour ha&thorn; lad &thorn;is child to feste</L>
<L>I may not tellen euerich circumstance /</L>
<L>Be as be may &thorn;er was he atte leste<MILESTONE N="88a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But so&thorn; is &thorn;is &thorn;at at his moodres heste</L>
<L>Byforn Alla duryng &thorn;e metes space</L>
<L N="1015">The child stood loking in &thorn;e kinges face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This alla king ha&thorn; of &thorn;e child gret wonder</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Senatour he sayde anon</L>
<L>Whos is &thorn;at faire child &thorn;at stonde&thorn; yonder</L>
<L N="1019">I not quod he by god and by seint Iohn</L>
<L>A mooder he ha&thorn; but fader ha&thorn; he non</L>
<L>That I of woot and schortly in a stounde /</L>
<L N="1022">he tolde alla how &thorn;at &thorn;is child was founde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But god wot quod &thorn;is Senatour also</L>
<L>So vertuous a lyuere in my lyf</L>
<L>Ne saugh I neuer as sche ne herde of mo</L>
<L N="1026">Of worldly wommen mayde ne of wijf</L>
<L>I dar wel sayn sche hadde leuer a knyf</L>
<L>Thurghout hire brest &thorn;an ben a womman wikke</L>
<L N="1029">Ther is noman kowde bringe hire to &thorn;at prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now was &thorn;is child as lik vnto Custance /</L>
<L>As possible as is a creature to be</L>
<L>This alla ha&thorn; &thorn;e face in remembrance</L>
<L N="1033">Of dame Custance and &thorn;er on mused he</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e childes moder were aught sche /</L>
<L>That is his wyf and priuily he sighte</L>
<L N="1036">And spedde him fro &thorn;e table &thorn;at he mighte
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="189"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="163"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Par fay he &thorn;ought &thorn;e fantome is in myn hed</L>
<L>I oughte demen of skilful Iuggement</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e salte see my wyf is deed</L>
<L N="1040">And aftirward he made his argument</L>
<L>What wot I if &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; hider sent</L>
<L>My wyf by see as wel as he hir sente</L>
<L N="1043">To my contre fro &thorn;ennes &thorn;at sche wente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And after non hom with &thorn;e Senatour</L>
<L>Go&thorn; alla for to seen &thorn;is wonder chaunce</L>
<L>This Senatour do&thorn; alla gret honour</L>
<L N="1047">And hastily he sente after Custance</L>
<L>But truste&thorn; wel hire luste nought to daunce<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche wiste wherfore was &thorn;at sonde</L>
<L N="1050">Vnne&thorn;e vppon hire feet sche mighte stonde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan alla saugh his wyf faire he hire grette /</L>
<L>And wepte &thorn;at it was reu&thorn;e for to se</L>
<L>ffor atte ferste look he on hire sette /</L>
<L N="1054">he knew wel verrely &thorn;at it was sche /</L>
<L>and for sorwe as domb stant as a tre</L>
<L>So was hir herte schet in hire distresse</L>
<L N="1057">Whan sche remembred his vnkyndenesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Twies sche swowne&thorn; in his owne sight</L>
<L>he wepte and him excuseth pitously</L>
<L>Now god quod he and his halwes bright</L>
<L N="1061">So wisly on my saule as haue mercy</L>
<L>That of youre harm as gilteles am I</L>
<L>As is Maurice my sone so lik &yogh;oure face</L>
<L N="1064">Elles the feende me fecche out of &thorn;is place /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; longe was &thorn;e sobbyng and &thorn;e bittre peyne /</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at here wofulle hertes mighte cesse /</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e pite for to heere hem pleyne /</L>
<L N="1068">&thorn;urgh whiche pleyntes gan hire wo encresse /
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="190"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="164"></L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ou alle my labour to relesse</L>
<L>I may not tellen hir wo vntil to morwe</L>
<L N="1071">I am so wery for to speke of hire sorwe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But finally whan &thorn;at &thorn;e so&thorn;e is wist</L>
<L>That Alla gilteles was of hire woo /</L>
<L>I trowe an hundred tymes ben &thorn;ei kiste</L>
<L N="1075">And such a blisse is &thorn;er betwixe hem tuo</L>
<L>That saue &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at lasteth eueremo</L>
<L>Ther is non lik &thorn;at ony creature</L>
<L N="1078">ha&thorn; seyn or schal whil &thorn;e world may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tho preyed sche hire housbonde mekely</L>
<L>In relief of hir longe pitous pyne</L>
<L>That he wolde preye hire fader specially</L>
<L N="1082">That of his mageste he wolde enclyne</L>
<L>To fouche sauf som day with him to dyne</L>
<L>Sche preyde him eek he scholde by no weye<MILESTONE N="89a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1085">vnto hir fader no word of hire seye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Some men wolde sein how &thorn;at &thorn;e child Maurice</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &thorn;is message vntil &thorn;is Emperour</L>
<L>But as I gesse Alla was nought so nyce</L>
<L N="1089">To him &thorn;at was of so souereigne honour</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at is of cristene folk &thorn;e flour</L>
<L>Sent eny child but it is bet to deme</L>
<L N="1092">he went himself and so it may wel seme</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Emperour hath graunted gentily</L>
<L>To come to dyner as he him bysought</L>
<L>And wel redy he lokede bisily</L>
<L N="1096">vpon &thorn;is child and on his doughter &thorn;ought</L>
<L>Alla go&thorn; to his In and as him ought</L>
<L>Arrayed for &thorn;is feste in euery wise</L>
<L N="1099">As ferforth as his konnyng may suffise
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="191"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="165"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The morwe com and alla gan him dresse</L>
<L>And eek his wyf &thorn;is Emperour to meete</L>
<L>And for&thorn; &thorn;ey ryde in ioye and in gladnesse /</L>
<L N="1103">And whan sche seigh hir fader in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>Sche light a doun and falle&thorn; him to feet</L>
<L>ffader quod sche youre &yogh;onge child Custance</L>
<L N="1106">Is now ful clene out of &yogh;oure remembrance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I am &yogh;oure doughter Custance quod sche</L>
<L>That whilom ye sent vnto Surrye</L>
<L>I am I fader &thorn;at in &thorn;e salte see</L>
<L N="1110">Was putte allone and dampned for to dye</L>
<L>Now goode fader mercy to you I crye</L>
<L>Send me nomore vnto non hethenesse</L>
<L N="1113">But &thorn;onk my lord heer of his kyndenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who can &thorn;e pitous Ioye tellen al</L>
<L>Bitwexe hem &thorn;re syn &thorn;ey ben &thorn;us y-mette</L>
<L>But of my tale make an ende I schal</L>
<L N="1117">The day go&thorn; faste I wol no lenger lette</L>
<L>This glad folk to dyner &thorn;ey hem sette</L>
<L>In ioye and blisse at mete I lete hem dwelle</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand fold wel more &thorn;an I can telle /<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This child maurice was sitthen Emperour</L>
<L>Made by &thorn;e pope and lyuede cristenely</L>
<L>To cristes chirche he dede gret honour</L>
<L N="1124">But I letete<NOTE PLACE="marg">[so]</NOTE> alle his story passen by</L>
<L>Of Custance is my tale specially</L>
<L>In olde Romeyn gestes men may fynde<NOTE PLACE="marg"> &para; A mane vsque ad vesperam mutabitur tempus tenent tympanum &amp; gaudent ad sonum organi.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1127">Maurices lyf I bere it nought in mynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This king Alla. whan he his tyme say</L>
<L>With his Custance his holy wif so sweete</L>
<L>To Engelond &thorn;ei come &thorn;e redy way</L>
<L N="1131">Wher as &thorn;ay lyue in ioye and in quiete
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="192"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="166"></L>
<L>But litel while it laste&thorn; I &yogh;ou heete</L>
<L>Ioye of &thorn;is world for tyme wil nou&yogh;t abyde</L>
<L N="1134">ffro day to nyght it chaunge&thorn; as &thorn;e tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who lyued euere in such delyt a day<NOTE PLACE="marg"> Quis vnquam vnicam diem totam duxit in sua delecta|cione iocundam quem in aliqua parte diei reatus consciencie vel impetus ire vel motus concupiscencie inde non turbauerit quem liuor inuidie vel ardor auaricie vel tumor superbie non vexauerit vel quem aliqua iactura vel offensa vel passio non commo<SUP>a</SUP>uerit.</NOTE></L>
<L>That ne meued ey&thorn;er conscience /</L>
<L>Or Ire or talent of som kyn affray</L>
<L N="1138">Enuye or pride or passion or offense /</L>
<L>I ne say but for &thorn;is ende &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>That litel while in Ioye or in plesance</L>
<L N="1141">laste&thorn; &thorn;e blisse of alla wi&thorn; Custance /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor de&thorn; &thorn;at take&thorn; of heigh and lough his rent</L>
<L>Whan passed was a yeer euene as I gesse</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world &thorn;is king Alla he hent</L>
<L N="1145">ffor whom Custance ha&thorn; ful gret heuynesse /</L>
<L>Now lat vs prayen god his soule blesse /</L>
<L>And dame Custance finally to seye</L>
<L N="1148">Toward &thorn;e toun of Rome go&thorn; hire weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Rome is come &thorn;is holy creature</L>
<L>And fynde&thorn; hire freendes hol and sounde</L>
<L>Now is sche scaped alle hire auenture</L>
<L N="1152">And whan sche hir fader ha&thorn; I-founde</L>
<L>Doun on hir knees falleth sche to grounde</L>
<L>Wepynge for tendirnesse in herte bli&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1155">Sche herie&thorn; god an C. &thorn;ousand sithe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In vertue and holy almesdede /<MILESTONE N="90a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They lyuen alle and neuer asonder wende</L>
<L>Til deth departe hem &thorn;is lif &thorn;ey lede</L>
<L N="1159">And fare&thorn; now wel my tale is at an ende</L>
<L>Now ihesu crist &thorn;at of his might may sende</L>
<L>Ioye after wo gouerne vs in his grace</L>
<L N="1162">And kepe vs alle &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is place /</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000221.tif" N="193"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="167">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owre oost vpon his stiropes stood anoon<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 90</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyde goode men herkene&thorn; euerych on</L>
<L>This was a thrifty tale for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L N="1166">Sire parissche prest quod he for goddes boones</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale as was &thorn;i forward yore</L>
<L>I se wel &thorn;at ye lerned men in loore</L>
<L>Can moche good by goddes dignete</L>
<L N="1170">The parson him answerde benedicite</L>
<L>What eyle&thorn; &thorn;e man so synfully to swere /</L>
<L>Oure ost answerde. O Ianekyn be ye &thorn;ere</L>
<L>I smelle a lollere in &thorn;e wynd quod he</L>
<L N="1174">how goode men quod oure host herkene&thorn; me</L>
<L>Abyde&thorn; for goddes digne passion</L>
<L>ffor we schal han a predicacion</L>
<L>This lollere heer wil prechen vs som what</L>
<L N="1178">Nay by my fader soule &thorn;at schal he nat</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;e Esquier heer schal he nat preche</L>
<L>He schal no gospel glosen here ne teche</L>
<L>he leue&thorn; all in &thorn;e grete god he</L>
<L N="1182">he wolde sowen som difficulte</L>
<L>Or springen Cokkel in oure clene corn</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore oost I warne &thorn;e biforn</L>
<L>My Ioly body schal a tale telle</L>
<L N="1186">And I schal clynken &yogh;ou so mery a belle</L>
<L>That I schal waken al &thorn;is compaignie</L>
<L>But it schal not ben of philosophie</L>
<L>Ne Phislyas ne termes queinte of lawe</L>
<L N="1190">Ther is but litel latyn in my nawe<NOTE PLACE="end">[The Squire's Tale follows in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="F" TYPE="group">


<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000222.tif" N="194">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="479">
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Sarray in &thorn;e land of Tartarye<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ther dwelt a king &thorn;at werreyed Russye</L>
<L>Thurgh which &thorn;er deyed many a doughty man</L>
<L N="12">This noble king was cleped kambynskan</L>
<L>Which in his tyme was of so gret renon</L>
<L>That &thorn;er nas nowher in no region</L>
<L>So excellent a lord in alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="16">him lacked nought &thorn;at longed to a kyng</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e secte of which &thorn;at he was born</L>
<L>he kepte his lay to which &thorn;at he was sworn</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto he was hardy wys and riche</L>
<L N="20">And pitous and Iust alwey y-liche</L>
<L>So&thorn; of his word benigne and honorable</L>
<L>Of his corage as eny centre stable<NOTE PLACE="marg">centrum circuli</NOTE></L>
<L>yong freissh and strong in armes desirous</L>
<L N="24">As eny bacheler of alle his hous</L>
<L>A fair persone he was and fortunat</L>
<L>And kepte alway so wel real astat</L>
<L>That &thorn;er nas no wher swich ano&thorn;er man</L>
<L N="28">This noble king this Tartre Kambynskan</L>
<L>hadde tuo sones in Eltheta his wyf</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e eldest highte Algarsyf</L>
<L>That o&thorn;er was y-cleped Camballo</L>
<L N="32">A doughter hadde &thorn;is wor&thorn;y king also</L>
<L>That yongest was and highte Canace</L>
<L>But for to telle you al hire beaute</L>
<L>It ly&thorn; nought in my tonge ne in my konnyng</L>
<L N="36">I dar not vndertake so heigh a &thorn;ing
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="195"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="480"></L>
<L>Myn englissch eek is insufficient</L>
<L>It moste ben a Rethor excellent</L>
<L>That cou&thorn;e his colours longyng for &thorn;at art</L>
<L N="40">If he schulde hir discryue in any part</L>
<L>I am non swich I moot speke as I can</L>
<L>And so bifelle that whan &thorn;is Cambynskan</L>
<L>ha&thorn; twenty wynter born his Diademe</L>
<L N="44">As he was wonte fro yeer to yeer I deeme</L>
<L>he leet &thorn;e feste of his natiuite<MILESTONE N="91a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Don cryen &thorn;urgh Sarray his Cite</L>
<L>The laste Idus of March after &thorn;e &yogh;eer</L>
<L N="48">Phebus &thorn;e sonne Iolif was and cleer</L>
<L>ffor he was neigh his exaltacion</L>
<L>In martes face and his mansion</L>
<L>In aries &thorn;e Colerik &thorn;e hote signe</L>
<L N="52">fful lusty was &thorn;e weder and benigne</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e foules a&yogh;ein &thorn;e sonne sshene</L>
<L>What for &thorn;e seson and &thorn;e yonge grene</L>
<L>fful loude songe hire affections</L>
<L N="56">hem semed han geten hem protections</L>
<L>A&yogh;&edot;in &thorn;e swerd of wynter keene and cold</L>
<L>This Kambynskan of which I haue &yogh;ou told</L>
<L>In Real vestiment sit on his deys</L>
<L N="60">With dyademe ful heigh in his paleys</L>
<L>And halt his feste solempne and so riche</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is world ne was &thorn;er non it liche</L>
<L>Of which if I schal telle al &thorn;e array</L>
<L N="64">Than wold it occupye a someres day</L>
<L>And eek it neede&thorn; nat to deuyse</L>
<L>At euery cours &thorn;e ordre of here seruise</L>
<L>I wol not tellen of here straunge sewes</L>
<L N="68">Ne of here swannes ne of here heron-sewes</L>
<L>Ek in &thorn;at lond as tellen knightes olde</L>
<L>Ther is som mete &thorn;at is ful deynte holde</L>
<L>That in &thorn;is lond men recche but smal</L>
<L N="72">Ther nys no man &thorn;at may reporten al
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="196"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="481"></L>
<L>I wol not tarien yow for it is prime</L>
<L>And for it is no fruyt but los of tyme</L>
<L>vnto my first purpos I wole haue my recours /</L>
<L N="76">And so bifelle &thorn;at after &thorn;e &thorn;ridde cours</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at &thorn;is king sit &thorn;us in his nobleye</L>
<L>herknyng his menstreles here &thorn;inges pleye</L>
<L>Biforn him atte bord deliciously</L>
<L N="80">In atte halle dore al sodeinly</L>
<L>Ther com a knight vpon a steede of bras<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in his hond a brood Mirour of glas</L>
<L>vpon his thombe he hadde of gold a ryng</L>
<L N="84">And by his syde a naked swerd hangyng</L>
<L>And vp he ryde&thorn; to &thorn;e heihe bord</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;e halle ne was &thorn;er spoke a word</L>
<L>ffor merueille of &thorn;is knight him to biholde</L>
<L N="88">fful bysyly &thorn;ey wayten &yogh;onge and olde /</L>
<L>This strange knight &thorn;at com &thorn;us sodeynly</L>
<L>Al armed saue his heed ful richely</L>
<L>Salued &thorn;e king and queen and lordes alle</L>
<L N="92">By ordre as &thorn;ey seten in &thorn;e halle</L>
<L>with so heigh reuerence and obeissances</L>
<L>As wel in speche as in contenances</L>
<L>That Gawayn with his olde curtesye /</L>
<L N="96">Though he com agayn out of fayrie /</L>
<L>Ne cou&thorn;e him nought amende wi&thorn; no word</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is bifore &thorn;e heihe bord</L>
<L>he with a manly vois sayde his message</L>
<L N="100">After &thorn;e forme vsed in his langage</L>
<L>wi&thorn;oute vice of Sillable or of lettre</L>
<L>And for his tale scholde seme &thorn;e bettre</L>
<L>Acordant to his wordes was his chere /</L>
<L N="104">As teche&thorn; art of speche hem &thorn;at it lere /</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at I can nat sowne his stile</L>
<L>Ne can not clymben ouer so heigh a style</L>
<L>yet/ seye I &thorn;is &thorn;at as to commune entente</L>
<L N="108">Thus moche amounte&thorn; al &thorn;at euer he mente
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="197"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="482"></L>
<L>If it so be &thorn;at I haue it in my mynde</L>
<L>he seyde &thorn;e king of Arabie and of Inde</L>
<L>My liege lord on &thorn;is solempne day</L>
<L N="112">Salue&thorn; &yogh;ou as he best can and may</L>
<L>And sende&thorn; yow in honour of your feste</L>
<L>By me &thorn;at am redy at al your heste /</L>
<L>This steede of Bras &thorn;at esily and wel</L>
<L N="116">kan in &thorn;e space of a day naturel</L>
<L>This is to seie in .xxiiij<SUP>ti</SUP>. houres<MILESTONE N="92a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wher so yow list in droughte or in schoures</L>
<L>Beren youre body in to euery place /</L>
<L N="120">To which youre herte wilneth for to pace</L>
<L>wi&thorn;oute wem of &yogh;ou &thorn;orugh foul or fair</L>
<L>Or if &yogh;ou list to flee as hye in &thorn;air</L>
<L>As do&thorn; an Egle whan him list to sore</L>
<L N="124">This same steede schal bere &yogh;ou eueremore</L>
<L>wi&thorn;outen harm til ye be &thorn;er you leste</L>
<L>Though &thorn;at &yogh;e slepen on his bak or reste</L>
<L>And torne a&yogh;ayn wi&thorn; wry&thorn;ing of a pyn</L>
<L N="128">he &thorn;at it wroughte cou&thorn;e ful many a gyn</L>
<L>he waitede many a constellac&omacr;n</L>
<L>Or he hadde do &thorn;is operaci&omacr;n</L>
<L>And knew ful many a seal and many a bond</L>
<L N="132">This Mirour eek &thorn;at I haue in myn hond</L>
<L>ha&thorn; such a might that men may in it see</L>
<L>whan &thorn;er schal fallen any aduersite</L>
<L>Vnto youre regne or to your self also</L>
<L N="136">And openly who is &yogh;our frend or foo</L>
<L>And ouer al &thorn;is if ony lady bright</L>
<L>ha&thorn; set hire herte on any maner wight</L>
<L>If he be fals sche schal his trayson se</L>
<L N="140">his newe loue and al his subtilite</L>
<L>So openly &thorn;at &thorn;er schal no &thorn;ing hyde</L>
<L>wherfore ageyn &thorn;is lusty somer tyde</L>
<L>This mirour and &thorn;is ryng as ye may see /</L>
<L N="144">he ha&thorn; sent to my lady Canacee
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="198"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="483"></L>
<L>youre excellent doughter &thorn;at is heere</L>
<L>The vertu of &thorn;is ring if &yogh;e wol heere</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is. &thorn;at if hir list it for to were /</L>
<L N="148">vpon hir &thorn;ombe or in hir purs it bere</L>
<L>Ther is no foule &thorn;at fleigh vnder &thorn;e heuene</L>
<L>&thorn;at she ne schal vnderstonde his steuene</L>
<L>And knowe his menyng openly and pleyn</L>
<L N="152">And answere him in his langage ageyn</L>
<L>And euery gras &thorn;at growe&thorn; vpon a roote /<MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche schal wel knowe and whom it wol do boote</L>
<L>Al be his woundes neuer so deepe and wyde</L>
<L N="156">This naked swerd &thorn;at hongeth by my syde</L>
<L>Swich vertu ha&thorn; &thorn;at what man so ye smyte</L>
<L>Thurghout his armour it wole kerue and byte</L>
<L>Were it as &thorn;ikke as is a braunched oke</L>
<L N="160">And what man &thorn;at is wounded wi&thorn; &thorn;e stroke</L>
<L>Schal neuer be hol til &thorn;at yow list of grace</L>
<L>To stroke him wi&thorn; &thorn;e plat in &thorn;ilke place</L>
<L>Ther he is hurt &thorn;is is as moche to sayn</L>
<L N="164">ye moote with &thorn;e platte swerd agayn</L>
<L>Stroke him on &thorn;e wounde and it wil close</L>
<L>This is a verray soth wi&thorn;outen glose</L>
<L>It faille&thorn; nought whiles it is in youre hold</L>
<L N="168">And whan &thorn;is knight ha&thorn; &thorn;us his tale told</L>
<L>he rydeth out of &thorn;e halle and doun he light</L>
<L>his steede which &thorn;at schon as sonne bright</L>
<L>Stant in &thorn;e court stille as ony stoon</L>
<L N="172">This knight in to his chambre is lad anoon</L>
<L>And is vnarmed and to &thorn;e mete y-set</L>
<L>The presentes ben ful richely y-fet</L>
<L>This is to sein &thorn;e swerd and &thorn;e mirour</L>
<L N="176">And born anon vnto &thorn;e hihe tour</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; certein officers ordeyned &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>And vnto Canacee &thorn;e ryng is bore</L>
<L>Solempnely &thorn;er sche sitt atte table</L>
<L N="180">But sikerly wi&thorn;outen eny fable /
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="199"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="484"></L>
<L>The hors of bras &thorn;at may nat be remewed</L>
<L>It stant as it were to &thorn;e ground y-glewed</L>
<L>Ther may noman out of &thorn;e place it dryue</L>
<L N="184">ffor non engyn of wyndas or polyue /</L>
<L>And cause why for &thorn;ey can nou&yogh;t &thorn;e craft</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore in the place &thorn;ei han it laft</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e knight ha&thorn; taught hem &thorn;e maneere</L>
<L N="188">To voyden him as &yogh;e schal after heere</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e prees &thorn;at swarmed to and fro<MILESTONE N="93a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To gauren on &thorn;is hors &thorn;at stonde&thorn; so</L>
<L>ffor it so heih was and so brood and long</L>
<L N="192">So wel proporciouned for to be strong</L>
<L>Right as it were a steede of lumbardye</L>
<L>Ther with so horsly and so quyk of ye</L>
<L>As it a gentil poyleys courser were</L>
<L N="196">ffor certes fro his tail vnto his eere</L>
<L>Nature ne art ne cou&thorn;e him nought amende</L>
<L>In no degre as al &thorn;e poeple wende</L>
<L>But euermore here mooste wonder it was</L>
<L N="200">how &thorn;at it cowde gon and was of Bras</L>
<L>It was of ffaierye as &thorn;e peple semede</L>
<L>diuerse folk diuersely han demede</L>
<L>As many heedes as many wittes &thorn;er been</L>
<L N="204">They murmerede as don a swarm of been</L>
<L>And maden skyles after here fantasyes</L>
<L>Rehersyng of &thorn;e olde poetries<NOTE PLACE="marg">.i. equs pedasdus</NOTE></L>
<L>And seyden it was lik &thorn;e Pagasee</L>
<L N="208">The hors &thorn;at hadde wynges for to flee</L>
<L>Or elles it was &thorn;e Grekes hors Synon</L>
<L>That broughte troye to destruction</L>
<L>As men in &thorn;ise olde gestes reede</L>
<L N="212">Myn herte quod oon is eueremore in drede</L>
<L>I trowe som men of armes ben &thorn;er Inne</L>
<L>That schapen hem &thorn;is cite for to wynne</L>
<L>It were right good &thorn;at alle swich &thorn;ing were knowe</L>
<L N="216">Ano&thorn;er rowned to his felawe lowe
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="200"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="485"></L>
<L>And seyde he lyeth for it is ra&thorn;ere lik</L>
<L>An apparence y-maad by som magyk</L>
<L>As Iogelours pleyen at &thorn;ese festes grete /</L>
<L N="220">Of sondry &thorn;oughtes &thorn;us &thorn;ey Iangle and trete</L>
<L>As lewed peple deme&thorn; communly</L>
<L>Of &thorn;inges &thorn;at been more maad subtily</L>
<L>Than &thorn;ey can in here lewednesse comprehende /</L>
<L N="224">They demen gladly to &thorn;e baddere ende</L>
<L>And some of hem wondren on &thorn;e mirour<MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That born was vp vnto &thorn;e maistre tour</L>
<L>how men might in it suche &thorn;inges se</L>
<L N="228">Ano&thorn;er answerde and seyde it might wel be</L>
<L>Naturelly by composicions</L>
<L>Of aungels and of sleygh reflexions</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;at in Rome was such oon</L>
<L N="232">They speke of alocen and vitilion</L>
<L>And of aristotle &thorn;at writen in here lyues</L>
<L>Of queinte mirours and of perspectyues</L>
<L>As knowen &thorn;ey &thorn;at han here bookes herde</L>
<L N="236">And o&thorn;er folk han wondred on &thorn;e swerde</L>
<L>That wolde perce &thorn;urgh euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And fille in speche of Thelophus &thorn;e king</L>
<L>And of achilles for his queinte spere /</L>
<L N="240">ffor he cou&thorn;e with it bo&thorn;e hele and dere /</L>
<L>Right in swich wise as men may wi&thorn; &thorn;e swerd</L>
<L>Of which right now ye haue youre seluen herd</L>
<L>They speken of sondry hardyng of metalle</L>
<L N="244">And speke of medicynes &thorn;er wi&thorn;alle</L>
<L>And how and whanne it scholde harded be</L>
<L>Which is vnknowe algate vnto me /</L>
<L>Tho speeke &thorn;ey of Canaces ryng</L>
<L N="248">And seyden alle &thorn;at swich a wonder &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Of craft of rynges herde &thorn;ey neuere non</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;at he moyses and king Salomon</L>
<L>hadde a name of konnyng in swich art</L>
<L N="252">Thus seyen &thorn;e peple and drawen hem a part
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="201"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="486"></L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles somme seyde &thorn;at it was</L>
<L>Wonder to maken of fern aisshen glas</L>
<L>And &yogh;it is glas not lik aisshen of fern</L>
<L N="256">But for &thorn;ey han knowen it so fern</L>
<L>Therfore cese&thorn; here Ianglyng and here wonder</L>
<L>As sore wondren some on cause of &thorn;onder</L>
<L>On ebbe and flood on gossomer and on myst /</L>
<L N="260">And alle &thorn;ing til &thorn;e cause is wist<MILESTONE N="94a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thus Ianglen &thorn;ei and demen and deuyse</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e king gan fro his bord arise</L>
<L>&para; Phebus ha&thorn; laft &thorn;e angle meridional</L>
<L N="264">And &yogh;it ascendyng was &thorn;e best roial</L>
<L>The gentil leon wi&thorn; his Aldrian</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;is Tartre kyng Kambynskan</L>
<L>Ros from his bord ther as he sat ful hye</L>
<L N="268">Biforn him go&thorn; &thorn;e lowde menstralcie /</L>
<L>Til he com to his chambre of paramentz</L>
<L>Ther as &thorn;ey sownen diuerse instrumentz</L>
<L>That is lik an heuene for to heere /</L>
<L N="272">Now dauncen lusty venus children deere</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e fisshe hir lady sat ful hye<NOTE PLACE="marg">Piscis</NOTE></L>
<L>And loke&thorn; on hem with a freendy yhe</L>
<L>This noble king is set vp on his troone</L>
<L N="276">This straunge knight is fet to him ful sone /</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e daunce he go&thorn; with Canacee</L>
<L>here is &thorn;e reuel and &thorn;e Iolite</L>
<L>That is nat able a dul man to deuyse /</L>
<L N="280">he moste han knowe loue and his seruise /</L>
<L>And ben a festlich man as freisch as may</L>
<L>That scholde &yogh;ow deuisen such array</L>
<L>who cou&thorn;e telle yow &thorn;e forme of daunces</L>
<L N="284">So vncouthe and such freissche continaunces</L>
<L>Swich subtile lokynges and dissimulynges</L>
<L>ffor drede of Ialouseye mennes aperceyuynges</L>
<L>Noman but lancelet and he is deed</L>
<L N="288">Therfore I passe ouer al &thorn;is lustyhed
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="202"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="487"></L>
<L>I say nomore but in &thorn;is Iolynesse</L>
<L>I lete hem til men to soper hem dresse</L>
<L>The stiward bit spices for to hye</L>
<L N="292">And eek &thorn;e wyn in al &thorn;is melodye</L>
<L>The vssheres and &thorn;e squyers ben y-gon</L>
<L>The spices and &thorn;e wyn is come anon</L>
<L>They eete and dronke and whan &thorn;is hadde an ende</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e temple as resoun was &thorn;ey wende<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; The seruise doon. &thorn;ey soupen al by day</L>
<L>What neede&thorn; you rehersen here aray</L>
<L>Ech man woot wel &thorn;at at/ a kinges feste</L>
<L N="300">ha&thorn; plente to &thorn;e meste and to &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>And deyntees mo &thorn;an ben in my knowyng</L>
<L>And after souper go&thorn; &thorn;is noble king</L>
<L>To seen &thorn;is hors of bras wi&thorn; al a route</L>
<L N="304">Of lordes and of ladyes him aboute</L>
<L>Swich wondryng was &thorn;er on &thorn;is hors of bras</L>
<L>That si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e grete seege of Troye was</L>
<L>Ther as men wondren on an hors also</L>
<L N="308">Ne was &thorn;er swich a wondryng as was &thorn;o /</L>
<L>But finally &thorn;e king aske&thorn; &thorn;e knight</L>
<L>The vertue of &thorn;is courser and &thorn;e might</L>
<L>And preyde him to telle his gouernance</L>
<L N="312">The hors anon bigan to trippe and daunce</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;is knight layde hond vpon his reyne /</L>
<L>And seyde sire &thorn;er is namore to seyne</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;ou list to ryden eny where</L>
<L N="316">ye moote trille a pyn stant in his eere</L>
<L>which I schal telle you bitwen vs tuo /</L>
<L>ye moot nempne him to what place also</L>
<L>Or to what Contre &thorn;at yow list to ryde</L>
<L N="320">And whan ye come &thorn;er as yow list tabyde</L>
<L>Bid him descende and trille ano&thorn;er pyn</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er-in li&thorn; &thorn;effect of al &thorn;at gyn</L>
<L>And wole doun descende and don your wille</L>
<L N="324">And in &thorn;at place he wol abyde stille
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="203"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="488"></L>
<L>&thorn;eigh alle &thorn;e world hadde &thorn;e contrarie swore</L>
<L>he schal not &thorn;ennes be &thorn;rowe ne y-bore</L>
<L>Of if yow liste bidde him &thorn;ennes gon</L>
<L N="328">Trille &thorn;is pynne and he wil vanyssche anon</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e sight of euery maner wight</L>
<L>And come ayein be it day or night</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at yow list to clepen him agayn</L>
<L N="332">In swich a gyse as I schal to yow sayn<MILESTONE N="95a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bitwixen yow and me and &thorn;at ful soone</L>
<L>Ryd whan yow list &thorn;er is no more to doone</L>
<L>Enformed whan &thorn;e kyng was of &thorn;e knight</L>
<L N="336">And ha&thorn; conceyued in his witt aright</L>
<L>The maner and &thorn;e forme of alle &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>fful glad and bli&thorn;e &thorn;e noble doughty kyng</L>
<L>Repeyryng to his reuel as biforn</L>
<L N="340">The brydel is in to &thorn;e tour y-born</L>
<L>And kept among his Ieweles lief and diere</L>
<L>The hors vanyssht y not in what manere</L>
<L>Out of here sight ye gete namore of me</L>
<L N="344">But &thorn;us I lete in lust and Iolite</L>
<L>This Kambynskan his lordes festeynge</L>
<L>Til wel neigh &thorn;e day bigan to springe</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prima pars</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; The Stag of an hert</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The norice of digestion is slepe</L>
<L N="348">Gan on hem wynke and bad hem take kepe</L>
<L>That moche mete and labour wol haue reste /</L>
<L>And with a galpyng hem alle he keste /</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;at it was tyme to lye a doun</L>
<L N="352">ffor blood was in his dominacion</L>
<L>Cherisshe&thorn; blood natures frend quod he</L>
<L>&thorn;ey &thorn;anken him galpynge by tuo by &thorn;re</L>
<L>And euery wight gan drawen him to his reste</L>
<L N="356">As sleep hem bad &thorn;ey tooke it for &thorn;e beste
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="204"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="489"></L>
<L>here dremes schulle not mowe be told for me</L>
<L>fful were here heedes of fumosite</L>
<L>That cause&thorn; drem of which &thorn;er is no charge /</L>
<L N="360">They sleepen til it was pryme large /</L>
<L>The moste part but it were Canace</L>
<L>Sche was ful mesurable as wommen be</L>
<L>ffor of hire fader hadde sche take hir leeue</L>
<L N="364">To go to reste sone after it was eue</L>
<L>hir list not appalled for to be</L>
<L>ffor on &thorn;e morwe vnfestlich for to see /</L>
<L>And slepte hir ferste sleep and awok<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="368">ffor swich a ioye sche in hir herte took</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of hire queynte ryng and hire mirour</L>
<L>That twenty tyme sche chaungeth hire colour</L>
<L>And in hire sleep right for impression</L>
<L N="372">Of hire mirour sche hadde a vision</L>
<L>Wherfore ar &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne vp gan glyde</L>
<L>Sche cleped vp on hire maystresse bysyde</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;at hir liste for to arise</L>
<L N="376">Thise olde wommen &thorn;at ben gladly wyse</L>
<L>As is hire maystresse answerde anon</L>
<L>And seyde ma dame whider wolde ye gon</L>
<L>Thus erely for folk ben alle in reste</L>
<L N="380">I wole quod sche arise for me leste /</L>
<L>No lengere sleepen but walken aboute</L>
<L>hire maistresse clepe&thorn; wommen a gret route /</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ey risen wel ten or twelue</L>
<L N="384">vp rise&thorn; freisshe Canace hir selue</L>
<L>As rody as bright as &thorn;ey &thorn;e yonge sonne</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e Ram. is ten degrees vpronne</L>
<L>Non hiher was he whan sche redy was</L>
<L N="388">And forth sche walkede eesyly a pas</L>
<L>Arrayed after &thorn;e lusty seson soote</L>
<L>lightly for to pleye and walke on foote</L>
<L>Nat but .v. or .vj. of hire meyne</L>
<L N="392">And in a trench fer in &thorn;e park go&thorn; sche
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="205"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="490"></L>
<L>The vapour which &thorn;at fro &thorn;e er&thorn;e glood</L>
<L>make&thorn; &thorn;e sonne to seeme rody and brood</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles it was so fair a sight</L>
<L N="396">That it made alle here hertes for to light</L>
<L>What for &thorn;e sesoun and &thorn;e morwenynge</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e foules &thorn;at sche herde synge</L>
<L>ffor right anon sche wiste what &thorn;ey mente</L>
<L N="400">Right by here song and knew alle here entente</L>
<L>// The knotte why &thorn;at euery tale is told</L>
<L>If it be taryed til lust be cold</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han it herkned after yore<MILESTONE N="96a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="404">The sauour passe&thorn; euer lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>ffor fulsomnesse of prolixite</L>
<L>And by &thorn;is same resoun &thorn;enke&thorn; me</L>
<L>I scholde to &thorn;e knotte condescende</L>
<L N="408">And maken of hire walkyng sone an ende</L>
<L>&para; Amydde a tree for-drye as whit as chalk/</L>
<L>As Canacee was pleyng in hire walk</L>
<L>Ther sat a ffaukon ouer hir heed ful hye</L>
<L N="412">That with a pitous voys so gan to crye</L>
<L>That al &thorn;e woode resede of hire crye</L>
<L>And beten hadde hire self so pitously /</L>
<L>With bo&thorn;en hire wynges til &thorn;e reede blood</L>
<L N="416">Ran endelong/ &thorn;e tree &thorn;er as sche stood</L>
<L>And euer in oon sche cryed alwey and schrighte</L>
<L>And with hire beek hir seluen so sche pighte</L>
<L>That &thorn;er ne was tygre ne cruel beste</L>
<L N="420">That duelle&thorn; ey&thorn;er in woode or in foreste</L>
<L>&thorn;at nolde han wept if &thorn;at he wepe cou&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor sorwe of hire sche schright alwey so lou&thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er nas neuere yit/ no man on lyue</L>
<L N="424">If &thorn;at I cou&thorn;e a fawkon wel descryue</L>
<L>That herde of such ano&thorn;er of fayrnesse</L>
<L>As wel of plumage as of gentilnesse</L>
<L>Of schap of al &thorn;at mighte rekened be</L>
<L N="428">A fawkon peregryn &thorn;anne semed sche
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="206"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="491"></L>
<L>Of fremde londe and euermore as sche stood</L>
<L>Sche swounede now and now for lak of blood</L>
<L>Til wel neigh is sche fallen fro &thorn;e tree</L>
<L N="432">This faire kinges doughter &thorn;is kanacee</L>
<L>That on hir fynger bar &thorn;e queynte ryng</L>
<L>&thorn;urgh which sche vnderstood wel euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That any foul may in his ledne sayn</L>
<L N="436">And kowde answere him in his ledne agayn</L>
<L>ha&thorn; vnderstande &thorn;at &thorn;is fawkon sayde</L>
<L>And wel neigh for &thorn;e rou&thorn;e almost sche deyde</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e tree sche go&thorn; ful hastily<MILESTONE N="96b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="440">And on &thorn;is fawkon loke&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>And held hire lappe abrood for wel sche wiste /</L>
<L>The fawkon moste falle from &thorn;e twyste /</L>
<L>whan &thorn;at it swownede next for lakke of blood</L>
<L N="444">A long while to wayte hire sche stood</L>
<L>Til atte laste sche spak in &thorn;is maneere</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e hauk as &yogh;e schal after heere</L>
<L>what is &thorn;e cause if it be for to telle</L>
<L N="448">That ye ben in &thorn;is furial peyne of helle</L>
<L>Quod Canacee vnto &thorn;is hawk aboue</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is for sorwe of deth or los of loue</L>
<L>ffor as I trowe &thorn;ise be&thorn; causes tuo</L>
<L N="452">That causen moost a gentil herte woo</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er harm it rede&thorn; nought/ to speke</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;i your self vpon your self yow wreke</L>
<L>which &thorn;at proue&thorn; wel &thorn;at ey&thorn;er Ire or drede</L>
<L N="456">Moot ben encheson of youre cruel dede</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at I se non o&thorn;er wight yow chace</L>
<L>ffor loue of god so do&thorn; your selue grace</L>
<L>Or what may be your help for west nor est</L>
<L N="460">Ne saugh I neuer er now no bryd ne best</L>
<L>That ferde with himself so pitously</L>
<L>ye slee me with youre sorwe verrayly</L>
<L>I haue of yow so gret compassioun</L>
<L N="464">ffor goddes loue com fro &thorn;e tree a doun
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="207"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="492"></L>
<L>And as I am a kinges doughter trewe</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I verraily &thorn;e causes knewe</L>
<L>Of youre disease if it lay in my might</L>
<L N="468">I wolde amende it or &thorn;at it were night</L>
<L>Als wisly help me grete god of kynde</L>
<L>And herbes schal I right ynowe fynde</L>
<L>To hele wi&thorn; &yogh;our hurtes hastily</L>
<L N="472">Tho schrighte &thorn;is faukon yet more pitously</L>
<L>Than euer sche dide and fil to grounde anon</L>
<L>And li&thorn; on swowne deed as ony stoon</L>
<L>Til Canacee ha&thorn; in hir lappe hire take<MILESTONE N="97a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="476">vnto &thorn;at tyme sche gan of swowne awake /</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at sche of swowne gan abreide</L>
<L>Right in hir hawkes leodne &thorn;us sche seyde</L>
<L>That pite renneth sone in gentil herte</L>
<L N="480">ffeelyng his similitude in peynes smerte /</L>
<L>Is proued alday as men may it see</L>
<L>As wel by werk as by auctorite</L>
<L>ffor gentil herte kepe&thorn; gentillesse</L>
<L N="484">I se wel &thorn;at ye han of my distresse</L>
<L>Compassion my faire Canace /</L>
<L>Of verray wommanly benignite /</L>
<L>That nature in youre principles ha&thorn; set</L>
<L N="488">But for non hope for to fare &thorn;e bet</L>
<L>But for to obeye vnto youre herte fre /</L>
<L>And for to maken o&thorn;er be war by me /</L>
<L>As by &thorn;e whelp chastised is &thorn;e leon</L>
<L N="492">Right for &thorn;at cause and for &thorn;at conclusion</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at I haue a leyser and a space</L>
<L>Myn harm I wol confessen er I pace</L>
<L>And euer whil sche can hir sorwe tolde</L>
<L N="496">That o&thorn;er wepte as sche to water wolde</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e fawkon bad hir to be stille /</L>
<L>And with a sike &thorn;us sche seyde hire tille</L>
<L>Ther I was bred allas &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L N="500">And fostred in a roche of marbul gray
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="208"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="493"></L>
<L>So tendrely &thorn;at no&thorn;ing eylede me</L>
<L>I ne wiste nought what was aduersite</L>
<L>Til I cou&thorn;e flee ful hye vnder &thorn;e sky</L>
<L N="504">&thorn;o dwelte a tercelet me faste by</L>
<L>That semede welle of alle gentilnesse</L>
<L>Al were he ful of treson and falsnesse /</L>
<L>It is wrapped vnder humble cheere</L>
<L N="508">And vnder hiew of trou&thorn;e and in swich manere</L>
<L>Vnder plesance and vnder bysy peyne</L>
<L>That no wight cou&thorn;e han wende he coude feyne</L>
<L>So deepe in greyn he dyed his colours<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="512">Right as a serpent hit him vnder flours</L>
<L>Til he may se his tyme for to byte</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;is god of loues ypocrite</L>
<L>Do&thorn; so his cerymonijs obeissances</L>
<L N="516">And kepte in semblant alle his obseruances</L>
<L>That sowne&thorn; in to gentilesse of loue</L>
<L>As in a tombe is al &thorn;e faire aboue</L>
<L>And vnder is &thorn;e corps swich as &yogh;e woot</L>
<L N="520">Swich was &thorn;is ypocrite bo&thorn;e cold and hoot</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is wise he serued his entente</L>
<L>That saue &thorn;e feende non wiste what he mente</L>
<L>Til he so longe hadde wopen and compleyned</L>
<L N="524">And many a yeer his seruise to me feyned</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at myn herte to pitous and to nyce</L>
<L>Al Innocent of his crowned malice</L>
<L>ffor-fered of his de&thorn; as &thorn;oughte me</L>
<L N="528">vpon his o&thorn;es and his seurte</L>
<L>Grauntede him loue vpon &thorn;is condicion</L>
<L>That euer mo myn honour &amp; reno&umacr;n</L>
<L>were saued bo&thorn;e preuy and apert</L>
<L N="532">This is to sein &thorn;at after his dissert</L>
<L>I yaf him al myn herte and my &thorn;ought</L>
<L>God woot and he &thorn;at o&thorn;er wise nought</L>
<L>And tok his herte in chaunge of myn for ay</L>
<L N="536">But so&thorn; is seyd go sethen many a day
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="209"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="494"></L>
<L>A trewe wight and a &thorn;eef &thorn;enke&thorn; nat oon</L>
<L>And whan he saugh &thorn;e &thorn;ing so fer y-gon</L>
<L>That I grauntede him fully my loue /</L>
<L N="540">In swich a gyse as I haue sayd aboue /</L>
<L>And yeuen him my trewe herte as fre /</L>
<L>As he swore he yaf his herte to me /</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;is Tygre ful of doublenesse</L>
<L N="544">ffil on his knees wi&thorn; so deuoute humblesse</L>
<L>wi&thorn; hye reuerence and as by his cheere /</L>
<L>So lik a gentil louere of manere /</L>
<L>So rauysshed as it semede for &thorn;e ioye<MILESTONE N="98a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="548">That neuere Iason ne paris of Troye</L>
<L>Iason certes ne non o&thorn;er man</L>
<L>Syn lameth was &thorn;at Aldirfirst bygan</L>
<L>To louen tuo as writen folk biforn</L>
<L N="552">Ne neuer si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e firste man was born</L>
<L>Ne cou&thorn;e man by twenty &thorn;ousand part</L>
<L>Countrefete &thorn;e sophimes of his art</L>
<L>Ne were wor&thorn;i to vnbokele his galoche</L>
<L N="556">Ther doublenesse or feynyng scholde aproche</L>
<L>Ne so cou&thorn;e &thorn;anke a wight as he dide me /</L>
<L>his manere was an heuene for to se</L>
<L>Til eny womman were sche neuer so wys</L>
<L N="560">So peynted he and kembe&thorn; at poynt devys</L>
<L>As wel his wordes as his continance</L>
<L>And I so loued him for his obeissance</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e trou&thorn;e I demed in his herte</L>
<L N="564">That if so were &thorn;at any &thorn;ing him smerte</L>
<L>Al were it neuer so lite and I it wiste</L>
<L>Me &thorn;oughte I felte de&thorn; at myn herte twiste</L>
<L>And schortly so ferforth &thorn;is &thorn;ing went</L>
<L N="568">That my wille has his willes Instrument</L>
<L>This is to sein my wille obeyede his wille</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;ing as fer as reson fille</L>
<L>Kepyng &thorn;e boundes of my worschipe euere</L>
<L N="572">Ne neuer hadde I &thorn;ing so leef ne leuere
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="210"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="495"></L>
<L>As him god woot ne neuere schal no mo</L>
<L>This laste lengere &thorn;an a yer or tuo</L>
<L>&para; That I supposed of him no &thorn;ing but good</L>
<L N="576">But fynally &thorn;us atte laste it stood</L>
<L>That fortune wolde &thorn;at he moste twynne</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at place which &thorn;at I was Inne</L>
<L>Wher me was wo it is no question</L>
<L N="580">I kan not make of it discripcion</L>
<L>ffor o &thorn;ing dar I telle boldely</L>
<L>I knowe what is &thorn;e peyne of de&thorn; &thorn;er by</L>
<L>Such harm I felte for he ne mighte beleue<MILESTONE N="98a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="584">So on a day of me he tok his leue /</L>
<L>So sorwfully eek I wende verrayly</L>
<L>That he hadde feeled as moche harm as I</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at I herde him speke and sawe his hewe /</L>
<L N="588">But na&thorn;eles I &thorn;oughte he was so trewe/</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;at he repaire scholde agayn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne a litel while so&thorn; to sayn</L>
<L>And reson wolde eek &thorn;at he moste go</L>
<L N="592">ffor his honour as ofte happe&thorn; so</L>
<L>That I made vertu of necessite /</L>
<L>&amp; took it wel syn &thorn;at it / moste be</L>
<L>As I best mighte I hidde from him my sorwe</L>
<L N="596">And took him by &thorn;e hond seint Iohn to borwe</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;us lo I am youres al</L>
<L>Be&thorn; swich as I haue be to yow and schal</L>
<L>What he answerde it neede&thorn; nat reherse</L>
<L N="600">Who can seyn bet &thorn;an he who can do werse</L>
<L>Whan he ha&thorn; al wel seyd &thorn;an ha&thorn; he doon</L>
<L>Therfore byhoue&thorn; him a wel long spoon</L>
<L>That schal eten wi&thorn; a feend &thorn;us herde I seye /</L>
<L N="604">So atte laste he moot for&thorn; his weye</L>
<L>And forth he fle&thorn; til he com &thorn;er him leste</L>
<L>Whan it com him to purpos for to reste /</L>
<L>I trowe he hadde &thorn;ilke text in mynde /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Reditui suo singula gaudent/.</NOTE></L>
<L N="608">That alle &thorn;ing repeyryng to his kynde /
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="211"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="496"></L>
<L>Glade&thorn; himself / &thorn;us seyn men as I gesse /</L>
<L>Men louen of propre kynde newfangilnesse /</L>
<L>As briddes doon &thorn;at men in cages feede /</L>
<L N="612">ffor &thorn;eigh &thorn;ou night &amp; day take of hem heede /</L>
<L>And strawe here cages faire as softe as silk</L>
<L>And yeue hem sucre hony bred and mylk</L>
<L>Yet right anon as &thorn;at his dore is vppe</L>
<L N="616">he wi&thorn; his feet wil sporne doun his cuppe</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e woode he wole and wormes ete</L>
<L>So newefangel ben &thorn;ei of here mete</L>
<L>And louen noueleries of propre kynde<MILESTONE N="99a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="620">No gentilesse of blood may hem bynde</L>
<L>So ferde &thorn;is tercelet allas &thorn;e day</L>
<L>Though he were gentil born fressche and gay</L>
<L>And goodly for to seen and humble and fre</L>
<L N="624">he saugh vpon a tyme a kyte flee</L>
<L>And sodeinly he loued &thorn;e kyte so</L>
<L>That alle his loue is clene fro me go</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; his trou&thorn;e falsed in &thorn;is wyse</L>
<L N="628">Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;e kite my loue in hire seruise</L>
<L>And I am lorn wi&thorn;oute remedye</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word &thorn;is faukon gan to crye</L>
<L>And swouned eft/ in Canacees barm</L>
<L N="632">Gret was &thorn;e sorwe for &thorn;e haukes harm</L>
<L>That Canacee and alle hire wommen maade</L>
<L>They nyste how &thorn;ey mighte &thorn;e fawkon glade</L>
<L>But Canacee home bere&thorn; hire in hire lappe</L>
<L N="636">And softely in plastres gan hire wrappe</L>
<L>Ther as sche with hir beek ha&thorn; hurt hir selue</L>
<L>Now kan not Canace but herbes delue</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e grounde and maken salues newe</L>
<L N="640">Of herbes preciouses and fyn of hewe</L>
<L>To helen wi&thorn; &thorn;e hauk fro day to nyght</L>
<L>Sche do&thorn; hir besynesse and alle hire myght</L>
<L>And by hire beddes heed sche made a muwe</L>
<L N="644">And couered it with veluettes bluwe
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="212"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="497"></L>
<L>In signe of trou&thorn;e &thorn;at is in wommen seene</L>
<L>And alle wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e muwe is peynted greene</L>
<L>In which were peynted alle &thorn;ese false fowles</L>
<L N="648">As ben &thorn;ise tydifs tercelettes and owles</L>
<L>Right for &thorn;e spyte were peynted hem bysyde</L>
<L>Pyes on hem for to crye and chyde</L>
<L>Thus leet I Canacee hire hawk keeping</L>
<L N="652">I wole nomore as now speke of hire ryng</L>
<L>Til it come eft to purpos for to seyn</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;is ffaukon gat hire loue ageyn</L>
<L>Repentant as &thorn;e storie telle&thorn; vs<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="656">By mediacion of Camballus</L>
<L>The kinges sone of which I yow tolde /</L>
<L>But hennes forth I wol proces holde</L>
<L>To speke of auentures and of batailles</L>
<L N="660">That yet was neuer herde so gret meruailles</L>
<L>ffirst wil I telle yow of Kambynskan</L>
<L>That in his tyme many a cite wan</L>
<L>And after wol I speke of Algarsif</L>
<L N="664">how &thorn;at he wan Theodora to his wyf</L>
<L>ffor whan ful ofte in gret peril he was</L>
<L>Ne hadde he ben holpen by &thorn;e hors of bras</L>
<L>And after wol I speken of Camballo</L>
<L N="668">That faught in listes with &thorn;e bre&thorn;eren tuo</L>
<L>ffor Canacee er &thorn;at he might hir wynne</L>
<L>And &thorn;er I lefte I wol ageyn bygynne</L>
<L>Appolo whirleth vp his char so hye<NOTE PLACE="marg">Apollo i. sol.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e god mercurius hous &thorn;e slye /</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit .ij<SUP>a</SUP>. pars.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="D" TYPE="group"><PB REF="00000241.tif" N="213"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="334">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>D.</B> FRAGMENT V.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> WIFE OF BATH'S PREAMBLE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>CORPUS MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prologus vxoris de Bathe. [<I>headline</I>]<MILESTONE N="100a" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Experiment &thorn;ough non auctorite<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Prologus vxoris de Bathe .C<SUP>o</SUP>.vij<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were in &thorn;is world is right ynough for me</L>
<L>To speke of wo &thorn;at is in mariage</L>
<L N="4">ffor lordynges syn I twelue &yogh;eer was of age /</L>
<L>Thanked be god &thorn;at is eterne alyue</L>
<L>housbondes atte chirche dore I haue had fyue/</L>
<L>If I so often might haue wedded be</L>
<L N="8">But alle were wor&thorn;y men in here degre</L>
<L>But me was told certein nought longe agones</L>
<L>[that criste ne wente / neuere but onys]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14.]</NOTE></L>
<L>To weddyng in &thorn;e Cane of Galile /</L>
<L N="12">That by &thorn;ilke ensample taught he me</L>
<L>That I ne schulde wedded be but ones</L>
<L>herk eek lo which a scharpe worde for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>Besyde a welle Ihesu god and man</L>
<L N="16">Spak in repreef of &thorn;e Samaritan</L>
<L>Thow hast y-hadde .v. housebondes quod he.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilke man &thorn;at now ha&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Is not &thorn;in housbonde &thorn;us sayde he certayne</L>
<L N="20">What he mente &thorn;er-by I can nought sayne</L>
<L>Wele But &thorn;at/ I axe why &thorn;e fyfte man</L>
<L>Was non housbonde to &thorn;e Samaritan</L>
<L N="23">how many might sche han in mariage</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">[This line is by another hand, over an erasure.]</NOTE>&YOGH;itt hardde I neuere telle in al myn age
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="214"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="335"></L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;is nombre diffinicioun</L>
<L>Men may deuyne and glosen vp and doun</L>
<L>But wel I woot expresse wi&thorn;outen lye</L>
<L N="28">God bad vs for to wexe and multiplye</L>
<L>That gentil text can I wel vnderstonde</L>
<L>Eke wel I woot he seyde myn housebonde</L>
<L>Schulde lete fader &amp; mooder and take to me<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Relinquet homo patrem &amp; matrem &amp; adherebit &amp;c/</NOTE></L>
<L>But of noon nombre mension made he /</L>
<L N="33">Of Bigamye or of Octogamye</L>
<L>Why schulde men &thorn;enne haue it in vilanye /</L>
<L>loke here &thorn;e wise man king Salomon</L>
<L>I trowe he hadde wyues moo &thorn;an on<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Genesis ij<SUP>o.</SUP> Quamobrem</NOTE></L>
<L N="37">Now wolde god it leeful were to me /</L>
<L>To be refreisshed half so ofte as he<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Which &yogh;ifte of god hadde he for alle his wyues</L>
<L N="40">No man ha&thorn; such &thorn;at in &thorn;is world a lyue is</L>
<L>God wot &thorn;is noble king as to my witte</L>
<L>The firste night hadde many a mery fitte</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; iche of hem so wel was him alyue</L>
<L N="44">Blissed be god &thorn;at I haue wedded fyue</L>
<L>Welcome &thorn;e sixte whan &thorn;at euer he schal</L>
<L>ffor si&thorn;&thorn;e I wille nought kepe chaste in al</L>
<L>Whan myn housebonde is fro &thorn;e world y-gon</L>
<L N="48">Som crystne man schal wedde me anon</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;an &thorn;e apostle sei&thorn; &thorn;at I am free</L>
<L>To wedde a goddes half wher it like&thorn; me</L>
<L>he sei&thorn; &thorn;at to be wedded is no senne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Melius est nubere quam vri</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">Betre is it to be wedded &thorn;an to brenne</L>
<L>What rekke&thorn; me &thorn;ough folk sey vylanye</L>
<L>Of schrewed lameth and his Bygamye /</L>
<L>I woot wel Abraham was an holy man</L>
<L N="56">And Iacob eek as fer as euer I can</L>
<L>And ech of hem hadde wyues mo &thorn;an tuo</L>
<L>And many ano&thorn;er holy man also</L>
<L>Wher can &yogh;e say in any maner age</L>
<L N="60">That vs god defended mariage
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="215"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="336"></L>
<L>By expresse word I pray yow telle&thorn; me</L>
<L>Or wher comaunded he virginite</L>
<L>I wot as wel as ye it is no drede</L>
<L N="64">&thorn;e apostel whan he speke&thorn; of maydenhede</L>
<L>he seyde &thorn;er-of precepte hadde he noone</L>
<L>Men may counseille a womman to ben oone</L>
<L>But counseilling is no comaundement</L>
<L N="68">he putte it in oure owne Iuggement</L>
<L>ffor hadde god commaunded maydenhede</L>
<L>&thorn;anne hadde he dampned weddyng with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>And certes if &thorn;er were no seed y-sowe</L>
<L N="72">virginite &thorn;anne wher-of scholde it growe</L>
<L>Poule dorste nought comanden at &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>A &thorn;ing of which his mayster &yogh;af him non heste<MILESTONE N="101a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The darte is sette vppe fro virginite</L>
<L N="76">Chase who so may who so renne&thorn; best lat see</L>
<L>But &thorn;is word is nought take of euery wight</L>
<L>But &thorn;ere as god wolde yeue it of his might</L>
<L>I wot wel &thorn;at &thorn;e apostel was a mayde /</L>
<L N="80">But na&thorn;eles &thorn;ough &thorn;at he wrot or sayde</L>
<L>he wolde &thorn;at euery wight were such as he /</L>
<L>Al nys nat but counseile to virginite</L>
<L>And for to be a wijf he yaf me leue</L>
<L N="84">Of Indulgence so is it no repreue</L>
<L>To wedde me if &thorn;at my make deye /</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;oute excepcion of Bygamie /</L>
<L>Al were it good no womman for to touche</L>
<L N="88">he mente as his body or in his couche</L>
<L>ffor peril is bo&thorn;e to touche and for to assemble</L>
<L>&YOGH;e knowe what &thorn;is ensample may resemble</L>
<L>This al and some he heeld virginite</L>
<L N="92">More perfyt &thorn;an wedded in freelte</L>
<L>ffreltee clepe I not but &thorn;at he and sche</L>
<L>Wolde leede here lijf al in chastite</L>
<L>I graunte it wel I haue non envye</L>
<L N="96">Though maydenhede preferre Bygamye
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="216"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="337"></L>
<L>It like&thorn; hem to be clene in body and gost</L>
<L>Of myn estate I wole make no boost</L>
<L>ffor wel &yogh;e knowe a lord in his houshold</L>
<L N="100">ha&thorn; not euery vessele of golde /</L>
<L>Some ben of tree / and doon here lord seruise</L>
<L>God clepe&thorn; folk to him in sondry wise</L>
<L>And euerich ha&thorn; of god a propre &yogh;ifte /</L>
<L N="104">Some &thorn;is some &thorn;at as him like&thorn; schifte</L>
<L>virginite is gret perfection</L>
<L>And conscience eek with deuocion</L>
<L>But crist &thorn;at of perfection is welle</L>
<L N="108">Bad nought euery wight he schulde selle</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he hadde and &yogh;iue it to &thorn;e pore</L>
<L>And in swich wise folwe him and his lore<MILESTONE N="101b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he spak to hem &thorn;at wolde lyue parfitly<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Mathei xix<SUP>o</SUP>. Dixit autem ihesus vade &amp; vende omnia que habes &amp; da pauperibus</NOTE></L>
<L>And lordynges by &yogh;oure leue &thorn;at am not I</L>
<L N="113">I wole bystowe &thorn;e flour of alle myn age</L>
<L>In charite and fruyt of maryage</L>
<L>Telle me also to what conclusion</L>
<L N="116">Were membres maade of generacion</L>
<L>And of so parfyt wise and why y-wrought</L>
<L>Triste&thorn; right wel &thorn;ey were not made for nought</L>
<L>Glose who so wile and seye bo&thorn;e vp and doun</L>
<L N="120">That &thorn;ey were made for purgacioun</L>
<L>Of vryne and oure bo&thorn;e &thorn;inges smale</L>
<L>Were eek to knowe a femal from a male</L>
<L>And for non o&thorn;er cause what seye &yogh;e no;</L>
<L N="124">The experience woot it is nou&yogh;t so</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e clerkes be not with me wro&thorn;e</L>
<L>I seye &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;ey maked be for bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>This is to seyn for office and for eese</L>
<L N="128">Of engendrynge &thorn;are we not god displese</L>
<L>Why schulden men elles in here bokes sette</L>
<L>That man schal yelde to his wijf his dette</L>
<L>Now wher-wi&thorn; scholde he paye his payement</L>
<L N="132">yf &thorn;at he ne vsed his seely instrument
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="217"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="338"></L>
<L>Than were &thorn;ey maade vpon a creature</L>
<L>To purgie vryne and eek for engendure</L>
<L>But I seye nought &thorn;at euery wight is holde</L>
<L N="136">That ha&thorn; such harneys as I to yow of tolde</L>
<L>To gon and vsen hem in engendrure</L>
<L>Thanne scholde men take of chastite no cure</L>
<L>Crist was a mayden and schapen as a man</L>
<L N="140">And many a seynt syn &thorn;at &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L>Yet lyued &thorn;ey euere in parfyt chastite</L>
<L>I nel envye with no virginite</L>
<L>lete hem ete brede of pured whete seed</L>
<L N="144">And late vs wyues ete barly breed</L>
<L>And yet with barly breed Mark telle can</L>
<L>Oure lord<NOTE PLACE="marg">[catchword: a leaf out; a sheet misplaced]</NOTE> [Ihesu refresshed / many a man<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="84b"></L>
<L>in suche estate as god hath cleped vs</L>
<L N="148">I wol perceiver / I am nought precious</L>
<L>in wiffhode wol I vse myn instrument</L>
<L>as frely as my maker / hath hit sent</L>
<L>yiff I be dangerous / god yeve me sorowe</L>
<L N="152">myn housbonde shal it haue both eve and amorwe</L>
<L>whan that him list / com forth and pay his dette</L>
<L>an housbonde wol I haue / I wol not lette</L>
<L>which shal be / both my dettour and my thralle</L>
<L N="156">and han his tribulacioun with-alle</L>
<L>vppon his flesshe / while that I am his wiff</L>
<L>I haue the power / durynge al my liff<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ad Corinthios vij<SUP>o</SUP> vir sui corporis non habet potestatem set mulier &amp;c</NOTE></L>
<L>vppon his propre body / and not he</L>
<L N="160">right thus the Appostel / tolde vn-to me</L>
<L>and bad oure housbondes / for to love vs welle</L>
<L>alle this sentence / me liketh euerydelle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Uppe sterte the pardoner / and that anoon</L>
<L N="164">now dame quod he / bi god and bi seint Iohn</L>
<L>ye ben a noble prechoure / in this caas</L>
<L>I was abovte to wedde a wiff allaas</L>
<L>what shulde I bye it / on my flesshe so dere</L>
<L N="168">yit had I lever wedde noon to yere
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="218"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="339"></L>
<L>abyde quod she / my tale is not bigonne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>nay thow shalt drynken / of another tonne</L>
<L>or that I go / shal sauour wers than ale<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="85a"></L>
<L N="172">and whan I haue tolde forth my tale</L>
<L>of tribulacioun / that is in mariage</L>
<L>of which I am expert / in myn age</L>
<L>this is to seie / my-silff hath ben the whippe</L>
<L N="176">than maistow chese / whether thow wih sippe</L>
<L>of thilke tonne / that I shal abroche</L>
<L>be war of hit / or thow to nygh approche</L>
<L>for I shal telle ensamples / mo than ten</L>
<L N="180">who so that wil not / be war bi other men</L>
<L>by him shulle other men corrected be</L>
<L>these same wordis / writeth Protholome<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Protholome</NOTE></L>
<L>rede in his Almageste / and take it there</L>
<L N="184">dame I wol pray yow / if youre wille were</L>
<L>seide this Pardoner / as ye bigan</L>
<L>telle forth youre tale / spare for no man</L>
<L>and teche vs yongemen / of youre practike</L>
<L N="188">gladly quod she / sith it may yow like</L>
<L>but that I pray / to al this companye</L>
<L>if that I speke / after my fantesie</L>
<L>as taketh nought agreff / of that I seye</L>
<L N="192">for myn entente / is not / but for to pleye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw sirs than shal I telle yow my tale</L>
<L>as euere mot y drynke wyn or ale</L>
<L>I shal sey soth / tho housbondes that I hadde</L>
<L N="196">as thre of hem were goode / and two were badde</L>
<L>the thre were goode men / riche and olde</L>
<L>vnneth myghten thei / the statute holde</L>
<L>in which thei were bounden vn-to me</L>
<L N="200">ye wot wel what I meene of this parde</L>
<L>as god me helpe / I laugh whan I thynke</L>
<L>how pitously a nyght / I made hem swynke</L>
<L>but bi my fay / I tolde of hit no store</L>
<L N="204">thei hadde me yeve here londe / and here tresore
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="219"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="340"></L>
<L>me nedede nought / do lenger diligence<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>to wynne here love / and do hem reuerence</L>
<L>they loued me so wel / bi god above<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="85b"></L>
<L N="208">that I ne tolde no deynte / of here love</L>
<L>a wise woman wol besy hir / euere in oon</L>
<L>to gete hir love / ye there as she hath noon</L>
<L>but sith I hadde hem / holly in myn honde</L>
<L N="212">and that thei hadde / yeve me al here londe</L>
<L>what shulde I take kepe hem for to please</L>
<L>but if it were my profyte / and myn ease</L>
<L>I sette hem so a worke / bi my fay</L>
<L N="216">that many a night / thei songen welaway</L>
<L>the Bacoun was not fette for hem I trowe]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Arch. Seld. B. 14</B> <I>ex|tract stops</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>That some men haue in Essexe at Dunmowe<MILESTONE N="107a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> 102</NOTE></L>
<L>I gouerned hem so wel after my lawe</L>
