<L N="244">Wi&thorn;oute gilte &yogh;e chide as a feende</L>
<L>If &thorn;at I walke or pleye vnto his hous</L>
<L>&thorn;ou comest home as drunken as a mous</L>
<L>And prechest on &thorn;i benche wi&thorn; euel preef</L>
<L N="248">&thorn;ou seist to me it is a gret meschief</L>
<L>To wedde a pouer womman for costage</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at sche be riche of gret parage</L>
<L>&thorn;anne seistow &thorn;at it is a tormentrie /</L>
<L N="252">To suffre hire pryde and hire malencolie /</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at sche be fair &thorn;ou verray knaue /</L>
<L>Thow seist &thorn;at euery holour wol hir haue /<MILESTONE N="107b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche may no while in chastite abyde</L>
<L N="256">That is assayed vppon eche syde</L>
<L>Thou seist some folk desire vs for richesse</L>
<L>Some for oure schapp and some for oure fayrnesse</L>
<L>And some for sche can o&thorn;er synge or daunce</L>
<L N="260">&thorn;us saistow wernard god &yogh;iue &thorn;e meschance</L>
<L>Some for here hondes and here armes smale</L>
<L>Thus go&thorn; al to &thorn;e deuel by &thorn;y tale/</L>
<L>&thorn;ou seist men may not kepe a castel walle</L>
<L N="264">It may so longe assailed ben ouer alle /</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at sche be foule &thorn;ou seist &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>Coueite&thorn; euery man &thorn;at sche may see</L>
<L>ffor as a spaynel sche wol on him lepe</L>
<L N="268">Til &thorn;at sche fynde som man &thorn;at wol hir chepe</L>
<L>Ne non so grey goos go&thorn; &thorn;er in &thorn;e lake</L>
<L>As seist &thorn;ou &thorn;at wol be wi&thorn;outen make</L>
<L>And seist it is an hard &thorn;ing for to weelde</L>
<L N="272">A wight &thorn;at noman wille his &thorn;ankes helde</L>
<L>Thus seistow lorel whan &thorn;ou gost to bedde</L>
<L>And &thorn;at no wys man neede&thorn; for to wedde</L>
<L>And noman &thorn;at entendi&thorn; to &thorn;e heuene</L>
<L N="276">Wi&thorn; wilde &thorn;under dent and fyre leuene /
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="221"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="342"></L>
<L>Mote &thorn;y wicked necke be to-broke</L>
<L>&thorn;ou seist &thorn;at droppyng houses and eek smoke</L>
<L>And chydyng wyues maken men to fle</L>
<L N="280">Out of here owne houses a benedicite</L>
