<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000266.tif" N="238"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="359">
<HEAD>[<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS cut away.]</NOTE>Here bigynneth] &thorn;e goode wyues tale of bathe<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on lf</I> 101, <I>bk</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN olde dayes of &thorn;e king arthour</L>
<L>[O]f which &thorn;at britons speken gret honour</L>
<L>[A]l was &thorn;is land fulfild of fayerie</L>
<L N="860">[T]he elfe queen with hire ioly compaignie</L>
<L>[D]aunced wi&thorn;outen in many a greene meede</L>
<L>[T]his was &thorn;e olde opynion as I rede</L>
<L>[I speke of many] hundred &yogh;eer ago</L>
<L N="864">[But] now can noman see non elues moo</L>
<L>[For] &thorn;e grete charite and &thorn;e preyeres</L>
<L>[Of] lymytoures and o&thorn;re pouere freeres</L>
<L>[T]hat serchen euery land and euery streem</L>
<L N="868">[A]s &thorn;ikke as motes in &thorn;e sonne beem</L>
<L>Blissynge halles chambres boures</L>
<L>[C]itees burghes castels hihe toures</L>
<L>[T]hropes bernes schipenes dayeries</L>
<L N="872">This make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;er ben no fayeries</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er as wont to walke was an elf</L>
<L>Ther walke&thorn; now &thorn;e lymytour himself</L>
<L>In vndermeles and in morwenynges</L>
<L N="876">And sei&thorn; his matyns and his holy &thorn;inges</L>
<L>As he go&thorn; in his lymytacioun</L>
<L>Wommen may go now saufly vp and doun</L>
<L>In euery busch or vnder euery tree</L>
<L N="880">&thorn;er is non o&thorn;er Incubus but he</L>
<L>And he wol do hem but dishonour</L>
<L>And so felle it / &thorn;at &thorn;is king arthour</L>
<L>hadde in his hous a lusty bacheler</L>
<L N="884">&thorn;at on a day cam rydyng fro ryuer
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="239"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="360"></L>
<L>And happed alone as sche was born</L>
<L>he saugh a mayden walkyng him biforn</L>
<L>Of which mayde maugre hire heed</L>
<L N="888">By verray force he refte hir maydenhed</L>
<L>ffor which oppression was such clamour</L>
<L>And swich pursute vnto &thorn;e king artour<MILESTONE N="102a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> 111</NOTE></L>
<L>That dampned was &thorn;is knight for to be deed</L>
<L N="892">By cours of lawe and scholde haue lost his heed</L>
<L>Perauenture such was &thorn;e statute &thorn;o</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;e queene and o&thorn;er ladyes mo</L>
<L>So longe preyede &thorn;e king of grace /</L>
<L N="896">Til he his lijf him graunted in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>And yaf him to &thorn;e queen al at hire wille</L>
<L>To cheese whe&thorn;er sche wolde him saue or spille</L>
<L>The queen &thorn;anke&thorn; &thorn;e king with alle hire might</L>
<L N="900">And after &thorn;is &thorn;us spak sche to &thorn;e knight</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche seigh hir tyme on a day</L>
<L>&thorn;ou stondest &yogh;et quod sche in such aray</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;i lijf &yogh;et hast &thorn;ou no suerte</L>
<L N="904">I graunte &thorn;e lijf if &thorn;ou canst telle me</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing is it/ &thorn;at wommen most desiren</L>
<L>Be war and keep &thorn;i neeke bon from yren</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou canst nought telle it me anon</L>
<L N="908">&yogh;it/ wol I &yogh;iue &thorn;e leue for to gon</L>
<L>A twelf mon&thorn;e and a day to seeke and lere</L>
<L>An answere sufficant/ in &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L>And seurte wil I han or &thorn;at &thorn;ou pace</L>
<L N="912">Thy body for to yelden in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Wo was &thorn;is knight and sorufully he sike&thorn;</L>
<L>But what he may not do al as him like&thorn;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e laste he chese him for to wende /</L>
<L N="916">And come a&yogh;ein right at &thorn;e yeres ende /</L>
<L>With swich answere as god wolde him purueye /</L>
<L>And take&thorn; his leue and wende&thorn; for&thorn; his weye</L>
<L>he seeke&thorn; euery hous and euery place /</L>
<L N="920">Wher as he hope&thorn; for to fynde grace
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="240"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="361"></L>
<L>To lerne what &thorn;ing wommen louen most</L>
<L>But he now cou&thorn;e arryuen in no coost</L>
<L>Wher as he mighte fynde in &thorn;is matere /</L>
<L N="924">Tuo creatures acordyng in feere</L>
<L>Some seyden wommen loue best richesse</L>
<L>Some seyde honour some seyden Iolynesse /<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Some riche array some seyden lust a bedde /</L>
<L N="928">And ofte time to be wydewe and wedde /</L>
<L>Some seyden &thorn;at we be most yesed</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at we ben y-flatered and y-plesed</L>
<L>he go&thorn; ful neigh &thorn;e so&thorn;e I wol nat lye</L>
<L N="932">A man schal wynne vs best wi&thorn; flaterie</L>
<L>And with attendaunce and wi&thorn; besynesse</L>
<L>Ben we y-lymed bo&thorn;e more and lesse /</L>
<L>And some men sein how &thorn;at we louen best</L>
<L N="936">ffor to be fre and do right as vs lest</L>
<L>And &thorn;at noman / repreue vs of oure vice</L>
<L>But seye &thorn;at we be wyse and no&thorn;ing nyce</L>
<L>ffor trewely &thorn;er nys non of vs alle /</L>
<L N="940">If eny wight wol clawe vs on &thorn;e galle /</L>
<L>&thorn;at we nyl loke or he sei&thorn; vs so&thorn;</L>
<L>Assay and he schal fynde it &thorn;at he do&thorn;</L>
<L>ffor be we neuer so vicious wi&thorn;inne</L>
<L N="944">We wil be holden wys and clene of synne</L>
<L>And some men sein &thorn;at gret delyt haue we</L>
<L>ffor to be holden stable and ek secre</L>
<L>And in oo purpos stedefastly to dwelle</L>
<L N="948">And not bewreye &thorn;ing &thorn;at men vs telle</L>
<L>But &thorn;at tale is not wor&thorn; a rake stele</L>
<L>Parde we wommen konnen no&thorn;ing hele</L>
<L>Witnesse on Myda wil &yogh;e heere &thorn;e tale /</L>
<L N="952">Ovide amonges o&thorn;er &thorn;inges smale</L>
<L>Setthe myda hadde vnder his longe heris</L>
<L>Growynge vp his heed two assis eeres</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche vice he hidde as he best might</L>
<L N="956">fful sotilly from euery mannes sight
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="241"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="362"></L>
<L>&thorn;at saf his wijf &thorn;er wist of it no mo</L>
<L>he loued hire most and trusted to hire also</L>
<L>he preyde hire most &thorn;at vnto no creature</L>
<L N="960">Sche scholde not tellen of his disfigure</L>
<L>Sche swor him nay for al &thorn;is world to wynne /</L>
<L>Sche wolde do &thorn;at vylanye or &thorn;at synne<MILESTONE N="103a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> 112</NOTE></L>
<L>To make hire housbonde han so foul a name</L>
<L N="964">ffor reproeuyng of him and foule schame</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles hir &thorn;oughte &thorn;at sche dyde</L>
<L>That sche so longe scholde a counseil hyde</L>
<L>hir &thorn;ought it sat so sore aboute hir herte</L>
<L N="968">That needely som word hir most asterte</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;e sche dorste tellen it no man</L>
<L>Doun to a mareys faste sche ran</L>
<L>Til sche cam &thorn;er hir herte was a fyre</L>
<L N="972">And as a bytore bumli&thorn; in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Sche leyde hire mou&thorn; vnto &thorn;e water doun</L>
<L>Bewreye me nought &thorn;ou water with &thorn;y soun</L>
<L>Quod sche to &thorn;e I telle it and nomo</L>
<L N="976">Myn housebonde ha&thorn; longe asses eeres tuo</L>
<L>Now is myn herte al hool now it is oute</L>
<L>I might no lenger kepe it out of doute</L>
<L>here may &yogh;e see &thorn;ough we a tyme abyde</L>
<L N="980">Yet out it moot we mowe no counseil hyde</L>
<L>The remenant of &thorn;e tale if ye wol heere</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; Ovyde and &yogh;e may it leere</L>
<L>This knight of which my tale is specially</L>
<L N="984">Whan &thorn;at he saugh he mighte nought come &thorn;erby</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to seye what wommen louen most</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne his herte sorwful was &thorn;e gost</L>
<L>But home he go&thorn; he mighte nought soiourne</L>
<L N="988">&thorn;e day was come &thorn;at homward most he tourne</L>
<L>And in his way it happed him to ryde</L>
<L>In alle his care vnder a forest syde</L>
<L>Wher he saugh on one daunce go</L>
<L N="992">Of ladyes xxiiij. and &yogh;it mo
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="242"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="363"></L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e daunce he drowe him yerne</L>
<L>In hope &thorn;at som wisdam schulde he lerne</L>
<L>But certeinly or he cam fully &thorn;ere /</L>
<L N="996">Vanyssched was &thorn;e daunce he nyste not where /</L>
<L>No creature saugh he &thorn;at bar lyf</L>
<L>Saue in &thorn;e grene he saugh sittyng a wijf<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A foulere wight &thorn;er may non deuyse</L>
<L N="1000">Agayn &thorn;e knight &thorn;e olde wijf gan arise</L>
<L>And seyde sire knight here for&thorn; ne li&thorn; no wey</L>
<L>Telle me what &thorn;at &yogh;e seken by &yogh;oure fey</L>
<L>Perauenture it may &thorn;e bettre be /</L>
<L N="1004">This olde folk konne mochel &thorn;ing quod sche /</L>
<L>my leeue mooder quod &thorn;is knight certeyn</L>
<L>I am but ded but if &thorn;at I can seyn</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing it is &thorn;at wommen most desire</L>
<L N="1008">Cowde &yogh;e me wisse I wolde wel quyte youre hyre</L>
<L>Plight me &thorn;i trou&thorn;e here in myn hand quod sche</L>
<L>The nexte &thorn;ing &thorn;at I require &thorn;e</L>
<L>Thou schalt it do if it lye in &thorn;y might</L>
<L N="1012">And I wil telle it &yogh;ou or it be night</L>
<L>haue here my trou&thorn;e quod &thorn;e knight I graunte</L>
<L>Than quod sche I may me wel auaunte</L>
<L>Thy lyf is sauf for I wol stonde &thorn;er by</L>
<L N="1016">vpon my lijf &thorn;e queen wole seye as I</L>
<L>lat se which is &thorn;e proudest of hem alle</L>
<L>That were&thorn; on a kerchef or a calle</L>
<L>&thorn;at dar say nay of &thorn;at I schal &yogh;ou teche</L>
<L N="1020">lat vs go for&thorn; wi&thorn;oute lenger speche</L>
<L>Tho rowned sche a pystel in his eere</L>
<L>And bad him to be glad and haue no feere</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ey be comen to &thorn;e court &thorn;is knight</L>
<L N="1024">Seyde he hadde holde his day as he hadde hight</L>
<L>And redy was his answere as he sayde</L>
<L>fful many a noble wijf and many a mayde</L>
<L>And many a wydowe for &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben wyse /</L>
<L N="1028">The queen hir seluen sittyng as Iustyse
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="243"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="364"></L>
<L>Assembled ben his answer for to heere</L>
<L>And afterward &thorn;is knight was bode appeere</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e knight schal telle in audience</L>
<L N="1032">To euery wight comanded was scilence</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing &thorn;at worldly wommen louen meest</L>
<L>This knight ne stood nat stille as do&thorn; a beest<MILESTONE N="104a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> 113</NOTE></L>
<L>But to his question anon answerde /</L>
<L N="1036">With manly vois &thorn;at al &thorn;e court/ it herde</L>
<L>My liege lady generally quod he /</L>
<L>Womman desire&thorn; to haue soueraynte</L>
<L>As wel ouer hir housbonde and hire loue</L>
<L N="1040">And for to be in maystrie him aboue</L>
<L>&thorn;is is &yogh;oure most desyr &thorn;ough &yogh;e me kille</L>
<L>Do&thorn; as you list I am heer at your wille</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e court ne was &thorn;er wijf ne mayde</L>
<L N="1044">Ne wydewe &thorn;at contraried &thorn;at he sayde</L>
<L>But seyden he was wor&thorn;y han his lijf</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word vp sterte &thorn;at olde wijf</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;e knight saugh sittyng on &thorn;e grene</L>
<L N="1048">Mercy quod sche my souerayn lady queene/</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at youre court departe do me right</L>
<L>I taughte &thorn;is answere vnto &thorn;is knight</L>
<L>ffor which he plighte me his treu&thorn;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1052">The firste &thorn;ing I wolde of him requere</L>
<L>he wolde it do if it lay in his might</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e court &thorn;an preye I &thorn;e sire knight</L>
<L>Quod sche &thorn;at &thorn;ou me take vnto &thorn;i wijf</L>
<L N="1056">ffor wel &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at I haue kept &thorn;y lijf</L>
<L>If I seye fals sey nay vpon &thorn;y fey</L>
<L>This knight answerde allas and weylowey</L>
<L>I wot right wel &thorn;at such was my biheste /</L>
<L N="1060">ffor goddes loue chese a newe requeste/</L>
<L>Tak al my good and lat my body go</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;an quod sche I schrewe vs bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough &thorn;at I be foule and olde and poure</L>
<L N="1064">I nolde for al &thorn;e metal ne for oure
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="244"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="365"></L>
<L>&thorn;at vnder er&thorn;e is graue or li&thorn; aboue</L>
<L>But if &thorn;at I &thorn;y wyf were and &thorn;i loue</L>
<L>My loue quod he nay my dampnacion</L>
<L N="1068">Allas &thorn;at eny of my nacion</L>
<L>Scholde euere so foule y-disparaged be</L>
<L>But al for nought &thorn;e ende is &thorn;is &thorn;at he<MILESTONE N="104b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Constreyned was he nedes moste hire wedde</L>
<L N="1072">And take&thorn; &thorn;is olde wijf and go&thorn; to bedde</L>
<L>Now wolden some men seyn perauenture</L>
<L>That for my necgligence I do no cure</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ou &thorn;e Ioye and &thorn;e array</L>
<L N="1076">That at &thorn;e feste was &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L>To which &thorn;ing schortly answere I schal</L>
<L>I seye &thorn;er was no ioye ne feste at al</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas but heuynesse and mochil sorwe</L>
<L N="1080">ffor priuely he wedded hire on a morwe</L>
<L>And al day after hidde him as an owle /</L>
<L>So wo was him his wijf loked so foule</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e sorwe &thorn;e knight hadde in his &thorn;ought</L>
<L N="1084">Whan he was with his wyf a bedde brought</L>
<L>he walwe&thorn; and torne&thorn; to and fro</L>
<L>his olde wijf lay smylyng eueremo</L>
<L>And seide O dere housbonde o benedicite</L>
<L N="1088">ffare&thorn; euery knight &thorn;us with his wijf as &yogh;e</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is &thorn;e lawe of king arthures hous</L>
<L>Is euery knight of his loue &thorn;us daungerous</L>
<L>I am &yogh;our owne loue and eek &yogh;oure wijf</L>
<L N="1092">I am sche which &thorn;at saued ha&thorn; &yogh;oure lijf</L>
<L>And certes &yogh;it dede I &yogh;ou neuer vnright</L>
<L>Why fare &yogh;e &thorn;us wi&thorn; me &thorn;e ferste night</L>
<L>&yogh;e faren like a man &thorn;at hadde lost his wit</L>
<L N="1096">ffy what is my gilt for godes loue tel it</L>
<L>And it schal ben amended if I may</L>
<L>Amended quod &thorn;is knight nay nay</L>
<L>That wil nat ben amended neueremo</L>
<L N="1100">&thorn;ou art so lo&thorn;ly and so olde also
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="245"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="366"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to comen of so lowh a kynde</L>
<L>That litel wonder is &thorn;ough I walwe &amp; wynde</L>
<L>So wolde god myn herte wolde breste</L>
<L N="1104">Is &thorn;is quod sche &thorn;e cause of &yogh;oure vnreste;</L>
<L>&yogh;e&middot; certeinly quod he no wonder is</L>
<L>Now sire quod sche I cou&thorn;e amende al &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="105a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> 114</NOTE></L>
<L>If &thorn;at me liste or it were dayes &thorn;re</L>
<L N="1108">So wel &yogh;e mighte bere &yogh;ou vnto me</L>
<L>&para; But for &yogh;e speken of such gentilesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nota bene de Nobilitate</NOTE></L>
<L>As is descended out of alle richesse /</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;erfore schulden &yogh;e be gentil men</L>
<L N="1112">Such erregance nys nat wor&thorn; an hen</L>
<L>lo who &thorn;at most is vertuous alway</L>
<L>Preuy and aperte and most ende&thorn; ay</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e gentil dedes &thorn;at he can</L>
<L N="1116">And take him for &thorn;e grettest gentil man</L>
<L>Crist wole we clayme of him oure gentilnesse</L>
<L>Nat of oure eldres for here olde richesse</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough &thorn;ey &yogh;eue vs alle here heritage</L>
<L N="1120">ffor which we clayme to be of heigh parage</L>
<L>&yogh;et may &thorn;ey not beque&thorn;e for no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>To non of vs here vertuous lyuyng</L>
<L>That made hem gentil men y-called be</L>
<L N="1124">And bad vs folwen hem in such degre</L>
<L>Wel can &thorn;e wise poete of fflorence</L>
<L>That highte dante speke in &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>Lo in swich maner ryme is dauntes tale</L>
<L N="1128">fful seelde vp rise&thorn; by his branches smale</L>
<L>Prowesse of man for god of his prowesse /</L>
<L>Wil &thorn;at of him we clayme oure gentilnesse</L>
<L>ffor of oure eldres may we no&thorn;ing clayme</L>
<L N="1132">But temperel &thorn;ing &thorn;at we may hurte and mayme</L>
<L>Ek euery wight wot &thorn;is as wel as I</L>
<L>If gentilesse were plaunted naturelly</L>
<L>Vnto a certein linage doun &thorn;e lyne</L>
<L N="1136">Pryue and aperte &thorn;anne wolde &thorn;ey neuer fyne
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="246"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="367"></L>
<L>To don of gentilesse &thorn;e faire office</L>
<L>&thorn;ey mighten do no vylanye ne vice</L>
<L>Tak fyre and bere it in &thorn;e derkest hous</L>
<L N="1140">Bitwixe &thorn;is and &thorn;e mount of Caucasous</L>
<L>And lat men schette &thorn;e dores and go &thorn;enne</L>
<L>&yogh;et wol &thorn;e fyr as faire lye and brenne<MILESTONE N="105b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &thorn;ough a &thorn;ousand men might it beholde</L>
<L N="1144">his office naturel ay wol it holde /</L>
<L>vp peril of lyf til &thorn;at it dye /</L>
<L>here may &yogh;e se wel how &thorn;at genterie /</L>
<L>Is not annexed to possession</L>
<L N="1148">Si&thorn;&thorn;e folk do nat here operacion</L>
<L>alwey as do&thorn; &thorn;e fir lo in his kinde</L>
<L>ffor god it wot men may ful often fynde</L>
<L>A lordes sone do schame and vilanye</L>
<L N="1152">And he &thorn;at wol haue pris of his gentrie</L>
<L>ffor he was boren of a gentil hous</L>
<L>And hadde his eldres noble and vertuous</L>
<L>And nyl himseluen do no gentil dedes</L>
<L N="1156">Ne folwe his gentil ancestre &thorn;at ded is</L>
<L>he nys nat gentil be he duk or eerle</L>
<L>ffor vyleyns synful dedes make a cheerle</L>
<L>ffor gentilnesse nys but reneute</L>
<L N="1160">Of &thorn;in ancestres for here beaute</L>
<L>Which is a strong &thorn;ing for &thorn;i persone</L>
<L>The gentilesse come&thorn; fro god allone</L>
<L>Thanne come&thorn; oure verray gentilesse of grace</L>
<L N="1164">It was no&thorn;ing byque&thorn;e vs wi&thorn; oure place /</L>
<L>&thorn;inke&thorn; how noble as sei&thorn; valerius</L>
<L>Was &thorn;ilke Tullius hostilius</L>
<L>That out of pouert ros to heigh noblesse</L>
<L N="1168">Rede&thorn; Senec/ and rede&thorn; eek Boesse /</L>
<L>&thorn;er schulde &yogh;e seen expres &thorn;at it no dredis</L>
<L>That he is gentil &thorn;at do&thorn; gentil dedis</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore deere housebonde I &thorn;us conclude</L>
<L N="1172">Al were it &thorn;at myn ancestres were rude
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="247"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="368"></L>
<L>&yogh;et may &thorn;at heye god and so hope I</L>
<L>Graunte me grace to lyue vertuously</L>
<L>Thanne am I gentil whan &thorn;at I begynne</L>
<L N="1176">To lyuen vertuously and weyuen synne</L>
<L>And &thorn;er as ye of pouert me repreue</L>
<L>The hihe god on whom &thorn;at we bileeue<MILESTONE N="106a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>for</I> 115a</NOTE></L>
<L>In wilful pouert chese to leese his lijf<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota de paupertate</NOTE></L>
<L N="1180">And certes euery man and mayde and wijf</L>
<L>May vnderstonde ihesu heuen king</L>
<L>Ne wolde not chese a vicious lyuyng</L>
<L>Glad pouert is an honest &thorn;ing certeyn</L>
<L N="1184">&thorn;is wille Senec/ and o&thorn;er clerkes sein</L>
<L>Who so &thorn;at holt him payed of his pouert</L>
<L>I holde him riche al hadde he nought cert</L>
<L>he &thorn;at coueyte&thorn; is a pouere wight</L>
<L N="1188">ffor he wolde han &thorn;at nys nat in his might</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at nought ha&thorn; ne coueyte&thorn; to haue</L>
<L>Is riche al &thorn;ough men holde him but a knaue</L>
<L>Verray pouert is synne proprely</L>
<L N="1192">Iuuenal sei&thorn; of pouert myrily</L>
<L>The pouere man whan he go&thorn; by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;e &thorn;eues he may synge and play</L>
<L>Pouert is hatel good and as I gesse /</L>
<L N="1196">A ful gret brynger out of busynesse</L>
<L>A gret amender eek of Sapience</L>
<L>To him &thorn;at lacke&thorn; it in pacience</L>
<L>Pouert is &thorn;is al &thorn;ough it seme alenge</L>
<L N="1200">Possession &thorn;at no wight wol chalenge</L>
<L>Pouert ful often whan a man is lowe</L>
<L>Make&thorn; his god and eek himself to knowe</L>
<L>Pouert a spectacle is as &thorn;inke&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1204">&thorn;urgh which he may his verray freendes se</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore syn &thorn;at I you nought greue</L>
<L>Of my pouerte nomore me repreue</L>
<L>Now sire of eelde &yogh;e reproeue me</L>
<L N="1208">And certes sire &thorn;ough non auctorite
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="248"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="369"></L>
<L>Were in no book / &yogh;e gentil of honour</L>
<L>Seyn &thorn;at men schulde an old wijf do fauour</L>
<L>And clepe him fader for &yogh;our gentilnesse /</L>
<L N="1212">And auctours schal I fynden as I gesse /</L>
<L>Now &thorn;er &yogh;e seyn &thorn;at I am foul and olde</L>
<L>Than drede &yogh;ou nought to ben a cokewolde<MILESTONE N="106b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor fil&thorn;e and hel&thorn;e al so mote I &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1216">Ben grete wardeyns vpon chastite</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles syn I knowe &yogh;oure delyt</L>
<L>I schal fulfille your worldly appetyt</L>
<L>Chees now quod sche on of &thorn;ese &thorn;inges tweye /</L>
<L N="1220">To han me foule and olde til &thorn;at I deye</L>
<L>And be to &yogh;ow a trewe humble wijf</L>
<L>And neuere &yogh;ow displese in alle my lijf</L>
<L>Or elles &yogh;e wol haue me &yogh;ong and fair</L>
<L N="1224">And take &yogh;our auenture of &thorn;e repair</L>
<L>That schal come to your hous by cause of me</L>
<L>Or in som o&thorn;er place wel may be</L>
<L>Now chees &yogh;our seluen whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &yogh;ou like&thorn;</L>
<L N="1228">&thorn;is knight auysed him and sore sike&thorn;</L>
<L>But atte laste he seyde in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>My lady and my loue and wijf so deere</L>
<L>I putte me in &yogh;oure wise gouernance</L>
<L N="1232">Chese&thorn; &yogh;our self which may be most plesance</L>
<L>And most honour to yow and me also</L>
<L>I do no force &thorn;e whe&thorn;er of &thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>ffor as &yogh;ou like&thorn; it suffice&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1236">&thorn;anne haue I gote of &yogh;ou maystrie quod sche</L>
<L>Syn I may cheese and gouerne as me list</L>
<L>&yogh;e certes wijf quod he I holde it for best</L>
<L>kisse me quod sche we be no lenger wro&thorn;e /</L>
<L N="1240">ffor by my trou&thorn;e I wol be to yow bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to sein / to be bo&thorn;e fair and good</L>
<L>I pray to god &thorn;at I mote steruen wood</L>
<L>But I to &yogh;ou be also sad and trewe /</L>
<L N="1244">As euer was wijf syn &thorn;at &thorn;e world was newe
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="249"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="370"></L>
<L>And but I be to morwe as fair to seene</L>
<L>As eny lady emperice or queene /</L>
<L>&thorn;at is bitwen &thorn;e est and eek &thorn;e weste /</L>
<L N="1248">Do wi&thorn; my lijf and de&thorn; right as &yogh;ou leste</L>
<L>Cast vp &thorn;e curteyne loke how it is /<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>bottom of leaf</I> 106</NOTE></L>
<L>And whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e knight sawh al &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sche so fair was and so &yogh;ong &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="1252">ffor ioye he hente hir in his armes tuo</L>
<L>his herte ba&thorn;ed in a ba&thorn; of blisse</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand tyme a rowe he gan hire kisse</L>
<L>And sche obeyed him in euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="1256">That mighte doon him pleisance or likyng</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;ey lyued vnto here lyues ende</L>
<L>In perfyt ioye and ihesu crist vs sende</L>
<L>housbondes meke &yogh;onge and freissche abedde</L>
<L N="1260">And grace to ouerlede hem &thorn;at we wedde</L>
<L>And eek I pray to Ihesu schorte here lyues</L>
<L>That wol not be gouerned by here wyues</L>
<L N="1263">And olde and angry nyggardes of dispence</L>
<L>God send hem sone a verray pestilence</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000278.tif" N="250"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="371">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e ffrere /</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This wor&thorn;y lymytour &thorn;is noble ffrere<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Incipit pro|logus ffratris</NOTE></L>
<L>he made alway lowrynge cheere</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e somnour but for honeste</L>
<L N="1268">No vyleynes word as &yogh;it spak he /</L>
<L>But atte laste he seyde vnto &thorn;e wijf</L>
<L>Dame goode god &yogh;if &yogh;ou right good lijf</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han touched heer al so mote I &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1272">In scole matier gret difficulte</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han seid mochel &thorn;ing right wel I seye</L>
<L>But dame heere as we ryden by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>Vs nede&thorn; nat to speken but of game</L>
<L N="1276">And late auctoritees a goddes name</L>
<L>To preching &amp; to scole eek of clergie /</L>
<L>But if it like vnto &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>I wol &yogh;ou of a somnour telle a game</L>
<L N="1280">Parde &yogh;e may wel knowe by &thorn;e name</L>
<L>That of no somnour may no good be sayd</L>
<L>I pray &thorn;at non of &yogh;ou be yuele payd</L>
<L>A somnour is a romere vp and doun</L>
<L N="1284">Wi&thorn; amendement of fornicacioun</L>
<L>And is y-bete at euery townes ende<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Oure host &thorn;o spak a sire &yogh;e scholde ben heende</L>
<L>And curteys as a man of &yogh;our astat</L>
<L N="1288">In companye we wille no debat /</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; &yogh;oure tale and late&thorn; &thorn;e somnour be</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e somnour lat him seye to me</L>
<L>What so him list whan it com&thorn; to my lot</L>
<L N="1292">By god I schal him quiten euery grot</L>
<L>I schal him telle such a gret honour</L>
<L>It is to be a flateryng lymytour</L>
<L>And eek of ful many an o&thorn;er cryme</L>
<L N="1296">Which nede&thorn; nat/ rehersen at &thorn;is tyme</L>
<L>And his office I schal him telle y-wys</L>
<L>Oure host answerde pees nomore of &thorn;is</L>
<L>And afterward he seyde vnto &thorn;e frere /</L>
<L N="1300">Telle for&thorn; &yogh;oure tale my leue mayster deere
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000279.tif" N="251"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="372">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynneth &thorn;e &para; ffreres tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom &thorn;er was dwellyng in Couentre</L>
<L>An erchedekne a man of heih degre</L>
<L>That boldely dide execuci&omacr;n</L>
<L N="1304">In punysschyng of fornicacion</L>
<L>Of wichcraf and eek of Bawderie</L>
<L>Of diffamacion and auoutrie</L>
<L>Of chirche reeues and of testamentes</L>
<L N="1308">Of contractes and of lak of sacramentes</L>
<L>Of vsure and Symonye also</L>
<L>But certes lecchours dede he grettest wo</L>
<L>They scholden syngen if &thorn;ey were hent</L>
<L N="1312">And smale ty&thorn;eres weren foule y-schent</L>
<L>If eny person wolde vpon hem pleyne</L>
<L>Ther might astirte him no pecunial peyne</L>
<L>ffor smale ty&thorn;es and eek for smal offrynge</L>
<L N="1316">he made &thorn;e poeple spitously to synge</L>
<L>ffor or &thorn;e bisschop caught hem wi&thorn; his hook</L>
<L>They weren in &thorn;e Erchedeknes book</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne hadde he &thorn;urgh his Iurdiction</L>
<L N="1320">Power to don on hem correction</L>
<L>he hadde a somnour redy to his hande<MILESTONE N="116a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A sleyere boy was non in engelande</L>
<L>ffor sotilly he hadde his especiaile</L>
<L N="1324">That taughte him where &thorn;at him mighte auayle</L>
<L>he coude spare of lecchours on or tuo</L>
<L>To techen him to foure and twenty mo</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough &thorn;is somnour wood were as an hare</L>
<L N="1328">To telle his harlottrie I wil not spare
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="252"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="373"></L>
<L>ffor we ben oute of here correction</L>
<L>They han of vs no Iuresdiction</L>
<L>We neuer schullen terme of alle hire lyues</L>
<L N="1332">Petur so ben &thorn;e wommen of &thorn;e Styues</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;is Somnour y-putt out of oure cure</L>
<L>Pees with meschance and with mysauenture</L>
<L>Thus seyde oure host and let him telle his tale</L>
<L N="1336">Now telle&thorn; for&thorn; and late &thorn;e somnour gale</L>
<L>Ne spare&thorn; nought myn oughne maister deere</L>
<L>This false &thorn;eef &thorn;is somnour quod &thorn;e ffrere /</L>
<L>hadde alwey bawdes redy to his hond</L>
<L N="1340">As eny hauke to lure in Engelond</L>
<L>That telle him al &thorn;e secre &thorn;at &thorn;ey knewe</L>
<L>ffor here aqueintance was nat come of newe</L>
<L>&thorn;ey weren his approwours priuely</L>
<L N="1344">he tok himself a gret profyt &thorn;erby</L>
<L>his maister knew nat alwey what he wan</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen maundement of a lewed man</L>
<L>he coude somne on peyne of cristes curs</L>
<L N="1348">And &thorn;ey were ynly gladde to fille his purs</L>
<L>And made him grete festes atte nale</L>
<L>And right as Iudas hadde purses smale</L>
<L>And was a &thorn;eef right swich a &thorn;eef was he</L>
<L N="1352">his mayster hadde but half his dewete</L>
<L>he was if I schal &yogh;iuen him his laude</L>
<L>A theef and eek a sompnour and a baude</L>
<L>he hadde eek wenches of his retenue</L>
<L N="1356">That whe&thorn;er &thorn;at sir Roberd or sir huwe</L>
<L>Or Iohn or Rauf or who &thorn;at it were<MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That lay by hem &thorn;at tolde it in his eere</L>
<L>Thus was &thorn;e wenche and he of oon assent</L>
<L N="1360">And he wolde fecche a feyned maundement</L>
<L>And somne hem to &thorn;e Chapitre bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>And pile &thorn;e man and late &thorn;e wenche go</L>
<L>&thorn;anne wolde he seye I schal freend for &thorn;y sake</L>
<L N="1364">Do strike &thorn;e out of oure lettres blake
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="253"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="374"></L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ar nomore as in &thorn;is cas trauayle</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i frend &thorn;er I &thorn;e may auayle</L>
<L>Certein he knew of briberies mo</L>
<L N="1368">&thorn;an possible is to telle &yogh;ou vnto</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;is worlde is dogge for no bowe</L>
<L>That knew an hurt deer from an old bite kowe</L>
<L>Than &thorn;at &thorn;is sompnour knew a sleigh lecchour</L>
<L N="1372">Or avouter or elles a paramour</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at was &thorn;e fruyt of alle &thorn;e rent</L>
<L>Therfore on it he sette al his entent</L>
<L>And so bifelle &thorn;at ones on a day</L>
<L N="1376">This somnour euer waytyng on his pray</L>
<L>Rode for to somne an old wijf a ribibe</L>
<L>ffeynyng a cause for he wolde bribe</L>
<L>And happede &thorn;at he seigh byfore hym ryde /</L>
<L N="1380">A gay yoman vnder a forest syde</L>
<L>A bowe he bar and arwes bright and keene</L>
<L>he hadde vppon a courtepy of grene /</L>
<L>An hatte vppon his heed wi&thorn; frenges blake</L>
<L N="1384">Sire quod &thorn;is Sompnour hail and wel atake /</L>
<L>Welcome quod he and euery good felawe</L>
<L>Whider ridestow vnder &thorn;is greene schawe</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is &yogh;eman wilt &thorn;ou fer to day</L>
<L N="1388">This somnour him answerde and seyde nay</L>
<L>here faste by quod he is myn entente</L>
<L>To ryden for to reysen vp a rente /</L>
<L>It longe&thorn; to my lordes dewete</L>
<L N="1392">Art &thorn;ou &thorn;anne a baillif &yogh;e quod he</L>
<L>he dorste nou&yogh;t for verray fil&thorn;e and schame<MILESTONE N="117a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seie &thorn;at he was a somnour for &thorn;e name</L>
<L>Depardieux quod &thorn;is &yogh;oman dere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1396">&thorn;ou art a bailly and I am ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>I am vnknowen as in &thorn;is cuntre</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in aqueintance I wil preye &thorn;e</L>
<L>And eek of bre&thorn;erhode if &thorn;at &thorn;ou leste</L>
<L N="1400">I haue golde and siluer in my cheste
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="254"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="375"></L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;e happed come in-to oure schire</L>
<L>Al schal be &thorn;in right as &thorn;ou wolt desyre</L>
<L>Graunt mercy quod &thorn;is somnour by my fei&thorn;</L>
<L N="1404">Euerich in o&thorn;eres hond his trou&thorn;e lei&thorn;</L>
<L>ffor to be swore bro&thorn;er til &thorn;ey deye</L>
<L>and wi&thorn; &thorn;at word &thorn;ey ryden for&thorn; here weye</L>
<L>This somnour wi&thorn; &thorn;at was so /</L>
<L N="1408">As ful of venym ben &thorn;is wary-angles</L>
<L>And euer enquiryng vpon euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he wher is &yogh;oure dwellyng</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er day if I scholde &yogh;ou seche</L>
<L N="1412">This &yogh;oman him answerde in softe speche</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he fer in &thorn;e Nor&thorn; cuntre</L>
<L>Wher as I hope som tyme I schal &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Or we departe I schal &thorn;e so wel wisse</L>
<L N="1416">That of myn hous schalt &thorn;ou neuer misse /</L>
<L>Now bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;is sompnour I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>Teche me whil we ryden by &thorn;e way /</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at &yogh;e ben a baillyf as am I</L>
<L N="1420">Som subtilte telle me fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>In myn office how &thorn;at I may most wynne</L>
<L>And spare&thorn; not for conscience ne synne</L>
<L>But as my bro&thorn;er tell me how do &yogh;e</L>
<L N="1424">Now by my trou&thorn;e bro&thorn;er deere seyde he</L>
<L>As I schal tellen &thorn;e a fei&thorn;ful tale /</L>
<L>My wages ben ful streyte and smale /</L>
<L>My lord is hard to me and daungerous</L>
<L N="1428">And my office ful laborious</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by extorciouns I lyue<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e I [take] al &thorn;at men wil me &yogh;iue</L>
<L>Algate be sleigte or violence</L>
<L N="1432">ffrom &yogh;eer to &yogh;er I wynne al my dispence /</L>
<L>I can no bettre tellen fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>Now certes quod &thorn;is sompnour so fare I</L>
<L>I spare not to take god it wot</L>
<L N="1436">But if it be to heuy or to hoot
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="255"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="376"></L>
<L>What I may gete in counseil priuely</L>
<L>No maner conscience of &thorn;at haue I</L>
<L>Ner myn extorcion I might no&yogh;t lyuen</L>
<L N="1440">Of swiche iapes wil I nat be schriuen</L>
<L>Stomake ne fro conscience knowe I noon</L>
<L>I schrewe &thorn;ese schriftefadres euerichon</L>
<L>Wel be we mette by god and by seint Iame</L>
<L N="1444">But leeue bro&thorn;er telle me &thorn;anne &thorn;y name</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;is somnour in &thorn;is mene while</L>
<L>This &yogh;eman gan a litel for to smyle</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he wiltow &thorn;at I &thorn;e telle</L>
<L N="1448">I am a steue my dwellyng is in helle</L>
<L>And heer I ryde aboute my purchasyng</L>
<L>To wite wher men wil &yogh;if me eny &thorn;ing</L>
<L>my purchace is to fette of alle my rente</L>
<L N="1452">loke how &thorn;ou rydest for &thorn;e same entente</L>
<L>To wynne good &thorn;ou rekkest neuer how</L>
<L>Right so fare I for ryde wolde I now</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e worldes ende for a preye</L>
<L N="1456">A quod &thorn;is somnour benedicite what &yogh;e seye</L>
<L>I wende &yogh;e were a yoman trewely</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han a mannes schappe as wel as I</L>
<L>han &yogh;e a figure &thorn;anne determinat</L>
<L N="1460">In helle &thorn;er &yogh;e ben in &yogh;oure estat</L>
<L>Nay certeinly quod he &thorn;er han we noon</L>
<L>But whan vs like&thorn; we can take vs oon</L>
<L>Or elles make &yogh;ou wene we ben schape</L>
<L N="1464">Som tyme [like] a man or like an ape /</L>
<L>Or lik an aungel can I ryde or go<MILESTONE N="118a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It is no wonder &thorn;ing &thorn;ough it be so</L>
<L>A lousy iogulour can deceyue &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1468">And par de &yogh;it can I more craft &thorn;an he /</L>
<L>Why quod &thorn;is somnour ryde &yogh;e &thorn;anne or gon</L>
<L>In sondry schappe and nat alwey in oon</L>
<L>ffor we quod he wille vs swich forme make</L>
<L N="1472">As most able is oure prayes for to take
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="256"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="377"></L>
<L>What make&thorn; &yogh;ou to han al &thorn;is labour</L>
<L>fful many a cause leeue sire somonour</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is feend but al &thorn;ing ha&thorn; tyme</L>
<L N="1476">The day is schort and it is passed prime</L>
<L>And &yogh;et ne wan I no &thorn;ing in &thorn;is day</L>
<L>I wil entende to wynnyng if I may</L>
<L>And nat entende oure wittes to declare</L>
<L N="1480">ffor bro&thorn;er myn &thorn;i witte is al to bare</L>
<L>To vnderstonde &thorn;ough I tolde hem &thorn;e</L>
<L>But for &thorn;ou axest whi labouren we</L>
<L>ffor somtyme ben we goddes instrumentz</L>
<L N="1484">And menes to do his comaundementz</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at him list vpon his creatures</L>
<L>In diuerse acte and in diuers figures</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen him we han no might certayn</L>
<L N="1488">If &thorn;at him liste to stonden &thorn;er agayn</L>
<L>And som time at oure praye han we leue</L>
<L>Only &thorn;e body and not &thorn;e soule greeue /</L>
<L>Witnesse on Iob whom &thorn;at we dyden wo</L>
<L N="1492">And som tyme han we might of bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>&thorn;is is to seyn of soule and body eeke</L>
<L>And som tyme we ben suffred for to seeke</L>
<L>vpon a man and do his soule vnreste</L>
<L N="1496">Nat his body and al is for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Whan he wi&thorn;stonde&thorn; oure temptacion</L>
<L>It is a cause of his saluacion</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at it was not oure entente</L>
<L N="1500">he schulde be sauf but &thorn;at we wolde him hente</L>
<L>And som tyme be we seruantz vn-to man<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As &thorn;e erchebisschope seint Dunstan</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e apostles seruant/ was I</L>
<L N="1504">&yogh;et telle&thorn; me quod &thorn;e somnour fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>Make &yogh;e &yogh;ow newe bodyes &thorn;us alwey</L>
<L>Of elementz &thorn;e feend answerde nay</L>
<L>Som tyme we feyne and som tyme we arise /</L>
<L N="1508">Wi&thorn; dede bodyes in ful sondry wise
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="257"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="378"></L>
<L>And speke as renabely and faire and wel</L>
<L>As to &thorn;e phitonessa dede Samuel /</L>
<L>And &yogh;it wol some men say it was nat he</L>
<L N="1512">I do no force of &yogh;oure diuinite</L>
<L>But o &thorn;ing warne I &thorn;e I wil nat Iape</L>
<L>Thou wilt algates wite how we be schape /</L>
<L>&thorn;ou schalt her aftirward my bro&thorn;er deere</L>
<L N="1516">Come wher &thorn;e neede&thorn; nat of me to leere</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou schalt by &thorn;in owne experience</L>
<L>Come in-to &thorn;e chayer rede &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>Bet &thorn;an virgile whil he was a lyue</L>
<L N="1520">Or dante also now lat vs ryde blyue</L>
<L>ffor I wil holde company wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Til it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ou forsake me</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;is somnour &thorn;at schal nat betyde</L>
<L N="1524">I am a &yogh;eman knowe is ful wyde</L>
<L>my trou&thorn;e wil I holde to &thorn;e as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey &thorn;ou were &thorn;e deuyl Sathanas</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e wil I holde to my bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1528">As I am sworne and eche of vs to o&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor to be trewe bro&thorn;er in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>And bro&thorn;er we gon to oure purchas</L>
<L>Take &thorn;ou &thorn;y part what men &thorn;e wole yiue</L>
<L N="1532">And I schal myn &thorn;us may we bo&thorn;e lyue</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at eny of vs haue more &thorn;an o&thorn;er</L>
<L>lat him be trewe and parte it wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>I graunte quod &thorn;e deuyl by my fay</L>
<L N="1536">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word &thorn;ey ryden for&thorn; here way</L>
<L>And right at &thorn;entryng of &thorn;e tounes ende<MILESTONE N="119a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To which &thorn;e somnour schop him for to wende</L>
<L>They say a carte &thorn;at charged was with hey</L>
<L N="1540">Which &thorn;at a cartere drof for&thorn; on his wey</L>
<L>Deep was &thorn;e wey for whiche &thorn;e carte strood</L>
<L>This cartere smot and striued as he were wood</L>
<L>hayt brok hayt scot what spare we for &thorn;e stones</L>
<L N="1544">The feend quo&thorn; he &yogh;ow fecche bo&thorn;e body and bones /
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="258"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="379"></L>
<L>As ferfor&thorn;ly as euere were &yogh;e foled</L>
<L>So moche woo as I haue for &yogh;ou &thorn;oled</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuel haue al bo&thorn;e hors and cart and hey</L>
<L N="1548">&thorn;oughte &thorn;is somnour he schulle we haue a pley</L>
<L>And neer &thorn;e feend he drough as nought ne were</L>
<L>fful priuely and rouned in his eere</L>
<L>herkne my bro&thorn;er herkne by &thorn;y fei&thorn;</L>
<L N="1552">herestow nat how &thorn;e cartere sei&thorn;</L>
<L>hente it anone for he ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen &thorn;e</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e hey and carte and eek his caples &thorn;re /</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e deuyl god not neuer a del</L>
<L N="1556">It is not his entente truste me wel</L>
<L>Aske him &thorn;iself if &thorn;ou nat trowest me</L>
<L>Or elles stynte a while and &thorn;ou schalt se</L>
<L>This carter &thorn;akked his hors on &thorn;e croupe /</L>
<L N="1560">And &thorn;ey bygonne to drawe and to stoupe /</L>
<L>hayt now quod he &thorn;at Ihesu crist &yogh;ou blisse</L>
<L>And alle his hondywerk bo&thorn;e more and lesse /</L>
<L>&thorn;at was wel twight myn owne lyard boy</L>
<L N="1564">I pray god saue &thorn;e and seinte Loy.</L>
<L>Now is my carte out/ of &thorn;e slough par de</L>
<L>lo bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;e feend what tolde I &thorn;e /</L>
<L>here may ye see myn oughne deere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1568">The carle spak o &thorn;ing but he &thorn;ought ano&thorn;er</L>
<L>late vs go for&thorn; abouten oure viage</L>
<L>here wynne I no&thorn;ing vpon cariage</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey comen somwhat out of &thorn;e toun</L>
<L N="1572">&THORN;is somnour to his bro&thorn;er gan to roun</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he here wone&thorn; an old rebekke<MILESTONE N="119b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That hadde almost as leef to leese hire necke</L>
<L>As for to &yogh;iue a peny of hire good</L>
<L N="1576">I wil haue twelue pens &thorn;ough &thorn;at sche be wood</L>
<L>Or I wille sompne hire to oure office</L>
<L>And &yogh;it god woot of hire knowe I no vice</L>
<L>But for &thorn;ou canst nat as in &thorn;is contre</L>
<L N="1580">Wynne &thorn;i coste tak here ensample of/ me
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="259"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="380"></L>
<L>This somnour clappe&thorn; at &thorn;e wydowes gate</L>
<L>Com out he seyde &thorn;ou olde viritrate</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;ou hast som frere or prest wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1584">Who clappe&thorn; seyde &thorn;is wijf benedicite</L>
<L>God saue &yogh;ou sire what is &yogh;our swete wille</L>
<L>I haue quod he a somonur of &thorn;e here a bille</L>
<L>vp peyne of cursyng loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be</L>
<L N="1588">To morwe biforn oure erchedekenes kne</L>
<L>To answere to &thorn;e court of certein &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Now lord quod sche crist ihesu heuen kinges</L>
<L>So wisly helpe me as I ne may</L>
<L N="1592">I haue ben syk and &thorn;at ful many a day</L>
<L>I may nat gon so fer quod sche ne ryde</L>
<L>But I be deed so prike&thorn; it in my syde /</L>
<L>May I nat axe a libel sire somonour</L>
<L N="1596">And answere &thorn;ere by my procutour</L>
<L>To swich a &thorn;ing as men wolde appose me /</L>
<L>&yogh;is quod &thorn;is somnour pay anon lat se</L>
<L>Twelue pens to me and I wil &thorn;e aquite</L>
<L N="1600">I schal no profyt haue &thorn;er-by but lite</L>
<L>My maister ha&thorn; &thorn;e profyt/ and nat I</L>
<L>Come of and late me ryden hastily</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me twelue [pens] I may no lenger tarye</L>
<L N="1604">twelue quod sche lady seinte marie</L>
<L>So wisly help me out of care and synne</L>
<L>&thorn;is wyde world &thorn;ough &thorn;at I scholde it wynne</L>
<L>Ne haue I not xij. pens wi&thorn;inne myn holde</L>
<L N="1608">&yogh;e knowen wel &thorn;at I am pouer and olde</L>
<L>ky&thorn;e &yogh;oure almesse on me pouere wrecche<MILESTONE N="120a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nay &thorn;anne quod he &thorn;e foule feend me fecche</L>
<L>If I &thorn;e excuse &thorn;ough &thorn;ou scholde be spilt</L>
<L N="1612">Allas quod sche god wot I haue no gilt</L>
<L>Pay me quod he or by &thorn;e swete seint anne</L>
<L>As I wol bere a-way &thorn;y newe panne /</L>
<L>ffor dette which &thorn;ou owest me of old</L>
<L N="1616">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou madest &thorn;in housbond kukkewold
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="260"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="381"></L>
<L>I preyde at home for &thorn;y correction</L>
<L>Thow lixt quod sche by my sauacion</L>
<L>Ne was I neuer or now wydewe ne wijf</L>
<L N="1620">Somoned vnto your court in al my lijf</L>
<L>Ne neuer I nas but of my body trewe /</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e deuel blake and rowe of hewe</L>
<L>yeue I &thorn;y body and my panne</L>
<L N="1624">And whan &thorn;e deuyl herde hir curse so</L>
<L>vpon hir knees he seyde in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Now mabely myn owne mooder deere</L>
<L>It is &yogh;our wille in ernest &thorn;at &yogh;e seye</L>
<L N="1628">&thorn;e deuyl quod sche fette him or he deye /</L>
<L>And panne and al but he wil him repente</L>
<L>Nay olde stot &thorn;at is not myn entente</L>
<L>Quo&thorn; &thorn;is somnour for to repente me</L>
<L N="1632">ffor any &thorn;ing &thorn;at I haue had of &thorn;e</L>
<L>I wolde I hadde &thorn;y smok and euery clo&thorn;</L>
<L>Now bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;e deuyl be nat wro&thorn;</L>
<L>&thorn;y body and &thorn;is panne is myn by right</L>
<L N="1636">&thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn; me to helle yet to night</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;ou schalt knowen of oure priuete</L>
<L>More &thorn;an a mayster of diuinite</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word &thorn;is foule feend him hent</L>
<L N="1640">Body and soule he with &thorn;e deuyl went</L>
<L>Where &thorn;at somnours han here heritage</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at made after his ymage</L>
<L>Mankynde saue and gyde vs alle and some</L>
<L N="1644">And leeue &thorn;is somnour good man to bycome</L>
<L>lordinges I cou&thorn;e han told &yogh;ou quod &thorn;is frere<MILESTONE N="120b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hadde I had leysir for &thorn;is somnour heere</L>
<L>After &thorn;e tixte of crist poule and Iohn</L>
<L N="1648">And of oure o&thorn;er doctours many oon</L>
<L>Suche peynes &thorn;at &yogh;oure hertes might agrise</L>
<L>Al be it so no tonge may deuyse /</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at I might a &thorn;ousand wynter telle</L>
<L N="1652">&thorn;e peyne of &thorn;ilke cursed hous of helle
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="261"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="382"></L>
<L>But for to kepe vs fro &thorn;at cursed place</L>
<L>Wake&thorn; and praye&thorn; ihesu for his grace</L>
<L>So kepe vs fro &thorn;e temptour Sathanas</L>
<L N="1656">herkne&thorn; &thorn;is word be war as in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>&thorn;e leoun sitte in his awayte alway</L>
<L>To sle &thorn;e Innocent if &thorn;at he may</L>
<L>Dispose&thorn; ay &yogh;our hertes to wi&thorn;stonde</L>
<L N="1660">&thorn;e feend &thorn;at &yogh;ou wolde make &thorn;ralle and bonde</L>
<L>he may nat tempten yow ouer your might</L>
<L>ffor crist wille be &yogh;our champion and knight</L>
<L N="1663">And preye&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is somnour him repente</L>
<L>Of his mysdede or &thorn;at &thorn;e feend him hente</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Her ende&thorn; &thorn;e ffrere his tale /</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="262">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="383">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Somnour in his styrop heyhe stood<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 120, <I>back</I></NOTE></L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is frere his herte was so wood</L>
<L>That lik an aspen leef he quok for Ire</L>
<L N="1668">lordynges quod he but o &thorn;ing I desire /</L>
<L>I &yogh;ou beseche &thorn;at of &yogh;our curtesye</L>
<L>Si&thorn; &yogh;e han herde &thorn;is false frere lye</L>
<L>As suffre&thorn; me I may a tale telle</L>
<L N="1672">This frere boste&thorn; &thorn;at he knowe&thorn; helle/</L>
<L>And god wot &thorn;at it is litel wonder</L>
<L>ffreres and feendes ben but litel asonder</L>
<L>ffor parde &yogh;e han. ofte tyme herd telle/</L>
<L N="1676">how &thorn;at a frere rauyssched was in helle</L>
<L>In spirit ones by avisioun</L>
<L>And as an aungel ladde him vp and doun</L>
<L>To schewen him &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at &thorn;er were</L>
<L N="1680">In alle &thorn;e place saugh he nat a ffrere<MILESTONE N="121a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er folk he saugh ynowe in woo</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;is aungel spak &thorn;e frere &thorn;o</L>
<L>Now sire quod he han freres such a grace /</L>
<L N="1684">That non of hem schal come to &thorn;is place /</L>
<L>&YOGH;is quod &thorn;is aungel many a milioun</L>
<L>And vnto Sathanas he hadde him doun</L>
<L>And now ha&thorn; Sathanas sai&thorn; he a taile</L>
<L N="1688">Bradder &thorn;an of &thorn;e Caryk is &thorn;e saile</L>
<L>hold vp &thorn;i tayl &thorn;ou Satanas quod he /</L>
<L>Schew for&thorn; &thorn;in ersand lat &thorn;e frere se /</L>
<L>Wher is &thorn;e neste of ffreres in &thorn;is place</L>
<L N="1692">And er &thorn;at half a forlong wey of space
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="263"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="384"></L>
<L>Right so as bees swermen out of an hyue</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e deueles ers &thorn;ey gon to dryue</L>
<L>Twenty &thorn;ousand freres on a route</L>
<L N="1696">And &thorn;oughte helle swarme al aboute</L>
<L>And camen a&yogh;ein as faste as &thorn;ey mighte gon</L>
<L>And in his ers &thorn;ey crepeden euerichon</L>
<L>he clapte his tayl a&yogh;ein and lay stille</L>
<L N="1700">This frere whan he loked hadde his fille</L>
<L>vppon &thorn;is tormentes of &thorn;is sory place /</L>
<L>his spirit god restored of his grace /</L>
<L>Vnto his body a&yogh;ein and he awok</L>
<L N="1704">But na&thorn;eles for feere &yogh;it he quok</L>
<L>So was &thorn;e deueles ars ay in his mynde</L>
<L>&thorn;at is his heritage of verray kinde</L>
<L>God saue &yogh;ow alle saue &thorn;is cursed frere /</L>
<L N="1708">My prologe wol I ende in &thorn;is manere /
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000292.tif" N="264"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="385">
<HEAD>&para; Here begynne&thorn; &thorn;e Somnours tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrdynges &thorn;er is in york schire / as I gesse</L>
<L>A mersshy countre called Holdernesse</L>
<L>In which &thorn;er wente a lymytour aboute /</L>
