<L>To make vs for oure olde synnes wepe</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at &thorn;y tale make vs not to sleepe<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Pausacio</NOTE></L>
<L>Telle vs som mery &thorn;ing of auentures /</L>
<L N="16">&yogh;oure termes &yogh;oure coloures &yogh;oure figures</L>
<L>keep hem in store til so be &yogh;e enditen</L>
<L>by stile as when &thorn;at men to kinges writen</L>
<L>Speke&thorn; so plein at &thorn;is tyme I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>&thorn;at we may vnderstonde what &yogh;e say<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Pausacio</NOTE></L>
<L>This wor&thorn;i clerk benignely answerde</L>
<L>Oft quod he I am vnder &yogh;our &yogh;erde</L>
<L>&yogh;e han of vs as now &thorn;e gouernance</L>
<L N="24">And &thorn;erfore wol I do yow obeissance
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="283"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="404"></L>
<L>As fer as reson axe&thorn; hardel</L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou telle a tale which &thorn;at I</L>
<L>lernede at paradovse of a wor&thorn;i clerk</L>
<L N="28">As preued by his wordes and his werk</L>
<L>he is now deed and nayled in his cheste</L>
<L>I pray to god to &yogh;iue his soule reste<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Pausacio</NOTE></L>
<L>ffraunces Petrake &thorn;e laureat poete</L>
<L N="32">highte &thorn;is clerk whos retorique sweete<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a leaf out]</NOTE></L>
<L>[enlumynede al ytaille / of Poyetrie<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="66a"></L>
<L>as Lynyan dide / of Philosophie</L>
<L>or lawe / or other arte par-ticulere</L>
<L N="36">but deth that wol not suffre vs / duelle here</L>
<L>but as it were / a twynkelyng of an yghe</L>
<L>hem both hath sleyn / and alle shulle we dye</L>
<L>but forthe to tellen / of this worthy man</L>
<L N="40">that taughte me this tale / as I bigan</L>
<L>I sey that he first / wight highe stile enditeth</L>
<L>er he the body of his tale writeth</L>
<L>a proheme / in the which discerneth he</L>
<L N="44">the mounde / and of Saluce the contre</L>
<L>and spekith of Appenyn the hilles highe</L>
<L>that ben the boundes / of west Lumbardie</L>
<L>and of the Mounte Vesulus / in special</L>
<L N="48">where as the Poo / out of a wel smal</L>
<L>takith his first spryngyng / and his sours</L>
<L>and holte even streighte wey / his cours</L>
<L>to Emel-ward / to Ferrare / and to Venyse</L>
<L N="52">the which a longe thing were / to devise</L>
<L>and trewely / as to my Iugement</L>
<L>me thinkith it a thing / inpertynent</L>
<L>save he wol conveye / his matiere</L>
<L N="56">but this is the tale / which ye shal hiere</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endith the clerke of Oxonford his prolog</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="284">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="405">
<HEAD>And next folwyng bigynneth his tale of Gresilde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS Arch. Seld. B. 14, <I>on leaf</I> 66</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was in the weste side of ytaylle</L>
<L>down at the rote / of Vesulus the colde</L>
<L>a lusty playne / habundaunte of vitaylle</L>
<L N="60">where many a toure and towne / thow maist biholde</L>
<L>that founded were / in tyme of faders olde</L>
<L>and many a-nother / dilectable sight</L>
<L N="63">and Saluces / this noble contre hight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">A Marques whilom / was lord of that londe</L>
<L>as were his worthi eldres / him bifore</L>
<L>and obeysaunte / ay redy to his honde</L>
<L N="67">were alle his liges / both lesse and more<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="66b"></L>
<L>thus in delite he lyved / and hath done yore</L>
<L>biloued and drad / thorugh favour of fortune</L>
<L N="70">both of his lordis / and of his comune</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="71">&para; Therwith he was / to speken of lynage</L>
<L>the gentilest borne / of al Lumbardye</L>
<L>a faire persone and strong / and yonge of age</L>
<L N="74">and ful of honoure / and of curtesie</L>
<L>discrete I-nough / his contre for to gye</L>
<L>saue in som thingis / he was to blame</L>
<L N="77">and Walter was this yonge lord-is name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="78">&para; I blame him thus / that he considred noughte</L>
<L>in tyme comyng / what myghte him betide</L>
<L>but on his lust present / was al his thoughte</L>
<L N="81">as for to havke and hounte / on euery side</L>
<L>wel nygh al other cures / lete he slide</L>
<L>and eke he nolde / and that was worst of alle</L>
<L N="84">wedde no wiff / for aughte that myghte bifalle
<PB REF="00000312.tif" N="285"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="406"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oonly that poynt / his peple bare soore<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14.]</NOTE></L>
<L>that flokmele on a day / they to him wente</L>
<L>and oon of hem / that wysest was of loore</L>
<L N="88">or ellis that the lord / best wolde assente</L>
<L>that he shulde telle him / what his peple mente</L>
<L>or ellis coude he wel / shewe suche matire</L>
<L N="91">he to the Marques seide / as ye shulle hire</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="92">&para; O noble Marques / youre humanite</L>
<L>assurith vs / and yevith vs hardynesse</L>
<L>as offte as tyme / is of necessite</L>
<L N="95">that we to yow mow telle / oure hevynesse</L>
<L>acceptith now lord / of youre gentilnesse</L>
<L>that we with pitevous herte / to yow pleyne</L>
<L N="98">and lete not youre eeris / my voys disdeyne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="99">&para; Al haue I nought to done / in this matire</L>
<L>more than a-nother man hath / in this place</L>
<L>yit for as meche / as ye my lord / so dere</L>
<L N="102">haue alwey shewed to me / favoure and grace</L>
<L>I dar the better axe of yow / a space<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="67a"></L>
<L>of audience / to shewe oure requeste</L>
<L N="105">and ye my lord / to do right as ye leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="106">&para; For certes lord / so wel vs likith yow</L>
<L>and al youre werke / and haue done that we]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Arch. Seld. B. 14 <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne coude nought vs self deuysen how<NOTE PLACE="marg">Corpus MS</NOTE><MILESTONE N="130a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="109">We mighte lyue in more felicite</L>
<L>Saue o &thorn;ing lord if it &yogh;our wille be</L>
<L>That for to be a wedded man &yogh;ou leste</L>
<L N="112">&thorn;en were &yogh;oure peple in souereyn hertes reste<NOTE PLACE="inter">[No breaks in the Corpus MS between the stanzas.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="113">Bowe&thorn; &yogh;oure nekke vnder &thorn;at blisful &yogh;ok</L>
<L>Of souerainte and nought of seruise</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at men clepe spousaile or wedlok</L>
<L N="116">And &thorn;enke&thorn; lord amonges &yogh;oure &thorn;oughtes wise
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="286"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="407"></L>
<L>[how that oure dayes pas / in sondre gise]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Arch. Seld. B. 14.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough we slepe or wake or renne or ryde</L>
<L N="119">Ay flee&thorn; &thorn;e tyme and wol noman abyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="120">And &thorn;ough &yogh;oure greene &thorn;oughtes floure as &yogh;it</L>
<L>In crepe&thorn; age alway as stille as stoon</L>
<L>And deth manace&thorn; euery age and smyt</L>
<L N="123">In ech astat for &thorn;er askape&thorn; noon</L>
<L>And also certein as we knowe echoon</L>
<L>&thorn;at we schulle deye as vncertein we alle</L>
<L N="126">Ben of &thorn;at day &thorn;at de&thorn; schal on vs falle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="127">&para; Accepte&thorn; &thorn;anne of vs &thorn;e trewe entent</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuere &yogh;it ne refused &yogh;our heste</L>
<L>And we lord if &thorn;at &yogh;e wile assent</L>
<L N="130">To chese &yogh;ou a wijf in schort tyme atte leste</L>
<L>Borne of &thorn;e gentilest and of &thorn;e meste</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;is lond so &thorn;at it oughte seme</L>
<L N="133">honour to god and &yogh;ou as we can deme</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="134">&para; Delyuer vs out of al &thorn;is busy dede</L>
<L>And tak a wijf for hihe goddes sake</L>
<L>ffor if it so bifelle as god forbede</L>
<L N="137">&thorn;at &thorn;orugh &yogh;oure de&thorn; &yogh;our lynage schulde slake</L>
<L>And &thorn;at a straunge successour schulde take</L>
<L>&yogh;oure heritage. o wo were vs on lyue</L>
<L N="140">wherfore we pray &yogh;ow hastily to wyue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="141">&para; here meke preyer and here pitous cherte</L>
<L>Made &thorn;e marquys herte haue pite</L>
<L>[ye wol quod he / myn owne peple dere]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Arch. Seld. B. 14.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="144">To &thorn;at I neuer erst &thorn;ou&yogh;te streyne me</L>
<L>I me reioysed of my liberte</L>
<L>That selden tyme is founden mariage<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="147">Ther I was free I moste be in seruage
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="287"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="408"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="148">&para; But na&thorn;eles I se &yogh;our trewe entente</L>
<L>And truste vpon &yogh;our witte and haue don ay</L>
<L>Wherfore with al my fre wille I wil assente</L>
<L N="151">To wedde me as sone as euer I may</L>
<L>But &thorn;er as &yogh;e han profred me to day</L>
<L>To chese me a wijf I &yogh;ou relesse</L>
<L N="154">&thorn;at choys and pray &yogh;ou of &yogh;oure profre cesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="155">&para; ffor I wot &thorn;at children often ben</L>
<L>vnlike here eldres hem byfore</L>
<L>Bounte com&thorn; al of god not of &thorn;e stren</L>
<L N="158">Of which &thorn;ei be&thorn; engendred and y-bore</L>
<L>I truste in goddes bounte and &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>my mariage and myn astat and reste</L>
<L N="161">I him bitake he may do as him leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="162">&para; lat me alone in chesyng of my wijf</L>
<L>But I &yogh;ou pray and charge vpon &yogh;our lijf</L>
<L>That charge vpon my bak I wil endure</L>
<L N="165">&thorn;at what wijf I take I &thorn;e assure</L>
<L>To worschipe hire whil &thorn;at hire lijf may dure</L>
<L>In word in werk bo&thorn;e heere and euerywhere</L>
<L N="168">As sche an Emperoures doughter were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="169">&para; And for&thorn;ermore &thorn;is schal &yogh;e swere &thorn;at &yogh;e</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein my choys schulle neuer grucche ne stryue</L>
<L>ffor si&thorn;&thorn;e I schal forgo my liberte</L>
<L N="172">At &yogh;oure request as euer mote I &thorn;riue</L>
<L>[there as myn herte is sett / there woll I wyve]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Arch. Seld. B. 14.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And but &yogh;e wol assente in such manere</L>
<L N="175">I pray &yogh;ou speke nomore of &thorn;is matiere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="176">&para; Wi&thorn; hertly wil &thorn;ey sweren and assenten</L>
<L>To al &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;er seyde no wight nay</L>
<L>Beseking him of grace or &thorn;at &thorn;ei wenten</L>
<L N="179">&thorn;at he wolde graunten hem a certein day
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="288"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="409"></L>
<L>Of his spousaile as sone as euer he may</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;et alway &thorn;e poeple somwhat dredde</L>
<L N="182">lest &thorn;at &thorn;is marquys no wijf wolde wedde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="183">He graunted hem a day such as him leste<MILESTONE N="131a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On which he wolde be wedded sikerly</L>
<L>And sayde he dide al &thorn;is at &thorn;air requeste</L>
<L N="186">And &thorn;ay wi&thorn; humble entent ful buxomly</L>
<L>knelyng vpon here knees ful reuerently</L>
<L>him &thorn;onkyng alle and &thorn;us &thorn;ay haue an ende</L>
<L N="189">Of here entent and home a&yogh;ein &thorn;ei wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="190">And her vpon he to his officers</L>
<L>Comande&thorn; for &thorn;e feste to purveye</L>
<L>And to his priue knightes and squyers</L>
<L N="193">Such charge &yogh;af as him list on hem leye</L>
<L>And &thorn;ay to his comaundement obeye</L>
<L>And ech of hem do&thorn; al his diligence</L>
<L N="196">To do vnto &thorn;e feste reuerence</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART II.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; Prima pars</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="197">NOught fer fro &thorn;e paleys honurable</L>
<L>Wher as &thorn;e marquys schop his mariage</L>
<L>Ther stood a throop of &thorn;e Cite delitable</L>
<L N="200">In which &thorn;at pore folk of &thorn;at village</L>
<L>hadden here bestes and here herbergage</L>
<L>And of here labour toke here sustienance</L>
<L N="203">After &thorn;e er&thorn;e &yogh;af hem abundance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="204">Among &thorn;is pore folk &thorn;er dwelled a man</L>
<L>Which was holde pouerest of hem alle</L>
<L>But heihe god sum tyme sende can</L>
<L N="207">his grace in to a litel oxe stalle</L>
<L>Ianicula men of &thorn;at throop him calle</L>
<L>A doughter hadde he fair ynough to sight</L>
<L N="210">&para; And Grisildis &thorn;is &yogh;onge mayden highte
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="289"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="410"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="211">But for to speke of verteuous beaute</L>
<L>&thorn;anne was sche on &thorn;e fairest vnder sonne</L>
<L>fful pouerely y-fostered was sche</L>
<L N="214">No likerous lust was in hire herte ronne</L>
<L>Wel oftere of &thorn;e welle &thorn;an of &thorn;e tonne</L>
<L>Sche drank for sche wolde vertues plese</L>
<L N="217">Sche knew wel labour but non ydel ese</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="218">&para; But &thorn;ough &thorn;is mayden tendre were of age</L>
<L>&yogh;et in &thorn;e brest of hire virginite<MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ther was y-closed rype and scharpe corage</L>
<L N="221">And in a gret reuerence and charite</L>
<L>hire olde pouere fader fostred sche</L>
<L>A fewe scheep spynnyng on feld sche kepte</L>
<L N="224">Sche nolde not ben ydel til &thorn;at sche slepte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">And whan sche com homward sche wolde bringe</L>
<L>Wortes or o&thorn;er herbes tymes ofte</L>
<L>The which sche schredde and seth for hir lyuynge</L>
<L N="228">And made hir bed ful harde and no &thorn;ing softe /</L>
<L>And ay sche kepte hir faderes lif on lofte</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; euery obeissance and diligence</L>
<L N="231">That childe may do to faderes reuerence /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="232">&para; vpon Grisilde &thorn;e pouer creature</L>
<L>fful ofte si&thorn;e &thorn;e marquys sette his ye</L>
<L>As he on huntyng rood perauenture</L>
<L N="235">And whan it fell &thorn;at he might hir aspye</L>
<L>he not wi&thorn; wantoun lokyng of folye</L>
<L>his eyen caste on hire but in sad wyse</L>
<L N="238">vpon hir cheere he wolde him ofte auyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="239">&para; Commendyng in his herte hir wommanhede</L>
<L>And eek hire vertu passyng any wight</L>
<L>Of so &yogh;ong age as wel in cheere as in dede</L>
<L N="242">ffor &thorn;ough &thorn;e poeple haue no gret insight
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="290"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="411"></L>
<L>In vertu he considerd ful right</L>
<L>hir bounte and disposed &thorn;at he wolde</L>
<L N="245">Wedde hir oonly if euer he wedde scholde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="246">The day of weddyng com but no wight can</L>
<L>Telle what womman &thorn;at it schulde be</L>
<L>ffor which meruayle wondre&thorn; many man</L>
<L N="249">And seyde whan &thorn;ey were in pryuyte</L>
<L>Wil nat oure lord &yogh;it leue his vanite</L>
<L>Wil he nat wedde allas allas &thorn;e while</L>
<L N="252">Why wol he &thorn;us himself and vs begile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="253">But na&thorn;eles &thorn;is marquys ha&thorn; don make</L>
<L>Of gemmes sette in golde and in asure</L>
<L>Broches and rynges for Grisildes sake<MILESTONE N="132a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="256">And of hire clo&thorn;ing tok he &thorn;e mesure</L>
<L>Of a mayden like to hire stature</L>
<L>And eek of o&thorn;er ornamentes alle</L>
<L N="259">That vnto such a weddyng schulde falle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="260">&para; &thorn;e tyme of vnderne of &thorn;e same day</L>
<L>Approche&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is weddyng schulde be</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e paleys but was in aray</L>
<L N="263">Bo&thorn;e halle and chambre eche in his degre</L>
<L>houses of offices stuffed wi&thorn; plente</L>
<L>Ther maystow se of deynteuous vitayle</L>
<L N="266">That may be founde as feer as last ytayle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="267">&para; This real marquys richely arrayed</L>
<L>lordes and ladyes in his companye</L>
<L>The which vnto &thorn;e feste were prayed</L>
<L N="270">And of his retenue &thorn;e bachelrie</L>
<L>With many a soun of sondry melodye</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e vilage of which I tolde</L>
<L N="273">In &thorn;is array &thorn;e righte wey ha&thorn; holde
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="291"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="412"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="274">&para; Grisilde of &thorn;is god wot ful Innocent</L>
<L>&thorn;at for hire schapen al &thorn;is array was</L>
<L>To fecche water at a welle is wente</L>
<L N="277">And come&thorn; home as sone as euer sche may</L>
<L>ffor wel sche hadde herd seyde &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L>That marquys schulde wedde and if sche might</L>
<L N="280">Sche wolde fayn han seyn some of &thorn;at sight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="281">&para; Sche &thorn;ought I wille wi&thorn; o&thorn;re maydens stonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at ben my felawes in oure dore and se</L>
<L>The marquisesse and &thorn;erfore wol I fonde</L>
<L N="284">To do at home as sone as it may be</L>
<L>&thorn;e labour which &thorn;at longe&thorn; vnto me</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne I may at leysyr hire by-holde</L>
<L N="287">If sche &thorn;is wey vnto &thorn;e castel holde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="288">&para; And as sche wolde ouer hire &thorn;resshfold gon</L>
<L>The marquys cam and gan hir for to calle</L>
<L>And sche sette doun hir water potte anon&middot;</L>
<L N="291">Bysyde &thorn;is &thorn;resshfolde of &thorn;is oxe stalle<MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And doun vpon hir knees sche gan to falle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sad contynance and knele&thorn; stille</L>
<L N="294">Til sche had herd what was &thorn;e lordes wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">&thorn;is &thorn;oughtful marquys spak vnto &thorn;is mayde</L>
<L>fful soberly and seyde in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Wher is &yogh;our fader Grisildis he sayde</L>
<L N="298">And sche wi&thorn; reuerence in humble chere</L>
<L>Answerde lord he is al redy heere</L>
<L>And in sche go&thorn; wi&thorn;oute lenger lette</L>
<L N="301">And to &thorn;e marquys hir fader sche fette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="302">&para; he by &thorn;e hond &thorn;an took &thorn;is olde man/</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us whan he him hadde a syde</L>
<L>Ianycala I ney&thorn;er may ne can</L>
<L N="305">lengere &thorn;e plesaunce of myn herte hyde
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="292"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="413"></L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;ou vouche saff what so betyde</L>
<L>&thorn;y doughter I wol take or &thorn;at I wende</L>
<L N="308">As for my wijf vnto hire lyues ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="309">&para; &thorn;ou louest me I wot it wel certain</L>
<L>And art my fei&thorn;ful liege man y-bore</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at like&thorn; me I dar wel sayn</L>
<L N="312">It like&thorn; &thorn;e and specialliche &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;at poynt as I haue sayd bifore</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt vnto &thorn;at purpos drawe</L>
<L N="315">To take me as for &thorn;i sone in lawe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="316">&para; The sodeyn cas &thorn;e man astoned so</L>
<L>&thorn;at reed he wax abayst and al quakynge</L>
<L>he stood vnne&thorn;e he sayde worde no mo</L>
<L N="319">But only &thorn;us lord quod he my willynge</L>
<L>Is as &yogh;e wille nought a&yogh;eins &yogh;our likynge</L>
<L>I wole no&thorn;ing &yogh;e be my lord so dere</L>
<L N="322">But as &yogh;ou luste gouerne&thorn; &thorn;is matiere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="323">&para; &yogh;it wol I quod &thorn;is marquys softely</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;i chambre I and &thorn;ou and sche.</L>
<L>haue a collacion and wostow why</L>
<L N="326">ffor I wil axe if &thorn;at hire wille be</L>
<L>To be my wijf and reule hire after me<MILESTONE N="133a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And al &thorn;is schal be doon in &thorn;i presence</L>
<L N="329">I wol not speke out of &thorn;in audience</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="330">&para; And in here chambre whil &thorn;ay were aboute</L>
<L>here tretees which &thorn;at &yogh;e schul after heere</L>
<L>&thorn;e poeple cam in to &thorn;e hous wi&thorn;oute</L>
<L N="333">And wondred hem in hor honeste manere</L>
<L>And tentyfly sche kepte hir fader deere</L>
<L>But outerly Grysildis wondre might</L>
<L N="336">ffor neuer erst ne saugh sche such a sight
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="293"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="414"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="337">&para; No wonder is &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at sche were astoned</L>
<L>To se so gret a geste in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Sche neuer was to suche gestes woned</L>
<L N="340">ffor which sche loked wi&thorn; ful pale face</L>
<L>But schortly for&thorn; &thorn;is mater for to chace</L>
<L>This aren &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at &thorn;e marquys sayde</L>
<L N="343">To his benigne verray fey&thorn;ful mayde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="344">&para; Grisilde he seyde &yogh;e schule wel vnderstonde</L>
<L>It like&thorn; to &yogh;oure fader and to me</L>
<L>That I &yogh;ou wedde and eek it may so stonde</L>
<L N="347">As I suppose &yogh;e wil &thorn;at it so be</L>
<L>But &thorn;ese demaundes ax I first quod he</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;at si&thorn;&thorn;en it schal be don in hasty wise</L>
<L N="350">Wille &yogh;e assente or elles &yogh;ou auyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="351">I seye &thorn;is be redy wi&thorn; good herte</L>
<L>To al my lust and &thorn;at I frely may</L>
<L>As me best &thorn;inke&thorn; do &yogh;ou knowe or smerte</L>
<L N="354">And neuer &thorn;e to grucche it night ne day</L>
<L>And eek whan I say &yogh;e ne say not nay</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er by word ne by frounyng contynance</L>
<L N="357">Swere &thorn;is and heer I swere oure alliance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="358">&para; Weddyng vpon &thorn;is word quakyng for drede</L>
<L>Sche sayde lord vndigne or vnwor&thorn;y</L>
<L>Am I to &thorn;at ilke honour &thorn;at &yogh;e me bede</L>
<L N="361">But as &yogh;e wille &yogh;oure self right so wol I</L>
<L>And here I swere &thorn;at neuer willyngly</L>
<L>In werk ne &thorn;ought I nyl &yogh;ou disobeye<MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="364">ffor to be deed &thorn;ough me were lo&thorn; to deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">&para; This is ynough Grisylde myn quod he</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; wi&thorn; a ful sobre cheere</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;e dore and after &thorn;at cam sche</L>
<L N="368">And to &thorn;e poeple he sayde in &thorn;is manere
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="294"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="415"></L>
<L>&thorn;is is my wyf quod he &thorn;at stonde&thorn; heere</L>
<L>honoure&thorn; hire and loue&thorn; eek I preye</L>
<L N="371">Who so me loue&thorn; &thorn;er is no more to seye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="372">And for &thorn;at no&thorn;ing of hir olde gere</L>
<L>Sche scholde bringe in to his hous he bad</L>
<L>That wommen schulde dispoylen hire right &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="375">Of which &thorn;is ladyes were no&thorn;ing glad</L>
<L>To handle hire clo&thorn;es wher Inne sche was clad</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles &thorn;is mayden bright of hewe</L>
<L N="378">ffro foot to heed &thorn;ey clo&thorn;ed han al newe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="379">&para; hire heres han &thorn;ey kempte &thorn;at layn vntressed</L>
<L>fful rudely and wi&thorn; hire fyngres smale</L>
<L>&thorn;ay tyred hire heed &thorn;at longe rudely lay dressed</L>
<L N="382">Of hire array what schulde I make a tale</L>
<L>Sche is now fair of hew &thorn;at arst was pale</L>
<L>vnne&thorn;e &thorn;e poeple hir knew for hir fairnesse</L>
<L N="385">Whan sche transmewed was in such richesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="386">&para; This marquys ha&thorn; hir wedded wi&thorn; a ryng</L>
<L>Brou&yogh;t for &thorn;e same cause and hire sette</L>
<L>vpon an hors snow whyt and wel amblyng</L>
<L N="389">And to &thorn;e paleys or he lenger lette</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioyful poeple &thorn;at hire ladde and mette</L>
<L>Conueyed hire and &thorn;us &thorn;e day &thorn;ay spende</L>
<L N="392">In reuel til &thorn;e sonne gan descende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="393">&para; And schortly for&thorn; &thorn;is tale for to chace</L>
<L>I seye &thorn;at to &thorn;is newe marquysesse</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; such fauour sent hire of his grace</L>
<L N="396">That it ne semed nought be kykenesse</L>
<L>That sche was born and fedde in iudenesse</L>
<L>As in a cote or in an Oxe stalle/</L>
<L N="399">But norisshed in an emperoures halle<MILESTONE N="134a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="295"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="416"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="400">&para; To euery wight sche woxen is so deere</L>
<L>And worschipful &thorn;at folk &thorn;er sche was bore</L>
<L>And from hire bur&thorn;e knewe hire &thorn;ere by &yogh;eere</L>
<L N="403">vnne&thorn;e trowede &thorn;ey but durst han swore</L>
<L>&thorn;at to Ianicle of which I spak byfore</L>
<L>Sche doughter nas for as by coueiture</L>
<L N="406">hem &thorn;oughte sche was ano&thorn;er creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="407">&para; ffor &thorn;ough euere vertuous was sche</L>
<L>Sche was encressed in such excellence</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ewes good y-sette in heih bounte</L>
<L>And so discrete and fair of eloquence</L>
<L>So benigne and digne of reuerence</L>
<L>And coude so &thorn;e poeples herte embrace</L>
<L N="413">&thorn;at ech hir loue&thorn; &thorn;at loke&thorn; on hir face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="414">&para; Not only of salues in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Pirplissched was &thorn;e bounte of hir name</L>
<L>But eek besyde in many a region</L>
<L N="417">If on sayde wel ano&thorn;er sayde &thorn;e same</L>
<L>So sprede&thorn; of hire heih bounte &amp; fame</L>
<L>That men and wommen als wel &yogh;onge as olde</L>
<L N="420">Gon to salice vpon hir to byholde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="421">&para; Thus Walter lowly nat but really</L>
<L>Wedded wi&thorn; fortunate honeste</L>
<L>In goddes pees lyue&thorn; ful esily</L>
<L N="424">At hom and outward grace ynough hadde he</L>
<L>And for he saugh &thorn;at vnder lough degre</L>
<L>Was ofte vertu hyd &thorn;e poeple him helde</L>
<L N="427">A prudent man and &thorn;at is seyn ful seelde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="428">&para; Nat oonly &thorn;is Grisildis &thorn;urgh hir witte</L>
<L>Coude al &thorn;e fait of wyfly homlynesse</L>
<L>But eke whan &thorn;at &thorn;e cas requyred it</L>
<L N="431">The comun profyt coude sche redresse
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="296"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="417"></L>
<L>&thorn;er nas discorde rancour ne heuynesse</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at lond &thorn;at sche cou&thorn;e appese</L>
<L N="434">And wisly bringe hem alle in hertes eese</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Though &thorn;at hire housbonde absent were anon<MILESTONE N="134b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>If gentil men or o&thorn;er of hire countre /</L>
<L>Were wro&thorn;e sche wolde bringen hem at on</L>
<L N="438">So wys and rype wordes hadde sche /</L>
<L>And Iuggements of so gret equite</L>
<L>&thorn;at sche from heuen sent was as men wende</L>
<L N="441">&thorn;e poeple to plese and euery wrong to amende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="442">&para; Nat long tyme after &thorn;at &thorn;is Grisilde</L>
<L>Was wedded sche a dou&yogh;ter ha&thorn; y-bore</L>
<L>Al hadde hir leuer haue born a knaue childe</L>
<L N="445">Glad was &thorn;is marquys and his folk &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough a mayden childe come al bifore</L>
<L>Sche may vnto a knaue child atteyne</L>
<L N="448">Be lykened si&thorn;&thorn;e sche is not bareyne</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit ij<SUP>a</SUP> pars.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="449">Ther felle as it bifalle&thorn; tymes mo</L>
<L>When &thorn;at &thorn;is childe had souked but a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>This marquys in his herte longe&thorn; so</L>
<L N="452">To tempte his wyf hir sadnesse for to knowe</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne might out of his herte &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>&para; This merueylous desir his wijf to assaye</L>
<L N="455">Needeles god wot he &thorn;ought hir to affraye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="456">he hadde assayed hire ynough bifore</L>
<L>And fond hir euer good what needed it</L>
<L>hire for to tempte and alway more and more</L>
<L N="459">But as for me I seye &thorn;at euele it sitte</L>
<L>&thorn;ough some men it preyse for a subtil witte</L>
<L>To assaye a wijf whan &thorn;at it is no neede</L>
<L N="462">And putten hire in anguissche and in dreede
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="297"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="418"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="463">&para; ffor which &thorn;is marquys wrought in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>he com a night allone &thorn;er as sche lay</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sterne fate and wi&thorn; trouble cheere</L>
<L N="466">And seyde &thorn;us Grisilde quod he &thorn;at day</L>
<L>&thorn;at I &yogh;ou took out of &yogh;oure pore aray</L>
<L>And putte &yogh;ou in astat of heye noblesse</L>
<L N="469">&yogh;e haue nou&yogh;t forgeten as I gesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="470">&para; I seye Grisilde &thorn;is present dignite</L>
<L>In which I haue putte &yogh;ow as I trowe<MILESTONE N="135a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>make&thorn; &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t for&yogh;eteful for to be</L>
<L N="473">&thorn;at I &yogh;ou took in pouer astate ful lowe</L>
<L>ffor eny wele &yogh;e mote &yogh;oure selue knowe</L>
<L>Tak heed of euery word &thorn;at I &yogh;ou say</L>
<L N="476">&thorn;er nys no wight &thorn;at heere&thorn; it but we tway</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="477">&para; &yogh;e wote &yogh;oure selue wel how &thorn;at &yogh;e come here</L>
<L>In to &thorn;is hous &thorn;at nys nat longe ago</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough to me &yogh;e be right leeue and deere</L>
<L N="480">vnto my gentiles &yogh;e ben no&thorn;ing so</L>
<L>&thorn;ey say to hem it is gret schame and wo</L>
<L>ffor to be sogette and ben in seruage</L>
<L N="483">To &thorn;e &thorn;at art born of a smal vilage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="484">&para; And namely si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;y dou&yogh;ter was y-bore</L>
<L>This wordes han &thorn;ey spoke douteles</L>
<L>But I desire as I haue don byfore</L>
<L N="487">To lyue my lyf wi&thorn; hem in reste and pees</L>
<L>I may not in &thorn;is cas be recheles</L>
<L>I mot do wi&thorn; &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L N="490">Nou&yogh;t as I wolde but as my gentils leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="491">&para; And &yogh;it god wot &thorn;is is ful lo&thorn; to me</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles wi&thorn;outen &yogh;our wetynge</L>
<L>I wil nat do but &thorn;is wil I quod he</L>
<L N="494">That &yogh;e to me assent/ as in &thorn;is &thorn;inge
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="298"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="419"></L>
<L>Schewe now &yogh;our pacience as in werkynge</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e me hight and swor in &yogh;our village</L>
<L N="497">That day &thorn;at maked was our mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="498">&para; Whan sche had herd al &thorn;is sche nat ameued</L>
<L>Noy&thorn;er in word ne cheere ne contynance</L>
<L>ffor as it semed sche was nat agreued</L>
<L N="501">Sche sayde lord al li&thorn; in &yogh;our plesaunce</L>
<L>My childe and I wi&thorn; hertely obeissance</L>
<L>ben &yogh;oures al and &yogh;e mowe saue &amp; spille</L>
<L N="504">&yogh;oure owne &thorn;ing worki&thorn; after &yogh;our wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">&para; Ther may no &thorn;ing so god my soule saue</L>
<L>liken to &yogh;ou &thorn;at may displesen me</L>
<L>Ne I desyre no&thorn;ing for to haue<MILESTONE N="135b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="508">Ne drede for to lese saue oonly &thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;is wille is in myn herte and ay schal be</L>
<L>No leng&thorn;e of tyme or de&thorn; may &thorn;is deface</L>
<L N="511">Ne chaunge my corrage to ano&thorn;er place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="512">&para; Glad was &thorn;is marquys for hire answeryng</L>
<L>But &yogh;it he feigned as it were not so</L>
<L>Al dreery was his cheer as his lokyng</L>
<L N="515">Whan &thorn;at he schulde out/ of &thorn;e chambre go</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;is a forlong way or tuo</L>
<L>he priuely ha&thorn; tolde al his entente</L>
<L N="518">vnto a man and to his wijf him sente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="519">&para; A maner sergeant was &thorn;is priue man</L>
<L>The which he fei&thorn;ful often founden hadde</L>
<L>In &thorn;inges gret and eek such folk wel can</L>
<L N="522">Don execucion of &thorn;inges badde</L>
<L>The lord knew wel &thorn;at he him loued and dradde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is sergaunt knew his lordes wille</L>
<L N="525">In to &thorn;e chambur he stalked him ful stille
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="299"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="420"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="526">&para; Ma dame he sayde &yogh;e moote for&yogh;iue it me</L>
<L>Though I do &thorn;ing &thorn;e which I am constreyned</L>
<L>&yogh;e ben so wys &thorn;at ful wel knowe &yogh;e</L>
<L N="529">&thorn;at lordes heestes mowe not be feyned</L>
<L>&thorn;ey mowe wel be weyled or compleyned</L>
<L>But men moot needes to here lust obeye</L>
<L N="532">And so wol I &thorn;er nys nomore to seye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="533">&para; &thorn;is child am I comaunded for to take</L>
<L>And spak no more but out &thorn;e childe he hente</L>
<L>Dispitously and gan a cheere make</L>
<L N="536">As &thorn;ough he wold han slayn it or he wente</L>
<L>Grisildes mot al soffre and consente</L>
<L>And as a lombe sche sitte&thorn; meke &amp; stille</L>
<L N="539">And lete &thorn;is cruel sergant han his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="540">&para; Suspeccious was &thorn;e defame of &thorn;is man</L>
<L>Suspecte his face suspecte his word also</L>
<L>Suspecte &thorn;e tyme in which he &thorn;is bygan.</L>
<L N="543">Allas hir doughter &thorn;at sche loued so<MILESTONE N="136a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche wende he wolde haue slayen it right &thorn;o</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles sche nou&thorn;er weep ne siked</L>
<L N="546">Conformyng hire to &thorn;at &thorn;e marquys liked</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="547">&para; But atte laste speke sche bigan</L>
<L>And mekely sche to &thorn;e sergaunt preyed</L>
<L>So as he was a wor&thorn;y gentil man</L>
<L N="550">&thorn;at sche moste kisse hir childe or &thorn;at it deyde</L>
<L>And in hir barm &thorn;is litel child sche leyde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ful sadde face and gan &thorn;is childe to blisse</L>
<L N="553">And lulled it and after gan it kisse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="554">&para; And &thorn;us sche seyde in hire benigne vois</L>
<L>ffar wel my child I schal &thorn;e neuer se</L>
<L>But si&thorn; I haue &thorn;e marked wi&thorn; &thorn;e croys</L>
<L N="557">Of &thorn;ilke fader blessed mote &thorn;ou be
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="300"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="421"></L>
<L>&thorn;at for vs deyed vpon a crosse of tre</L>
<L>&thorn;y soule litel child I him bytake</L>
<L N="560">ffor &thorn;is night schalt &thorn;ou deye for my sake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="561">&para; I trowe to a norice in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>It hadde ben hard &thorn;is reu&thorn;e for to se</L>
<L>Wel might a mooder &thorn;an han cryed allas</L>
<L N="564">But na&thorn;eles so sadde stedefast was sche</L>
<L>&thorn;at sche endured alle aduersite</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e sergeaunt mekely sche sayde</L>
<L N="567">haue her a&yogh;ein &yogh;our litel &yogh;onge mayde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="568">&para; Go&thorn; now quod sche and do&thorn; my lordes heste</L>
<L>But o &thorn;ing wold I pray &yogh;ou of &yogh;our grace</L>
<L>&thorn;at but my lord forbad &yogh;ou atte leste</L>
<L N="571">Burie&thorn; &thorn;is litel body in som place</L>
<L>&thorn;at bestes ne no briddes it to-race</L>
<L>But he ne wolde no word to &thorn;e purpos seye</L>
<L N="574">But/ tok &thorn;e childe and went vpon his weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="575">&para; &thorn;is sergaunt cam vnto &thorn;is lord ageyne</L>
<L>And of Grisildes wordes and hir cheere</L>
<L>he tolde him word for word in schort and pleyne</L>
<L N="578">And him presente&thorn; with his dou&yogh;ter dere</L>
<L>Somwhat &thorn;is lord hadde reu&thorn;e in his manere<MILESTONE N="136b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles his purpos held he stille</L>
<L N="581">As lordes don whan &thorn;ay wol haue here wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="582">And bad &thorn;is sergaunt &thorn;at he priuyly</L>
<L>Schulde &thorn;is child ful ofte wynde and wrappe</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle circumstaunces tendrely</L>
<L N="585">And carye it in a coffre or in a lappe</L>
<L>But vpon peyne his heed of for to swappe</L>
<L>&thorn;at noman schulde knowe of his entent</L>
<L N="588">Ne when he come ne whider &thorn;at he went
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="301"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="422"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="589">&para; But at Boloigne it to his suster deere</L>
<L>That ilke time of Panyke was Countesse /</L>
<L>he schulde it take and schewe hir &thorn;is mateere /</L>
<L N="592">Besekyng hire to don hire besynesse</L>
<L>This child to fostre in alle gentilnesse</L>
<L>And whos child &thorn;at it was he bad hire hyde</L>
<L N="595">ffrom euery wight for ought &thorn;at may betyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="596">&para; &thorn;is sergaunt go&thorn; and ha&thorn; fulfild &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>But now to &thorn;is markys retorne we</L>
<L>ffor now go&thorn; he ful ofte ymagynyng</L>
<L N="599">If by his wyffes cheer he mighte se</L>
<L>Or by hire word apparceyue &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>Were chaunged but he neuer coude hir fynde</L>
<L N="602">But euer in oon ylike sad and kynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="603">&para; As glad as besy as humble in seruice</L>
<L>And eek in loue as sche was wont to be</L>
<L>Was sche to him in euery maner wyse</L>
<L N="606">Ne of hir doughter nought a word spak sche</L>
<L>Accident for non aduersite</L>
<L>Was seyn in hire ne neuer hir dou&yogh;ter name</L>
<L N="609">Ne nempned sche in ernest ne in game</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit iij<SUP>a</SUP> pars.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="610">IN &thorn;is astat &thorn;er ben passed .iiij. &yogh;er</L>
<L>sche wi&thorn; childe was but as god wolde</L>
<L>A knaue childe sche bar by &thorn;is walter</L>
<L N="613">fful gracious and fair for to biholde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at folk it to his fader tolde</L>
<L>Nat onlich he but al &thorn;e contre merye<MILESTONE N="137a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="616">Was for &thorn;is child and god &thorn;ey &thorn;ank and herye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="617">&para; Whan it was tuo &yogh;eer old and fro be breste</L>
<L>Departed of his norice on a day</L>
<L>This marquys caughte &yogh;it ano&thorn;er leste
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="302"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="423"></L>
<L N="620">To tempte his wijf &yogh;it ofter if he may</L>
<L>O nedeles was sche tempted in assay</L>
<L>But wedded men knowen no mesure</L>
<L N="623">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay fynde a pacient creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="624">&para; Wijf quod &thorn;is marquys &yogh;e han herd of &thorn;is</L>
<L>My poeple sekerly bere&thorn; heuy of oure mariage</L>
<L>And namely si&thorn;&thorn;e my sone boren is</L>
<L N="627">Now is it wers &thorn;an euer in al oure age</L>
<L>The murmur sle&thorn; myn herte and my corage</L>
<L>ffor to myn eeres come&thorn; &thorn;e voys so smerte</L>
<L N="630">That it wel neih destroyed ha&thorn; myn herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="631">&para; Now sey &thorn;ey &thorn;us whan walter is agon</L>
<L>&thorn;anne schal &thorn;e blood of Ianicle succede</L>
<L>And ben oure lord for o&thorn;er haue we non</L>
<L N="634">Suche wordes sei&thorn; my poeple it is no drede</L>
<L>Wel ought I of such murmur taken heede</L>
<L>ffor certeinly I drede such sentence</L>
<L N="637">&thorn;ough &thorn;ey nought pleyne speke in myn audience</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="638">&para; I wolde lyue in pees if &thorn;at I mighte</L>
<L>Wher fore I am disposed outerly</L>
<L>As I his suster seruede be nighte</L>
<L N="641">Right so &thorn;enke I to serue him priuely</L>
<L>&thorn;us warne I &yogh;ou for &yogh;e nou&yogh;t sodeinly</L>
<L>Out of &yogh;our self for no wo schulde outraye</L>
<L N="644">Be&thorn; pacient and &thorn;erfore I &yogh;ou praye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="645">&para; I haue quod sche sayd &thorn;us and euer schal</L>
<L>I wille no &thorn;ing ne nyl no &thorn;ing certayne</L>
<L>But as &yogh;ou liste nou&yogh;t greue&thorn; me al</L>
<L N="648">&thorn;ough &thorn;at my doughter and my sone be slayne</L>
<L>At &yogh;our comaundement &thorn;is is to sayne</L>
<L>I haue nou&yogh;t had no part of children tweyne</L>
<L N="651">But first siknesse and after wo and peyne<MILESTONE N="137b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="303"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="424"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="652">&para; &yogh;e ben oure lord do&thorn; wi&thorn; &yogh;our owne &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as &yogh;ou liste aske&thorn; no rede at me</L>
<L>ffor as I lifte at home al my clo&thorn;inge</L>
<L N="655">Whan I first come to &yogh;ou right so quod sche</L>
<L>lefte I my wille and al my liberte</L>
<L>And tok &yogh;our clo&thorn;ing wherfore I &yogh;ou preye</L>
<L N="658">Do&thorn; &yogh;our plesance I wil &yogh;our lust obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="659">&para; And certes if I hadde prescience</L>
<L>&yogh;oure wille to knowe or &yogh;e &yogh;our lust me tolde</L>
<L>I wolde it do wi&thorn;outen necligence</L>
<L N="662">But now I wot &yogh;our lust and what &yogh;e wolde</L>
<L>Al &yogh;our plesaunce ferme and stable I holde</L>
<L>ffor wiste I &thorn;at my de&thorn; wolde do &yogh;ou ese</L>
<L N="665">Right gladly wolde I deye &yogh;ou to plese</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="666">&para; De&thorn; may not make no comparisoun</L>
<L>vnto oure loue and whan &thorn;is marquys say</L>
<L>&thorn;e contenaunce of his wijf he cast a doun</L>
<L N="669">his ey&yogh;en tuo and wondre&thorn; &thorn;at sche may</L>
<L>In pacience suffre al &thorn;is array</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; wi&thorn; drery contynaunce</L>
<L N="672">But to his herte it was right gret plesance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="673">&para; &thorn;is Oggel sergaunt in &thorn;e same wise</L>
<L>&thorn;at he hir dou&yogh;ter caughte right so he</L>
<L>Or worse if men worse can deuyse</L>
<L N="676">ha&thorn; hent hir sone &thorn;at ful was of beaute</L>
<L>And euer in oon so pacient was sche</L>
<L>That sche no cheere made of heuynesse</L>
<L N="679">But kiste hir sone and after gan it blesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="680">&para; Saue &thorn;is sche preyed him if &thorn;at he mighte</L>
<L>hir litel sone he wolde in er&thorn;e graue</L>
<L>his tendre lymes delicat to sight</L>
<L N="683">ffro foules and fro bestes for to saue
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="304"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="425"></L>
<L>but sche non answer of him mighte haue</L>
<L>he wente his wey as he no &thorn;ing ne roughte</L>
<L N="686">But to Boloigne he tendrely it brou&yogh;te</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="687">&para; This marquys wondre&thorn; euer lenger &thorn;e more<MILESTONE N="138a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vpon hir pacience and if &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Ne hadde so&thorn;ly knowe &thorn;er bifore</L>
<L N="690">&thorn;at parfitly hir children loued sche</L>
<L>he wolde haue wende &thorn;at of som subtilte</L>
<L>And of malice or for cruel corrage</L>
<L N="693">That sche hadde suffred &thorn;is wi&thorn; sad visage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="694">&para; But wel he knewe next himself certayne</L>
<L>Sche loued hir children best in euery wise /</L>
<L>But now of wommen wolde I aske fayne</L>
<L N="697">If &thorn;ise assayes mighte nou&yogh;t suffise /</L>
<L>What cou&thorn;e a stordy housbonde more deuyse</L>
<L>To proeue his wijf and hire stedfastnesse</L>
<L N="700">And he contynuyng euer in sturdynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="701">&para; But &thorn;er ben folk of such condicion</L>
<L>That whan &thorn;ey haue a certein purpos take</L>
<L>They can nought stynte of here entencion</L>
<L N="704">But right as &thorn;ey were bounden to a stake</L>
<L>&thorn;ey wil nat of &thorn;at firste purpos slake /</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;is marquys fully ha&thorn; purposed</L>
<L N="707">To tempte his wijf as he was first disposed</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="708">&para; he wayte&thorn; if by word or contynance</L>
<L>That sche to him was chaunged of corage</L>
<L>But neuer coude he fynde variance</L>
<L N="711">Sche was ay oon in hert and in visage</L>
<L>And ay &thorn;e fur&thorn;er &thorn;at sche was in age</L>
<L>&thorn;e more trewe if &thorn;at it were possible</L>
<L N="714">Sche was to him more lowe and more pesible
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="305"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="426"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">&para; ffor which it semed &thorn;us &thorn;at of hem tuo</L>
<L>&thorn;er nas but oo wille for as walter liste</L>
<L>That same lust was hire plesance also</L>
<L N="718">And god he &thorn;anked al fel for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Sche schewed weel for no worldly vnreste</L>
<L>A wijf as of hir self no &thorn;ing ne scholde</L>
<L N="721">Wille in effecte but as hir housbond wolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="722">&thorn;e sclaundre of walter ofte and wyde spradde</L>
<L>That of a cruel herte he wikkedly<MILESTONE N="138b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor he a pore womman wedded hadde</L>
<L N="725">ha&thorn; murdred bo&thorn;e his children priuely</L>
<L>Such murmur was among hem comunly</L>
<L>No wonder is for to &thorn;e poeples eere</L>
<L N="728">Ther com no word but &thorn;at &thorn;ay mordred were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="729">ffor which &thorn;er as his poeple &thorn;er bifore</L>
<L>hadde loued him wel &thorn;e sclaunder of his diffame</L>
<L>Made hem &thorn;at &thorn;ey him hatede &thorn;erfore</L>
<L N="732">To ben a murdrer is an hateful name</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles for ernest ne for game</L>
<L>he of his cruel purpos nolde stente</L>
<L N="735">To tempte his wijf was sette al his entente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="736">&para; Whan &thorn;at his dou&yogh;ter twelf &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>he to &thorn;e court of Rome in subtil wise</L>
<L>Enformed of his wille and sente his message</L>
<L N="739">Comaundyng hem suche bulles to deuyse/</L>
<L>In &thorn;is maner and in &thorn;is same gyse</L>
<L>how &thorn;at &thorn;e pope as for his poeples reste</L>
<L N="742">Bad him to wedde ano&thorn;er if him leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="743">&para; I say he bad &thorn;ay scholden countrefete</L>
<L>The popes bulles making mencion</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ha&thorn; leue his firste wijf to lete</L>
<L N="746">As by &thorn;e popes dispensacion
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="306"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="427"></L>
<L>To stynte rancour and discencion</L>
<L>Bitwixe his poeple and him &thorn;us spak &thorn;e bulle</L>
<L N="749">&thorn;e which &thorn;ey han publisshed atte fulle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="750">&para; The rude poeple as it no wonder is</L>
<L>Wenden ful wel &thorn;at it hadde be ri&yogh;t so</L>
<L>But whan &thorn;is ty&thorn;inges come to Grisildis</L>
<L N="753">I deme &thorn;at hir herte was ful wo</L>
<L>And sche ylike sad for euermo</L>
<L>Disposed was &thorn;is humble creature</L>
<L N="756">To aduersite of fortune al tendure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="757">&para; Abydyng euer his lust and his plesance</L>
<L>To whom sche was &yogh;iuen herte and al</L>
<L>As to hire worldly verray suffisaunce<MILESTONE N="139a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="760">But schortly if &thorn;is story telle I schal</L>
<L>This marquys writen ha&thorn; in special</L>
<L>A lettre in which he schewe&thorn; his entente</L>
<L N="763">And secretly he to boloigne it sente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="764">&para; To &thorn;e erl of Panyke which &thorn;at hadde &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wedded his suster preyed he specially</L>
<L>To bringen home a&yogh;ein his children tuo</L>
<L N="767">But he o &thorn;inge preyed outrely</L>
<L>With alle his herte ful affectuously</L>
<L>&thorn;at he to no wight &thorn;ough men wolde enquere</L>
<L N="770">Schulde nought telle whos children &thorn;at &thorn;ei were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="771">&para; But seye &thorn;e mayden schulde y-wedded be</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e marquys of Saluce right anon</L>
<L>And as &thorn;is erle was preyed right so dede he</L>
<L N="774">ffor at day sette he on his day is goon</L>
<L>Toward Saluce and lordes many oon</L>
<L>In riche array &thorn;is mayden for to gyde</L>
<L N="777">hire &yogh;onge bro&thorn;er ryding by hir syde
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="307"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="428"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="778">Arrayed was toward hir mariage</L>
<L>This freisshe mayde ful of gemmes cleere</L>
<L>hir bro&thorn;er which &thorn;at vij. &yogh;eer was of age</L>
<L N="781">Arrayed eek ful freissch in his manere</L>
<L>And &thorn;us in gret noblesse and wi&thorn; glad cheere</L>
<L>Toward Saluces schapynge hire iourneye</L>
<L N="784">ffro day to day &thorn;ey ryden in here weye<NOTE PLACE="end">&para; Quarta pars.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART V.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">AMong al &thorn;is after his wicked vsage</L>
<L>&thorn;is marquys &yogh;it his wijf gan tempte more</L>
<L>To &thorn;e outrest proef of hire corage</L>
<L N="788">ffully to han experiment and lore</L>
<L>If &thorn;at sche was as stidefast as bifore</L>
<L>he on a day in open audience</L>
<L N="791">fful boustously ha&thorn; seid hir &thorn;is sentence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="792">Certes Grisildis I hadde ynough plesaunce</L>
<L>To han &yogh;ou to my wijf for &yogh;our goodnesse</L>
<L>As for &yogh;our trou&thorn;e and &yogh;our obeissance</L>
<L N="795">Nat for &yogh;our lignage ne for &yogh;our richesse<MILESTONE N="139b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But now quod he in verray so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at in gret lorschipe if I wol auyse</L>
<L N="798">&thorn;er is gret seruytute in sondry wise</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="799">&para; I may not do as euery ploughman may</L>
<L>My poeple me constreyne&thorn; for to take</L>
<L>ano&thorn;er wijf and cryen day by day</L>
<L N="802">And eek &thorn;e pope rancour for to slake</L>
<L>Consente&thorn; it &thorn;at dar I vndertake</L>
<L>And trewelich &thorn;us meche I wil &yogh;ou seye</L>
<L N="805">My newe wijf is comynge by &thorn;e weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="806">&para; Be strong of herte and voyde anon hire place</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilke doware &thorn;at &yogh;e broughten me</L>
<L>Tak it a&yogh;ein and graunte it of my grace
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="308"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="429"></L>
<L N="809">Retorne&thorn; to &yogh;our fadres hous quod he</L>
<L>No man may alwey haue prosperite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; euene herte I rede &yogh;ou tendure</L>
<L N="812">&thorn;e strok of fortune or of auenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="813">&para; And sche a&yogh;ein answerde in pacience</L>
<L>My lord seyde sche I wot &amp; wiste alway</L>
<L>how &thorn;at bitwixe &yogh;oure magnificence</L>
<L N="816">And my pouerte no wight can ne may</L>
<L>maken comparison it/ is no nay</L>
<L>I helde me neuer digne in no manere</L>
<L N="819">To be &yogh;our wijf ne &yogh;it &yogh;our chamberere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="820">And in &thorn;is hous &thorn;er &yogh;e me lady made</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e hihe god take I for my witnesse</L>
<L>And also wisly he my soule glade</L>
<L N="823">I neuer heelde me lady ne maystresse</L>
<L>But humble seruaunt to &yogh;our wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>And euere schal whil &thorn;at my lijff may dure</L>
<L N="826">Abouen euery worldly creature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="827">&para; That &yogh;e so longe of &yogh;oure benignite</L>
<L>han holde me in honour and nobleye</L>
<L>Wher as I was nou&yogh;t wor&thorn;y for to be</L>
<L N="830">&thorn;at &thorn;anke I god and &yogh;ow whom I preye</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;elde it &yogh;ow &thorn;er nys no more to seye<MILESTONE N="140a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vnto my fader gladly wol I wende</L>
<L N="833">And wi&thorn; him dwelle vnto my lyues ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="834">&para; Ther I was fostred of a child ful smal</L>
<L>Til I be dede my lijf &thorn;er wil I lede</L>
<L>A wydewe clene in body herte and al</L>
<L N="837">ffor si&thorn;&thorn;e I &yogh;af to &yogh;ow my maydenhede</L>
<L>And am &yogh;our trewe wijf it is no drede</L>
<L>God schilde such a lordes wijf to take</L>
<L N="840">Ano&thorn;er man to housbonde or to make
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="309"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="430"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="841">&para; And of &yogh;oure newe wyf god of his grace</L>
<L>So graunte &yogh;ou wele and heigh prosperite</L>
<L>ffor I wille gladly &yogh;elden hire my place</L>
<L N="844">In which I was blisful wont to be</L>
<L>ffor si&thorn;&thorn;e it like&thorn; &yogh;ow my lord quod sche</L>
<L>That whilom weren al myn hertes reste</L>
<L N="847">&thorn;at I schal go I wol go whan &yogh;ou leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="848">&para; But &thorn;er as &yogh;e me profre swich dowayre</L>
<L>Ay I first brought it is wel in my mynde</L>
<L>It were my wrecched clo&thorn;es no &thorn;ing fayre</L>
<L N="851">The whiche to me were now ful hard to fynde</L>
<L>O goode god how gentil and how kynde</L>
<L>&yogh;e semede by &yogh;our speche and &yogh;our visage</L>
<L N="854">&thorn;e day &thorn;at maked was our mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="855">But so&thorn; is seyde algate I fynde it trewe</L>
<L>ffor in effecte it preuede is on me</L>
<L>loue is nat olde as whan &thorn;at it is newe</L>
<L N="858">But certes lord for non aduersite</L>
<L>To deyen in &thorn;e cas it schal not be</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer in word or werk I schal repente</L>
<L N="861">&thorn;at I &yogh;ou &yogh;af myn herte in hol entente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="862">&para; My lord &yogh;e wot &thorn;at in my fadres place</L>
<L>&yogh;e dede me strepe out of my pore wede</L>
<L>And richely me cladden of &yogh;our grace</L>
<L N="865">To &yogh;ou brought I nou&yogh;t elles out of drede</L>
<L>But fei&thorn; and nakednesse and maydenhede</L>
<L>And here a&yogh;ein &yogh;our clo&thorn;ing I restore<MILESTONE N="140b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="868">And eek &yogh;our weddyng ryng for euermore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="869">&para; The remenaunt of &yogh;oure Iewellis redy be</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne &yogh;our chambre dar I sauely sayn</L>
<L>Naked out of my fadres hous quod sche</L>
<L N="872">I cam and naked I mot agayn
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="310"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="431"></L>
<L>Al &yogh;oure plesaunce wolde I folwe fayn</L>
<L>But &yogh;it I hope it be nat &yogh;oure entente</L>
<L N="875">That smokles out of &yogh;oure paleys I wente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="876">&para; &yogh;e coude nou&yogh;t do so dishoneste a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That &thorn;ilke wombe in which &yogh;our children leye</L>
<L>Schulde bifore &thorn;e poeple in my walkyng</L>
<L N="879">Be seyn al bare wher fore I &yogh;ou preye /</L>
<L>lat me not lik a worme go by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>Remembre &yogh;ou myn owne lord so deere</L>
<L N="882">I was &yogh;oure wijf &thorn;ough I vnwor&thorn;y were</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="883">Wherfore in guerdon of my maydenhede</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at I brought and not awey I bere</L>
<L>As vouche&thorn; sauf to &yogh;if me to my mede</L>
<L N="886">But such a smok as I was wont to were</L>
<L>&thorn;at I &thorn;er wi&thorn; may wrye &thorn;e wombe of here</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &yogh;our wijf and here take I my leue</L>
<L N="889">Of &yogh;ou myn owen lord lest I &yogh;ou greue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="890">&para; The smok/ quod he &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast on &thorn;i bak</L>
<L>lat it be stille and bere it for&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>But vnne&thorn;es &thorn;ilke word he spak</L>
<L N="893">But wente his wey for rew&thorn;e and pite</L>
<L>Biforn &thorn;e folk hir seluen strepe&thorn; sche</L>
<L>And in hire smok wi&thorn; heued and foot al bare</L>
<L N="896">Toward hir fader hous is sche fare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="897">The folk hir folwen wepyng in hire weye</L>
<L>And fortune ay &thorn;ey cursen as &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L>But sche fro weepyng kepte hire eyhen dreye</L>
<L N="900">Ne in &thorn;is tyme word ne spak sche noon</L>
<L>hire fader &thorn;at &thorn;is tydinge herde anon</L>
<L>Curse&thorn; &thorn;e day and tyme &thorn;at nature</L>
<L N="903">Schope him to be a lyues creature<MILESTONE N="141a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="311"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="432"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="904">&para; ffor out of doute &thorn;is olde pouere man</L>
<L N="906">&thorn;at whan &thorn;e lord had fulfilde his corage</L>
<L N="905">ffor euer it demed si&thorn; it ferst bigan</L>
<L N="907">him wolde &thorn;inke it were disparage</L>
<L>To wedde oon of so pore a lynage</L>
<L>To his astat so lowe to alighte</L>
<L N="910">And voyde hire as sone as euer he mighte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="911">&para; A&yogh;ein his doughter hastely go&thorn; he</L>
<L>ffor he by noyse of folk knew hire comyng</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hire olde cote as it mighte be</L>
<L N="914">he couered hire ful sorwfully wepynge</L>
<L>But on hir body might he it not bringe</L>
<L>ffor rude was &thorn;e clo&thorn; and more of age</L>
<L N="917">By fele dayes &thorn;an was hire mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="918">Thus wi&thorn; hir fader for a certein space</L>
<L>Dwelle&thorn; &thorn;is flour of wyfly pacience</L>
<L>&thorn;at ney&thorn;er by hir wordes ne hir face</L>
<L N="921">Biforn &thorn;e folk ne eek in here absence /</L>
<L>Ne schewede sche &thorn;at hire was don offence</L>
<L>Ne of hire heih astat &thorn;e remembrance</L>
<L N="924">Ne hadde sche as by hire contynaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="925">No wonder is for in hire gret astate</L>
<L>hire gost was euer in plein humilite</L>
<L>No tendre mou&thorn; non herte delicate</L>
<L N="928">No pompe ne semblant of realte</L>
<L>But ful of pacience and benignite</L>
<L>Discrete and prydeles ay honorable</L>
<L N="931">And to hir housbonde euer meeke and stable</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="932">&para; Men speke of Iob. and most for his humblesse</L>
<L>As clerkes whan hem liste can endite</L>
<L>Namly of men but as in so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L N="935">&thorn;ough clerkes preyse wommen but a lite
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="312"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="433"></L>
<L>&thorn;er can no man in humblesse him aquite</L>
<L>As wommen can ne can be half so trewe</L>
<L N="938">As wommen ben but it be falle of newe</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART VI.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffro Boloigne is &thorn;is erl of Panyke come /<MILESTONE N="141b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e fame vp sprong to more &amp; lesse /</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e poeples eres alle and some /</L>
<L N="942">Was cou&thorn; eek &thorn;at a newe marquysesse</L>
<L>he wi&thorn; him brought in such pompe and richesse</L>
<L>That neuer was &thorn;er seyn wi&thorn; mannes eye</L>
<L N="945">So noble array in al west lumbardye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="946">&para; The marquys which &thorn;at schope and knew al &thorn;is</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &thorn;is erl were come sent his message</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ilke sely pore Grisildis</L>
<L N="949">And sche with humble herte and glad visage</L>
<L>nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; no swollen herte in hire corage</L>
<L>Cam at his heste and on hir knees hir sette</L>
<L N="952">And reuerently and wysly sche him grette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="953">&para; Grisildis quod he my wille is vtterly</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayden &thorn;at schal be wedded to me</L>
<L>Receyued be to morn als really</L>
<L N="956">As possible is in myn hous for to be</L>
<L>And eke &thorn;at euery wight in his degre</L>
<L>haue his astat in sittyng and seruise</L>
<L N="959">And heih plesaunce as I can best deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="960">&para; I haue no womman sufficaunt certayn</L>
<L>&thorn;e chambres for to arraye in ordinance</L>
<L>After my lust and &thorn;erfore wolde I fayn</L>
<L N="963">Thyn were al such maner gouernance</L>
<L>&thorn;ou knowest eek of olde al my plesaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;in array be badde and yuel beseye</L>
<L N="966">Do &thorn;ou &thorn;i deuer atte leste weye
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="313"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="434"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="967">&para; Nat oonly lord &thorn;at I am glad quod sche</L>
<L>To do &yogh;oure lust but I desire also</L>
<L>&yogh;ou for to serue and plese in my degre</L>
<L N="970">Wi&thorn;outen feynyng and schal eueremo</L>
<L>Ne neuer for no wele ne no woo</L>
<L>Ne schal &thorn;e goost wi&thorn;inne myn herte stente</L>
<L N="973">To loue &yogh;ou best/ wi&thorn; al my trewe entente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="974">&para; And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word sche gan the house to dighte</L>
<L>And tables for to sette and beddes make<MILESTONE N="142a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And peyned hire to do al &thorn;at sche mighte</L>
<L N="977">Preyinge &thorn;e chambereres for goddes sake</L>
<L>To hasten hem and faste swepe and schake</L>
<L>And sche &thorn;e moste seruisable of alle</L>
<L N="980">ha&thorn; euery chambre arrayed and his halle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="981">&para; Abouten vndren gan &thorn;is erl alighte</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; him brought his noble children tweye</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; &thorn;e poeple ran to see &thorn;e sight</L>
<L N="984">Of hire array so richely byseye</L>
<L>And &thorn;an at erst amonges hem &thorn;ey seye</L>
<L>That walter was no fool &thorn;ough &thorn;at him liste</L>
<L N="987">To chaunge his wyf for it was for &thorn;e beste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="988">&para; ffor sche is fairer as &thorn;ey demen alle</L>
<L>&thorn;an is Grisilde and more tendre of age</L>
<L>And fairer fruyt betwen hem schulde falle</L>
<L N="991">And more plesaunce for hire heih lynage</L>
<L>hire bro&thorn;er eek so fair was of visage</L>
<L>That hem to se &thorn;e poeple ha&thorn; cau&yogh;t plesaunce</L>
<L N="994">Commendynge now &thorn;e marquys gouernaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="995">&para; O stormy poeple vnsad and euer vntrewe</L>
<L>Ay vndiscrete and chaungyng as a fane</L>
<L>Delityng ay in rombile &thorn;at is newe</L>
<L N="998">ffor lik &thorn;e mone ay wexen &yogh;e and wane
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="314"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="435"></L>
<L>Ay ful of clappyng dere y-nough a Iane</L>
<L>&yogh;oure dome is fals &yogh;our inconstance wel preue&thorn;</L>
<L N="1001">A ful gret fool is he &thorn;at on &yogh;ou leeue&thorn;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1002">&para; Thus saiden sadde folk in &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e peple gazed vp and doun</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey were glade right for &thorn;e nouelte</L>
<L N="1005">To han a newe lady of oure toun</L>
<L>No more of &thorn;is now make I mencioun</L>
<L>But to Grisilde anon wil I me dresse</L>
<L N="1008">And telle hire constance and hire besynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1009">&para; fful besy was Grisilde in euery &thorn;ing</L>
<L>That to &thorn;e feste was apertenent</L>
<L>Right nought was sche abayssht of hire clo&thorn;ing<MILESTONE N="142b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1012">&thorn;ough it were rude and eek somdel torent</L>
<L>But with glad chere to &thorn;e gate is went</L>
<L>With o&thorn;er folk to grete &thorn;e marquysesse</L>
<L N="1015">And after &thorn;at do&thorn; for&thorn; hire besynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1016">&para; Wi&thorn; so glad chere his gestes sche resceyue&thorn;</L>
<L>And connyngly euerich in his degre</L>
<L>That defaute no man apparceyue&thorn;</L>
<L N="1019">But ay &thorn;ey wondren what sche mighte be</L>
<L>&thorn;at in so pore array was for to se</L>
<L>And coude such honour &amp; reuerence</L>
<L N="1022">And wor&thorn;ily &thorn;ey preysen hire prudence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1023">&para; In al &thorn;is mene while sche ne stente</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayde and eek hir bro&thorn;er to comende</L>
<L>With alle hire herte in ful benigne entente</L>
<L N="1026">So wel &thorn;at no man cou&thorn;e hire pris amende</L>
<L>But atte laste whan &thorn;ise lordes wende</L>
<L>To sitte doun at mete he gan to calle</L>
<L N="1029">Grisilde as sche was besy in his halle
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="315"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="436"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1030">&para; Grisilde quod he as it were in his play</L>
<L>how like&thorn; &thorn;e my wijf and hire beaute</L>
<L>Right wel quod sche my lord for in good fey</L>
<L N="1033">A fairer sawe I neuer non &thorn;an sche</L>
<L>I pray to god &yogh;if &yogh;ou prosperite</L>
<L>And so hope I &thorn;at he wil to &yogh;ou sende</L>
<L N="1036">Plesaunce ynow vnto &yogh;our lyues ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1037">&para; O &thorn;ing beseke I &yogh;ou and warne also /</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e prike wi&thorn; no tormentynge</L>
<L>&thorn;is tendre mayden as &yogh;e han do mo</L>
<L N="1040">ffor sche is fostred in hire norischinge</L>
<L>more tenderly and to my supposynge</L>
<L>Sche coude nought aduersite endure</L>
<L N="1043">As coude a pore fostred creature/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1044">And whan &thorn;is walter saugh hir pacience</L>
<L>hire glad cher and no malice at al</L>
<L>And he so often hadde don hire offence</L>
<L>And sche ay sadde and constant as a wal<MILESTONE N="143a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Continuyng euere hire Innocence oueral</L>
<L>This sturdy marquys gan hire herte dresse</L>
<L N="1050">To rewen on hire wyfly stedfastnesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1051">&para; This is ynough Grisilde myn quod he</L>
<L>Be now no more agast ne yuel apayed</L>
<L>I haue &thorn;y fei&thorn; and &thorn;i benignite</L>
<L N="1054">As wel as euer womman was assayed</L>
<L>In gret astate and pouereliche arrayed</L>
<L>Now knowe I deere wijf &thorn;y stedfastnesse /</L>
<L N="1057">And hire in armes toke and gan hire kesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1058">&para; And sche for wonder took of hit no keepe</L>
<L>Sche &thorn;ou&yogh;te nought what &thorn;ing he to hir sayde/</L>
<L>Sche ferde as sche hadde stirte out of hir slepe</L>
<L N="1061">Til sche out of hir masednesse abrayde
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="316"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="437"></L>
<L>Grisilde quod he god &thorn;at / for vs deyed</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art my wyf ne non o&thorn;er I haue</L>
<L N="1064">Ne neuer hadde so god my soule saue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1065">&para; This is &thorn;y doughter which &thorn;ou hast supposed</L>
<L>To be my wijf &thorn;at o&thorn;er fei&thorn;fully</L>
<L>Schal be myn [heir] as I haue ay purposed</L>
<L N="1068">&thorn;ou bare him in &thorn;i body trewely</L>
<L>At boloygne haue I kept hem pryuyly</L>
<L>Tak hem a&yogh;ein for now mayst &thorn;ou not seye</L>
<L N="1071">&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast lorn non of &thorn;y children tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1072">&para; And folk &thorn;at o&thorn;erwise han sayd of me</L>
<L>I warne hem wel &thorn;at I haue don &thorn;is dede</L>
<L>ffor no malice ne for no cruelte</L>
<L N="1075">But for tassaye in &thorn;e &thorn;y wommanhede</L>
<L>And nat to slee my children god forbede</L>
<L>But for to kepe hem pryuyly and stille</L>
<L N="1078">Til I &thorn;i purpos knewe and al &thorn;y wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1079">&para; Whan &thorn;is herde a swowne doun sche falle&thorn;</L>
<L>ffor pytous ioye and after hir swownynge</L>
<L>Sche bo&thorn;e hire &yogh;onge children to hire calle&thorn;</L>
<L N="1082">And in his armes pitously wepynge</L>
<L>Embrace&thorn; hem and tendrely kissinge<MILESTONE N="143b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>fful like a moder wi&thorn; hire salte teeres</L>
<L N="1085">Sche ba&thorn;e&thorn; bo&thorn;e hire visage and hire heres</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1086">&para; O which a pytous sight it was to see</L>
<L>hir swownyng and hire humble voys to heere</L>
<L>Graunt mercy lord god I &thorn;anke it &yogh;ou quod she</L>
<L N="1089">&thorn;at &yogh;e han saued me my children deere</L>
<L>now rekke I neuer to be ded right heere</L>
<L>Si&thorn;&thorn;e I stonde in &yogh;our loue and in &yogh;our grace</L>
<L N="1092">No fors of de&thorn; ne whan my spirit pace
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="317"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="438"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1093">&para; O tendre o dere o &yogh;onge children myne</L>
<L>&yogh;our woful moder wende stedefastly</L>
<L>That cruel houndes or som foul vermyne</L>
<L N="1096">hadde eten &yogh;ou but god of his mercy</L>
<L>And &yogh;oure benigne fader tenderly</L>
<L>ha&thorn; don &yogh;ou kepte and in &thorn;e same stounde</L>
<L N="1099">Al sodeinly sche swapte a doun to grounde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1100">&para; And in hire swowne so sadly holde&thorn; sche</L>
<L>hire children tuo whan sche gan hem enbrace</L>
<L>&thorn;at with gret sleighte and wi&thorn; gret difficulte</L>
<L N="1103">&thorn;e children from hire arm &thorn;ei gon arace</L>
<L>O many a teer on many a pitous face</L>
<L>Doun ran of hem &thorn;at stooden hire besyde</L>
<L N="1106">vnne&thorn;e aboute hire mighten &thorn;ey abyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1107">Walter hir glade&thorn; and hir sorwe slake&thorn;</L>
<L>Sche ryse&thorn; vp abaysshed from hire traunce</L>
<L>And euery wight hire ioye and feste make&thorn;</L>
<L N="1110">til sche ha&thorn; caught a&yogh;ein hir contenance</L>
<L>Walter hire do&thorn; fei&thorn;fully plesaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;at it is deynte for to se &thorn;e cheere</L>
<L N="1113">Bitwixe hem tuo now &thorn;ey ben mett in feere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1114">&para; This ladyes whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey here tyme saye</L>
<L>han taken hire and in to chambre goon</L>
<L>And streepen hire out of hire ruyde array</L>
<L N="1117">And in a clo&thorn; of gold &thorn;at brighte schoon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a coroune of many a riche stoon</L>
<L>vppon hire heed &thorn;ey in to halle hir broughte<MILESTONE N="144a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1120">And &thorn;an sche was honoured as sche oughte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1121">&para; Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is pitous day a blisful ende</L>
<L>ffor euery man and womman do&thorn; here might</L>
<L>This day in mir&thorn;e and reuel to dispende</L>
<L N="1124">Til on &thorn;e welken schone &thorn;e sterres bright
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="318"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="439"></L>
<L>ffor more solempne in euery mannes sight</L>
<L>&thorn;is feste was and gretter of costage</L>
<L N="1127">Than was &thorn;e reuel of hire mariage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1128">&para; fful many a &yogh;eer in hih prosperite</L>
<L>lyuen &thorn;ise tuo in concord and in reste</L>
<L>And richely his dou&yogh;ter maryed he</L>
<L N="1131">vnto a lord on of &thorn;e wor&thorn;ieste</L>
<L>Of alle ytayle &thorn;anne and pes &amp; reste</L>
<L>his wyues fader in his court he kepe&thorn;</L>
<L N="1134">Til &thorn;at his soule out of his body creepe&thorn;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1135">&para; his sone succedi&thorn; in his heritage</L>
<L>In reste and pees after his fader day</L>
<L>And fortunat eek was in mariage</L>
<L N="1138">Al putte he not his wijf in gret assay</L>
<L>This world is not so strong it is no nay</L>
<L>As it ha&thorn; ben in olde tyme &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="1141">And herkne&thorn; what &thorn;is auctor sei&thorn; &thorn;erfore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1142">This story is sayd not for &thorn;at wyues scholde</L>
<L>ffolwen grisilde as in humilite</L>
<L>ffor it were importable &thorn;ough &thorn;ey wolde</L>
<L N="1145">But for &thorn;at euery wight in his degre</L>
<L>Schulde be constante in aduersite</L>
<L>As was Grisilde &thorn;erfore Petrayke write&thorn;</L>
<L N="1148">&thorn;is story which he wi&thorn; his stile endite&thorn;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1149">ffor si&thorn;&thorn;e a womman was so paciente</L>
<L>vnto a mortel man wel more vs ou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Resceyuen al in gree &thorn;at god vs sente</L>
<L N="1152">ffor grete skiles he preeue&thorn; &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L>But he ne tempte&thorn; no man &thorn;at he brou&yogh;te</L>
<L>As sei&thorn; seint Iame &yogh;if &yogh;e his pistil rede</L>
<L N="1155">He preue&thorn; folk alday it is no drede<MILESTONE N="144b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="319"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="440"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1156">And suffre&thorn; vs as for oure excercise</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scharpe scorges of aduersite</L>
<L>fful often to ben betyn in sondry wyse</L>
<L N="1159">Nought for to knowe oure wille for certes he</L>
<L>Or we were born knew al oure frelete</L>
<L>And for oure beste is al oure gouernance</L>
<L N="1162">lat vs &thorn;anne lyue in vertuous suffraunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1163">&para; But lordinges o word herkene&thorn; ar I go</L>
<L>It were ful hard to fynde now a dayes</L>
<L>In alle a toun Grisildes &thorn;re or tuo</L>
<L N="1166">ffor if &thorn;at &thorn;ey were putte to suche assayes</L>
<L>The golde of hem ha&thorn; now so badde layes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bras &thorn;at &thorn;ough &thorn;e coyne be fayr at eye</L>
<L N="1169">It wolde ra&thorn;er berst/ a tuo &thorn;an plye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1170">&para; ffor which here for &thorn;e wyues loue of Ba&thorn;e</L>
<L>Whos lijf and al hire hel&thorn;e god mayntene</L>
<L>In hire maystrye and elles were it ska&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1173">I wolde wi&thorn; lusty herte freisshe and grene</L>
<L>Sey &yogh;ou a song to glade &yogh;ou I wene</L>
<L>And late vs stynte of ernestful matiere</L>
<L N="1176">herkne&thorn; my song &thorn;at sei&thorn; in &thorn;is manere</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>&para; lenvoye de Chaucere</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Grisild is deed and eek hir pacience</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e at oones buryed in ytayle</L>
<L N="1179">Wher fore I crye in open audience</L>
<L>No wedded man be hardy to assayle /</L>
<L>his wyues pacience in hope to fynde /</L>
<L N="1182">Grisildis for in certes he schal fayle /
<PB REF="00000347.tif" N="320"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="441"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O noble wyues ful of heih prudence</L>
<L>lat non humilite &yogh;oure tonge nayle /</L>
<L N="1185">Ne lat no clerk haue cause or diligence</L>
<L>To write of &yogh;ou a story of such meruayle</L>
<L>As Grisildis pacient and kynde</L>
<L N="1188">lest chychevache &yogh;ow swolwe in hire entrayle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffolwe&thorn; herto and holde&thorn; no scilence<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a leaf out]</NOTE></L>
<L>[but euere answerith / in the contir-taille<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="82a"></L>
<L N="1191">beth nat bidaffid / for youre innocence</L>
<L>but sharply take on yow / the gouernaille</L>
<L>enpoynteth wel this lessoun / in youre mynde</L>
<L N="1194">for comune profit / sith hit may availle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ye Archiwivis / stondith at defence</L>
<L>syn ye be stronge / as is a grete Camaille</L>
<L N="1197">ne suffrith not / that men do yow offence</L>
<L>and slender wivis / as feble in bataille</L>
<L>beith egre as a Tigre / bi-yende the se fer in ynde</L>
<L N="1200">ay clappith as a mylle / I yow consaille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne dredith hem nought doith hem no reuerence</L>
<L>for though thyn housbond armed be / in maille</L>
<L N="1203">the wordis of thi crabbed eloquence</L>
<L>shal persshe his breste / and eke his auentaille</L>
<L>in gelousie I rede eke / thow him bynde</L>
<L N="1206">and thow shalt make him covche / as a quaille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yf thow be feyre / there folk ben in presence</L>
<L>shewe thow thi visage / and thin apparaille</L>
<L N="1209">yf thow be foule / be fre of thi dispence</L>
<L>to gete the frendis / ay do thi travaille</L>
<L>be euer of chere as light / as leff on lynde</L>
<L N="1212">and lete him care &middot; wepe / wrynge and waille</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Here endith the Clerke of Oxonford his tale /]</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="321">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="443">
<HEAD>[and next folwith his tale of Ianuare and May.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whilom ther was dwellyng / in Lumbardye</L>
<L>a worthi knyght / that borne was in Pavie</L>
<L>in which he lived / in grete prosperite</L>
<L N="1248">and sexti yere / a wiffles man was he</L>
<L>and folwed ay / his bodyly delite</L>
<L>on women / there as was his appetite</L>
<L>as don these foolis / that ben seculere</L>
<L N="1252">and whan he was passed sexti yere</L>
<L>were hit for holynes / or for dotage</L>
<L>I can not sey / but suche a grete corage</L>
<L>had this knyght / to be a wedded man</L>
<L N="1256">that day and night / he doth al that he can</L>
<L>to espien where he myghte / wedded be</L>
<L>prayng oure lord / graunte him that he</L>
<L>myghte onys knowe / of that blisful liff</L>
<L N="1260">that is bitwixe an housbonde / and his wiff</L>
<L>and for to live / vnder that holy bonde</L>
<L>with which first / god man and woman bonde</L>
<L>noon other liff seide he / is worthe a bene</L>
<L N="1264">for wedlok is so esy / and so clene</L>
<L>that in this world / hit is a paradise</L>
<L>thus seide this olde knyght / that was so wise</L>
<L>and certeynly / as soth as god is kynge</L>
<L N="1268">to take a wiff / hit is a glorious thinge</L>
<L>and namely whan a man is olde / and hore</L>
<L>than is a wiff the fructe / of his tresore</L>
<L>than shulde he take a yonge wiff / and a feyre<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="115b"></L>
<L N="1272">on which he myghte / engender him an heyre
<PB REF="00000349.tif" N="322"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="444"></L>
<L>and lede his liff in ioye / and in solas<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>where that these bachelers / synge alas</L>
<L>whan that thei fynden / any aduersite</L>
<L N="1276">in love / which nys but childis vanyte</L>
<L>and trewely hit sit wel / to be so</L>
<L>that bachelers han ofte peyne and wo</L>
<L>on brotil gronde thei bilde / and brotilnes</L>
<L N="1280">they fynden / whan thei wenyn sikernes</L>
<L>thei live but as a brid / or as a beste</L>
<L>in liberte / and vnder noon a-reste</L>
<L>there as a wedded man / in his estate</L>
<L N="1284">livith a liff blisful / and ordynate</L>
<L>vnder the yoke of mariage I-bounde</L>
<L>wel may his herte / in ioye and blis habounde</L>
<L>for who can be so boxom / as a wiff</L>
<L N="1288">who is so trewe / and eke so ententiff</L>
<L>to kepe him sike and hole / as his make</L>
<L>for wel or wo / she wol him not forsake</L>
<L>she is not wery / him to loue and serue</L>
<L>though that he lye bedred / til he sterve]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>MS Arch. Seld. B. 14</B> <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;it some clerkes seyn it nys nou&yogh;t so<NOTE PLACE="marg">Corpus MS</NOTE><MILESTONE N="145a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of which Theoffraste / is on of &thorn;o</L>
<L>What fors &thorn;ei&yogh; theofraste luste lye</L>
<L N="1296">Ne take no wijf quod he for husbandrye</L>
<L>As for to spare in housholde &thorn;in dispence</L>
<L>A trewe seruaunt do&thorn; more diligence</L>
<L>&thorn;y good to kepe &thorn;an &thorn;in owen wijf</L>
<L N="1300">ffor sche wol clayme half part al hire lijf</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at &thorn;ou be seek so god me saue</L>
<L>&thorn;y verray frendes o&thorn;er a trewe knaue</L>
<L>Wol kepe &thorn;e bet &thorn;an sche &thorn;at wayte&thorn; ay</L>
<L N="1304">After &thorn;y good and ha&thorn; don many a day</L>
<L>[and if thow take a wiff / in thin age oolde</L>
<L>fful lightly maist thow be a Cokewoolde]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1307">To &thorn;is entente and an C si&thorn;es wurse</L>
<L>[writeth this man / there / god his bonys cors]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="323"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="445"></L>
<L>But tak no kepe of alle such vanyte</L>
<L>Defye theofrast and herkne me</L>
<L>A wyff is goddes &yogh;ifte verrayly</L>
<L N="1312">Alle o&thorn;er maner &yogh;iftes hardily</L>
<L>As landes rentes pasture or comune</L>
<L>O&thorn;er o&thorn;er &yogh;iftes &thorn;at moebles of fortune</L>
<L>&thorn;at passen as a schadewe on a wall</L>
<L N="1316">But drede nought if pleynly speke I schall</L>
<L>A wyf wil laste and in &thorn;in hous endure</L>
<L>Wel lenger &thorn;an &thorn;e luste to endure</L>
<L>mariage is a ful gret sacrament</L>
<L N="1320">he which ha&thorn; no wijf I holde him schent</L>
<L>he lyue&thorn; helples and is al desolat</L>
<L>I speke of folk in seculer estat</L>
<L>And herkne why I say nou&yogh;t &thorn;is for nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1324">&thorn;e womman is for mannes help y-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e hihe god when he hadde adam maked</L>
<L>And sawe him allone bely naked</L>
<L>God of his grete goodnesse sayde he &thorn;anne</L>
<L N="1328">lete vs now make an helpe to &thorn;is manne</L>
<L>ylike to himself and &thorn;en he made Eue</L>
<L>here may &yogh;e se and here-by &yogh;e preue</L>
<L>That wijf is mannes helpe and his comfort</L>
<L N="1332">his paradis terreste and his disport<MILESTONE N="145b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So buxom and so vertuous is sche</L>
<L>&thorn;ey mosten needes lyue in vnite</L>
<L>Of fleisshe &thorn;ei ben and O fleisch as I gesse</L>
<L N="1336">nou&yogh;t but on herte in wele and in distresse</L>
<L>A wyf; A seinte mary benedicite</L>
<L>how might a man han any aduersite</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn; a wyf certes I can nou&yogh;t say</L>
<L N="1340">&thorn;e blisse &thorn;at is bitwexe hem tway</L>
<L>&thorn;er may no tonge telle or herte &thorn;ynke</L>
<L>If he be pore sche helpe&thorn; him to swynke</L>
<L>Sche keepi&thorn; his good and waste&thorn; neuer a del</L>
<L N="1344">And al &thorn;at hire housband lust hir like&thorn; wel
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="324"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="446"></L>
<L>Sche sai&thorn; nou&yogh;t ones nay whan he sai&thorn; &yogh;e</L>
<L>Do &thorn;is sai&thorn; he al redy sire sey&thorn; sche</L>
<L>O blisful ordre O wedlok precious</L>
<L N="1348">&thorn;ou art so mery and eek so vertuous</L>
<L>And so comended and aproued eke</L>
<L>That euery man &thorn;at halt/ him wor&thorn; a leek</L>
<L>vpon his bare knees aught al his lijf</L>
<L N="1352">&thorn;anken his god &thorn;at him ha&thorn; sent a wyf</L>
<L>O&thorn;er preyed god him for to sende</L>
<L>A wijf to laste vnto his lyues ende</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;anne his lijf is sett in sikernesse</L>
<L N="1356">he may nou&yogh;t be desceyued as I gesse</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he werche after his wyues reed</L>
<L>&thorn;anne may he boldely beren vp his heed</L>
<L>&thorn;ey ben so trewe and so wys</L>
<L N="1360">ffor which if &thorn;ou wolt worchen as &thorn;e wyse</L>
<L>Do alway so as &thorn;e womman wol &thorn;e rede</L>
<L>lo how &thorn;at Iacob as &thorn;ise clerkes rede</L>
<L>By good counseil of his moder rebekke</L>
<L N="1364">Band &thorn;e kydes skyn abouten his nekke</L>
<L>ffor which his fadres benyson he wan</L>
<L>lo Iudith as &thorn;e story eek telle can</L>
<L>By wys counseil sche goddes poeple kepte</L>
<L N="1368">And slough him Olophinus whiles he slepte<MILESTONE N="146a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Lo how Abygayle by good counseil how &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>Saued hire housbonde Nabal whan &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Schulde han be slayn and loke after also</L>
<L N="1372">By good counseil delyuered out of wo</L>
<L>The poeple of god and made him mardoche</L>
<L>Of Assuer enhaunced for to be</L>
<L>Ther is no &thorn;ing gree superlatiff</L>
<L N="1376">As sei&thorn; Senek aboue an humble wyf</L>
<L>Suffre &thorn;yn wyues tonge as Catoun byt</L>
<L>Sche schal comaunde and &thorn;ou schalt suffre yt</L>
<L>And &yogh;it sche wolde obeye of curtesye</L>
<L N="1380">A wyf is kepere of &thorn;in housbondrye
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="325"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="447"></L>
<L>Wel may &thorn;e seeke man bewayle and wepe /</L>
<L>Ther as &thorn;er nys no wijf &thorn;e hous to keepe</L>
<L>I warne &thorn;e if wysly &thorn;ou wilt wirche</L>
<L N="1384">loue wel &thorn;y wyf as crist loue&thorn; his chirche</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou loue &thorn;y self &thorn;ou louest &thorn;y wyf</L>
<L>No man hate&thorn; his flesch but in his lyf</L>
<L>he fostre&thorn; it/ and &thorn;erfore byd I &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1388">Cherissche &thorn;y wijf or &thorn;ou schalt neuer &thorn;e</L>
<L>housbond &amp; wijf what so men Iape or pleye</L>
<L>Of worldly folk holde &thorn;e righte weye</L>
<L>&thorn;ey ben so knyt &thorn;er may non harm betyde</L>
<L N="1392">And namely vpon &thorn;e wyues syde</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;is Ianuarye of which I tolde</L>
<L>Considere&thorn; ha&thorn; in wi&thorn; his dayes olde</L>
<L>&thorn;e lusty &thorn;e vertuous quyete</L>
<L N="1396">&thorn;at is in mariage hony swete</L>
<L>And for his frendes on a day sent</L>
<L>To telle hem &thorn;effect of his entent</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; face sadde he ha&thorn; hem &thorn;is tale tolde</L>
<L N="1400">he sayde frendes I am hoor and olde</L>
<L>And almost god wot at my pittis brinke</L>
<L>vpon my sowle somwhat most I &thorn;inke</L>
<L>I haue my body folyly dispended</L>
<L N="1404">y-blessed be god &thorn;at it schal ben amended<MILESTONE N="146b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor I wol be certein a wedded man</L>
<L>And &thorn;at in alle &thorn;e haste &thorn;at I can</L>
<L>vnto som mayde fayr and tendre of age</L>
<L N="1408">I pray you schape&thorn; for my mariage</L>
<L>Al sodeinly for I wol nou&yogh;t abyde</L>
<L>And I wole fonde aspye on my syde</L>
<L>To whom I may be wedded hastely</L>
<L N="1412">But for as moche &thorn;at &yogh;e ben mo &thorn;en I</L>
<L>&yogh;e schullen ra&thorn;er such a &thorn;ing aspyen</L>
<L>&thorn;an I and wher me luste best allyen</L>
<L>But o &thorn;ing warne I &yogh;ou my frendes deere</L>
<L N="1416">I wol non old wyf haue in no manere /
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="326"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="448"></L>
<L>She schal nou&yogh;t passe xvj &yogh;er certayn</L>
<L>Old fleissh and &yogh;ong fleissh &thorn;at wolde I han ful fayn</L>
<L>Bet is quod he a pyk &thorn;an a pykrelle</L>
<L N="1420">And bet &thorn;an olde beef is &thorn;e tendre feelle</L>
<L>I wol no womman xx<SUP>ti</SUP> &yogh;er of age</L>
<L>It nys but benestraw and gret forage</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;is olde wydewes god it woot</L>
<L N="1424">&thorn;ey konne so moche craft on wades boot</L>
<L>So mochil broken harme whan &thorn;at hem liste</L>
<L>&thorn;at wi&thorn; hem schulde I neuer lyuen in reste</L>
<L>ffor sondry scoles make&thorn; subtile clerkys</L>
<L N="1428">Wommen of many a scole half a clerk is</L>
<L>But certeinly a &yogh;ong &thorn;ing may me gye</L>
<L>Right as men may warm wax wi&thorn; handes to-plye</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore I sey &yogh;ow pleinly in a clause</L>
<L N="1432">I wol non old wijf haue for &thorn;is cause</L>
<L>ffor if so were if I hadde so myschaunce</L>
<L>That I in hire ne cou&thorn;e han &middot; no plesaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;enne scholde I lede my lijf in aduoutrye</L>
<L N="1436">And so streyt to &thorn;e deuyl whan I dye</L>
<L>Ne children schulde I non vpon hire geten</L>
<L>&yogh;it were me leuer houndes hadde me eten</L>
<L>&thorn;an &thorn;at myn heritage scholde falle</L>
<L N="1440">In straunge hande and &thorn;us I telle &yogh;ou alle<MILESTONE N="147a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I dowte nought I wot &thorn;e cause why</L>
<L>men schulde wedde and for&thorn;ermore wot I</L>
<L>&thorn;er speke&thorn; many men of mariage</L>
<L N="1444">&thorn;at wot nomore of hit &thorn;en wot my page</L>
<L>ffor whiche causes men schulde take a wyf</L>
<L>If he may not chaste be by his lijf</L>
<L>Tak him a wijf wi&thorn; gret deuocioun</L>
<L N="1448">By cause of leofful procreacion</L>
