<L N="1336">ffor quyk or deed right &thorn;us &yogh;e schulle me fynde</L>
<L>In &yogh;ow li&thorn; al to do me lyue or deye</L>
<L>But wel I wot &thorn;e rokkes ben aweye /</L>
<L>he took his leeue and sche astoned stood</L>
<L N="1340">In alle hir face &thorn;er nas a drop of blood</L>
<L>Sche wende neuer han comyn in such a trappe</L>
<L>Allas quod sche &thorn;at &thorn;is euer schulde happe</L>
<L>ffor wende I neuer by possibilite</L>
<L N="1344">&thorn;at such a muster or such a meruaile schulde be
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="369"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="518"></L>
<L>It is a&yogh;ein &thorn;e processe of nature<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are trans|posed in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And home sche go&thorn; a sorwsul creature<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are trans|posed in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor verray feere vnne&thorn;es may sche go</L>
<L N="1348">Sche wepe&thorn; and wayle&thorn; a day or tuo</L>
<L>And swowne&thorn; &thorn;at it rou&thorn;e was to se</L>
<L>But why it was to no wight tolde sche</L>
<L>ffor out of toune was gon arneragus</L>
<L N="1352">But to hir self sche sayde and spak &thorn;us</L>
<L>In hire compleynt as &yogh;e schullen after heere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; face pale and wi&thorn; sorweful cheere<MILESTONE N="168a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Allas quod sche on &thorn;e fortune I pleyne</L>
<L N="1356">That vnwar hast wrapped me in &thorn;i cheyne</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e eschape wot I no socour</L>
<L>Saue oonly de&thorn; o&thorn;er elles dishonour</L>
<L>On of &thorn;ese tuo bihoue&thorn; me to chese</L>
<L N="1360">But na&thorn;eles &yogh;it hadde I leuer to lese /</L>
<L>My lif &thorn;an of my body to han a schame</L>
<L>O&thorn;er knowe my self fals o&thorn;er lese my name /</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; my de&thorn; I may be quyte y-wys</L>
<L N="1364">ha&thorn; &thorn;er nou&yogh;t many a wyf er &thorn;is</L>
<L>And many a mayden y-slayn hem self allas</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ir &thorn;an wi&thorn; here bodyes don trespas</L>
<L>And certes lo &thorn;ise stories beren witnesse</L>
<L N="1368">Whan xxx tyrauntz ful of cursednesse</L>
<L>hadde slayn Phydon in athenes atte leste</L>
<L>&thorn;ey comaunded his dou&yogh;tres to areste /</L>
<L>And bryngen hem byforn hem in dispyt</L>
<L N="1372">Al naked to fulfille here foule delyt</L>
<L>And in here fadres blod &thorn;ey made hem daunce</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;e pament god &yogh;eue hem meschaunce</L>
<L>ffor whiche &thorn;ese woful maydens ful of drede /</L>
<L N="1376">Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ey wolde lese here maydenhede /</L>
<L>&thorn;ay pryuely ben stert in to a welle /</L>
<L>And dreynt hemselue as &thorn;e bookes tell</L>
<L>They of mesue lete enquere and seke</L>
<L N="1380">Of lacedemye .L. maydens eeke
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="370"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="519"></L>
<L>On which &thorn;ey wolden don here leccherie</L>
<L>But was &thorn;er non of al &thorn;at companye /</L>
<L>&thorn;at sche nas slayn and wi&thorn; a glad entent</L>
<L N="1384">Chese ra&thorn;ir for to dye &thorn;an for to assent</L>
<L>To ben oppressed of here maydenhede</L>
<L>Why schulde I &thorn;anne to deye ben in drede</L>
<L>lo eke &thorn;e tyraunt Anstoclydes</L>
<L N="1388">&thorn;at loued a mayde &thorn;at/ hight Symphalides</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at hir fader slayn was on a night/</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e Dyanes temple go&thorn; sche anon right<MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hente &thorn;e ymage with hire armes tuo</L>
<L N="1392">ffro which ymage wolde sche neuere go</L>
<L>No wight might of hit hir armes race</L>
<L>Til sche was slayn in &thorn;e selue place /</L>
<L>Now se&thorn;yns &thorn;at maydens hadde such despit/</L>
<L N="1396">To ben defouled wi&thorn; mannes foul delyt</L>
<L>Wel aught a wyf ra&thorn;er hirself to sle/</L>
<L>&thorn;an ben defouled as &thorn;enke&thorn; me</L>
<L>&thorn;at schal I sayn of hasdrubaldes wyf</L>
<L N="1400">That/ at kartage byraft hir self hir lyf</L>
<L>ffor whan sche sawh &thorn;at/ Romayns wan &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Sche took hir children alle and swept a doun</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e fuyr and ches ra&thorn;er to dye</L>
<L N="1404">&thorn;an eny Romeyn did hir vilanye</L>
<L>ha&thorn; nou&yogh;t lucres y-slayn hir self allas</L>
<L>At Rome &thorn;ere sche oppressed was</L>
<L>Of Tarquyn for hir &thorn;ought it was a schame /</L>
<L N="1408">To lyue whan &thorn;at sche had lost hire name /</L>
<L>The viij. maydens of Milesye also /</L>
<L>han slayn hem self for drede and for wo</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ir &thorn;an folke of gaule scholde hem oppresse /</L>
<L N="1412">Mo &thorn;en a &thorn;ousend stories as I gesse /</L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e I now telle as touchinge &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>Whan habradas was slayn his wyf so dere</L>
<L>hire self slough and let hir blood to glyde</L>
<L N="1416">In habradas woundes brode and wyde /
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="371"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="520"></L>
<L>And seyde my body at &thorn;e leste way</L>
<L>&thorn;er schal no wight defoule it if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>What schulde I mo ensamples her of sayn</L>
<L N="1420">Si&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at so many han hemselue slayn</L>
<L>Wel ra&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ey wolde defouled be /</L>
<L>I wol conclude what is best for me</L>
<L>[to sle my selue / than be defouled thus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1424">I wol be trewe / to Arueragus]</L>
<L>O&thorn;ir ra&thorn;er sle my self in som manere</L>
<L>As Demonicious doughter dere</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at sche nolde not defouled be /</L>
<L N="1428">O Cedasus it is ful gret pite<MILESTONE N="169a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To reden how &thorn;i doughtren deyeden allas</L>
<L>&thorn;at slowe hemself for such a maner caas</L>
<L>As gret appetyt was it or more</L>
<L N="1432">The Theban mayden &thorn;at for Nichasore</L>
<L>[hir selue slowe / right for suche manere woo<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>another Theban maiden dide right so]</L>
<L>hire hadde wedded and y-dressed<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1435">ffor on of Macedoigne hadde hire oppressed</L>
<L>&thorn;at schal I sayn of Nicharatiffs wijf</L>
<L>&thorn;at for such cas byrafte hir self hir lyf</L>
<L>how trewe was eek to alcebiades</L>
<L N="1440">his loue &thorn;at for to deyen chees</L>
<L>&thorn;an for to suffren his body vmbreyde be</L>
<L>lo which a wyf was Alcestem quod sche</L>
<L>What Emore of good Penolope /</L>
<L N="1444">Al Grece knowe&thorn; of hir chastite</L>
<L>Pardee of leodomia is write &thorn;us</L>
<L>That when at Troye was slayn protheselayus</L>
<L>No lenger nolde sche lyue after his day</L>
<L N="1448">The same of noble Porcia I telle may</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;oute Brutus cou&thorn;e sche not lyue</L>
<L>To whom he hadde al hol his herte &yogh;iue</L>
<L>The parfyt wyfhod of archemesy</L>
<L N="1452">honoured is &thorn;urgh al &thorn;e Barbary
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="372"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="521"></L>
<L>O teuta queen in &thorn;y wyfly chastite</L>
<L>To alle wyfes may a myrour be</L>
<L>. . . <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS: these lines</NOTE></L>
<L N="1456"> . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">known only in Ellesmere MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;us playned Dorigen a day or tweye</L>
<L>Purposed euere &thorn;at sche wolde deye</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles vpon &thorn;e &thorn;ridde night</L>
<L N="1460">hom cam arneragus &thorn;e wor&thorn;y knight</L>
<L>And asked hire why &thorn;at sche weep so sore</L>
<L>And sche gan weepen euer lenger &thorn;e more</L>
<L>Allas quod sche &thorn;at euer was I born</L>
<L N="1464">&thorn;us haue I seyd quod he &thorn;us haue I sworn</L>
<L>I told him alle as &yogh;e han herde bifore</L>
<L>It neede&thorn; nou&yogh;t/ to rehersen it nomore</L>
<L>This housbond wi&thorn; glad cheere in sondry wise /</L>
<L>Answerd and sayde as I schal &yogh;ou deuyse /<MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Is &thorn;er ought elles Dorigen but &thorn;is</L>
<L>Nay nay quod sche god help me so as wis</L>
<L>This is to meche and it were goddes wille</L>
<L N="1472">&yogh;e wyf quod he let slepe &thorn;at is stille</L>
<L>It may be wel &yogh;it peraduenture to say</L>
<L>&yogh;e schullen &yogh;our trou&thorn;e holden by my fay</L>
<L>ffor god so wisly helpe me</L>
<L N="1476">I hadde wel leuere y-stiked for to be /</L>
<L>ffor verray loue which &thorn;at I to &yogh;ou haue</L>
<L>But if &yogh;e schulde &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e saue</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is &yogh;e heihest &thorn;ing &thorn;at man may kepe</L>
<L N="1480">But wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he brast anon to weepe /</L>
<L>And sayde I &yogh;ou forbede vp payne of de&thorn;</L>
<L>That neuer whiles &thorn;e laste&thorn; lyf and bre&thorn;</L>
<L>To no wight telle how &thorn;at &thorn;is matere /</L>
<L N="1484">As I may kepe I wole my woo endere</L>
<L>Ne make no contynaunce of heuynesse</L>
<L>That folk of &yogh;ou may deme harme or gesse</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he cleped a squyer and a mayde</L>
<L N="1488">Go&thorn; for&thorn; anon wi&thorn; Dorigen he sayde /
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="373"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="522"></L>
<L>And bringe&thorn; hire to such a place anon</L>
<L>&thorn;ey tooke her leue and on &thorn;air way &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L>But &thorn;ey ne wiste why sche &thorn;ider wente</L>
<L N="1492">he nolde no wight telle hire entente</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Not in Arch. Seld. B.</I> 14. <I>These lines known only in the Ellesmere MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="1496">. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>This squyer which &thorn;at hight Aurelyus</L>
<L N="1500">On Dorigen which &thorn;at was so amerous</L>
<L>Of aduenture happed hire to mete</L>
<L>Amyd &thorn;e toun right in &thorn;e quyke strete</L>
<L>As sche was boun to gon &thorn;e wey for&thorn; right</L>
<L N="1504">Toward &thorn;e gardyn &thorn;er as sche hadde hight</L>
<L>And he was to &thorn;e gardynward also</L>
<L>ffor wel he spyed whan sche wolde go</L>
<L>Out of hir hous to eny maner place</L>
<L N="1508">But &thorn;us &thorn;ey mette of auenture or of grace</L>
<L>And he saluy&thorn; hire wi&thorn; glad entent</L>
<L>And axed of hire whider &thorn;at sche wente /<MILESTONE N="170a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And sche answerde half as sche were mad</L>
<L N="1512">vnto &thorn;e gardyn as myn housbonde bad</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e for to holde allas allas</L>
<L>Aurelius gan wonder of &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>And in his herte had gret compassion</L>
<L N="1516">Of hire and of hire lamentacion</L>
<L>And of Arneragus &thorn;e wor&thorn;y knight</L>
<L>And bad hire holde al &thorn;at sche hight</L>
<L>So lo&thorn; he was his wijf schulde breke hir trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>And in his herte he caste of &thorn;is gret rou&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>blots over</I> e <I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Considerynge &thorn;e beste on euery syde /</L>
<L>That fro his luste were him better abyde</L>
<L>Than don so heigh a cherles wrecchednes</L>
<L N="1524">A&yogh;eins fraunchise and a&yogh;ein al gentilnes
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="374"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="523"></L>
<L>ffor which in fewe wordes sayde he &thorn;us</L>
<L>Ma dame sei&thorn; to &yogh;oure lord Arneragus</L>
<L>&thorn;at se&thorn;yns I se &thorn;is grete gentilnes /</L>
<L N="1528">To &yogh;ou and ek I se wel &yogh;oure distres</L>
<L N="1530">&thorn;en &yogh;e to me &thorn;us schulde breke &yogh;oure trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Certes me &thorn;inke&thorn; it were right gret rou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>spurious</I> 1529]</NOTE></L>
<L>I haue wel leuer euer to suffre wo</L>
<L N="1532">&thorn;en I departe &thorn;e loue betwixe &yogh;ou tuo</L>
<L>I &yogh;ou relesse ma dame in to &yogh;oure hand</L>
<L>Quyte euery surement and euery band</L>
<L>That &yogh;e han made to me as here byforn</L>
<L N="1536">Si&thorn;ens &thorn;ilke tyme that &yogh;e were born</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e I plight I schal &yogh;ou neuer repreue</L>
<L>Of no biheste and here I take my leue /</L>
<L>As of &thorn;e trewest and &thorn;e beste wyf</L>
<L N="1540">&thorn;at euer &yogh;it/ I knew in al my lyf</L>
<L>But euery wight be war of hire byheste</L>
<L>On Dorigen remembre&thorn; atte leste /</L>
<L>Thus can a squier don a gentil dede</L>
<L N="1544">As wel as can a knight wi&thorn;outen drede</L>
<L>Sche &thorn;anked him vppon hir knees al bare</L>
<L>And home vnto hire housbonde is sche fare<MILESTONE N="170b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And tolde hem alle as &yogh;e han herde me sayde</L>
<L N="1548">And be &yogh;e siker he was so wel a-payde /</L>
<L>&thorn;at it were inpossible to write /</L>
<L>What schulde I lengere of &thorn;is cas endite /</L>
<L>Arneragus and dorigen his wijff</L>
<L N="1552">In souerayn blisse leden for&thorn; here lyff</L>
<L>Neuer eft ne was &thorn;er anger hem betwene</L>
<L>he cherissche&thorn; hire as &thorn;ough sche were a quene</L>
<L N="1555">And sche was to him trewe for euermore</L>
<L N="1557">Aurelius &thorn;at his cost ha&thorn; al forlore</L>
<L N="1558">Curse&thorn; &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at euer he was y-born</L>
<L>ffor certes he sei&thorn; I am forlorn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L>Allas quod he allas &thorn;at I behight</L>
<L N="1560">Of pured gold a &thorn;ousand pound of wight/
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="375"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="524"></L>
<L>vnto &thorn;is philosofre how schal I do</L>
<L>I se no more but &thorn;at I am fordo /</L>
<L>Myn heritage moot I needes selle</L>
<L N="1564">And ben a beggere here may I no lenger dwelle</L>
<L>And schamen al my kynrede in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>But I of him may gete bettre grace /</L>
<L>[but natheles / I wol of him assaye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L N="1568">at certeyne dayes / yere bi yere to paye]</L>
<L>I wole &thorn;onke him of his grete curtesye</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e wol I kepe I wol nou&yogh;t lye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; herte sore he go&thorn; vnto his coffre</L>
<L N="1572">And broughte gold vnto his philosophre</L>
<L>The value of .v. hundred pound I gesse</L>
<L>And him beseche&thorn; of his gentilnesse</L>
<L>To graunte him dayes of &thorn;e remenant</L>
<L N="1576">And maister I dar wel make auaunt</L>
<L>I fayled neuer my trou&thorn;e as &yogh;it</L>
<L>ffor sikerly my dettes schal be quyt</L>
<L>Towardes &yogh;ou how euer &thorn;at I fare</L>
<L N="1580">To gon abegged in my kirtel bare</L>
<L>But wolde &yogh;e fouche sauf vpon suerte</L>
<L>Two &yogh;ere or &thorn;re to respiten me</L>
<L>&thorn;enne were I wel for elles moste I selle /<NOTE PLACE="marg">[a leaf out of the Corpus MS.]</NOTE></L>
<L>[myn heritage / ther is no more to telle<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="261b"></L>
<L>this Philosophre soburly answerde</L>
<L>and seide thus / whan he these wordes herde</L>
<L>haue I nat holden couenaunt / vn-to the</L>
<L N="1588">yis certes / wel &amp; trewely / quod he</L>
<L>hast thow nat had thi lady / as the liketh</L>
<L>no no quod he / &amp; sorowfully he siketh</L>
<L>what was the cause / telle me if thou can</L>
<L N="1592">Aurelius his tale / anoon bigan</L>
<L>and tolde him al / as ye han herde bifore</L>
<L>hit nedith nat / to rehersen it no more</L>
<L>he seide Arueragus / of gentilnesse</L>
<L N="1596">had leuer dien / in sorow &amp; distresse
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="376"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="525"></L>
<L>than his wiff / were of hir trouthe fals<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>the sorow of Dorigen / he told him als</L>
<L>how loth hir was / to ben a wikked wiff</L>
<L N="1600">and that she leuere had that day lost hir liff</L>
<L>and that hir trouthe she swore / thorugh innocence</L>
<L>she neuere erst herde speke / of apparence</L>
<L>that made me han of hir / so grete pite</L>
<L N="1604">and right as frely / as he sente hir to me</L>
<L>as frely sente I hir / to him ageyne</L>
<L>this is al &amp; som / ther is no more to seyne</L>
<L>this Philosophre answerde / leue brother<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="262a"></L>
<L N="1608">eueryche of yow dide gentilly / to other</L>
<L>thow art a squyer / &amp; he is a knyght</L>
<L>but god forbede / for his blisful myght</L>
<L>but if a Clerke / couthe do a gentil dede</L>
<L N="1612">as wel as any of yow / it is no drede</L>
<L>sir I relece the / thi thousand pounde</L>
<L>as thow right now / were crope out of the grounde</L>
<L>ne neuere er now / ne haddist thow knowe me</L>
<L N="1616">for sir I wol nat taken / a peny of the</L>
<L>for al my crafft / ne nought for my travaile</L>
<L>thow hast I-paide wel / for my vitaile</L>
<L>hit is I-now / &amp; farewel haue good day</L>
<L N="1620">and toke his hors / &amp; forth he goth his way</L>
<L>lordinges this question / than wold I axe now</L>
<L>whiche was the most fre / as thenketh yow</L>
<L>now telleth me / er that I ferther wende</L>
<L N="1624">I can no more / my tale is at an ende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Here endith the ffrankeleyne his tale]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Arch. Seld. <I>extr. ends</I>]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="G" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="377">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="527">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>G.</B> FRAGMENT VIII.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE SECOND NUN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>CORPUS MS.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE PROEM.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[No breaks in the Corpus MS between the stanzas.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD>[And next bigynneth the seconde nonne hir tale. &amp;c.<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="215a"></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">The ministre and norice / vn-to vices</L>
<L>which that men clepen / in englissh / Idelnesse</L>
<L>that porter of the gate is / of delices</L>
<L N="4">to eschewen / and bi hir contrarie to oppresse</L>
<L>that is to seyne / bi leoful besynesse</L>
<L>wel oughte we to don / al oure entente</L>
<L N="7">lest that the fende / thorugh Idelnesse vs hente.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">ffor he that with his thousand cordes slighe</L>
<L>contenuelly vs waiteth / to bi-clappe</L>
<L>whan he may man/ in Idelnesse aspie</L>
<L N="11">he can so lightly cacche him / in his trappe</L>
<L>til that a man be hente / right bi the lappe</L>
<L>he nys not ware / the fende hath him in honde</L>
<L N="14">wel oughte vs werche / and Idelnesse with-stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">And though men dradden neuere / for to die</L>
<L>yit se men wel bi reson / doutelese</L>
<L>that Idelnesse is hoten / slogardie</L>
<L N="18">of whiche cometh neuere / noon encrese</L>
<L>and sithen that slouth hir holdith in a lese</L>
<L>only for to slepe / and ete and drynke</L>
<L N="21">and to devouron / al that other swynke<MILESTONE UNIT="MS Arch. Seld. B. 14 folio" N="215b">
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="378"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="528"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And for to putten vs / from suche Idelnesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>that cause is / of so grete confusion</L>
<L>I haue here don / my feithful besynesse</L>
<L N="25">after the legende / in translacion</L>
<L>right after thi glorious liff / and passion</L>
<L>thow with thi garland / wroughte of rose and lylye</L>
<L N="28">the mene I / maide / and martir / seynt Cecelye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">&para; And thow that floure art / of virgynes alle</L>
<L>of whom that Bernard / list so wel to write</L>
<L>to the at my bigynnyng / first I calle</L>
<L N="32">thow comforte of vs wrecches / do me endite</L>
<L>thi maidens deth / that was thorugh hir merite</L>
<L>the eternal liff / and of the fende victorie</L>
<L N="35">as men mow after rede / in hir storie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thow maiden and moder / doughter of thi sone]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Arch. Seld. B. 14</B> <I>extr. ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thou welle of mercy synful soules cure<MILESTONE N="171a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In whom &thorn;at god for bounte chees to wone</L>
<L N="39">Thou humble and heih ouer euery creature</L>
<L>Thou nobledest so ferre oure nature</L>
<L>That no desdeyn &thorn;e makere hadde of kynde</L>
<L N="42">his sone in blood and fleissch to clo&thorn;e and wynde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">&para; Wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e cloystre blisful of &thorn;ine sydes</L>
<L>Took mannes schap &thorn;e eterne loue and pees</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e trine compas lord and gyde is</L>
<L N="46">Whom er&thorn;e and see and heuene out of reles</L>
<L>Ay herien and &thorn;ou virgine wemmeles</L>
<L>Bare of &thorn;y body and dwelledest/ mayde pure</L>
<L N="49">The creatour of euery creature
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="379"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="529"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="50">&para; Assembled is in &thorn;i magnificence</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mercy goodnesse and with such pite</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou art &thorn;e sonne of excellence</L>
<L N="53">Nou&yogh;t only helpest hem &thorn;at prayen &thorn;e</L>
<L>But ofte tyme of &thorn;in benignite</L>
<L>fful frely er &thorn;at men &thorn;in helpe beseche</L>
<L N="56">&thorn;ou gost byforn and art here lyfes leche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="57">&para; Now help &thorn;ou meke and blisful faire mayde</L>
<L>Me flemyd wrecche in &thorn;is desert of galle</L>
<L>Thenk on &thorn;e womman Canane &thorn;at sayde</L>
<L N="60">That whelpes eten some of &thorn;e crommes alle</L>
<L>&thorn;at from here lordes table ben y-falle</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough &thorn;at I &thorn;e vnwor&thorn;y sone of eue</L>
<L N="63">be synful &yogh;it accepte my byleeue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="64">And for &thorn;at fei&thorn; is deed wi&thorn;oute werkes</L>
<L>So for to worchen &yogh;if me witte and space</L>
<L>&thorn;at I be quyt from place &thorn;at most derk is</L>
<L N="67">O &thorn;ou &thorn;at art so fair and so ful of grace</L>
<L>Be myn aduocate in so heih a place</L>
<L>Ther as wi&thorn;outen ende is longe Osanna</L>
<L N="70">Thou cristes moder and doughter of Anna</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="71">And of &thorn;in light my soule kepe in prison</L>
<L>That troubled is by &thorn;e contagioun</L>
<L>[of my body / &amp; also bi the wighte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L N="74">of erthely lust / &amp; fals affeccion]</L>
<L>O heuene o refute O saluacion<MILESTONE N="171b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at ben in sorwe and in destresse /</L>
<L N="77">&middot; Now help for vnto my werk I wol me dresse /
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="380"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="530"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="78">&para; &yogh;et pray I &yogh;ou &thorn;at reden &thorn;at I write</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;eue&thorn; me for I do no diligence</L>
<L>&thorn;is ilke story subtil to endite</L>
<L N="81">ffor bo&thorn;e haue I &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e sentence /</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at atte seyntes reuerence /</L>
<L>The story wroot &amp; solewen hir legende</L>
<L N="84">And pray I &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e woln my werk amende</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13) [<I>THE TALE.</I>]</HEAD>
<L N="85">fferst wolde I &yogh;ou &thorn;e name of seint Cecile</L>
<L>Expoune as men may in here stories se</L>
<L>It is to say on englissh heuene lylye</L>
<L N="88">ffor pure chastnesse of virginite /</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for sche witnesse hadde of honeste</L>
<L>Of greue of conscience and of good fame</L>
<L N="91">The soote sauour lilye was hire name</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="92">Ou&thorn;er Cecile is to say &thorn;e way to blynde</L>
<L>ffor sche ensample was by good techynge</L>
<L>Or elles. Cecile is as I writen fynde</L>
<L N="95">Is ioyned by a maner conioygnynge</L>
<L>Of heuen and lya and heiher in figuringe</L>
<L>The heuen is set for &thorn;ought of holynesse</L>
<L N="98">And lya for hire lastyng busynesse /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="99">Cecile may eek be sayd in &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Wantynge of blyndnesse for hire grete light</L>
<L>Of sapiens and for hir &thorn;ewes clere</L>
<L N="102">O&thorn;er elles &thorn;is maydenes name bright/</L>
<L>Of heuen and leos come&thorn; for which by right</L>
<L>men mighte &thorn;e heuene of poeple hire calle</L>
<L N="105">Ensample of goode and wise werkes alle
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="381"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="531"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L N="106">ffor leos poeple in englissch is to say</L>
<L>And right as men may in &thorn;is heuene se</L>
<L>&thorn;e sonne and moone and &thorn;e sterres euery way</L>
<L N="109">Right so gostly in &thorn;is mayden fre</L>
<L>Seyen &thorn;e fei&thorn; of magnificence</L>
<L>And ekyng of hel&thorn;e and of sapience<MILESTONE N="172a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="112">And sondry werkes bright of excellence /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">And right as &thorn;is philosophres wryte</L>
<L>That heuen is swyft round and brynnyng</L>
<L>Right so was faire Cecile &thorn;e whyte</L>
<L N="116">fful swift and besy euer in good werkyng</L>
<L>And round &amp; hool in good perseueryng</L>
<L>And brenne euere in charite lighte /</L>
<L N="119">Now haue I declared &yogh;ou what sche highte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="120">This mayden bright Cecile as hire lyf sai&thorn;</L>
<L>Was comen of Romayns and of noble kynde</L>
<L>And so for&thorn; fostred vp in &thorn;e fai&thorn;</L>
<L N="123">Of crist and bar his gospel in hire mynde</L>
<L>Sche neuer cessede as I writen fynde</L>
<L>Of hire prayere and god to loue and drede</L>
<L N="126">Besechinge him to kepe hire maydenhede /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="127">And what &thorn;is mayden schulde vnto a man</L>
<L>y-wedded be &thorn;at was ful &yogh;ong of age</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at y-cleped was valerian</L>
<L N="130">And &thorn;e day was comen of hire mariage</L>
<L>Sche fil deuoute and humble /in hire corage</L>
<L>Vnder hire robe of gold &thorn;at sat ful faire</L>
<L N="133">And next hire fleissh sche clad hire in an haire
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="382"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="532"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="134">And whiles &thorn;e Orgles maden melodye</L>
<L>To god allone &thorn;us in herte sang sche</L>
<L>O lord my soule and eek my body gye</L>
<L N="137">Vnwemmed lest &thorn;at I confoundid be</L>
<L>And for his loue &thorn;at deyde vpon a tre</L>
<L>Euery secounde or &thorn;ridde day sche faste</L>
<L N="140">Ay byddyng in hire orisons ful faste</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="141">The night com and to bedde sche moste gon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire housbonde as often is &thorn;e manere</L>
<L>And pryuely sche sayde to him anon</L>
<L N="144">O swete and wel biloued spouse dere</L>
<L>Ther is a counseil and &yogh;e wolde it here /</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at right fayn I wol vnto &yogh;ou sayn</L>
<L N="147">So &thorn;at &yogh;e me assure it nought to bewrayn<MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="148">Valerian gan faste / vnto hire swere</L>
<L>That for no cas ne &thorn;ing &thorn;at mighte be</L>
<L>he scholde for no &thorn;ing neuer bywreyen hire</L>
<L N="151">And &thorn;anne at erst &thorn;us to him sayde sche</L>
<L>I haue an aungel which &thorn;at loue&thorn; me</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; gret loue whe&thorn;er so I wake or slepe</L>
<L N="154">Is redy ay my body for to kepe</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="155">And if &thorn;at he may felen out of drede</L>
<L>[that ye me touche / or loue in vilonye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>he right anoon wol sle yow / with the dede</L>
<L N="158">and in youre youthe / thus shul ye die</L>
<L>and if that ye / in clene loue me guye]</L>
<L>he wolde &yogh;ou loue as me for &yogh;our clennesse</L>
<L N="161">And schewe &yogh;ou of his ioye and his brightnesse
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="383"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="533"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="162">valerian corrected as god wolde</L>
<L>Answerde a&yogh;ein if I schal truste to &thorn;e /</L>
<L>let me &thorn;at aungel see and him biholde</L>
<L N="165">And if &thorn;at it a verray aungel be</L>
<L>Thanne wol I don as &thorn;ou hast preyed me</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou loue ano&thorn;er man for so&thorn;e /</L>
<L N="168">Right wi&thorn; &thorn;is swerd I wol sle &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="169">Cecily answerde anon in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;ou luste &thorn;at aungel schul &yogh;e se</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e trowe on crist and &yogh;ou baptise</L>
<L N="172">Go&thorn; for&thorn; to via apia quod sche</L>
<L>&thorn;at from &thorn;is toun ne stant by myles &thorn;re /</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pouere folkes &thorn;at &thorn;ere dwelle /</L>
<L N="175">Sey hem right &thorn;us as &thorn;at/ I schal &yogh;ou telle /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="176">Telle hem &thorn;at I Cecile &yogh;ou to hem sent</L>
<L>To schewen &yogh;ou &thorn;e goode vrban &thorn;e olde</L>
<L>ffor secre needes and fro good entent</L>
<L N="179">And whan &thorn;at &yogh;e seint vrban han byholde /</L>
<L>Telle him &thorn;e wordes whiche &thorn;at I &yogh;ou tolde /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he ha&thorn; purged &yogh;ou from synne</L>
<L N="182">&thorn;anne schal &yogh;e see &thorn;at aungel er &yogh;e twynne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="183">Valerian is to &thorn;at place y-gon</L>
<L>And right as him was taught by his lernyng</L>
<L>he fond &thorn;is holy Vrban &thorn;er anon</L>
<L N="186">Among &thorn;ese seyntes buriels lotying<NOTE PLACE="marg">.i. latitans</NOTE></L>
<L>And he anon wi&thorn;oute tarying<MILESTONE N="173a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dide his message and whan he hadde tolde</L>
<L N="189">Vrban for ioye gan his handes vpholde
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="384"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="534"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="190">The teeres from his eyhen leet he falle /</L>
<L>Almighty god O Ihesu crist quod he</L>
<L>Sowere of chaste counseille and herde of vs alle</L>
<L N="193">&thorn;e fruyt of &thorn;ilke seed of chastite /</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast sowe in Cecile tak to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Lo y-like a busy bee wi&thorn;oute gyle</L>
<L N="196">The serue&thorn; ay &thorn;in oughne &thorn;ralle Cecile</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="197">&para; ffor &thorn;ilke spouse &thorn;at sche tok but now /</L>
<L>fful like a fiers leon sche sende&thorn; heere /</L>
<L>As meke as eny lambe was to &yogh;ow /</L>
<L N="200">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word anon &thorn;er gan apeere /</L>
<L>An olde man clad wi&thorn; white clo&thorn;es cleere</L>
<L>And hadde a book wi&thorn; lettres of gold in honde</L>
<L N="203">And gan biforn Valerian to stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="204">Valerian as deed fel doun for drede</L>
<L>Whan he him saugh and him vp hente &thorn;o</L>
<L>And on his book right &thorn;us he gan to rede /</L>
<L N="207">O lord o fei&thorn; o god wi&thorn;oute mo<NOTE PLACE="marg">Et lamentat [<I>is the next line</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of cristendom and fader of al also</L>
<L>Abouen alle and ouer alle euery where</L>
<L N="210">This wordes alle with golde writen were /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="211">Whan &thorn;is was rad &thorn;an sayde &thorn;is olde man</L>
<L>leeuest &thorn;ou &thorn;is &thorn;ing or no sey &yogh;e or nay</L>
<L>I leeue alle &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;an &thorn;is [quod tho Valerian<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L N="214">for sother thing than this /] I dar wel say</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e heuene no wight/ ne &thorn;enke may</L>
<L>&thorn;o vanyssched &thorn;e olde man he nyste where</L>
<L N="217">And pope vrban him cristned right &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="385"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="535"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L N="218">Valerian go&thorn; hom and seint Cecile</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne his chambre an aungel stande</L>
<L>&thorn;is aungel hadde of Rose and of lylie</L>
<L N="221">Corounes tuo &thorn;e which he bar in hande</L>
<L>And ferst to Cecile as I vnderstande /</L>
<L>he &yogh;af &thorn;at oon and after gan he take<MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="224">&thorn;at o&thorn;er to Valerian hire make</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L N="225">With body clene and wi&thorn; vnwemmyd &thorn;ou&yogh;t /</L>
<L>kepe&thorn; ay wel &thorn;is corounes quod he</L>
<L>ffrom paradys to &yogh;ou haue I hem brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="228">Ne neuer more schulle &thorn;ey roten be</L>
<L>&para; Ne leese here swete sauour truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>Ne neuere wight schal seen hem wi&thorn; his yhe</L>
<L N="231">But he be chaste and hate vilonye /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L N="232">And &thorn;ou valerian for &thorn;ou so sone</L>
<L>Assentedest to good counseil also</L>
<L>Sey what &thorn;e luste and &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;y bone /</L>
<L N="235">I haue a bro&thorn;er quod valerian &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;is world I loue no man so</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ou &thorn;at my bro&thorn;er may han grace</L>
<L N="238">To knowe &thorn;e trou&thorn;e as I do in &thorn;is [place]</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L N="239">The aungel answerde god like&thorn; &yogh;oure requeste</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e with &thorn;e palme of martirdome</L>
<L>&yogh;e schulle come vnto &thorn;e blisful feste</L>
<L N="242">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word Tiburce his bro&thorn;er come</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;e sauour vndernome</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;e roses and &thorn;e lylies caste /</L>
<L N="245">Wi&thorn;inne his herte he gan to wondre faste /
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="386"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="536"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L N="246">And seyde in &thorn;is tyme I wondre of &thorn;e &yogh;eere</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;is swote sauour come&thorn; so /</L>
<L>And Rosis and lilyes &thorn;at I smelle heere</L>
<L N="249">ffor &thorn;ough I hadde hem in myn hondes tuo</L>
<L>The sauour might in me no deppere go</L>
<L>&thorn;e swete smelle &thorn;at in myn herte I fynde</L>
<L N="252">ha&thorn; chaunged me al in ano&thorn;er kinde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L N="253">valerian sayde tuo corounes han we</L>
<L>Snow whit and Rose Reed &thorn;at schyne&thorn; cleere</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;in yhe ha&thorn; no might to see</L>
<L N="256">And as &thorn;ou smellest hem &thorn;orugh my preyere</L>
<L>So schalt &thorn;ou seen hem leeue bro&thorn;er deere</L>
<L>If it/ so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt wi&thorn;outen slou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="259">Bileeue aright and knowe verray trou&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="174a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L N="260">Tiburce answerde saist &thorn;ou &thorn;is to me</L>
<L>In so&thorn;nesse or in drem herkne &yogh;e &thorn;is</L>
<L>In dremes quod valerian han we be</L>
<L N="263">vnto &thorn;is tyme bro&thorn;er myn y-wys</L>
<L>But now at erste oure trou&thorn;e dwellyng is</L>
<L>how wost &thorn;ou quod Tiburce and in what wyse /</L>
<L N="266">Quod valerian &thorn;at I schal &thorn;e deuyse /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L N="267">&thorn;e aungel of god ha&thorn; me &thorn;e trou&thorn;e y-taught</L>
<L>Which thou schalt seen if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt reneye</L>
<L>&thorn;e ydolis and be clene and elles naught</L>
<L N="270">And of &thorn;e miracles of &thorn;ise corounes tweye</L>
<L>Seint ambrose in his preface lust to seye</L>
<L>Solempnely &thorn;is noble doctor deere</L>
<L N="273">Comendi&thorn; it/ and sai&thorn; in &thorn;is maneere
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="387"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="537"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L N="274">The palme of martirdom for to receyue</L>
<L>Seint Cecile fulfilde of goddes &yogh;ifte</L>
<L>&thorn;e worlde and eek hire chambre gan sche weyue</L>
<L N="277">Witnesse Tiburce and Cecyles schrifte/</L>
<L>To which god of his bounte wolde schifte</L>
<L>Corounes two of floures wel smellynge /</L>
<L N="280">And made &thorn;e aungel hem &thorn;o corounes brynge</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L N="281">&para; &thorn;e mayde ha&thorn; brought &thorn;ise men to blisse aboue</L>
<L>The world ha&thorn; wist what it is wor&thorn; certeyn</L>
<L>Deuocion of chastite to loue</L>
<L N="284">&thorn;o schewed him Cecile open and pleyn</L>
<L>That alle ydolis nys but &thorn;ing in veyn</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ey ben dombe and &thorn;er-to &thorn;ey ben deue</L>
<L N="287">And charged him his ydolis for to leue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L N="288">&para; Who &thorn;at &thorn;is trowe&thorn; not a beste he is /</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;o Tiburce if &thorn;at I schal not lye</L>
<L>Sche gan &thorn;anne kisse his breste and &thorn;at herde &thorn;is</L>
<L N="291">And was ful glad he cou&thorn;e trou&thorn;e aspye</L>
<L>This day take &thorn;e for myn allye</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is blisful mayde fair and deere</L>
<L N="294">ffor after &thorn;at sche sayde as &yogh;e may heere</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L N="295">Lo right so &thorn;e loue of crist quod sche<MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>made me &thorn;in bro&thorn;eres wyf right in &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L>Anoon for myn allye here take I &thorn;e</L>
<L>Si&thorn;enes &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ink spilt over the page]</NOTE> &thorn;ine ydolis despise</L>
<L>Go with &thorn;y bro&thorn;er now and &thorn;e baptise /</L>
<L>And make &thorn;e clene so &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst beholde</L>
<L N="301">&thorn;e aungels face of which &thorn;y bro&thorn;er tolde
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="388"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="538"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L N="302">Tiburce answerde and seyde bro&thorn;er deere</L>
<L>fferst telle me whider I schal and to what man</L>
<L>To whom quod he com for&thorn; with right good cheere</L>
<L N="305">I wol &thorn;e lede vnto &thorn;e pope vrban</L>
<L>To Vrban bro&thorn;er myn Valerian</L>
<L>Quo&thorn; &thorn;o Tiburce wilt &thorn;ou me &thorn;ider lede</L>
<L N="308">Me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at it were a wonder dede</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L N="309">&para; Remenest &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t vrban quod he &thorn;o</L>
<L>That is so ofte dampned to be deed</L>
<L>And wone&thorn; in halkes to &amp; fro /</L>
<L N="312">And dar nou&yogh;t ones putte for&thorn; his heed</L>
<L>Men schulle him brenne in a fir so reed</L>
<L>If &thorn;at he were founde if &thorn;at men might him spye</L>
<L N="315">And we also &thorn;at bere him companye</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L N="316">And whiles we seken &thorn;ilke diuinyte</L>
<L>&thorn;at is y-hyd in heuene priuely</L>
<L>Algate y-brent in &thorn;is world schul we be</L>
<L N="319">To whom Cecile answerde bodyly</L>
<L>Men mighte drede wel and skilfully</L>
<L>&thorn;is lyf to lese myn owne deere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="322">yif &thorn;is were lyuynge oonly and non o&thorn;er</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L N="323">But &thorn;er is bettere lyf in o&thorn;er place</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer schal be lost ne drede &thorn;e nought</L>
<L>Which goddes sone vs tolde &thorn;orugh hi<SUP>s</SUP> grace</L>
<L>[that the fadris sone / hath al thing wrought<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>and al that wrought is / with a skilful thought</L>
<L>the goost that from the fader / gan procede</L>
<L N="329">hath souled hem / withouten eny drede.
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="389"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="539"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L>&para; By worde &amp; bi myracle / godis sone<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>whan he was in this world / declared here</L>
<L>that ther was other liff / there men may wone</L>
<L N="333">to whom answerde Tyburce / O suster dere</L>
<L>ne seidist thow right now / in this manere</L>
<L>ther nas but O god / lord in sothfastnesse</L>
<L N="336">and now of thre / how maist thow bere witnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>&para; That shal I telle quod she or that I go]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>MS Arch. Seld. B. 14</B> <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Right as a man ha&thorn; sapiences &thorn;re /</L>
<L>Memorie Ingenie and Intellecte also</L>
<L N="340">So in o beynge of diuynite /</L>
<L>Thre persones right wel &thorn;er may be</L>
<L>Tho gan sche him besyliche preche /</L>
<L N="343">Of cristes come. and of his peynes teche<MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L N="344">And many poyntes of his passion</L>
<L>how goddes sone in &thorn;is world was wi&thorn;holde</L>
<L>To do mankynde pleyn remission</L>
<L N="347">That was y-bounde in synne and cares colde</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is &thorn;ing sche vnto Tiburce tolde</L>
<L>And after &thorn;is Tiburce in good entent</L>
<L N="350">To pope vrban wi&thorn; Valerian he went</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L N="351">which &thorn;anked god and wi&thorn; glad herte &amp; light</L>
<L>he cristned him and made him in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Parfyt in his lyuynge goddes knight</L>
<L N="354">And after &thorn;is Tiburce gat such grace</L>
<L>&thorn;at euery day he seyh in tyme and space</L>
<L>&thorn;e aungel of god and euery maner bone</L>
<L N="357">&thorn;at he god asked it was sped ful sone
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="390"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="540"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L N="358">&para; It were ful hard by ordre for to seyn</L>
<L>how many wondres ihesu for him wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>But atte laste to telle schort and pleyn</L>
<L N="361">&thorn;e sergeaunt of &thorn;e toun of Rome hem sought</L>
<L>And hem byforn Almache &thorn;e prouost brought</L>
<L>Which hem opposede and knew al here entent</L>
<L N="364">And to &thorn;e ymage of Iubiter he hem sent /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L N="365">And sayde who so wol not Sacrifise</L>
<L>Swap of his heed &thorn;is is my sentence heere /</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ise martires &thorn;at I &yogh;ou deuyse /</L>
<L N="368">On Maximius &thorn;at was an officere /</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Prefectis and of Corniculere</L>
<L>hem hente and when he for&thorn; &thorn;e seintes ledde</L>
<L N="371">himself he weep for pite &thorn;at he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L N="372">&para; Whan maximine hadde herde &thorn;e seintes lore /</L>
<L>he gat hem of &thorn;e tormentoures leue /</L>
<L>And hadde hem in his hous wi&thorn;oute more</L>
<L N="375">And wi&thorn; here prechyng er &thorn;at it/ were eue</L>
<L>&thorn;ey gonne from &thorn;e tormentours to reue /</L>
<L>And from Maximius and from his folk ilkon</L>
<L N="378">&thorn;e false fei&thorn; to trowe in god allon</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L N="379">Cecile cam whan it was woxen night<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; prestes &thorn;at hem cristned alle in feere</L>
<L>And aftirward. whan day was waxen light</L>
<L N="382">Cecile hem sayde wi&thorn; a sobre chere</L>
<L>Now cristes owne knightes leeue and deere</L>
<L>Caste&thorn; alle a wey &thorn;e werkes of derknesse /</L>
<L N="385">And arme&thorn; &yogh;ou in armure of lightnesse
<PB REF="00000419.tif" N="391"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="541"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L N="386">&yogh;e han forso&thorn;e ydon grete bataille</L>
<L>&yogh;oure is doon &yogh;oure fei&thorn; han &yogh;e conserued</L>
<L>Go&thorn; to &thorn;e coroune of lyf &thorn;at may nou&yogh;t faille</L>
<L N="389">&thorn;e rightful Iuge which &thorn;at &yogh;e han [served<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>shal yeue hit yow / as ye han it] deserued</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &thorn;ing was sayd as I deuyse</L>
<L N="392">men ladde hem forth to don &thorn;e sacrifise /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L N="393">But whan &thorn;ey were vnto &thorn;e place y-brou&yogh;t /</L>
<L>To telle schortly &thorn;e conclusion</L>
<L>&thorn;ey nolde encense no sacrifice right nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="396">But on here knees &thorn;ey setten hem adoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; humble herte and sad deuocion</L>
<L>And losten bo&thorn;e here hedes in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="399">here soules wenten to &thorn;e kyng of grace</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L N="400">This maximius &thorn;at say &thorn;is &thorn;ing betyde /</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pitous tales tolde it/ anon right</L>
<L>&thorn;at he here soules saugh to heuen glyde</L>
<L N="403">With aungels ful of clernes and of light</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his word conuerted many a wight</L>
<L>ffor which Almachus dede him so to bete</L>
<L N="406">Wi&thorn; whippe of leed til he his lyf gan lete /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L N="407">Cecile him took and buried him anon</L>
<L>By Tyburce and Valerian softely</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne hire heryinge place vnder &thorn;e ston</L>
<L N="410">And after &thorn;is Almachius hastily</L>
<L>Bad his mynistres fecchen openly</L>
<L>Cecile so sche mighte in his presence</L>
<L N="413">Do sacrifice and Iubiter encense
<PB REF="00000420.tif" N="392"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="542"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L N="414">But &thorn;ey conuertid &thorn;orugh hire wise lore</L>
<L>Wepten sore and &yogh;auen credence /</L>
<L>Vnto hire word and cryden more and more<MILESTONE N="176a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="417">Crist goddes sone wi&thorn;outen difference</L>
<L>his verray god &thorn;is is alle oure sentence</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn; so good a seruant him to serue</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;us wi&thorn; oo vois we trowe &thorn;ey&yogh; we sterue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L N="421">Almachius &thorn;at herde al &thorn;is speking</L>
<L>Bad fecche Cecile &thorn;at he might hir se</L>
<L>And al&thorn;er first lo &thorn;is was his askyng</L>
<L N="424">What maner womman artow &thorn;o quod he /</L>
<L>I am a gentil womman born quod sche /</L>
<L>I aske quod he &thorn;ou&yogh; it &thorn;e greue</L>
<L N="427">Of &thorn;in religion and of &thorn;in byleeue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L N="428">Whi &thorn;anne bygan &yogh;oure question folily</L>
<L>Quod sche &thorn;at woldest tuo answers conclude /</L>
<L>In oo demaunde &yogh;e askide lewedly</L>
<L N="431">Almachie answerde to &thorn;at similitude /</L>
<L>[of whens cometh thin answere / so rude]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Arch. Seld. B. 14]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of whennes quod sche. whan &thorn;at sche was refreyned</L>
<L N="434">Of conscience and of good fei&thorn; vnfeyned</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L N="435">Almachius sayde takest &thorn;ou non heede /</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in answere and sche him answerde &thorn;us</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure might quod sche litel is to drede /</L>
<L N="438">ffor euery mortel mannes power nys</L>
<L>But y-like a bladdre ful of wynd y-wys /</L>
<L>ffor wi&thorn; a neldis poynt/ when &thorn;at is blowe</L>
<L N="441">may al &thorn;e bost of it be leyd ful lowe /
<PB REF="00000421.tif" N="393"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="543"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L N="442">fful wrongfully bigan &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>And &yogh;it in wrong is &thorn;in perseuerance</L>
<L>Wost &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t how oure mighty princes fre</L>
<L N="445">Ben &thorn;us comaundid and maken ordinannce</L>
<L>That euery cristne wight schal han penannce</L>
<L>But if &thorn;at he his cristendom wi&thorn;-seye</L>
<L N="448">And gon al quyt if he wol it receyue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L N="449">&para; &YOGH;oure princes erren as &yogh;oure noblen doth</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;o Cecile / and a wood sentence</L>
<L>&yogh;e make vs gulty and it nys nou&yogh;t so&thorn;</L>
<L N="452">ffor &yogh;e &thorn;at knowen wel oure Innocence</L>
<L>ffor as moche as we don a reuerence<MILESTONE N="176b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To crist. and for we bere a cristene name</L>
<L N="455">&yogh;e putte on vs a cryme and eek a blame</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L N="456">But we &thorn;at knowen &thorn;ilke name so</L>
<L>ffor vertuous we may it not say</L>
<L>Almachie answerde chese on of &thorn;ise tuo</L>
<L N="459">Do sacrifice or cristendom reneyne</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou mow now skapen by &thorn;at wey</L>
<L>At which &thorn;e holy blisful mayde</L>
<L N="462">gan for to laughe and to &thorn;e Iuge sche sayde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L N="463">O Iuge confuse in &thorn;y nycete</L>
<L>Wolt &thorn;ou &thorn;at I reneye Innocence /</L>
<L>To make me a wicked wight quod sche</L>
<L N="466">loo he dissimile&thorn; here in audience /</L>
<L>he stare&thorn; and woode&thorn; in his aduertence</L>
<L>To whom almachius O Vnseely wrecche /</L>
<L N="469">Ne wost &thorn;ou nought how fer my might may strecche
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="394"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="544"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<L N="470">ha&thorn; nought oure mighty prince to me y-&yogh;ouen</L>
<L>&yogh;e bo&thorn;e power and auctorite /</L>
<L>To make folk to deyen and to lyuen</L>
<L N="473">Why spekest &thorn;ou so proudly &thorn;enne to me</L>
<L>I ne speke it nou&yogh;t but stedefastly quod sche /</L>
<L>Nought proudly for I say as for my syde</L>
<L N="476">I hate dedly &thorn;ilke vice of pryde</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L N="477">&para; And if &thorn;ou drede nou&yogh;t a so&thorn; to heere</L>
<L>&thorn;an wol I schewen al openly by right</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou hast/ maad a ful gret lesyng heere</L>
<L N="480">&thorn;ou sayst &thorn;y princes han &yogh;eue &thorn;e might</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to sleen and eek for to quike a wight</L>
<L>&thorn;ou &thorn;at ne mayst but oonly lyf here byreue</L>
<L N="483">&thorn;an nast &thorn;erto ney&thorn;er power ne leeue</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L N="484">But &thorn;ou mayst see &thorn;in princes han &thorn;e maked</L>
<L>Ministre of de&thorn; for if &thorn;ou speke of mo /</L>
<L>&thorn;ou lyest for &thorn;y power is ful naked</L>
<L N="487">Do wey &thorn;y boldenesse/ seyde almachius &thorn;o</L>
<L>And sacrifice to oure goddes or two<MILESTONE N="177a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I ne recche nou&yogh;t what wrang &thorn;at &thorn;ou me profre</L>
<L N="490">ffor I can suffre it as a philosophre</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L N="491">But &thorn;ilke wronges may I nought endure</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou spekest of oure goddes here quod he /</L>
<L>Cecile answerde O nyce creature</L>
<L N="494">&thorn;ou saydest no word syns &thorn;ou speeke to me</L>
<L>&thorn;at I ne knewe &thorn;erwith &thorn;y nycete</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou were in euery maner wyse /</L>
<L N="497">A lewed officer and a vein Iustise
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="395"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="545"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<L N="498">&thorn;er lacke&thorn; no&thorn;ing to &thorn;in vtter yhen</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou nart blynd for &thorn;ing &thorn;at we seen alle</L>
<L>That is a ston yt men wel may aspyen</L>
<L N="501">That ilke ston a god &thorn;ou wilt it calle</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;e let &thorn;in hond vpon it falle</L>
<L>And taste it wel and stoon &thorn;ou schalt it fynde /</L>
<L N="504">Syns &thorn;at &thorn;ou sixt it nought wi&thorn; &thorn;in y&yogh;en blynde /</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L N="505">It is a schame &thorn;at &thorn;e poeple schall</L>
<L>So skorne &thorn;e and lawhe at &thorn;y folye /</L>
<L>ffor comunely wommen woot it wel ouer al</L>
<L N="508">&thorn;at mighty god is in his heuene<SUP>s</SUP> hihe</L>
<L>And &thorn;ese ymages wel &thorn;anne mayst &thorn;ou aspye</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ne to hemself may &thorn;ey not profyte</L>
<L N="511">ffor in here effecte &thorn;ey be not wor&thorn; a myte</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L N="512">&thorn;is and such o&thorn;er wordes seyde sche /</L>
<L>and he wax wro&thorn; and bad &thorn;ey schulde hire lede /</L>
<L>home to hire hous and in hire hous quod he</L>
<L N="515">Brenne hire in a fire wi&thorn; flammes reede</L>
<L>And as he bad right so was don in dede</L>
<L>And in a bathe &thorn;ey gan hire faste scheten</L>
<L N="518">And night and day gret fuyr vnder &thorn;ey beetyn</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L N="519">Al &thorn;e longe night and eek &thorn;e day also /</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;e fuyr and eek &thorn;e ba&thorn;es hete /</L>
<L>Sche satte al colde and felt of it/ no wo</L>
<L N="522">Ne made hire a drop nou&yogh;t for to swete /</L>
<L>But in &thorn;at ba&thorn;e hire lyf sche moste lete /</L>
<L>ffor he Almachie wi&thorn; ful wikked entent<MILESTONE N="177b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="525">To slen hure in &thorn;e bath his sonde sent
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="396"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="546"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<L N="526">&thorn;re strokes in &thorn;e necke he smot hire &thorn;o</L>
<L>The tormentour but for no maner chaunce</L>
<L>he might not smyten al hire necke a tuo</L>
<L N="529">And for &thorn;er was &thorn;at tyme an ordynaunce</L>
<L>That no man scholde do man such penance</L>
<L>&thorn;e fer&thorn;e strook to smyten softe or sore</L>
<L N="532">&thorn;is tormentour ne durste nomore</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L N="533">But half ded wi&thorn; hire necke koruen &thorn;ere /</L>
<L>he laft hir lye and in his wey he went</L>
<L>&thorn;e cristne folke whiche abouten hire were /</L>
<L N="536">Wi&thorn; scheetes home ful faire hire hent</L>
<L>&thorn;re dayes lyued sche in &thorn;is torment</L>
<L>And neuer cessed hem &thorn;e fei&thorn; to teche</L>
<L N="539">&thorn;at sche hadde fostred hem sche gan to preche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L N="540">And hem sche &yogh;aff hire moebles and hire &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pope vrban bitok hem &thorn;o /</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us I askede &thorn;is of heuen king</L>
<L N="543">To haue respyt &thorn;re dayes and no mo /</L>
<L>To recomande to &yogh;ou er &thorn;at I go</L>
<L>&thorn;ise soules lo and &thorn;at I mighte do wirche</L>
<L N="546">here of myn hous perpetuelliche a chirche</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L N="547">Seint vrban wi&thorn; his deaknes priuely</L>
<L>The body fette and buried it by nighte</L>
<L>Among his o&thorn;ere seintes honestely</L>
<L N="550">hire hous &thorn;e chirche of seint Cecile highte</L>
<L>Seynt vrban halwed it as he wel mighte</L>
<L>In &thorn;e which in to &thorn;is day in noble wyse /</L>
<L N="553">Men don to cryst and to his seintz seruise</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; Seint Ceciles Tale /</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="397">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="547">
<HEAD>&para; Hic incipit fabula Canonici<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 177, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan ended was &thorn;e lyf of seint Cecile</L>
<L>Er we fully hadde ryden fyue myle</L>
<L>At Boghton vnder &thorn;e blee. vs gan atake /</L>
<L N="557">A man &thorn;at clo&thorn;ed was in clo&thorn;es blake</L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;at he hadde a whit surplys</L>
<L>his hakeney &thorn;at was al pomel grys<MILESTONE N="178a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So swette &thorn;at it wonder was to see</L>
<L N="561">It semed he hadde priked myles &thorn;re</L>
<L>&thorn;e hors eek &thorn;at his &yogh;oman rood vpon</L>
<L>So swette &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e mighte he gon</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e peytrel stood &thorn;e foom ful hi&yogh;e</L>
<L N="565">he was of fome al flekked as a pye</L>
<L>A male twyfold on his croper lay</L>
<L>It semed &thorn;at he caryed lytel aray</L>
<L>Al light for somer rood &thorn;is wor&thorn;y man</L>
<L N="569">And in myn herte wondren I bygan</L>
<L>What &thorn;at he was til &thorn;at I vnderstood</L>
<L>how &thorn;at his cloke was sewed to his hood</L>
<L>ffor which whan I longe hadde avised me /</L>
<L N="573">I demed him som chanon for to be /</L>
<L>his hat hyng at his bak doun by a las /</L>
<L>ffor he hadde ryde more &thorn;an trot or pas /</L>
<L>he hadde ay priked lyk as he were wood</L>
<L N="577">A clote leef he hadde vnder his hood</L>
<L>ffor swot and for to kepe his heed from hete</L>
<L>But it/ was ioye for to seen him swete /</L>
<L>his forhed dropped as a stillatorie</L>
<L N="581">Were ful of plaunteyne and of peritorie
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="398"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="548"></L>
<L N="582">And whan &thorn;at he cam he bigan to crye</L>
<L>God saue quod he &thorn;is Ioly companye</L>
<L>ffaste haue I priked quod he for &yogh;oure sake</L>
<L N="585">By cause &thorn;at I wolde &yogh;ou ouertake /</L>
<L>To ryden in &thorn;is merye companye</L>
<L>His &yogh;oman eek was ful of curtesye</L>
<L>And sires now in &thorn;e morwe tyde /</L>
<L N="589">Out of &yogh;oure ostellerye I say&yogh; &yogh;ou ryde</L>
<L>And warned heer my lord and my souerayn</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at to ryde wi&thorn; &yogh;ou is ful fayn</L>
<L>ffor his disport he loue&thorn; daliaunce</L>
<L N="593">ffrend for &thorn;y warnyng god &yogh;iue &thorn;e good chaunce</L>
<L>Sayde oure oost certes it wolde seeme /</L>
<L>Thy lord were wys and so I may wel deme /<MILESTONE N="178b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he is ful iocunde also dar I lay</L>
<L N="597">Kan he ought telle a merye tale or tway</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; which he glade may &thorn;is companye</L>
<L>Who sire. my lord; &yogh;e &yogh;e wi&thorn;oute lye</L>
<L>he can of mer&thorn;e and eek of Iolite</L>
<L N="601">Nought but ynough also sire truste&thorn; to me</L>
<L>And &yogh;e him knewe als wel as do I</L>
<L>&yogh;e wolde wondre how wel and &thorn;riftyly</L>
<L>he cou&thorn;e werke and &thorn;at in sondry wyse</L>
<L N="605">he ha&thorn; take on him many sondry aprise</L>
<L>Which were ful hard for eny &thorn;at is heere /</L>
<L>To bringe aboute but &thorn;ey of him it lere /</L>
<L>As homely as he ryt amonges &yogh;ou</L>
<L N="609">If &yogh;e him knewe it wolde be &yogh;oure prow /</L>
<L>&yogh;e nolde not forgon his aqueintance</L>
<L>ffor mochil good I dar leye in balance</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I haue my possession</L>
<L N="613">he is a man of heigh discrecion</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;ou wel he is a passynge man</L>
<L>Wel quo&thorn; oure host I pray &thorn;e telle me &thorn;an</L>
<L>Is he a Clerk or noon telle what he is</L>
<L N="617">Nay he is gretter &thorn;an a clerk y-wys
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="399"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="549"></L>
<L N="618">Seyde &yogh;e &yogh;oman and in wordes fewe</L>
<L>Ost and of his craft somwhat I wol &yogh;ou schewe</L>
<L>I say my lord can such a sotilte</L>
<L N="621">But alle his crafte &yogh;e may not wite at me</L>
<L>And somwhat helpe I &yogh;it to his worchinge</L>
<L>That al &thorn;is ground which &thorn;at we ben on rydynge</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at we come to Caunturbury toun</L>
<L N="625">he cou&thorn;e al clene turne it/ vp se doun</L>
<L>And paue it al of siluer and of gold</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is &yogh;oman hadde &thorn;us y-told</L>
<L>vnto oure hoost // he seyde benedicite</L>
<L N="629">&thorn;is &thorn;ing is wonder merueylous to me</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;at &thorn;i lord is of so heigh prudence /</L>
<L>By cause of which men scholde him reuerence /<MILESTONE N="179a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That of his worschipe rekke&thorn; he so lyte</L>
<L N="633">his ouer sloppe / nys nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; a myte /</L>
<L>As in effecte to him so mote I go</L>
<L>It is al baudy and to-tore also</L>
<L>Whi is &thorn;i lord so sluttissche I &thorn;e prey</L>
<L N="637">And is of power better clo&thorn;es to bey</L>
<L>If &thorn;at his dede acorde wi&thorn; &thorn;y speche</L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;at and &thorn;at I &thorn;e byseche /</L>
<L>Why quod &thorn;is &yogh;eman wherto aske &yogh;e me /</L>
<L N="641">God help me so for he schal neuer y-the</L>
<L>But I wol not avowe &thorn;at I say</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore kepe it secre I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>he is to wys in fai&thorn; as I bileeue</L>
<L N="645">And &thorn;at is ouer doon it nyl not preue</L>
<L>And right as clerkes sein it is a vice /</L>
<L>Wherfore in &thorn;at I holde him lewed and nyce</L>
<L>ffor whan a ma[n] ha&thorn; ouer gret a witt</L>
<L N="649">fful often it happe&thorn; to mysvsen it</L>
<L>So do&thorn; my lord and &thorn;at me greue&thorn; sore</L>
<L>God it amende I can seye now no more</L>
<L>Ther-of no fors goode &yogh;oman quod oure hoost</L>
<L N="653">Si&thorn;ens of &thorn;e connyng of &thorn;y lord &thorn;ou woost
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="400"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="550"></L>
<L N="654">Telle how he do&thorn; I pray &thorn;e hertely</L>
<L>Si&thorn;ens &thorn;at he is so crafty and so sly</L>
<L>Wher dwellen &yogh;e if to telle be</L>
<L N="657">In Subarbes of a toun quod he</L>
<L>lurkyng in hernes and in lanes blynde</L>
<L>Where &thorn;ise Robbers and &thorn;eeues be kynde</L>
<L>holden here preuy ferful resydence</L>
<L N="661">As &thorn;ay &thorn;at dur nat schewe here presence</L>
<L>So fare we if I schal saye &thorn;e so&thorn;e</L>
<L>&yogh;it quod oure hoste lat me talke to&thorn;e</L>
<L>Why art &thorn;ou discoloured on &thorn;y face</L>
<L N="665">Peter quod he god &yogh;iue hit harde grace</L>
<L>I am so vsed in &thorn;e fyre to blowe</L>
<L>That it ha&thorn; chaunged my colour as I trowe<MILESTONE N="179b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I nam nat wont in myrour to prye</L>
<L N="669">But swynke sore and lerne to multiplye</L>
<L>We bloundren euer and pouren in &thorn;e fyr</L>
<L>And for al &thorn;at we faillen of oure desir</L>
<L>ffor euer we lacken oure conclusion</L>
<L N="673">To moche folk we ben but Illusion</L>
<L>And borwe gold be it a pound or tuo</L>
<L>Or ten or twelue or manye sommes mo</L>
<L>And make hem wenen atte leste weye</L>
<L N="677">&thorn;at of a pound we cou&thorn;e make tweye</L>
<L>&yogh;it is it fals and ay we han good hope</L>
<L>It for to don and after it we grope</L>
<L>But &thorn;at science is so fer vs biforn</L>
<L N="681">We mowe not al &thorn;ough we hadde it sworn</L>
<L>It ouertake it<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>a second</I> it <I>scratcht out</I>]</NOTE> slyt awey so faste</L>
<L>It wole us make beggeres atte laste</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;is &yogh;oman was &thorn;us in &thorn;is talking</L>
<L N="685">&thorn;is chanon drough him ner and herde alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;oman spak for suspecion</L>
<L>Of mennes speche euere hadde &thorn;is Chanon</L>
<L>ffor Caton seith he &thorn;at gulty is</L>
<L N="689">Deme&thorn; alle &thorn;ing be spoke of him ywys
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="401"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="551"></L>
<L N="690">By cause of &thorn;at he gan so neigh to drawe /</L>
<L>his &yogh;oman. &thorn;at he herde alle his sawe /</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sayde vnto his &yogh;oman &thorn;o</L>
<L N="693">holde now &thorn;y pees and speke wordes no mo /</L>
<L>ffor if &thorn;ou dost &thorn;ou schalt it dere abye</L>
<L>Thou sclaundrest me here in &thorn;is compaignye</L>
<L>And eek discouerest &thorn;at &thorn;ou scholdest hyde</L>
<L N="697">&yogh;ee quod oure hoost telle on what so betyde</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;is &thorn;retyng recche I nat a myte</L>
<L>I fai&thorn; quod he no more do I but a lite</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is Chanon say it wolde nat be</L>
<L N="701">But his &yogh;oman wolde telle his priuyte</L>
<L>he fledde away for verray sorwe and schame /</L>
<L>A quod &thorn;e &yogh;oman here schal aryse a game<MILESTONE N="180a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I can anon right/ wol I telle</L>
<L N="705">Si&thorn;ens he is gon &thorn;e foule feend him quelle /</L>
<L>ffor neuer her after wol I wi&thorn; him mete</L>
<L>ffor peny ne for pound I &yogh;ou biheete /</L>
<L>he &thorn;at me broughte ferst vnto &thorn;at game /</L>
<L N="709">Er &thorn;at he deye sorwe haue he and schame</L>
<L>ffor it is ernest to me by my fay&thorn;</L>
<L>That feele I wel what so eny man sai&thorn; /</L>
<L>And &yogh;it for al my smert and al my greef</L>
<L N="713">ffor al my sorwe labour and mescheef</L>
<L>I cou&thorn;e neuer leue it in no wyse</L>
<L>Now wolde god my witt/ mighte suffise</L>
<L>To tellen al &thorn;at longe&thorn; to &thorn;at art</L>
<L N="717">But na&thorn;eles &yogh;it wol I telle a part</L>
<L>Sy&thorn;ens &thorn;at my lord is gon I wol not spare</L>
<L>Such &thorn;ing as I knowe I wol declare /<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000430.tif" N="402">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="552">
<HEAD>[THE PREAMBLE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With &thorn;is chanon dwelled haue I seuen &yogh;eer</L>
<L N="721">And of his science am I neuer &thorn;e neer</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at I hadde I haue y-lost &thorn;erby</L>
<L>And god wot so haue many mo &thorn;an I</L>
<L>&thorn;er I was wont to be right freissch and gay</L>
<L N="725">Of clo&thorn;ing and of good array</L>
<L>Now may I were an hose vpon myn heed</L>
<L>And wher my colour was bo&thorn;e freissh and reed</L>
<L>Now is it wan and of a ledene hewe</L>
<L N="729">Who so it vseth sore schal he rewe</L>
<L>And of my swynk &yogh;it blered is myn y&yogh;e</L>
<L>lo which auauntage it is to multiplye</L>
<L>That slydynge science ha&thorn; me maad so bare</L>
<L N="733">That I haue no good where &thorn;at euer I fare</L>
<L>And &yogh;it I am endetted so &thorn;er by</L>
<L>Of gold &thorn;at/ I haue borwed trewely</L>
<L>&thorn;at whil I lyue I schal it quite neuere /</L>
<L N="737">lat euery man be war by me for euere</L>
<L>What maner man &thorn;at caste&thorn; him &thorn;erto</L>
<L>If he continue I holde his &thorn;rifte y-do<MILESTONE N="180b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So help me god &thorn;er-by schal he not wynne</L>
<L N="741">But empte his purs and make his wittes &thorn;inne</L>
<L>And whan he &thorn;orugh his madnesse and folye</L>
<L>ha&thorn; lost his owne good &thorn;orugh Iepardye</L>
<L>&thorn;anne he excite&thorn; o&thorn;er men &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="745">To lese here good as himself ha&thorn; do</L>
<L>ffor vnto schrewes Ioye it is and ese</L>
<L>To haue here felawes in peyne and disese
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="403"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="553"></L>
<L>Thus was I ones lerned of a clerk</L>
<L N="749">Of &thorn;at no charge I wol speke of oure werk</L>
<L>Whan we ben &thorn;ere as we schulle exercise</L>
<L>Oure eluysshe craft; we semen wonder wise</L>
<L>Oure termes ben so clergeal and so queynte</L>
<L N="753">I blowe &thorn;e fuyr. til &thorn;at myn herte feynte</L>
<L>What scholde I telle eche proporcion</L>
<L>Of &thorn;inges whiche &thorn;at we worchen vppon</L>
<L>As on fyue or sixe vnces may wel be</L>
<L N="757">Of siluer or of som o&thorn;er quantite</L>
<L>And besye me to telle &yogh;ou &thorn;e names</L>
<L>Of Opyment brent bones yren squames</L>
<L>That in to poudre grounden ben ful smal</L>
<L N="761">And in an er&thorn;en pot how &thorn;at put is al</L>
<L>And salt y-put in and also paupere</L>
<L>Bifore &thorn;ise poudres &thorn;at I speke of here</L>
<L>And wel y-couered wi&thorn; a laumpe of glas</L>
<L N="765">And of muche o&thorn;er &thorn;ing what &thorn;at &thorn;er was</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e pot and glas englutyng</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e aier mighte passe no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e esy fyr and smert also</L>
<L N="769">Which &thorn;at was mad and of &thorn;e care and wo</L>
<L>&thorn;at we hadde in oure matiers sublymynge</L>
<L>And amalgamynge and Calcenynge</L>
<L>Of quyk syluer y-cleped mercurie crude</L>
<L N="773">ffor alle oure sleightes we can nou&yogh;t conclude</L>
<L>Oure orpymed and sublimed mercurie</L>
<L>Oure grounde litarge eek on &thorn;e porphirie<MILESTONE N="181a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of ech of &thorn;ise of vnces a certayn</L>
<L N="777">Nou&yogh;t helpe&thorn; vs oure labour is in vain</L>
<L>Ne eek oure spirites ascencioun</L>
<L>Ne eek oure matieres &thorn;at lyn al fixe a doun</L>
<L>Mowen in oure werkynge no &thorn;ing vs auayle</L>
<L N="781">ffor lost is alle oure labour and trauaile</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e cost on twenty deuele wey</L>
<L>Is lost also which we vpon it ley
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="404"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="554"></L>
<L>&thorn;er is also many ano&thorn;er &thorn;ing/</L>
<L N="785">&thorn;at is to oure crafte aperteynyng</L>
<L>&thorn;ough I by ordre hem here ne reherse can</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at I am a lewed man</L>
<L>&yogh;it wol I telle hem as &thorn;ey come to mynde</L>
<L N="189">Though I ne kan nat sette hem in here kynde</L>
<L>As boole armonyak verdegres Boras</L>
<L>And sondry vesseles made of er&thorn;e and glas</L>
<L>Oure vrinales and oure descensories</L>
<L N="793">Violes creseletes and sublimatories</L>
<L>Concurbites and Alembykes eeke</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er swiche deere ynough a leeke</L>
<L>Nat neede&thorn; it/ to rehersen hem alle</L>
<L N="797">Wateres Rubysynge and boles galle</L>
<L>Arsynek Sal armonyak and Brymston</L>
<L>And herbes cou&thorn;e I telle eek many oon</L>
<L>As Egrymoyne Valerian and lunarie</L>
<L N="801">And o&thorn;er suche if &thorn;at me luste tarie</L>
<L>Oure laumpes brennyng bo&thorn;e night and day</L>
<L>To bringe aboute oure craft if &thorn;at we may</L>
<L>Oure fornays eke of Calcynacion</L>
<L N="805">And of watres albyficacion</L>
<L>vnslekked lym chalk and glaire of an ey</L>
<L>Poudres dyuers aisshes dong pisse and cley</L>
<L>Seryd pokettes Sal petre and vitriole</L>
<L N="809">And diuerse fyres made of woode and cole</L>
<L>Salt tartre Alcaly and Salt preparat</L>
<L>And combust matieres and coagulat<MILESTONE N="181b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Cley maad wi&thorn; horses or mannes heer and oyle</L>
<L N="813">Of tartre alym glas berme wort and argoyle</L>
<L>Rysalgar and o&thorn;er matieres enbykynge</L>
<L>And eek of oure matieres encorporynge</L>
<L>And eek of Siluer Citrynacion</L>
<L N="817">Oure sementynge and fermentacion</L>
<L>Oure Ingotes testes and many mo</L>
<L>I wol &yogh;ou telle as was me taught also /
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="405"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="555"></L>
<L>&thorn;e foure spirites and &thorn;e bodyes seuene /</L>
<L N="821">By ordre ofte as I herde my lord neuene</L>
<L>The fyfte spirit quyk siluer called is</L>
<L>&thorn;e seconde orpiment. &thorn;e &thorn;ridde y-wys</L>
<L>Sal armoniak and &thorn;e fer&thorn;e bremston</L>
<L N="825">The bodyes seuene eek lo hem heere anon</L>
<L>Sol gold is and luna siluer we threpe /</L>
<L>Mars yren mercurie quyk syluer we clepe</L>
<L>Saturnus leed and Iubiter is tyn</L>
<L N="829">And venus Copur by my fader kyn</L>
<L>This cursede craft who so wol exercise</L>
<L>he schal no good han &thorn;at may him suffise</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;e good he spende&thorn; &thorn;er aboute</L>
<L N="833">he lese schal &thorn;er-of haue I no doute</L>
<L>Who so &thorn;at list to outen his folye</L>
<L>let him come for&thorn; and lerne to multiplie</L>
<L>And euery man &thorn;at ha&thorn; aught in his cofre</L>
<L N="837">lat him appere and wexe a philosophre</L>
<L>As-scaunce &thorn;at craft is so light for to lere</L>
<L>Nay nay god woot al be he monk or frere /</L>
<L>Preste or Chanon or eny o&thorn;er wight</L>
<L N="841">&thorn;ough he sitte at his book bo&thorn;e day and night</L>
<L>In lernyng of &thorn;is eluyssh nyce lore /</L>
<L>Al is in veyn and par de moche more</L>
<L>Is to lerne a lewed man &thorn;is sotilte</L>
<L N="845">ffy speke nou&yogh;t &thorn;erof for it/ wol not be</L>
<L>Al cowde he letterure or cou&thorn;e he non</L>
<L>As in effecte he schal fynde it al on<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor bo&thorn;e tuo by my saluacion</L>
<L N="849">Concluden in multiplicacion</L>
<L>I-liche wel whan &thorn;ey han alle y-do</L>
<L>This is to seyn &thorn;ey faille bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>&yogh;it for&yogh;at I to moche rehersaille</L>
<L N="853">Of watres corosif and of lymaille</L>
<L>And of bodyes mollificacion</L>
<L>And also of here induracion
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="406"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="556"></L>
<L>Oyles ablucion and metalle fusible</L>
<L N="857">To tellen alle wolde passen ony bible</L>
<L>&thorn;at owher is wherfore as for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ise names now wole I me reste</L>
<L>ffor as I trowe I haue &yogh;ou told ynough</L>
<L N="861">To reysen a feende loke he neuer so rough</L>
<L>A nay let be &thorn;y philosophres ston</L>
<L>Elixir cleped we sechen faste echoon</L>
<L>ffor hadde we him &thorn;an were we syker ynough</L>
<L N="865">But vnto god of heuene I make avow</L>
<L>ffor alle oure craft whan we han al y-do</L>
<L>And al oure sleighte / he wol not come vs to</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; vs maad spende moche good</L>
<L N="869">ffor sorwe of which almost we wexen wood</L>
<L>But &thorn;at good hope crepe&thorn; in oure herte</L>
<L>Supposyng euere &thorn;ough we sore smerte</L>
<L>To be releuyd by him aftirward</L>
<L N="873">Supposyng and hope is scharp and hard</L>
<L>I warne &yogh;ou wel it is to seken euere</L>
<L>&thorn;at future temps ha&thorn; maad men disseuere</L>
<L>In trust &thorn;er-of fram al &thorn;at euer &thorn;ey hadde</L>
<L N="877">&yogh;it of &thorn;at art &thorn;ey cou&thorn;e not wexe sadde</L>
<L>ffor vnto hem it is a bitterswete</L>
<L>So seme&thorn; it for ne hadde &thorn;ey but a scheete</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;ey mighte wrappe hem In a night</L>
<L N="881">And a bak to walken in by day light</L>
<L>&thorn;ey wolde hem sellen and spenden on &thorn;is craft</L>
<L>They can nou&yogh;t stynte til no &thorn;ing be laft<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And euermore wher &thorn;at euer &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L N="885">men may hem knowe by smel of Bremston</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e world &thorn;ey stynken as a goot</L>
<L>here sauour is so Rammissh and so hoot</L>
<L>That &thorn;ough a man from hem a myle be</L>
<L N="889">That sauour wol enfecte him truste&thorn; me</L>
<L>lo &thorn;us by smellyng and by &thorn;red bare array</L>
<L>If &thorn;at men list &thorn;is folk &thorn;ey knowe may
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="407"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="557"></L>
<L>And if a man wol aske him priuely</L>
<L N="893">Why &thorn;ey ben clo&thorn;ed so vn&thorn;riftily</L>
<L>Right anon &thorn;ey wole rownen in his eere</L>
<L>And seye if &thorn;ay aspyed were</L>
<L>Men wolde hem sle by cause of here science</L>
<L N="897">lo &thorn;us &thorn;is folk bytrayen Innocence</L>
<L>Passe ouer &thorn;is I go my tale vnto</L>
<L>Er &thorn;en &thorn;e pot be on &thorn;e fyr y-do</L>
<L>Of metals wi&thorn; a certein quantite</L>
<L N="901">My lord hem tempre&thorn; and no man but he</L>
<L>Now he is gon. I dar say boldely</L>
<L>ffor as men sein he can do craftily</L>
<L>Algate I wot wel he ha&thorn; such a name</L>
<L N="905">And &yogh;it ful ofte he renne&thorn; in &thorn;e blame</L>
<L>And wite &yogh;e how ful ofte it happe&thorn; so</L>
<L>The pot tobreke&thorn; and far wel alle is go</L>
<L>&thorn;ise metals ben of so gret violence /</L>
<L N="909">Oure walles may not make hem resistence</L>
<L>But if &thorn;ey were wrou&yogh;t of lym and ston</L>
<L>&thorn;ey percen so and &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e wal &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L>And some of hem synken in to &thorn;e ground</L>
<L N="913">&thorn;us haue we lost by tymes many a pound</L>
<L>And somme are scatered al &thorn;e floor aboute</L>
<L>Somme lepen in to &thorn;e roof wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at &thorn;e fende nought in oure sighte him schewe</L>
<L N="917">I trowe &thorn;at he wi&thorn; vs be &thorn;at schrewe</L>
<L>In helle wher &thorn;at he is lord and sire /</L>
<L>Ne is &thorn;er no more woo ne angur nor Ire<MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at oure pot is broke as I haue sayd</L>
<L N="921">Euery man chit and halt him yuel payd</L>
<L>Som seyde it was long on &thorn;e fyr makyng</L>
<L>Somme sayde nay it was on &thorn;e blowyng</L>
<L>&thorn;an was I fered for &thorn;at was myn office</L>
<L N="925">Straw quod &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &yogh;e ben lewed and nyce</L>
<L>It was not tempred as it oughte be /</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e fer&thorn;e stynt and herkne me
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="408"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="558"></L>
<L>By cause oure fyr was nat made of bech</L>
<L N="929">&thorn;at is &thorn;e cause non o&thorn;er so peech</L>
<L>I can not telle wher-on it is a long</L>
<L>But wel I wot gret stryf is vs among</L>
<L>What quod my lord &thorn;er is nomore to done /</L>
<L N="933">Of &thorn;ise periles I wil be war eft sone /</L>
<L>I am right syker &thorn;at &thorn;e pot was crased</L>
<L>Be as be may be &yogh;e no &thorn;ing amased</L>
<L>As vsage is let swope &thorn;e floor as swy&thorn;e</L>
<L N="937">Pluk vp &yogh;our herte and be &yogh;e glad and bli&thorn;e</L>
<L>The mullok on an heep y-swoped was</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e floor cast a kaneuas</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is mullok in a Syue y-&thorn;rowe</L>
<L N="941">And y-sifted and y-plucked many a &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>Parde quod oon som what of oure metal</L>
<L>&yogh;et is &thorn;er heere &thorn;ough we haue not all</L>
<L>And &thorn;ough &thorn;is &thorn;ing myshapped ha&thorn; as now</L>
<L N="945">Ano&thorn;er tyme it may be wel ynow</L>
<L>vs moste putte oure good in aduenture /</L>
<L>A marchant parde may not ay endure /</L>
<L>Trustne&thorn; me wel in his prosperite</L>
<L N="949">Som tyme his good is drowned in &thorn;e see /</L>
<L>And som tyme come&thorn; it sauf vnto &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>Pees quod my lord &thorn;e nexte tyme I wol fonde</L>
<L>To bringe oure crafte alle in ano&thorn;er plyt</L>
<L N="953">And but I do sires lat me haue &thorn;e wyte</L>
<L>Ther was defaute in somwhat wel I woot</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er seyde &thorn;e fyr was ouer hoot<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But be it hoot or cold I dar seye &thorn;is</L>
<L N="957">&thorn;at we concluden eueremore amys /</L>
<L>We faille of &thorn;at which &thorn;at we wolde haue /</L>
<L>And in oure madnesse eueremore we raue</L>
<L>And whan we ben togidere euerich on</L>
<L N="961">Euery man seme&thorn; as wys as Salomon</L>
<L>But alle &thorn;ing which &thorn;at seme&thorn; as &thorn;e goolde /</L>
<L>Is nat golde as I haue herd it tolde /
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="409"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="559"></L>
<L>Ne euery appul &thorn;at is fair at ye</L>
<L N="965">Ne is not good what so men clappe or crye /</L>
<L>Right so lo fare&thorn; it amonges vs</L>
<L>he &thorn;at seme&thorn; &thorn;e wysest by Ihesus</L>
<L>Is most fool whan it come&thorn; to &thorn;e preef</L>
<L N="969">And he &thorn;at seme&thorn; trewest is a &thorn;eef</L>
<L>That schul &yogh;e knowe er &thorn;at I fro &yogh;ou wende /</L>
<L>By &thorn;at I of my tale haue maad an ende<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000438.tif" N="410">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="560">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther is a chanoun of Religioun</L>
<L N="973">Amonges vs wolde enfecte al a toun</L>
<L>&thorn;ough it as gret were as was Nynyue /</L>
<L>Rome Alisandre . Troye and o&thorn;re &thorn;re</L>
<L>his sleightes and his infinite falsnesse /</L>
<L N="977">&thorn;er cou&thorn;e noman writen as I gesse /</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at he mighte lyuen a &thorn;ousend &yogh;eer</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;is world of fal[s]nesse nys his peer</L>
<L>ffor in his termes he wole him so wynde</L>
<L N="981">And speke his wordes in so sleigh a kynde</L>
<L>Whan he commune schal wi&thorn; ony wight</L>
<L>What he wol make him dote anon right</L>
<L>But it &thorn;e feend be as his seluen is /</L>
<L N="985">fful many a man ha&thorn; he begyled er &thorn;is</L>
<L>And wile if &thorn;at he may lyue a while /</L>
<L>And &yogh;it men ryden and gon ful many a myle</L>
<L>him for to seeke and haue his aqueyntance</L>
<L N="989">Nou&yogh;t knowyng of his false gouernance /</L>
<L>And if ye lust to &yogh;iue me audience</L>
<L>I wol it tellen here in &yogh;oure presence<MILESTONE N="184a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But worschipful Chanon religious</L>
<L N="993">Ne deme&thorn; nou&yogh;t &thorn;at I sclaundre &yogh;our hous</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ough my tale of a Chanon be</L>
<L>Of euery ordre som schrewe is parde</L>
<L>And god forbede &thorn;at alle a compaignie</L>
<L N="997">Scholde rewe a synguler mannes folye</L>
<L>To sclaundre &yogh;ou it is not myn entent</L>
<L>But to correcten &thorn;at mys I-ment
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="411"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="561"></L>
<L>This tale nas nat oonly told for &yogh;ou</L>
<L N="1001">But eek for o&thorn;er mo &yogh;e wot wel how</L>
<L>That amonges cristes apostles twelue</L>
<L>Ther was no traytour but Iudas himselue</L>
<L>&thorn;anne why scholde &thorn;e remenant alle haue blame</L>
<L N="1005">That gulteles were by &yogh;ou sey I &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Sauf oonly &thorn;is if &yogh;e wiln herkne me</L>
<L>If ony Iudas in &yogh;oure couent be</L>
<L>Remeue&thorn; him by tyme I &yogh;ou rede</L>
<L N="1009">If schame or losse may causen ony drede</L>
<L>And be&thorn; no &thorn;ing displesed I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L>But in &thorn;is caas herkneth what I say</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN london was a prest an annueler</L>
<L N="1013">That &thorn;er-Inne dwelled hadde many a &yogh;eer</L>
<L>Which was so plesant / and so seruisable /</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e wyf wher he was at &thorn;e table</L>
<L>That sche wolde suffre him no &thorn;ing for to pay</L>
<L N="1017">ffor bord nor clo&thorn;ing wente he non so gay</L>
<L>And spendyng siluer had he right ynough</L>
<L>&thorn;er-of no force I wol procede as now /</L>
<L>And telle for&thorn; my tale of &thorn;e Chanon</L>
<L N="1021">&thorn;at brou&yogh;te &thorn;is prest to confusion</L>
<L>This false Chanon cam vpon a day</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e prestes chambre &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L>Byseching him to lene him a certeyn</L>
<L N="1025">Of golde and he wold quite it him ageyn</L>
<L>lene&thorn; me a mark quod he but dayes &thorn;re</L>
<L>And at my day I wol it quite &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou fynde me fals</L>
<L N="1029">Ano&thorn;er day hang me vp by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>This prest him tok a mark and &thorn;at as swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Chanoun him &thorn;anked often si&thorn;e</L>
<L>And took his leue and wente forth his wey</L>
<L N="1033">And atte &thorn;ridde day brou&yogh;t his money</L>
<L>And to &thorn;is prest he took &thorn;is gold a&yogh;ein</L>
<L>Ther-of &thorn;is prest was glad and fayn
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="412"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="562"></L>
<L>Certes quod he no &thorn;ing anoyeth me</L>
<L N="1037">To lene a man a noble or tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>Or what &thorn;ing were in my possession</L>
<L>Whan he so trewe is of condicion</L>
<L>&thorn;at in no wise he breke wole his day</L>
<L N="1041">To swich a man I can neuer say nay</L>
<L>What quod &thorn;is Chanon scholde I be vntrewe</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;at were &thorn;ing fallen al of &thorn;e newe</L>
<L>Trou&thorn;e is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at I wol euer kepe /</L>
<L N="1045">Vnto &thorn;e day in which &thorn;at I schal crepe</L>
<L>in to my graue and elles god forbede</L>
<L>Bileeue&thorn; &thorn;is as siker as is &yogh;oure Crede</L>
<L>God &thorn;anke I and in good tyme be it sayd</L>
<L N="1049">&thorn;at &thorn;er was neuer man &yogh;it euel payd</L>
<L>ffor gold ne siluer &thorn;at he to me lente</L>
<L>Ne neuere falshede in myn herte I mente</L>
<L>And sire quod he now of my priuyte</L>
<L N="1053">Si&thorn;ens &yogh;e so goodlich haue ben to me</L>
<L>And ki&thorn;ed to me so gret gentilnesse</L>
<L>Somwhat to quite with &yogh;oure kyndenesse</L>
<L>I wol &yogh;ou schewe and if &yogh;ou lest to leere /</L>
<L N="1057">I schal it schewe to &yogh;ou anon right heere</L>
<L>how I kan worchen in philosophie</L>
<L>Take&thorn; good heed &yogh;e schuln seen wel at ye</L>
<L>That I wol don a maystry ar I go</L>
<L N="1061">&yogh;e quo&thorn; &thorn;e prest / &yogh;e sire and wil &yogh;e so</L>
<L>Marie &thorn;er of I pray &yogh;ou hertily</L>
<L>At &yogh;oure comaundement sire trewely<MILESTONE N="185a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Quo&thorn; &thorn;e Chanon and elles god forbede</L>
<L N="1065">lo how &thorn;is &thorn;eef cou&thorn;e his seruise beede</L>
<L>fful so&thorn; it is &thorn;at such profred seruise</L>
<L>Stynke&thorn; as witnessen &thorn;ise olde wise</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ful sone I wol it verefye</L>
<L N="1069">In &thorn;is Chanon is roote of alle treccherie</L>
<L>&thorn;at eueremore delyt ha&thorn; and gladnesse/</L>
<L>Suche feendly &thorn;oughtes in his herte impresse /
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="413"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="563"></L>
<L>how cristes poeple he may to meschief bringe</L>
<L N="1073">God kepe vs from his fals dissimilynge</L>
<L>What wiste &thorn;is prest wi&thorn; whom &thorn;at he delte</L>
<L>Ne of his harm comynge no &thorn;ing he felte</L>
<L>O sely prest o sely Innocent</L>
<L N="1077">Wi&thorn; coueytise anon &thorn;ou schalt be blent</L>
<L>O graceles ful blynd is &thorn;y conceyt</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing artow war of &thorn;e deceyt</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;is fox y-schapen ha&thorn; to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1081">his wyly wrenches &thorn;ou mayst nou&yogh;t fle</L>
<L>Wher-fore to go to &thorn;e conclusion</L>
<L>&thorn;at referre&thorn; to &thorn;i confusion</L>
<L>vnhappy man anon I wol me hi&yogh;e</L>
<L N="1085">To telle &thorn;in vnwitte and &thorn;y folye</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;e falsnesse of &thorn;at o&thorn;er wrecche</L>
<L>As ferfor&thorn; as my connynge wol strecche</L>
<L>This Chanon was my lord &yogh;e wolde weene</L>
<L N="1089">Sire oste in faith and by &thorn;e heuen quene</L>
<L>It was ano&thorn;er chanoun and nat he</L>
<L>That can an hundred fold more sotyltee</L>
<L>he ha&thorn; bytrayed folkes many tyme</L>
<L N="1093">Of his falsnesse it/ dulle&thorn; me to Ryme</L>
<L>Euer whan I speke of his falshede</L>
<L>ffor schame of him my chekes wexen reede</L>
<L>Algates &thorn;ey bygynne for to glowe</L>
<L N="1097">ffor reednesse haue I now right wel I knowe</L>
<L>In my visage for fumes diuerse</L>
<L>Of metals whiche &yogh;e haue herd me reherce<MILESTONE N="185b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Consumed and wasted han my reednesse /</L>
<L N="1101">Now take heede of &thorn;is Chanons cursednesse</L>
<L>Sire quod he to &thorn;e prest lat &yogh;oure man gon</L>
<L>ffor quyk siluer &thorn;at we it hadde anon</L>
<L>And lat him bringe vnces tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L N="1105">And whan he come&thorn; as faste schul &yogh;e see</L>
