<L>Of hem &thorn;at han &thorn;erto here good y-lent</L>
<L>O fy for schame &thorn;ey &thorn;at haue be brent</L>
<L>Allas can &thorn;ey nat fle &thorn;e fyres hete</L>
<L N="1409">&yogh;e &thorn;at it vsen I rede &yogh;e it lete</L>
<L>lest &yogh;e lese al for bet &thorn;an neuer is late</L>
<L>Neuer to &thorn;riue were to longe a date</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &yogh;e prolle ay &yogh;e schulle it neuer fynde</L>
<L N="1413">&yogh;e ben as bolde as is bayard &thorn;e blynde</L>
<L>&thorn;at blundreth for&thorn; and peril caste&thorn; he non</L>
<L>he is as bold to renne a-gayn a stoon</L>
<L>As for to go bysydes in &thorn;e weye</L>
<L N="1417">So fare &yogh;e &thorn;at multiplie I seye</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;oure y&yogh;en may not seen aright</L>
<L>loke&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;oure mynd lakke nought his sight</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough &yogh;e loke neuer so brode and stare /</L>
<L N="1421">&yogh;e schulle nat wynne a myte in &thorn;at chaffare</L>
<L>But wasten al &thorn;at &yogh;e may Rappe and renne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;e fir lest it so faste brenne<MILESTONE N="190a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Medle&thorn; nomore wi&thorn; &thorn;at art I mene</L>
<L N="1425">ffor if &yogh;e doon &yogh;our &thorn;rift is gon ful clene /</L>
<L>And right as swithe I wol &yogh;ou telle heere</L>
<L>What &thorn;at &thorn;e philosophres sein in &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>lo &thorn;us sei&thorn; arnold of &thorn;e newe toun</L>
<L N="1429">As his Rosarie make&thorn; mencioun</L>
<L>he sei&thorn; right &thorn;us wi&thorn;outen eny lye</L>
<L>&thorn;er may no man mercurie mortifie
<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="423"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="573"></L>
<L>But if it be wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;eres knowleching</L>
<L N="1433">how &thorn;at he which &thorn;at first seyde &thorn;is &thorn;ing/</L>
<L>Of Philosophres fader was hermes /</L>
<L>he sai&thorn; how &thorn;at &thorn;e dragon douteles</L>
<L>Ne dye&thorn; not but if he be slayn</L>
<L N="1437">Wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;er and &thorn;at is for to sayn</L>
<L>By &thorn;e dragon mercurie and non o&thorn;er</L>
<L>he vnderstood &thorn;at bremston were his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>&thorn;at on of Sol and luna were y-drawe</L>
<L N="1441">And &thorn;erfore sayde he tak heed to my sawe</L>
<L>lat no man busye him &thorn;is art for to seche</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at &thorn;e entencion and &thorn;e speche</L>
<L>Of philosophres vnderstonde can</L>
<L N="1445">And if he do he is a lewed man</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is science and &thorn;is connyng quod he /</L>
<L>Is of &thorn;e secre of Secrees parde</L>
<L>Also &thorn;er was a disciple of Plato</L>
<L N="1449">That on a tyme sayde his mayster to</L>
<L>As his book Somer wil bere witnesse</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was his demaunde in so&thorn;fastnesse</L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;e name of &thorn;e pryuy stoon</L>
<L N="1453">And plato answerde vnto him anon</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;e stoon &thorn;at titanos men name</L>
<L>Which is &thorn;at quod he magnasia &thorn;e same /</L>
<L>Seyde Plato &yogh;ee Sire and is it &thorn;us</L>
<L N="1457">This is ignotum per ignocius</L>
<L>What is magnasia goode sire I pray</L>
<L>It is a water &thorn;at is maad I say<MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of elementes foure quod Plato</L>
<L N="1461">Tel me &thorn;e roche goode sire quod he &thorn;o</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at water if it be &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>Nay nay quod Plato certeyn &thorn;at I nylle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Philosophres were sworn echon</L>
<L N="1465">&thorn;at &thorn;ey scholde discouere it to no mon</L>
<L>Ne in no book it write in no manere</L>
<L>ffor vnto crist it is so leef and deere
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="424"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="574"></L>
<L>&thorn;at he wil nat &thorn;at it discouered be</L>
<L N="1469">But where it like&thorn; to his deite</L>
<L>Man to enspire and eek for to defende</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at him like&thorn; lo &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende /</L>
<L>Thanne conclude I &thorn;us si&thorn;ens &thorn;at god of heuene</L>
<L N="1473">Ne wole nat &thorn;at &thorn;e Philosophres neuene</L>
<L>how &thorn;at a man schal come vnto &thorn;is stoon</L>
<L>I rede as for &thorn;e beste lat it goon</L>
<L>ffor who so maketh god his aduersarie</L>
<L N="1477">As for to worche eny &thorn;ing in contrarie /</L>
<L>vnto his wille certes neuer schal he &thorn;riue</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at he multiplie terme of his lyue</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere a poynt for ended is my tale</L>
<L N="1481">God sende euery trewe man boote of his bale amen
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="C" TYPE="group"><PB REF="00000453.tif" N="425"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="303">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>C.</B> FRAGMENT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. THE DOCTOR'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>CORPUS MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; The doctour of phisik<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 190, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THer was as telle&thorn; vs Titus lyueus</L>
<L>A knight &thorn;at cleped was virgineus</L>
<L>ffulfilled of honoures and wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L N="4">And strong of frendes and of gret richesse</L>
<L>A doughter he hadde by his wyf</L>
<L>And neuere hadde he mo in alle his lyf</L>
<L>ffair was &thorn;is mayde in excellent beaute</L>
<L N="8">Abouen euery wight &thorn;at man may se</L>
<L>ffor nature ha&thorn; with souerein diligence</L>
<L>fformed hire in so gret excellence</L>
<L>As &thorn;ough sche wolde say lo I nature</L>
<L N="12">Thus can I forme and peinte a creature</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at me list who can me countrefete<MILESTONE N="191a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Pigmalion nou&yogh;t &thorn;ough he alwey forge and bete</L>
<L>Or graue or peynte for I dar wel sayn</L>
<L N="16">Apollus &yogh;ephirus schulde worche in vayn</L>
<L>To graue or paynte or forge or bete</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;ey presumede me for to countirfete</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;at is &thorn;e formour principal</L>
<L N="20">ha&thorn; maad me his viker general</L>
<L>To forme and peynte ech er&thorn;ely creature</L>
<L>Right as me lyst for al &thorn;ing is in my cure</L>
<L>vnder &thorn;e moone &thorn;at may wane and waxe</L>
<L N="24">And for my werke no &thorn;ing wol I axe
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="426"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="304"></L>
<L>My lord and I ben fully at acord</L>
<L>I made hire to &thorn;e worschip of my lord</L>
<L>So do I alle myn o&thorn;re creatures</L>
<L N="28">Of what colour &thorn;ey be or what figures</L>
<L>Thus seme&thorn; me &thorn;at nature wolde say</L>
<L>This mayde was of age .xij. &yogh;eer and tway</L>
<L>In which &thorn;at nature ha&thorn; such delyt</L>
<L N="32">ffor right as sche can paynte as lily whit</L>
<L>And rody as rose right wi&thorn; such peynture</L>
<L>Sche peynted ha&thorn; &thorn;is noble creature /</L>
<L>Er sche was born vppon hire lymes fre</L>
<L N="36">Were also bright as such colours scholde be /</L>
<L>And Phebus dyed ha&thorn; his tresses grete</L>
<L>like to &thorn;e stremes of his boornyd hete</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at excellent was hire beaute</L>
<L N="40">A &thorn;ousend fold more vertuous was sche</L>
<L>In hire ne lakke&thorn; no condicion</L>
<L>&thorn;at is to preise as by discrecion</L>
<L>As wel in body as gost chaste was sche</L>
<L N="44">ffor which sche floured in virginite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle humilite and abstinence</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; alle attemperance and pacience</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mesure eek and beryng of array</L>
<L N="48">Discret sche was in answering alway</L>
<L>&thorn;ough sche were wys as Pallas dar I seyn<MILESTONE N="191b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hire faucond eek ful wommanly and pleyn</L>
<L>None counterfeted termes hadde sche</L>
<L N="52">To seme wys but after hire degre</L>
<L>Sche spak and alle hire wordes more and lesse</L>
<L>Sownyng in vertue and in gentillesse</L>
<L>Schamefast sche was in maydens schamefastnesse</L>
<L N="56">Constant in herte and euere in busynesse</L>
<L>To dryue hire oute of hire slogardye</L>
<L>Bachus hadde of hir mou&thorn; no maystrie</L>
<L>ffor will and &thorn;ought doon venus encrece</L>
<L N="60">As men in fyr wol casten oyle or grece /
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="427"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="305"></L>
<L>And of hire owne vertue constreyned</L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn; ful ofte tyme hire seek feyned</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at sche wolde flee &thorn;e companye /</L>
<L N="64">Wher likly was to treten of folye</L>
<L>As is at festes . Reueles . and at Daunces</L>
<L>That ben occasions of dalyaunces</L>
<L>Suche &thorn;inges maken children for to be</L>
<L N="68">To sone rype and bolde as men may se</L>
<L>Which is ful perilous and ha&thorn; ben &yogh;ore</L>
<L>ffor al to sone may sche lerne lore /</L>
<L>Of boldenesse whan sche is a wijf</L>
<L N="72">And &yogh;e maystresses in &yogh;oure olde lyf</L>
<L>&thorn;at lordes doughtres han in gouernance /</L>
<L>Ne take&thorn; of my word no displesance</L>
<L>&thorn;inges &thorn;at ben sette in gouernynges</L>
<L N="76">Of lordes doughtres only for tuo &thorn;inges</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er for &yogh;e han kept &yogh;our honeste /</L>
<L>O&thorn;er &yogh;e han falle in frelete</L>
<L>And knowen wel ynough &thorn;e olde daunce</L>
<L N="80">And konne forsake fully meschaunce</L>
<L>ffor euermo &thorn;er-fore for cristes sake /</L>
<L>kepe&thorn; wel &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;e vndertake</L>
<L>A &thorn;eef of venyson &thorn;at ha&thorn; forlaft</L>
<L N="84">his likorousnesse and alle his theues craft</L>
<L>Kan kepe a forest best of ony man<MILESTONE N="192a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now kepe&thorn; hem wel for and &yogh;e wil &yogh;e can</L>
<L>loke&thorn; wel to no vice &thorn;at &yogh;e assente</L>
<L N="88">lest &yogh;e be dampned for &yogh;oure yuel entente</L>
<L>ffor who so do&thorn; a tretour is certayn</L>
<L>And take&thorn; heed of &thorn;at &thorn;at I schal sayn</L>
<L>Of alle tresoun suffreyn pestilence</L>
<L N="92">Is whan a wight betraye&thorn; Innocence</L>
<L>&yogh;e fadres and &yogh;e modres eek also</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &yogh;e haue children be it oon or mo</L>
<L>&yogh;oure is &thorn;e charge of alle here sufferance</L>
<L N="96">Whil &thorn;ey ben vnder &yogh;oure gouernance
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="428"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="306"></L>
<L>Be&thorn; war &thorn;at by ensample of &yogh;oure lyuynge</L>
<L>Ow&thorn;er by necligence in chastysynge</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey ne perissche I dar wel seye</L>
<L N="100">If &thorn;at &thorn;ey don &yogh;e schulle ful sore abeye</L>
<L>vnder a schepperde softe and necligent</L>
<L>&thorn;e wolf ha&thorn; many a scheep and lamb torent</L>
<L>Sufficeth oon ensample now as heere</L>
<L N="104">ffor I moot torne a&yogh;en to my mateere /</L>
<L>This mayde of which I telle my tale expresse /</L>
<L>Sche kepte hir self hir needed no maistresse</L>
<L>ffor in hire lyuyng maydens mighte rede /</L>
<L N="108">As in a book euery good word and dede</L>
<L>&thorn;at longe&thorn; to a mayde vertuous</L>
<L>Sche was so prudent and so bountyuous</L>
<L>ffor which out sprong &thorn;e fame on euery syde</L>
<L N="112">Bo&thorn;e of hire beaute and of hire bounte wyde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;urgh &thorn;e lond &thorn;ey preised hire echone</L>
<L>That louede vertu saue envye alone</L>
<L>&thorn;at sory is of o&thorn;er mennes wele</L>
<L N="116">And glad is of his sorwe and vnhele</L>
<L>The doctour make&thorn; &thorn;is discripcion</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayde wente on a day in-to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e temple wi&thorn; hire mooder deere</L>
<L N="120">As is of &yogh;onge maydens &thorn;e maneere</L>
<L>Now was &thorn;er a Iustice in &thorn;e toun<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That gouernour was of &thorn;at region</L>
<L>And so bifelle &thorn;is Iuge his yhen caste</L>
<L N="124">vppon &thorn;is mayde hire ful faste</L>
<L>As sche cam forthby &thorn;er &thorn;e Iuge stood</L>
<L>Anon his herte chaunge&thorn; and his mood</L>
<L>So was he caught wi&thorn; beaute of &thorn;is mayde /</L>
<L N="128">And to himself ful priuely he sayde /</L>
<L>This mayde schal be myn for ony man</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e feend in-to his herte ran</L>
<L>And taught him sodeynly by what sleighte</L>
<L N="132">&thorn;e mayde to his purpos wynne he mighte
<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="429"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="307"></L>
<L>ffor certes by no force ne by no meede</L>
<L>him &thorn;ought/ he was not able for to speede /</L>
<L>ffor he was strong of freendes and eek sche</L>
<L N="136">Confermed was in such souereyn beaute</L>
<L>&thorn;at wel he wiste he might hire neuer wynne</L>
<L>As for to make hire wi&thorn; hire body synne</L>
<L>ffor which wi&thorn; gret deliberacion</L>
<L N="140">he sente after a clerk in-to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>The which he knew for subtil and for bold</L>
<L>This Iuge vnto &thorn;is clerk his tale ha&thorn; told</L>
<L>In secre wise and made him to assure /</L>
<L N="144">he scholde telle it to no creature</L>
<L>And if he dide he scholde leese his heed</L>
<L>Whan assented was &thorn;is cursed reed</L>
<L>Glad was &thorn;e Iuge and made glad chere /</L>
<L N="148">And &yogh;af him &yogh;iftes precious and deere /</L>
<L>Whan schapen was al &thorn;is conspiracie</L>
<L>ffrom poynt to poynt how &thorn;at his leccherie</L>
<L>Parformed schulde be ful subtilly</L>
<L N="152">as &yogh;e schal here aftirward openly</L>
<L>hom go&thorn; &thorn;is clerk &thorn;at highte Claudius</L>
<L>&thorn;is false Iuge &thorn;at highte Apius</L>
<L>So was his name for it is no fable /</L>
<L N="156">But knowen for an historial &thorn;ing notable</L>
<L>The sentence of it so&thorn; is out of doute<MILESTONE N="193a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;is false Iuge go&thorn; now faste aboute</L>
<L>To hasten his delyt al &thorn;at he may</L>
<L N="160">And so bifelle sone after on a day</L>
<L>&thorn;is false Iuge as telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e story</L>
<L>As he was woned sat in his consistory</L>
<L>And &yogh;af his domes vpon sondry cas</L>
<L N="164">This false clerk cam for&thorn; a wel good paas</L>
<L>And seyde lord if &thorn;at it be &yogh;our wille /</L>
<L>As do&thorn; me right vpon &thorn;is pitous bille</L>
<L>In which I pleyne vppon virginius</L>
<L N="168">And if &thorn;at he wol seyn it is not &thorn;us
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="430"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="308"></L>
<L>I wol proue it and fynde good witnesse</L>
<L>That so&thorn; is &thorn;at my bille wol expresse</L>
<L>&thorn;e Iuge answerde of &thorn;is in his absence</L>
<L N="172">I may not &yogh;iue diffinityf sentence</L>
<L>let don him calle and I wol gladly heere</L>
<L>Thou schalt haue right and no wrong heere</L>
<L>Virginius cam to wite &thorn;e Iuges wille</L>
<L N="176">And right anon was rad &thorn;is cursed bille /</L>
<L>The sentence of it was as &yogh;e schul heere</L>
<L>To &yogh;ou my lord sire Apius so deere</L>
<L>Schewe&thorn; &yogh;oure pouere seruant Claudius</L>
<L N="180">how &thorn;at a knight called virginius</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e lawe a&yogh;eins alle equite</L>
<L>holde&thorn; expres a&yogh;eins &thorn;e will of me</L>
<L>my seruaunt which &thorn;at is my &thorn;ral by right</L>
<L N="184">Which from myn hous was stolen on a night</L>
<L>Whils sche was ful &yogh;ong I wol it preue</L>
<L>By witnesse lord so &thorn;at &yogh;e &yogh;ou not greue</L>
<L>Sche is nought his doughter what so he say</L>
<L N="188">Wherfore my lord &thorn;e Iuge to &yogh;ou I pray</L>
<L>&yogh;elde me my &thorn;ralle if &thorn;at it be &yogh;our wille</L>
<L>lo &thorn;is was al &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;e bille</L>
<L>Virgineus gan vpon &thorn;e clerk biholde</L>
<L N="192">But hastily er he his tale tolde /</L>
<L>he wolde haue defended it as scholde a knight<MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And by witnesse of many a trewe wight</L>
<L>That al was fals &thorn;at seyde his aduersarie</L>
<L N="196">This cursed Iuge wolde no lenger tarie /</L>
<L>Ne here a word more of virgineus</L>
<L>But &yogh;af his Iuggement and seyde &thorn;us</L>
<L>I deme anon &thorn;is clerk his seruaunt haue</L>
<L N="200">&thorn;ou schalt no lenger in &thorn;in hous hire saue</L>
<L>Go bring hire forth and put hire in oure warde</L>
<L>&thorn;is clerk schal haue his &thorn;ral &thorn;us I awarde /</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is wor&thorn;i knight virgineus /</L>
<L N="204">&thorn;urgh &thorn;e assent of &thorn;e Iuge apius
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="431"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="309"></L>
<L>Moste by force his deere doughter &yogh;yuen</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e Iuge in lecchorie to lyuen</L>
<L>he go&thorn; him hom and sette him in his halle</L>
<L N="208">And leet anon his deere dou&yogh;ter calle /</L>
<L>And with a face deed as ayssches colde</L>
<L>vppon hire humble face he gan biholde</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fadres pite stiking &thorn;orugh his herte</L>
<L N="212">Al wolde he not from his purpos conuerte</L>
<L>Doughter quod he virginea by &thorn;y name</L>
<L>&thorn;er ben tuo weyes o&thorn;er de&thorn; or schame</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou most suffre allas &thorn;at I was bore</L>
<L N="216">ffor neuer &thorn;ou deseruedest wherfore</L>
<L>To deyen with a swerd or wi&thorn; a knyf</L>
<L>O deere doughter endere of my lijf</L>
<L>Which I haue fostred vp wi&thorn; such plesaunce</L>
<L N="220">&thorn;at &thorn;ou ne were out of my remembrance /</L>
<L>O doughter which &thorn;at art my laste wo /</L>
<L>And in my lijf my laste ioye also</L>
<L>O gemme of chastite in pacience</L>
<L N="224">Tak &thorn;ou &thorn;i de&thorn; for &thorn;is is my sentence /</L>
<L>ffor loue and nat/ for hate &thorn;ou most be deed</L>
<L>My pitous hond moot smyten of &thorn;in heed</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at euer Apius &thorn;e say</L>
<L N="228">&thorn;us ha&thorn; he falsly iugged &thorn;e to day</L>
<L>And tolde hire al &thorn;e cas as &yogh;e bifore<MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>han herd it nede&thorn; not to telle it more</L>
<L>Mercy deere fader quod &thorn;is mayde</L>
<L N="232">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word sche bo&thorn;e hire armes layde</L>
<L>Aboute his necke as sche was woned to do</L>
<L>&thorn;e teeres barsten out of hire eyen tuo</L>
<L>And sayde goode fader schal I dye</L>
<L N="236">Is &thorn;er no grace is &thorn;er no remedye</L>
<L>No certes deere dou&yogh;ter myn quod he</L>
<L>&thorn;anne &yogh;if me leue fader myn quod sche</L>
<L>My de&thorn; to compleigne a litel space</L>
<L N="240">ffor parde Ieffa &yogh;af his dou&yogh;ter grace
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="432"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="310"></L>
<L>ffor to compleyne ar he hir slough allas</L>
<L>And god it wot no&thorn;ing was hire trespas</L>
<L>But &thorn;at sche ran hire fader first to see</L>
<L N="244">To welcome him wi&thorn; gret solempnite</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word sche felle on swown anon</L>
<L>And after whan hir swownyng was agon</L>
<L>Sche rise&thorn; vp and to hire fader sayde /</L>
<L N="248">Blessed be god &thorn;at I schal deye a mayde</L>
<L>&yogh;if me my deth er &thorn;at I haue a schame</L>
<L>Do&thorn; wi&thorn; &yogh;our child &yogh;our wil a goddes name</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word sche praye&thorn; him ful ofte</L>
<L N="252">&thorn;at wi&thorn; his swerd he schulde hir smyte softe</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word on swoune doun sche fel</L>
<L>hir fader wi&thorn; ful sorweful herte and fel</L>
<L>hire heed of smoot and by &thorn;e top it hente</L>
<L N="256">And to &thorn;e Iuge he &yogh;af it to presente</L>
<L>As he sat in his doom in consistory</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e Iuge it say as sai&thorn; &thorn;e story</L>
<L>He bad take him and honge him also faste</L>
<L N="260">But right anon al &thorn;e poeple in &thorn;raste</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e knight for rou&thorn;e and for pite</L>
<L>ffor knowen was &thorn;e fooles Iniquite</L>
<L>The poeple anon hadde suspecte in &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="264">By maner of &thorn;is clerkes chalangyng</L>
<L>That it was by &thorn;assent of Apius<MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They wisten wel &thorn;at he was lecchorous</L>
<L>ffor which vnto &thorn;is Apius &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L N="268">And casten him in prison right anon</L>
<L>Wher as he slough himself and Claudius</L>
<L>&thorn;at seruant was vnto &thorn;is Apius</L>
<L>Was demed for to honge vpon a tre</L>
<L N="272">But/ virgineus of his grete pite</L>
<L>Prayde for him &thorn;at he was exiled</L>
<L>And elles certes he hadde be bygyled</L>
<L>The remenant were honged more &amp; lesse</L>
<L N="276">&thorn;at consented were to his cursednesse
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="433"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="311"></L>
<L>Here may men se how synne ha&thorn; his meryt /</L>
<L>Be war for noman wot how god wol smyt</L>
<L>In no degre ne in which maner wise</L>
<L N="280">The worm of conscience wol arise</L>
<L>Of wicked lyf &thorn;ough it so preuy be</L>
<L>&thorn;at noman woot of it but god and he</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er he be lewed man or lered</L>
<L N="284">he not how soone &thorn;at he may ben afeered</L>
<L>&thorn;er-fore I rede &yogh;ou &thorn;is counseil take</L>
<L>fforsake&thorn; synne er synne &yogh;ou forsake
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000462.tif" N="434"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="312">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owre oost gan for to swere as he were wood<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prologus</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 194, <I>back</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="288">harrow quod he by nayles and by blood</L>
<L>This was a cursed &thorn;eef a fals Iustise</L>
<L>As schamful de&thorn; as herte can deuyse</L>
<L>So falle vpon his body and his bones<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>*</SUP>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="292">&thorn;e deuyl I bekenne him al at ones<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>*</SUP>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Allas to deere boughte sche hire beaute</L>
<L>Wherfore I say &thorn;at alle men may se</L>
<L>That &yogh;iftes of fortune or of nature</L>
<L N="296">Be&thorn; cause of de&thorn; of many a creature</L>
<L>hire beaute was hire de&thorn; I dar wel sayn</L>
<L>Allas so pitously as sche was slayn</L>
<L>But her of wil I not procede as now<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Men haue ful often more harm &thorn;an prow</L>
<L>But trewely myn owne mayster deere<MILESTONE N="195a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This is a pitous tale for to heere</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles passe ouer is no fors</L>
<L N="304">I pray to god so saue &thorn;in gentil cors</L>
<L>And &thorn;in vrynals and &thorn;in Iurdanes</L>
<L>Thyn ypocras and &thorn;in Galianes</L>
<L>And euery box ful of &thorn;in letuarie</L>
<L N="308">God blesse hem and oure lady seinte marie</L>
<L>So mote I &thorn;e &thorn;ou art a propre man</L>
<L>And ylike a prelat by seint Runyan</L>
<L>Sayde I nou&yogh;t wel can I nou&yogh;t speke in terme</L>
<L N="312">But wel I woot &thorn;ou dost myn herte to erme</L>
<L>That I almost haue caught a Cardyacle /</L>
<L>By Corpus bones but if I haue triacle</L>
<L>O&thorn;er elles a draught of moyste and corny ale /</L>
<L N="316">Or but I heere anoon a merye tale /
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="435"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="313"></L>
<L>Myn herte is lost for pite of &thorn;is mayde</L>
<L>&thorn;ou belamy Iohn Pardoner he sayde</L>
<L>es right anon<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Part of the MS is cut away here]</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">eint Runyon</L>
<L>re at &thorn;is ale stake</L>
<L>nke and eten of a Cake</L>
<L>&thorn;ise gentils bygonne to crye</L>
<L N="324">lle vs of no rybaudye</L>
<L>ortal &thorn;ing &thorn;at we may leere</L>
<L>&thorn;enne wol we gladly heere</L>
<L>wys quod he but I moot &thorn;ynke</L>
<L N="328">honest &thorn;ing whil &thorn;at I drinke
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000464.tif" N="436"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="314">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Part of the MS is cut away here]</NOTE>bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e Pardoneres tale folwynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> xvj<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrdynges quod he in chirches whan I preche</L>
<L>I peyne me to haue an hauteyn speche</L>
<L>I ryng it out as round as go&thorn; a belle</L>
<L N="332">ffor I can al by rote &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>My teeme is alway oon and euer was</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Part of the MS is cut away here]</NOTE>malorum est Cupiditas</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Part of the MS is cut away here]</NOTE>whennes &thorn;at I come</L>
<L>A &thorn;enne my bulles schewe I alle and some<MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Oure liege lordes seal is my patent</L>
<L>&thorn;at schewe I first my body to warant</L>
<L>That no man be so bolde ne prest ne clerk</L>
<L N="340">me to destourbe of cristes holy werk</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at telle I for&thorn; my tales</L>
<L>Bulles of Popes and of Cardinales</L>
<L>Of Patriarkes and bisschoppes I schewe</L>
<L N="344">And in latyn I speke wordes a fewe</L>
<L>To saffran wi&thorn; my predicacion</L>
<L>And for to stere men to deuoicon</L>
<L>&thorn;anne schewe I for&thorn; my lange cristal stones</L>
<L N="348">I-crammed ful of cloutes and of bones</L>
<L>Relikes &thorn;ey ben as wenen &thorn;ey echone</L>
<L>&thorn;an haue I in latoun a schulder bone</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at was of an holy iewes scheep</L>
<L N="352">Goode men say I take&thorn; of my wordes keep</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &thorn;is bon be waisshe in any welle</L>
<L>If kow or calf scheep or oxe swelle</L>
<L>That eny worme ha&thorn; y-bite or stronge</L>
<L N="356">Touche he &thorn;is boon anon he schal be sounde
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="437"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="315"></L>
<L>And &yogh;it also I seye for&thorn;ermore</L>
<L>Of pokkes of scabbes and of euery sore</L>
<L>Schal euery scheep be hool &thorn;at of &thorn;is welle</L>
<L N="360">Drinke&thorn; a draught and take keep what I telle</L>
<L>Wole euery wight er &thorn;at &thorn;e cok him crowe&thorn;</L>
<L>And do &thorn;ing &thorn;at him owe&thorn;</L>
<L>ffastynge drinke of &thorn;is welle a draught</L>
<L N="364">As &thorn;ilke holy iewe oure eldre ous taught</L>
<L>his bestes and his store schal multiplye</L>
<L>And sires also it hele&thorn; Ielousie</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey a man be falle in gelouse rage</L>
<L N="368">Let make wi&thorn; &thorn;is water his potage</L>
<L>And neuer schal he more his wijf mystreste</L>
<L>&thorn;ey he in so&thorn;e a defaute by hire wiste</L>
<L>Al had sche taken prestes tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L N="372">heer is a myteyn eek as &yogh;e may see<MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he &thorn;at his hond wol putte in &thorn;at myteyne</L>
<L>he schal haue multiplyyng of his greyne</L>
<L>When he ha&thorn; sowen be it whete or ootes</L>
<L N="376">So &thorn;at of pens o&thorn;er elles of grootes</L>
<L>And men and wommen o &thorn;ing warne I &yogh;ou</L>
<L>If any wight be in &thorn;is chirche now</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; don synne orrible &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="380">Dar nought for schame schriuen be</L>
<L>Or eny womman be sche &yogh;ong or old</L>
<L>&thorn;at ha&thorn; y-maad hire housbonde kokewold</L>
<L>Such folk schuln haue no power ne grace</L>
<L N="384">To offre to my relikes in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>And who so fynde&thorn; him out of such blame</L>
<L>&thorn;ey wole come vp and offre in goddes name</L>
<L>And I assoile him by &thorn;e auctorite</L>
<L N="388">Which &thorn;at by bulle was y-graunted me</L>
<L>By &thorn;is gande haue I wonne euery &yogh;ere</L>
<L>An hundred mark se&thorn;enes I was pardonere</L>
<L>I stande lik a clerk in many a pulpette</L>
<L N="392">And schewe lewed poeple and doun &thorn;ey sette
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="438"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="316"></L>
<L>I preche so as &yogh;e haue herd byfore</L>
<L>And telle an hundred Iapes more /</L>
<L>&thorn;enne peyne I me to strecche for&thorn; my nekke</L>
<L N="396">And Est and west vpon &thorn;e poeple I bekke</L>
<L>As do&thorn; a dowfe sittyng vpan a berne</L>
<L>myn handes and my tonge gon so &yogh;erne</L>
<L>&thorn;at is it ioye to se my busynes</L>
<L N="400">Of auarice and such o&thorn;er cursednes</L>
<L>Is al my prechinge to make hem fre</L>
<L>To &yogh;iue here pans and namely vnto me</L>
<L>ffor myn entent is nou&yogh;t but for to wynne</L>
<L N="404">And no&thorn;ing for correccion of synne</L>
<L>I rekke neuer whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben beried</L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at here soules gon a blake beryed</L>
<L>ffor certes many a predicacion</L>
<L N="408">Sowne&thorn; ofte tyme of yuel intencion<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Somme for plesaunce of folk and for flaterie</L>
<L>To ben auaunced by ypocresye</L>
<L>And somme for veynglorie and somme for hate /</L>
<L N="412">ffor whan I dar nou&yogh;t o&thorn;erwise debate</L>
<L>&thorn;anne wil I stynge hem with my tonge smerte</L>
<L>In preching so &thorn;at &thorn;ei schal nou&yogh;t asterte</L>
<L>To be diffamed falsly if &thorn;at he</L>
<L N="416">ha&thorn; trespassed to my bre&thorn;eren o&thorn;er to me</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough I telle nou&yogh;t his propre name</L>
<L>Men schal wel knowe &thorn;at it is &thorn;e same</L>
<L>By symony and by o&thorn;er circumstaunces</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;us quyte I folk &thorn;at do&thorn; vs displesaunces</L>
<L>&thorn;us spitte I out my venym vnder hewe</L>
<L>Of holynesse to seme holy and trewe</L>
<L>But schortly myn entent I wil deuyse</L>
<L N="424">I preche of no &thorn;ing but of coueytise</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore my teeme is &yogh;it and euer was</L>
<L>Radix malorum est cupiditas /</L>
<L>Thus gan I preche a&yogh;eins &thorn;e same vice</L>
<L N="428">Such &thorn;at I vse and &thorn;at is auarice
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="439"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="317"></L>
<L>That &thorn;ough I my self be gulty in &thorn;at synne</L>
<L>&yogh;it kan I make o&thorn;er folk for to wynne</L>
<L>ffrom auarice and sore to repente</L>
<L N="432">But &thorn;at nys nought my principal entente</L>
<L>I preche no &thorn;ing but for coueityse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is matiere I ought ynough suffise</L>
<L>&thorn;enne telle I of ensamples many on</L>
<L N="436">Of olde stories longe tyme agon</L>
<L>ffor lewed poeple louen tales olde</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;inges can &thorn;ey wel reporte and holde</L>
<L>What trowe &yogh;e whiles &thorn;at I may preche</L>
<L N="440">And wynne gold and siluer for I teche</L>
<L>That I wol lyue in pouert wilfully</L>
<L>Nay nay I &thorn;ought it neuer trewely</L>
<L>ffor I wol preche and begge in sondry landes</L>
<L N="444">ffor I wole do no labour wi&thorn; myn handes<MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And make basketes and lyue &thorn;erby</L>
<L>By cause I wol not beggen ydelly</L>
<L>I wole none of &thorn;e aposteles countrefete</L>
<L N="448">I wole haue money chese and whete</L>
<L>Al were it &yogh;euen of &thorn;e porest page</L>
<L>O&thorn;er of &thorn;e porest wydewe in a village</L>
<L>Al scholde here children sterue for famyne</L>
<L N="452">Nay I wol drynke &thorn;e likour of &thorn;e vyne</L>
<L>And haue a Ioly wenche in euery toun</L>
<L>But herkne&thorn; lordynges in conclusion</L>
<L>&yogh;oure liking is &thorn;at I schal telle a tale</L>
<L N="456">Now I haue drunke a draught of corny ale</L>
<L>By god I hope I schal telle &yogh;ou a &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal by resoun ben at &yogh;our liking</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough my selue be a vicious man</L>
<L N="460">A more-ille tale &yogh;it I &yogh;ou telle can</L>
<L>Which I am wont to preche for to wynne</L>
<L>Now holde &yogh;oure pees my tale I wol begynne
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000468.tif" N="440"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="318">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN fflaundres whilom was a companye /</L>
<L N="464">Of &yogh;ong folk &thorn;at haunteden folye</L>
<L>As Ryot hasard stewes and tauernes</L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP>Where as why&thorn; harpes lutes and gyternes<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>1_1</SUP> In a different hand.]</NOTE></L>
<L>They daunce and pleye at dyse bo&thorn;e day and night</L>
<L N="468">And eeten also and drunken ouer al here might</L>
<L>&thorn;orugh which &thorn;ey doon &thorn;e deueles sacrifise</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e deueles temple in cursed wyse</L>
<L>&thorn;e Superflues abhominable</L>
<L N="472">here o&thorn;es ben so grete and dampna[b]le /</L>
<L>&thorn;at it is grisly for to here hem swere</L>
<L>Oure blessed lordes body they to-tere</L>
<L>hem &thorn;oughte Iewes rent/ him nought ynough</L>
<L N="476">And ilke of hem at o&thorn;er synnes lowh</L>
<L>And right anon &thorn;enne come tomblisteres</L>
<L>ffetys and smal &yogh;ong fruytesteres /</L>
<L>Syngers with harpes bawdes wafereres</L>
<L N="480">Suche ben verray &thorn;e deueles officers<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To kyndle and blowe &thorn;e fyr of leccherie /</L>
<L>That is annexed to glotonye /</L>
<L>The holy writ take I to witnesse /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Nolite inebriari vino in</NOTE></L>
<L>That leccherie is in wyn and drunkenesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; quo est luxuria</NOTE></L>
<L N="485">Lo how &thorn;at drunken loth vnkyndely</L>
<L>lay by his doughtres tuo vnwetyngly</L>
<L>So drunke he was he nyste what he wrought</L>
<L N="487b">And &thorn;erfore sore repente him oughte<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE></L>
<L N="488">heroudes who so wole &thorn;e stories seche</L>
<L N="488b">&thorn;er may &yogh;e lerne and by ensample teche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[spurious]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="441"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="319"></L>
<L N="489">Whan he of wyn was replet at his feste</L>
<L>Right at his owen table &yogh;af his heste</L>
<L>To slen &thorn;e Baptist Iohan ful gulteles</L>
<L N="492">Senek sai&thorn; eek goode wordes douteles</L>
<L>he sei&thorn; he can no difference fynde</L>
<L>Bitwix a man &thorn;at/ is out of his mynde</L>
<L>And a man &thorn;at is drunkelewe</L>
<L N="496">But &thorn;at wodnesse is fallen in a schrewe</L>
<L>Perseuere&thorn; lenger &thorn;an do&thorn; drunkenes</L>
<L>O glotenye ful of cursednes</L>
<L>O cause ferst of oure confusion</L>
<L N="500">O original of oure dampnacion</L>
<L>Til crist hadde brought out wi&thorn; his blood agayn</L>
<L>lo how deere and schortly was to sayn</L>
<L>Aboute was &thorn;e cursed vilanye /</L>
<L N="504">Corrupte was al &thorn;is world &thorn;urgh glotenye</L>
<L>Adam oure fader and his wyf also<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ieronimus <I>contra</I> Iouinianum quamdiu ieiunauit in paradiso fuit commedit et eiectus est statim duxit vxorem</NOTE></L>
<L>ffro paradys to labour and to wo</L>
<L>Were dryuen for &thorn;at vice it nys no drede</L>
<L N="508">ffor whiles &thorn;at adam fasted as I rede</L>
<L>He was in paradys and whan &thorn;at he /</L>
<L>Ete of &thorn;e fruyte defended on a tre</L>
<L>Anon he was out cast to woo and pleyne</L>
<L N="512">O glotonye on &thorn;e wel oughte ous pleigne</L>
<L>O wiste a man how many maladyes</L>
<L>ffolwe&thorn; of excesse and of glotenyes<MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he schulde be &thorn;e more mesurable</L>
<L N="516">Of his diete sittyng at &thorn;e table</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;e schorte &thorn;rote &thorn;e tendre mou&thorn;</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;at Est and West north and sou&thorn;</L>
<L>In er&thorn;e in aier in water men to swynke /</L>
<L N="520">To gete a glotoun mete and drynke</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is matiere o poule wel canst &thorn;ou entrete</L>
<L>Mete vnto wombe and wombe eek vnto mete</L>
<L>Schal god discryuen bo&thorn;e as poule sai&thorn;</L>
<L N="524">Allas a foul &thorn;ing is it by my fai&thorn; /
