<L>What we schuln doon and bringe it wel aboute</L>
<L>I graunte quod &thorn;at o&thorn;er out of doute</L>
<L>&thorn;at by my trew&thorn;e I wol &thorn;e nou&yogh;t bewreye</L>
<L N="824">Now quo&thorn; &thorn;e firste &thorn;ou wost wel we be tweye</L>
<L>And tweyne of vs schuln strenger ben &thorn;an oon</L>
<L>loke whenne he is sette and &thorn;anne anon</L>
<L>Aryse as &thorn;ou woldest wi&thorn; him pleye</L>
<L N="828">And I schal renne him &thorn;urgh &thorn;e sydes tweye</L>
<L>Whiles &thorn;at &thorn;ou struggelist wi&thorn; him in game</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;y dagger loke &thorn;ou do &thorn;e same</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne schal al &thorn;is gold departed be</L>
<L N="832">My deere freend bitwixe &thorn;e and me</L>
<L>&thorn;enne may we bo&thorn;e oure lustes fulfille</L>
<L>And pleye atte dys right at oure owen wille</L>
<L>And &thorn;us accorded ben &thorn;ese schrewes tweye</L>
<L N="836">To sleen &thorn;e &thorn;ridde as &yogh;e herde me seye</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;ongest which &thorn;at wente to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>fful ofte in herte he rolle&thorn; vp and doun</L>
<L>&thorn;e beaute of &thorn;ese floreynes newe and bright</L>
<L N="840">O lord quo&thorn; he if so were &thorn;at I might<MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;is tresour wynne to my self allone</L>
<L>&thorn;er nys no man &thorn;at lyue&thorn; vnder &thorn;e trone /</L>
<L>Of god &thorn;at scholde lyue as mery as I</L>
<L N="844">And at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e feend oure enemy</L>
<L>Putte in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he schulde poyson beye</L>
<L>With which he mighte sleen his felawes tweye</L>
<L>ffor why &thorn;e feend fand him in such lyuyng</L>
<L N="848">That hadde leue him to sorwe brynge
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="451"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="329"></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;is was vtterly his entent</L>
<L>To slen hem bo&thorn;e and neuer to repent</L>
<L>And for&thorn; he go&thorn; no lenger nolde he tarye</L>
<L N="852">In-to &thorn;e toun vnto a potycarie /</L>
<L>And preyde him &thorn;at he him wolde selle</L>
<L>Som poysoun &thorn;at he might his rattes quelle</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;er was a polkat in his hawe</L>
<L N="856">&thorn;at as he sayde his Capons had y-slawe /</L>
<L>And sayde he wolde wreken him if he might</L>
<L>Of vermyn &thorn;at distroyed him by night</L>
<L>&thorn;e apotykaries answerde &thorn;ou schalt haue</L>
<L N="860">A &thorn;ing &thorn;at als god my soule saue</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is world &thorn;er nys no creature</L>
<L>&thorn;at eten or drunken ha&thorn; of &thorn;is confecture</L>
<L>Nought but &thorn;e mountaunce of a corn of whete</L>
<L N="864">&thorn;at he ne schal his lyf anon forlete</L>
<L>&yogh;e sterue he schal and &thorn;at in lasse while /</L>
<L>&thorn;enne &thorn;ou wolt gon a pace nought but a myle</L>
<L>&thorn;is poysoun is so strong and so vyolent</L>
<L N="868">&thorn;is cursed man ha&thorn; in his hand y-hent</L>
<L>&thorn;is &thorn;oysoun in a box and se&thorn;enes he ran</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e nexte strete vnto a man</L>
<L>And borwed him large botelles &thorn;re</L>
<L N="872">And in &thorn;e tweyne &thorn;is poyson poured he</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde he keped clene for his drynke</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e night he schop him to swynke</L>
<L>In karying of &thorn;e golde out of &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="876">And whan &thorn;is ryetour wi&thorn; sory grace<MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>had felled wi&thorn; him his grete botelles &thorn;re</L>
<L>To his felawes a&yogh;ayn repayre&thorn; he</L>
<L>What nede&thorn; it to sermone &thorn;er-of more</L>
<L N="880">ffor right as &thorn;ay hadde cast his de&thorn; afore</L>
<L>Right so &thorn;ey haue him slayn and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>And whenne &thorn;at &thorn;is was don &thorn;en spak &thorn;at oon</L>
<L>Now let vs drynke and sytte and make vs mery</L>
<L N="884">And afterward we wolen his body bery
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="452"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="330"></L>
<L>And aftirward it happed hem per cas</L>
<L>To take &thorn;e botel &thorn;er-in &thorn;e poyson was</L>
<L>And drank and &yogh;af his felawe drynke also</L>
<L N="888">ffor which anon &thorn;ey storuen bo&thorn;e tuo</L>
<L>But certes I suppose &thorn;at Auycenne</L>
<L>Wrot neuer in no Canoun ne in no fenne</L>
<L>Mo wonder sorwes of enpoysonyng</L>
<L N="892">Thus hadde &thorn;ise wrecches tuo here endynge</L>
<L>Thus ended ben &thorn;is Omycides tuo</L>
<L>And eek &thorn;e false enpoysonere also</L>
<L>O cursed synne ful of cursednes</L>
<L N="896">O traytours Omycyderes o wikkednes</L>
<L>O glotenye o luxurie O hasardye</L>
<L>&thorn;ou blasphemer of crist wi&thorn; vilenye</L>
<L>And o&thorn;es grete of vsage and of pryde</L>
<L N="900">Allas mankynde how may it betyde</L>
<L>&thorn;erto &thorn;in creatour / which &thorn;at &thorn;e wrought</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his precious blood &thorn;e bought</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art so fals and so vnkynde allas</L>
<L N="904">Now goode men god for&yogh;iue &yogh;oure trespas</L>
<L>And ware &yogh;ou fro &thorn;e synne of auarice /</L>
<L>Myn holy pardoun may &yogh;ou alle warische</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e offre nobles or sterlinges</L>
<L N="908">O&thorn;er elles seluer spones broches and rynges /</L>
<L>Bowe&thorn; &yogh;oure hed vnder &thorn;is holy bulles</L>
<L>Come&thorn; vp &yogh;e wyues offre&thorn; &yogh;oure wulles</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure name I entre here in my rolle anon</L>
<L N="912">In-to &thorn;e blisse of heuen schul &yogh;e gon<MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I &yogh;ou assoille by myn heih powere</L>
<L>&yogh;e &thorn;at woln offre as clene and eek as cleere</L>
<L>As &yogh;e were born and sires lo &thorn;us I preche</L>
<L N="916">And Ihesu crist &thorn;at is oure soules leche</L>
<L>So graunte &yogh;ou his pardoun to resceyue</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at is best I wol &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t disceyue</L>
<L>But sires o word forgat I in my tale</L>
<L N="920">I haue reliqes and pardon in my male
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="453"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="331"></L>
<L>As faire as eny man in Engelond</L>
<L>Whiche were me y-&yogh;oue by &thorn;e popes hond</L>
<L>If eny of &yogh;ou wole of deuocion</L>
<L N="924">Offren and haue myn absolucion</L>
<L>Come&thorn; for&thorn; anon and knele&thorn; doun heere</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schuln haue my pardon &thorn;at is deere</L>
<L>O&thorn;er elles take&thorn; pardoun as &yogh;e wende</L>
<L N="928">Al newe and freissche at euery tounes ende</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &yogh;e offren alway newe and newe /</L>
<L>Nobles and pens which &thorn;at ben good and trewe</L>
<L>It is an honour to euerich &thorn;at is heere</L>
<L N="932">&thorn;at &yogh;e may haue a suffisaunt pardonere</L>
<L>To assoille &yogh;ou in cuntre as I ryde</L>
<L>ffor auentures which &thorn;at may betyde</L>
<L>ffor peraduenture &thorn;er may falle on or tuo</L>
<L N="936">Doun of his hors and breke his necke a tuo</L>
<L>loke which a suerte it is to &yogh;ou alle</L>
<L>&thorn;at I am in &yogh;our felaschipe y-falle</L>
<L>&thorn;at may assoille &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e more and lasse</L>
<L N="940">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e soule schal fro &thorn;e body passe /</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;at oure hooste schal begynne</L>
<L>ffor he is most envoluped in synne</L>
<L>Come&thorn; for&thorn; sire Ost and offre&thorn; first anon</L>
<L N="944">And &thorn;ou schalt kisse &thorn;e relikes euerychoon</L>
<L>&yogh;e for a grote vnbokel anon &thorn;y purs</L>
<L>Nay nay quod he &thorn;enne haue I cristes curs</L>
<L>Let be quod he it / schal nou&yogh;t be so &thorn;eche</L>
<L N="948">&thorn;ou woldest make me kesse &thorn;in olde breche<MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And swere it were a relyk of a seint</L>
<L>&thorn;ough it were wi&thorn; &thorn;yn foundement depeynt</L>
<L>But by &thorn;e Crosse which &thorn;at seint Eleyne fand</L>
<L N="952">I wolde I hadde &thorn;ine coyllons in myn hand</L>
<L>In stede of relikes o&thorn;er of seintuary</L>
<L>let cutte hem of I wol &thorn;e helpe hem cary</L>
<L>&thorn;ey schuln be schryned in an hogges tord</L>
<L N="956">&thorn;is pardoner answerde nou&yogh;t a word
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="454"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="332"></L>
<L>So wro&thorn; he was he nolde no word say</L>
<L>Now quod oure Oost I wil no lenger play</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e ne with non o&thorn;er angry man</L>
<L N="960">But right anon &thorn;e wor&thorn;y knight bygan</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he saugh &thorn;at al &thorn;e poeple l[ough]</L>
<L>Nomore of &thorn;is for it is right ynough</L>
<L>Sire pardoner be mery and glad of cheere</L>
<L N="964">And &yogh;e sire Oste &thorn;at ben to me so deere</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e kisse &thorn;e pardoneere</L>
<L>And pardoner I pray &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou drawe &thorn;e neere</L>
<L N="967">And as we dide let vs laughe and pleye</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ey kisse and ryden for&thorn; here weye</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit. fabula Pardonarii
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group"><PB REF="00000483.tif" N="455"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="168">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&beta;. FRAGMENT III.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 4. THE SHIPMAN'S TALE.</HEAD>
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynne&thorn; &thorn;e schipmannes tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 204</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Marchaunt whilom dwelled at Seint Denys<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ca<SUP>m</SUP></NOTE></L>
<L>That riche was for which men heelde him wys<NOTE PLACE="marg">xvij<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wyf he hadde of excellent beaute</L>
<L>And compynable and reuerent was sche</L>
<L>Which is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at cause&thorn; more dispence</L>
<L N="1196">&thorn;en wor&thorn; is alle &thorn;e cheere and reuerence</L>
<L>That men haue doon at festes and at daunces</L>
<L>Suche salutaciouns and contynances</L>
<L>Passe&thorn; as do&thorn; &thorn;e schadewe on a wal</L>
<L N="1200">But woo is him &thorn;at paye moot for al</L>
<L>&thorn;e sely housband algates he moste paye</L>
<L>he moot vs clo&thorn;e and vs arraye</L>
<L>As for his owen worschipe richely</L>
<L N="1204">In which aray we daunce Iolyly</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he nou&yogh;t may per aduenture<MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Or elles luste no suche spenses endure /</L>
<L>But &thorn;enke&thorn; it is waste and y-loste /</L>
<L N="1208">Thenne moot ano&thorn;er payen for oure coste</L>
<L>Or lene us golde and &thorn;at is perilous</L>
<L>&thorn;is noble marchand held a noble hous</L>
<L>ffor which he hadde alday gret repayre</L>
<L N="1212">ffor his largenesse and for his wyf was fayre</L>
<L>&thorn;at wonder is but herkene&thorn; to my tale</L>
<L>Amonges all his gestes grete and smale /</L>
<L>&thorn;er was a monk a fair man and a bolde</L>
<L N="1216">I trowe a &thorn;ritty wynter he was olde /</L>
<L>That euer in oon was drawyng to &thorn;e place</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;onge monk &thorn;at was so fair of face
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="456"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="169"></L>
<L>Aqueynted was so wi&thorn; &thorn;is goode man</L>
<L N="1220">Si&thorn;enes &thorn;at here firste knowleche bygan</L>
<L>That in his hous as ffamuler was he</L>
<L>As it is possible eny frend to be</L>
<L>And for as mekel as &thorn;e goode man</L>
<L N="1224">And eek &thorn;is monk of which &thorn;at I bygan</L>
<L>Were bo&thorn;e tuo y-born in o village</L>
<L>The monk him clayme&thorn; as for cosynage</L>
<L>And he a&yogh;ein he sai&thorn; nought ones nay</L>
<L N="1228">But was as glad &thorn;er of as foul of day</L>
<L>ffor to his herte it was a gret plesaunce</L>
<L>&thorn;us ben &thorn;ay knitte wi&thorn; eterne alliaunce /</L>
<L>And ilke of hem gan o&thorn;er for to assure /</L>
<L N="1232">Of bro&thorn;erhode whiles &thorn;at here lyf may dure</L>
<L>ffre was daun Iohn and namely of dispense</L>
<L>As in &thorn;at hous and ful of diligence</L>
<L>To do plesaunce and also gret costage /</L>
<L N="1236">he nought forgat to &yogh;iue &thorn;e leste page /</L>
<L>In al &thorn;at hous but after here degre</L>
<L>He &yogh;af &thorn;e lord and se&thorn;ins al his meyne /</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he came som maner honest &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="1240">ffor which &thorn;ey were al glad of his comyng</L>
<L>As foul is fayn whan sonne vp arise&thorn;<MILESTONE N="205a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Namore of &thorn;is as now for it suffise&thorn;</L>
<L>But so bifell &thorn;is marchaund vpon a day</L>
<L N="1244">Schop him to make redy his array</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e toun of Bruges for to fare</L>
<L>To byen &thorn;ere a porcioun of ware</L>
<L>ffor which he ha&thorn; to Parys sent anon</L>
<L N="1248">A messanger and preyed ha&thorn; doun Ion</L>
<L>That he schulde come to seint Denys and pleye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him and with his wyf a day or tweye</L>
<L>Or he to Bruges wente in all wyse</L>
<L N="1252">This noble monk of which I &yogh;ou deuyse</L>
<L>ha&thorn; of his abbot as him lust licence</L>
<L>By cause he was a man of heih prudence
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="457"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="170"></L>
<L>And eek an officer out for to ryde</L>
<L N="1256">To see here graunges and here bernes wyde</L>
<L>And vnto seynt Denys he come&thorn; anon</L>
<L>Who was so welcome as my lord daun Iohn</L>
<L>Oure deere cosyn ful of curtesye</L>
<L N="1260">Wi&thorn; him brought he a Iobbe of maluesye</L>
<L>And eek ano&thorn;er ful of good vernage</L>
<L>And volatille as ay was his vsage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us I lete hem ete and drynke and pleye</L>
<L N="1264">This marchand and &thorn;is monk a day or tweye /</L>
<L>The &thorn;ridde day &thorn;is marchand vp arise&thorn;</L>
<L>And on his needes sadly him avise&thorn;</L>
<L>And vp in to his countourhous go&thorn; he /</L>
<L N="1268">To rekne wi&thorn; himselue wel may be</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ilke &yogh;eer how &thorn;at it with him stood</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at he despended hadde his good</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at he encresed were or non</L>
<L N="1272">his bokes and his bagges many oon</L>
<L>he ley&thorn; bifore him on his countyng bord</L>
<L>fful riche was his tresour and his hoord</L>
<L>ffor which ful faste his counterhous dore he schette</L>
<L N="1276">And eek he nolde noman schulde him lette</L>
<L>Of his acountes for &thorn;e mene tyme<MILESTONE N="205b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sitte til it was passed prime</L>
<L>Daun Iohn was rysen in &thorn;e morne also /</L>
<L N="1280">And in &thorn;e gardyn walke&thorn; to and fro</L>
<L>And ha&thorn; his &thorn;inges sayde deuoutely</L>
<L>&thorn;is goode wyf cam walkynge pryuely</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e gardyn &thorn;er he walke&thorn; softe</L>
<L N="1284">And him salueth as sche ha&thorn; don ofte</L>
<L>A mayden childe came in hire companye</L>
<L>Which at hire luste may gouerne and gye</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;it vnder &thorn;e &yogh;erde was &thorn;e mayde</L>
<L N="1288">O deere Cosyn myn daun Iohn sche sayde /</L>
<L>What eyle&thorn; &yogh;ou so ra&thorn;e to aryse</L>
<L>Nece quod he it aughte ynough suffise
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="458"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="171"></L>
<L>ffyue houres for to slepen on a nyght</L>
<L N="1292">But it were for an olde palled knight</L>
<L>As ben &thorn;ese wedded men &thorn;at lye and dare</L>
<L>As in a forme sitte alway an hare</L>
<L>Were al forstraught wi&thorn; houndes grete and smale</L>
<L N="1296">But deere neece why be &yogh;e so pale /</L>
<L>I trowe certes &thorn;at oure goode man</L>
<L>ha&thorn; &yogh;ou laboured se&thorn;enes &thorn;e night bygan</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;ou were neede to resten hastily</L>
<L N="1300">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he lough ful meryly</L>
<L>And of his owne &thorn;ought he wax al reed</L>
<L>This fayre wyf gan to schake hire heed</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us &yogh;e god wot al quod sche</L>
<L N="1304">Nay cosyn myn it stant nou&yogh;t so wi&thorn; me /</L>
<L>ffor by &thorn;at god &thorn;at &yogh;aff/ me soule and lyf</L>
<L>In all &thorn;e rewme of ffraunce is &thorn;er no wyf</L>
<L>That lasse lust ha&thorn; to &thorn;at sory pley</L>
<L N="1308">ffor I may synge allas and welawey</L>
<L>&thorn;at I was born but to no wight quod sche</L>
<L>Dar I nou&yogh;t telle how it stant wi&thorn; me</L>
<L>Wherfore I &thorn;enke out of &thorn;is lond to wende</L>
<L N="1312">Or elles of myself to make an ende /</L>
<L>So ful am I of drede and of care<MILESTONE N="206a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This monk bygan vpon &thorn;is wyf to stare</L>
<L>And sayde allas my neece god it forbede</L>
<L N="1316">That &yogh;e for eny sorwe or ony drede</L>
<L>ffordo &yogh;oure self but telle&thorn; for&thorn; &yogh;oure greef</L>
<L>Peraduenture I may in &yogh;our mescheef</L>
<L>Counseile or helpe and &thorn;erfore telle&thorn; me</L>
<L N="1320">All &yogh;oure annoye for it schal be secre</L>
<L>ffor on my portos I make an oth</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer in my lijf for leef ne lo&thorn;</L>
<L>Ne schal I of no counseil &yogh;ou bewreye</L>
<L N="1324">The same a&yogh;ein to &yogh;ou quod sche I seye</L>
<L>By god and by &thorn;is portos I swere</L>
<L>&thorn;ey men wolde me al to peeces tere
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="459"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="172"></L>
<L>Ne schal I neuer for to go in to helle</L>
<L N="1328">Bewreye a word of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e me telle /</L>
<L>Nought for no cosynage ne alliaunce</L>
<L>But verreily for loue and affiaunce</L>
<L>Thus ben &thorn;ey swore and her-vpon y-kiste</L>
<L N="1332">And ilk of hem tolde o&thorn;er what hem liste</L>
<L>Cosyn quod sche if I hadde a space</L>
<L>As I haue non and namely in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>&thorn;anne wolde I telle a legende of my lyf</L>
<L N="1336">What I haue suffred sethens I was a wyf</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; myn housband and &thorn;eigh he be &yogh;our cosyn</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;is monk by god and by seint Martyn</L>
<L>he nys no more cosyn vnto me</L>
<L N="1340">&thorn;an is &thorn;is leef &thorn;at hange&thorn; on &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>I clepe him so by seint Denys in ffraunce</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e more cause of acqueyntaunce</L>
<L>Of &yogh;ou which I haue loued specially</L>
<L N="1344">Abouen all wommen sikerly</L>
<L>This were ynough on my profession</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; &yogh;oure greef lest &thorn;at he come a-doun</L>
<L>And haste&thorn; &yogh;ou and go&thorn; &yogh;oure wey anon</L>
<L N="1348">My deere loue quod sche O daun Iohn</L>
<L>fful leef me were &thorn;is counseil to hyde<MILESTONE N="206b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But out it mot it may no lenger abyde</L>
<L>myn housbond is to me &thorn;e worste man</L>
<L N="1352">&thorn;at euer was si&thorn;enes &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L>But si&thorn;enes I am a wyf it sit nou&yogh;t me</L>
<L>To telle no wight of oure pryuyte</L>
<L>Ney&thorn;er a bedde ne in non o&thorn;er place</L>
<L N="1356">God schilde I scholde telle it for his grace</L>
<L>A wyf ne schal nat seyn of hire housband</L>
<L>But all honour as I can vnderstande</L>
<L>Saue vnto &yogh;ou &thorn;us moche telle I schal</L>
<L N="1360">As help me god he nys nou&yogh;t wor&thorn; at al</L>
<L>In no degre &thorn;e value of a flye</L>
<L>But &yogh;it me greue&thorn; most his nyggardye
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="460"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="173"></L>
<L>And wel &yogh;e woot &thorn;at wommen naturelly</L>
<L N="1364">Desyren &thorn;inges seuen as wel as I</L>
<L>&thorn;ey wolden &thorn;at here housbandes scholde be</L>
<L>hardy and wys riche and &thorn;er-to fre</L>
<L>And buxum to his wyf and freissch a bedde</L>
<L N="1368">But by &thorn;at ilke lord &thorn;at for vs bledde</L>
<L>ffor his honour my selue to arraye</L>
<L>A sonday next I moste paye</L>
<L>An hundred ffrankes or elles am I lorn</L>
<L N="1372">&YOGH;et were me leuer &thorn;at I were vnborn</L>
<L>&thorn;enne me were don a sclaunder or vilenye</L>
<L>And if myn housbande eeke might aspye</L>
<L>I nere but lost and &thorn;erfore I &yogh;ou preye</L>
<L N="1376">lene me &thorn;is somme and elles mot I deye</L>
<L>Daun Iohn I say lene me &thorn;ese hundred frankes</L>
<L>Par de I wol not fayle &thorn;e my &thorn;ankes</L>
<L>If &thorn;at &yogh;ou luste to do &thorn;at I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L N="1380">ffor at a certein day I wole &yogh;ou pay</L>
<L>And do to &yogh;ou what plesaunce and seruise</L>
<L>That I may do right as &yogh;ou lust deuyse</L>
<L>And but I do god take on me vengaunce</L>
<L N="1384">As foule as hadde genylon of ffraunce</L>
<L>This gentil monk answerde in &thorn;is manere<MILESTONE N="207a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now trewely myn owen lady deere</L>
<L>I haue quod he on &yogh;ou so gret a rou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1388">That I &yogh;ou swere and plighte &yogh;ou my trou&thorn;e</L>
<L>That whan &yogh;oure housbonde is to fflaundres fare</L>
<L>I wol delyuer &yogh;ou out of &thorn;is worldes care /</L>
<L>ffor I wol bringen &yogh;ou an hundred frankes</L>
<L N="1392">And wi&thorn; &thorn;at he caught hir by &thorn;e schankes</L>
<L>And hire enbraced harde and kissed ofte</L>
<L>Go&thorn; now &yogh;oure weye quod he al stille and softe</L>
<L>And let vs dyne as sone as euer &yogh;e may</L>
<L N="1396">ffor by my chilyndre it is prime of &thorn;e day</L>
<L>Go&thorn; now and be&thorn; as trewe as I schal be /</L>
<L>Now elles god forbede sire quod sche
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="461"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="174"></L>
<L>And for&thorn; sche go&thorn; as gelous as a pye</L>
<L N="1400">And bad &thorn;e cokes &thorn;at &thorn;ey schulde hem hye</L>
<L>So &thorn;at men mighte dyne and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>vp to hir housbonde is &thorn;is wyf y-gon</L>
<L>And knokke&thorn; at his countour boldely</L>
<L N="1404">Quy la quod he peter it am I</L>
<L>Quo&thorn; sche what how longe wol &yogh;e faste /</L>
<L>how longe tyme wol &yogh;e rekne and caste</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure sommes &yogh;oure bokes and &yogh;oure &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="1408">&thorn;e deuyl haue part on all suche rekenynges</L>
<L>&YOGH;e han ynough parde of goddes sonde</L>
<L>Come doun to day and lete &yogh;oure bagge stonde</L>
<L>Ne be &yogh;e nought aschamed &thorn;at Daun Iohn</L>
<L N="1412">Schal fastyng al &thorn;is day elenge gon</L>
<L>What lete vs heere masse go we dyne</L>
<L>Wyf quod &thorn;is man ful lytel canstow dyuyne</L>
<L>The curious busynesse &thorn;at we haue</L>
<L N="1416">ffor of vs chapmen so god me saue</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at lord &thorn;at called is seint yue</L>
<L>Skarsly amonges twelue tweye schuln &thorn;riue</L>
<L>Continuelly lastyng vnto oure age</L>
<L N="1420">We may wel make chere and good visage</L>
<L>And dryue for&thorn; &thorn;e world as it may be<MILESTONE N="207b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And kepen oure estate in priuite</L>
<L>Til we be deed or elles &thorn;at we pleye</L>
<L N="1424">A pylgrymage or gon out of &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore haue I gret necessite</L>
<L>vpon &thorn;is queynte worlde to auyse me</L>
<L>ffor euermore we mote stande in drede</L>
<L N="1428">Of happe and fortune in oure chapmanhede</L>
<L>To fflaundres wol I go to morne at day</L>
<L>And come a&yogh;ein as sone as euer I may</L>
<L>ffor which my deere wyff I &thorn;e beseke</L>
<L N="1432">As be to euery wight buxom and meke</L>
<L>And for to kepe oure good be curious</L>
<L>And honestly gouerne wel oure hous
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="462"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="175"></L>
<L>&thorn;ou hast ynough in euery maner wyse</L>
<L N="1436">That to a thrifty housbonde may suffise</L>
<L>The lakke&thorn; non array ne no vitayle</L>
<L>Of Siluer in &thorn;i purs &thorn;ou mayst nou&yogh;t fayle</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;at word his countour dore he schette</L>
<L N="1440">And doun he go&thorn; no lenger nolde he lette</L>
<L>And hastyly a masse was &thorn;er sayde</L>
<L>And speedly &thorn;e tables were layde</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e dyner faste &thorn;ey hem speede</L>
<L N="1444">And richely &thorn;is monk &thorn;e Chapman fedde</L>
<L>And after dyner daun Iohn soburly</L>
<L>This Chapman took a part al pryuyly</L>
<L>he seyde him &thorn;us cosyn it stande&thorn; so</L>
<L N="1448">&thorn;at wel I see to Bruges wolle &yogh;e go</L>
<L>God and seint austyn spede &yogh;ou and gyde</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ou Cosyn wysly &thorn;at &yogh;e ryde</L>
<L>Gouerne&thorn; &yogh;ou also of &yogh;oure dyete</L>
<L N="1452">And temperally and namely in &thorn;is hete</L>
<L>Bytwixe vs tuo neede&thorn; no straunge fare</L>
<L>ffare wel cosyn god schilde &yogh;ou fro care</L>
<L>If eny &thorn;ing &thorn;er be by day or by night</L>
<L N="1456">If it ligge in my power and my might</L>
<L>That &yogh;e me wol comaunde in eny wyse<MILESTONE N="208a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It schal be doon right as &yogh;e wil deuyse</L>
<L>O &thorn;ing er &thorn;at &yogh;e gon if &thorn;at it may be</L>
<L N="1460">I wolde preye &yogh;ou for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L>An hundred frankes for a wyke or tweye</L>
<L>ffor certeyn bestes &thorn;at I moste beye</L>
<L>To store with a place &thorn;at is owres</L>
<L N="1464">God helpe me I wolde &thorn;at it were &yogh;owres</L>
<L>I schal nought fayle suerly of my day</L>
<L>Nought for a &thorn;ousand frankes a myle way</L>
<L>But lete &thorn;is &thorn;ing be secre I &yogh;ou preye</L>
<L N="1468">&YOGH;e schulle be payed wher &thorn;at I lyue or deye</L>
<L>And fare now wel myn owen cosyn dere</L>
<L>Graunt mercy of &yogh;oure cost and of &yogh;oure chere
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="463"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="176"></L>
<L>This noble marchaunt gentilly anon</L>
<L N="1472">Answerde and sayde O Cosyn daun Iohn</L>
<L>Now sikerly &thorn;is is a smal requeste</L>
<L>My gold is &yogh;oures whan &thorn;at euer &yogh;ou leste</L>
<L>And nought oonly my gold but my chaffare</L>
<L N="1476">Tak what &yogh;ou leste god schilde &thorn;at &yogh;e spare</L>
<L>But o &thorn;ing is &yogh;e knowe it wel ynough</L>
<L>Of chapmen &thorn;at here monee is here plough</L>
<L>We may creaunce whiles we haue a name /</L>
<L N="1480">But goldles for to be it is no game</L>
<L>Pay it a&yogh;ein whan it li&thorn; in &yogh;our ese</L>
<L>After my might ful fayn wolde l &yogh;ou plese</L>
<L>&thorn;ise hundred frankes he fette for&thorn; anon</L>
<L N="1484">And pryuyly he took hit to daun Iohn</L>
<L>No wight in al &thorn;is world wist of &thorn;is lone</L>
<L>Sauyng &thorn;is marchaunt and daun Iohn allone</L>
<L>&thorn;ey dranken and romed out to pleye</L>
<L N="1488">Til &thorn;at daun Iohn ryde&thorn; to his abbeye</L>
<L>&thorn;e morne came and for&thorn; &thorn;is marchaunt ryde&thorn;</L>
<L>To fflaundres ward his prentys wel him gyde&thorn;</L>
<L>Til he cam in to Bruges meryly</L>
<L N="1492">Now go&thorn; &thorn;is marchaunt faste and bysyly</L>
<L>Aboute his neede and bye&thorn; and creaunce&thorn;<MILESTONE N="208b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he ney&thorn;er pleye&thorn; at &thorn;e dys ne daunce&thorn;</L>
<L>But as a marchand schortly for to telle</L>
<L N="1496">he leet his wyf and &thorn;er I lete him dwelle</L>
<L>&thorn;e sonday next &thorn;e marchaunt was agon</L>
<L>To seint Denys I-comen is Daun Iohn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; croune and berde freissch and newe schaue</L>
<L N="1500">In al &thorn;e hous &thorn;er nas so lite a knaue</L>
<L>Ne no wight elles &thorn;at he nas fayn</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at my lord doun Iohn was come agayn</L>
<L>And schortly to here poynt for to gon</L>
<L N="1504">&thorn;is fayre wyf acorde&thorn; to daun Iohn</L>
<L>And for &thorn;is hundred ffrankes he schulde al night</L>
<L>haue hire in his armes bolt vpright
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="464"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="177"></L>
<L>And &thorn;is acorde parfourmed was in dede</L>
<L N="1508">In myr&thorn;e al night / a busy lyf &thorn;ey lede</L>
<L>Til it was day &thorn;at daun Iohn went his way</L>
<L>And bade &thorn;e meyne far wel haue good day</L>
<L>ffor non of hem ne no wight in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L N="1512">ha&thorn; of daun Iohn right non suspecioun</L>
<L>and for&thorn; he ryde&thorn; home to his abbay</L>
<L>Or wher him luste no more of him I say</L>
<L>This marchaunt whan &thorn;at ended was &thorn;e ffayre</L>
<L N="1516">To seint Denys he gan for to repayre</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his wyf he make&thorn; feste and chere</L>
<L>And telle&thorn; hire &thorn;at chaffare is so deere</L>
<L>&thorn;at needes moste he make a Cheuesaunce</L>
<L N="1520">ffor he was bounden in a reconysaunce</L>
<L>To paye xx &thorn;ousand scheldes anon</L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;is marchaunt is y-wont to gon</L>
<L>To borwe of certein frendes &thorn;at he hadde</L>
<L N="1524">A certeyn frankes and some wi&thorn; him he ladde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at he was come in to &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>ffor gret chierte and gret/ affeccioun</L>
<L>vnto daun Iohn he ferst him go&thorn; to pleye</L>
<L N="1528">Nought for to borwe of him no moneye</L>
<L>But for to wite and se of his welfare<MILESTONE N="209a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And for to tellen him of his chaffare</L>
<L>As frendes don when &thorn;ey ben mette in feere</L>
<L N="1532">Daun Iohn him make&thorn; feste and mery cheere</L>
<L>And he him tolde a&yogh;ein ful specially</L>
<L>how he hadde brought ful wel and graciously</L>
<L>&thorn;anked be god al hool his marchaundise</L>
<L N="1536">Saue &thorn;at he moste in all maner wyse</L>
<L>Maken a cheuysance as for his beste</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne he schulde be in ioye and reste</L>
<L>Daun Iohn answerde certes I am fayn</L>
<L N="1540">&thorn;at &yogh;e in hele be come home agayn</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at I were riche as haue I blisse</L>
<L>Of twenty &thorn;ousand scheldes scholde &yogh;e nou&yogh;t misse
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="465"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="178"></L>
<L>ffor &yogh;e so kyndely &thorn;is o&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="1544">Lente me golde as I can and may</L>
<L>I &thorn;anke &yogh;ou by god and by seint Iame</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles I took vnto oure dame</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure wyf at home &thorn;e same gold a&yogh;ain</L>
<L N="1548">vpon &yogh;oure benche sche wot it wel certain</L>
<L>By certein toknes &thorn;at I can hire telle /</L>
<L>Now by &yogh;oure leue I may no lenger dwelle</L>
<L>Oure abbot wol out of &thorn;is toun anon</L>
<L N="1552">And in his companye mot I gon</L>
<L>Gret wel oure dame myn owen nece swete</L>
<L>And fare wel dere cosyn til we mete</L>
<L>This marchaunt wi&thorn; &thorn;at was ful war and wys</L>
<L N="1556">Creaunsed ha&thorn; and eek payed in Parys</L>
<L>To certein lumbardes redy in here hand</L>
<L>&thorn;is somme of gold and gat of hem &thorn;e band</L>
<L>And home he go&thorn; mery as popyngay</L>
<L N="1560">ffor wel he knew he stood in such aray</L>
<L>&thorn;at needes moste he wynne in such a viage</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend frankes abouen al his costage</L>
<L>his wyf ful redy mette him atte gate</L>
<L N="1564">As sche was wont of old vsage algate</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at night in mir&thorn;e &thorn;ey besette /<MILESTONE N="209b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor he was riche and clerly out of dette</L>
<L>Whan it was day &thorn;is marchant gan enbrace /</L>
<L N="1568">his wyf al newe and kissed hire on hire face</L>
<L>And vp he go&thorn; and make&thorn; it wonder tough</L>
<L>No more quod sche by god &yogh;e haue ynough</L>
<L>And wantounly a&yogh;ein wi&thorn; him sche pleyde</L>
<L N="1572">Tille atte laste &thorn;at &thorn;is marchant seyde</L>
<L>By god quod he I am a litel wro&thorn;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;ou my wyf &thorn;ough it be me loth</L>
<L>And wote &yogh;e why by god as &thorn;at I gesse</L>
<L N="1576">ffor ye haue made a maner straungenesse</L>
<L>Bytwixen me and my cosyn daun Iohn</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schulde haue warned me er I hadde gon
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="466"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="179"></L>
<L>&thorn;at he hadde &yogh;ou an hundred frankes payed</L>
<L N="1580">By redy tokne and he him held yuel payed</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at I to him spak of cheuysaunce</L>
<L>Me semed so as by his contynaunce</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles by god and heuen king</L>
<L N="1584">I &thorn;oughte nought to axe of him no &thorn;ing</L>
<L>I pray &thorn;e wyf ne do no more so</L>
<L>Telle me alway er &thorn;at I fro &thorn;e go</L>
<L>If eny dettour ha&thorn; in myn absence</L>
<L N="1588">I-payed &thorn;e leste &thorn;urgh &thorn;in necligence</L>
<L>I might him axe a &thorn;ing &thorn;at he ha&thorn; payed</L>
<L>&thorn;is was nas nough affered ne affrayed</L>
<L>But boldely sche seyde and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L N="1592">Mary I diffye &thorn;at false monk daun Iohn</L>
<L>I kepe nought of his tokenes neuer a deel</L>
<L>he tok me certein gold &thorn;is wot I wel</L>
<L>What euele &thorn;edam on his monkes snowte /</L>
<L N="1596">ffor god it wot I wende wi&thorn;outen doute /</L>
<L>&thorn;at he hadde &yogh;oue it me by cause of &yogh;ou</L>
<L>To do &thorn;er wi&thorn; myn honour and my prow</L>
<L>ffor cosynage and eek for bele chere</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ha&thorn; had fulofte tyme heere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Skip a leaf which is headed</I> Thopas.]</NOTE></L>
<L>But se&thorn;ins I see I stonde in such disioynt<MILESTONE N="211a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I wol answere &yogh;ou schortly to &thorn;is poynt</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue mo slakker dettours &thorn;en am I</L>
<L N="1604">ffor I wol paye &yogh;ow wel and redily</L>
<L>ffro day to day and if so be I fayle</L>
<L>I am &yogh;our wyf score it vpon my tayle</L>
<L>And I schal paye as sone as euer I may</L>
<L N="1608">ffor by my trou&thorn;e I haue on myn array</L>
<L>And nought on waste bestowed euery del</L>
<L>And for I haue bestowed it so wel</L>
<L>To &yogh;oure honour for goddes sake I say</L>
<L N="1612">As be nought wro&thorn; but lete vs laughe and play</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schuln my ioly body haue to wedde /</L>
<L>By god I nyl nought paye &yogh;ou but a bedde
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="467"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="180"></L>
<L>ffor&yogh;iue it me myn owen spouse deere /</L>
<L N="1616">Turne hiderward and make&thorn; bettre cheere</L>
<L>This marchaunt seyh &thorn;er was no remedye</L>
<L>And for to chyde it nere but folye /</L>
<L>Se&thorn;ins &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ing may nought amended be</L>
<L N="1620">Now wyf he sayde and I for&yogh;iue it &thorn;e</L>
<L>But by &thorn;in lyf ne be no more so large</L>
<L>kepe bet my good &thorn;is &yogh;iue I &thorn;e in charge /</L>
<L>&thorn;us ende&thorn; now my tale and god vs sende</L>
<L N="1624">Toylyng ynough vnto oure lyues ende</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e schipmannes tale</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="468">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="181">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WEl seyde by corpus dominus</L>
<L>Now lange mote &thorn;ou sayle by &thorn;e coste</L>
<L>Sire gentil mayster gentil marynere /</L>
<L N="1628">God &yogh;iue &thorn;e monk a &thorn;ousand last quade &yogh;ere /</L>
<L>A ha felawes be&thorn; war of such a Iape /</L>
<L>&thorn;e monk putte in &thorn;e mannes hood an ape /</L>
<L>And in his wyues eek by seint austyn</L>
<L N="1632">Drawe&thorn; no monkes more in to &yogh;oure In</L>
<L>But now passe ouer and let vs seke aboute</L>
<L>Who schal now telle ferst of al &thorn;is route</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er tale and wi&thorn; &thorn;at word he sayde</L>
<L>As curteysly as it hadde ben a mayde<MILESTONE N="211b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My lady prioresse by &yogh;our leue</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I wiste I schulde &yogh;ou nought greue /</L>
<L>I wolde deme &thorn;at &yogh;e telle schulde</L>
<L N="1640">A tale next if so were &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde</L>
<L>Now wole &yogh;e fouche sauf my lady deere /</L>
<L>Gladly quo&thorn; sche and sayde in &thorn;is manere
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000497.tif" N="469"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="182">
<HEAD>Here begynneth &thorn;e tale of Alma redemptoris &thorn;e prioresses Tale. <NOTE PLACE="head">[No gaps between the stanzas.]</NOTE>
</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH><Q>&para; Domine dominus noster</Q></EPIGRAPH>
<DIV3 TYPE="prologe"><HEAD>&para; Prologe</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O lord oure lord &thorn;in name how merueilous</L>
<L>Is in &thorn;is large word y-spredde quod she</L>
<L>ffor nought only &thorn;yn laud precious</L>
<L N="1646">Parfourned is by men of dignite</L>
<L>But by &thorn;e mouth of children &thorn;in bounte</L>
<L>Parformed is for on oure brest soukynge</L>
<L N="1649">Som tyme schewen &thorn;ey &thorn;in heryynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wherfore in laude as I can best or may</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e and of &thorn;e white lyly flour</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at &thorn;e bar and is a mayde alwey</L>
<L N="1653">To telle a story I wol don my labour</L>
<L>Nought &thorn;at I may encrece hire honour</L>
<L>ffor sche hireself is honour and &thorn;erto roote /</L>
<L N="1656">Of bounte next hire sone of soules boote</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O mooder mayde O mayde moder fre</L>
<L>O busch vnbrent brennyng in moyses sight</L>
<L>That rauysche&thorn; doun fro &thorn;e deytele</L>
<L N="1660">&thorn;urgh &thorn;in humbles &thorn;e gost &thorn;at in &thorn;e alight</L>
<L>Of whos vertu whan he in &thorn;in herte alight</L>
<L>Conceyued was &thorn;e fadres sapience</L>
<L N="1663">Help me to telle it in &thorn;in reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lady &thorn;in bounte and &thorn;in magnificence</L>
<L>&thorn;in vertu and &thorn;in gret humilite</L>
<L>Ther may no tonge expresse in no science</L>
<L N="1667">ffor som tyme lady er men preye to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;ou gost biforn and &thorn;in benignite</L>
<L>And getest vs to light &thorn;urgh &thorn;in prayere</L>
<L>To gyden vs vnto &thorn;in sone so clere<MILESTONE N="212a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="470"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>My connyng is to wayk o blisful queene</L>
<L>ffor to declare &thorn;in grete wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>That I ne may &thorn;e weighte nought susteene /</L>
<L N="1674">But as a childe of xij monthe elde or lesse</L>
<L>That can vnne&thorn;es any word expresse /</L>
<L>Right so fare I and &thorn;erfore I &yogh;ou preye</L>
<L N="1677">Gyde&thorn; my song &thorn;at I schal of &yogh;ou seye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was in a cite in a gret cite</L>
<L>Amonges cristen folk and Iewerye</L>
<L>Susteyned by a lord of &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L N="1681">ffor foule vsure and lucre of vilanye</L>
<L>hatful to crist and to his companye</L>
<L>And &thorn;urgh &thorn;e strete men mighte ryde or wende</L>
<L N="1684">ffor it was fre and open at euery ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A lytel scole of cristen folk &thorn;er stood</L>
<L>Doun at &thorn;e fur&thorn;er ende in which &thorn;er were</L>
<L>Children an heepe y-come of cristes blood</L>
<L N="1688">That lered in &thorn;at scole &yogh;ere by &yogh;eere</L>
<L>Such maner doctrine as men vsed &thorn;ere</L>
<L>This is to say to syngen and to rede</L>
<L N="1691">As smale children don in here childhede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Among &thorn;is children was a wydewes sone</L>
<L>A litel clergoun vij &yogh;er of age</L>
<L>That day by day to scole was his wone /</L>
<L N="1695">And eek also wher he saugh the ymage /</L>
<L>Of cristes mooder hadde he in vsage</L>
<L>As him was taught to knele a doun and seye</L>
<L N="1698">his aue marie as he go&thorn; by &thorn;e weye
<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="471"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is wydewe hire litel child y-tau&yogh;t</L>
<L>Oure blisful lady cristes mooder deere /</L>
<L>To worschipe ay and he forgat it nought</L>
<L N="1702">ffor sely child wol alday sone lere</L>
<L>But ay whan I remembre me on &thorn;is matere</L>
<L>Seynt Nicholas stant euer in my presence</L>
<L N="1705">ffor he so &yogh;onge to crist dede reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This child his litel book lernynge<MILESTONE N="212b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As he sat in &thorn;e scole at his primere</L>
<L>he alma redemptoris herde synge /</L>
<L N="1709">As children lerned here antiphoner</L>
<L>And as he durste he drough him ner and neer</L>
<L>And herkned ay &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e noote /</L>
<L N="1712">Til he &thorn;e firste vers cou&thorn;e al by roote /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou&yogh;t wiste he what &thorn;e latyn was to say</L>
<L>ffor he so &yogh;ong and tender was of age /</L>
<L>But on a day his felawe gan he preye</L>
<L N="1716">To expounen him &thorn;is song in his langage /</L>
<L>Or tellen him why &thorn;is song was in vsage /</L>
<L>This preyde he him to construe and declare /</L>
<L N="1719">fful ofte tyme vpon his knees bare /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>his felawe which &thorn;at elder was &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Answerde him &thorn;us &thorn;is song I haue herd say</L>
<L>Was maked of oure blisful lady fre</L>
<L N="1723">hire to salue and eeke hire for to pray</L>
<L>To ben oure helpe and socour whan we deye</L>
<L>I can no more expounde in &thorn;is matiere</L>
<L N="1726">I lerne song I can but smale gramere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And is &thorn;is song ymade in reuerence</L>
<L>Of cristes mooder sayde &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Now certes I wol don my diligence</L>
<L N="1730">To konne it er Cristemas be went
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="472"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="185"></L>
<L>&thorn;ough &thorn;at I for my prymer schal be schent</L>
<L>And schal [be] beten &thorn;ries in an houre</L>
<L N="1733">I wol it konne oure lady to honoure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his felawe taught him homward pryuyly</L>
<L>ffro day to day til he cou&thorn;e it by roote</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne he sang it wel and boldely</L>
<L N="1737">ffro word to word acordyng to &thorn;e note /</L>
<L>&thorn;ries on a day it passe&thorn; &thorn;urgh his &thorn;rote /</L>
<L>To scoleward and homward whan he went</L>
<L N="1740">On cristes moder sette was his entent/</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As I haue sayde &thorn;urghout &thorn;e Iewerie</L>
<L>This litel childe as he came to and fro<MILESTONE N="213a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>fful meryly &thorn;en wolde he synge and crye /</L>
<L N="1744">On alma redemptoris euermo</L>
<L>The swetnes ha&thorn; his herte perced so</L>
<L>Of cristes mooder &thorn;at to hure to preye</L>
<L N="1747">He can nought stynte of syngynge by &thorn;e weye /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oure firste foo &thorn;e serpent Sathanas</L>
<L>That ha&thorn; in Iewes his waspes neste</L>
<L>vp swalle and sayde O Ebrayke poeple allas /</L>
<L N="1751">Is &thorn;is a &thorn;ing to &yogh;ou &thorn;at is honeste /</L>
<L>&thorn;at suche a boy schal walken as him leste /</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure despite and syngen of such sentence</L>
<L N="1754">Which is a&yogh;ein oure lawes reuerence /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffro &thorn;ennes forth &thorn;e Iewes han conspired</L>
<L>This Innocent out of &thorn;is world to chace</L>
<L>In homicidie &thorn;er-to han &thorn;ey hyred</L>
<L N="1758">&thorn;at in an aley had a pryue place</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e childe gan forby for to pace</L>
<L>&thorn;is cursed Iew him hente and heeld faste</L>
<L N="1761">And cutte his &thorn;rote and in a putte him caste /
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="473"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I say &thorn;at in a wardrobe &thorn;ey him drewe /</L>
<L>Wher as &thorn;ise Iewes purgen entraille</L>
<L>O cursed folk of heroudes al newe /</L>
<L N="1765">What may &yogh;oure euyl entent &yogh;ou auayle /</L>
<L>Mordre wole out certain it wol nought fayle</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;ere honour of god schulde sprede</L>
<L N="1768">&thorn;e blood out crye&thorn; on &yogh;our cursed dede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O martyr sonded to virginite</L>
<L>Now maystow syngen folwyng euer in oon</L>
<L>The white lambe celestial quod he /</L>
<L N="1772">Of which &thorn;e grete euaungelist seint Iohn</L>
<L>In Pathmos wrot which sei&thorn; &thorn;ey &thorn;at gon</L>
<L>Byforn &thorn;is lambe and synge a song al newe</L>
<L N="1775">&thorn;at neuer fleisschly wommen &thorn;ey knewe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;is pore wydewe wayte&thorn; al &thorn;at night</L>
<L>After &thorn;is litel childe but hom cam he nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor whom as sone as it was dayes light<MILESTONE N="213b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1779">Wi&thorn; face pale for drede and busy &thorn;ought</L>
<L>Sche ha&thorn; at scole and elles wher him sought</L>
<L>Til fynally sche gan so fer aspye</L>
<L N="1782">&thorn;at he was seyn last in &thorn;e Iewerye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; With moodres pyte in hire brest enclosed</L>
<L>Sche go&thorn; as &thorn;ough sche were half out of mynde /</L>
<L>To euery place where sche ha&thorn; supposed</L>
<L N="1786">By lyklyhede hire childe for to fynde</L>
<L>And euer on cristes moder meke and kynde</L>
<L>Sche cryed and at &thorn;e laste &thorn;us sche wrought</L>
<L N="1789">Among &thorn;e cursed Iewes sche him sought</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche freyne&thorn; and sche preye&thorn; pitously</L>
<L>To euery Iewe &thorn;at dwelt in &thorn;ilke place</L>
<L>To telle hire if hire child went hem by</L>
<L>They sayden nay but ihesus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS ihc]</NOTE> of his grace
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="474"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="187"></L>
<L>&YOGH;af in hire &thorn;ought wi&thorn;-in a litel space</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;at place after hire sone sche cryede</L>
<L N="1796">&thorn;er he was caste in a putte besyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O grete lord &thorn;at parformed &thorn;in laude</L>
<L>By mou&thorn; of Innocence lo here &thorn;y might</L>
<L>This gemme of chastite &thorn;is Emeraude</L>
<L N="1800">And eek of martirdome &thorn;e ruby bright</L>
<L>&thorn;er he wi&thorn; &thorn;rote y-korue lay vpright</L>
<L>he alma redemptoris gan to synge</L>
<L N="1803">So loude &thorn;at al &thorn;e place gan to rynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The cristen folk &thorn;at &thorn;urgh &thorn;e strete went</L>
<L>In comen for to wondren on &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And hastely &thorn;ey for &thorn;e prouost sent</L>
<L N="1807">he came anon wi&thorn;outen eny taryyng</L>
<L>And herie&thorn; crist &thorn;at is of heuen king</L>
<L>And eek his mooder honour of mankynde</L>
<L N="1810">And after &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewes let he bynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This childe wi&thorn; pitous lamentacion</L>
<L>vp taken syngyng his song alway</L>
<L>And with honour and gret procession /</L>
<L>They carien him to &thorn;e next abbay<MILESTONE N="214a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>his moder swownyng by &thorn;e bere lay</L>
<L>vnne&thorn;es mighte &thorn;e poeple &thorn;at was &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1817">This newe rachel bringe fro his bere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; torment and with schameful de&thorn; ilkon</L>
<L>This prouost do&thorn; &thorn;is Iewes for to sterue</L>
<L>That of &thorn;is moerdre wiste and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L N="1821">he nolde non such cursednesse obserue /</L>
<L>Euel schal haue &thorn;at euel wol deserue</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore with wilde hors he dede him drawe</L>
<L N="1824">And after &thorn;at he hynge him by &thorn;e lawe
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="475"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vpon &thorn;is beere ay li&thorn; &thorn;is Innocent</L>
<L>Biforn &thorn;e chief auter whiles masse last</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;e abbot/ wi&thorn; his couent</L>
<L N="1828">hadde spedde him for to burye him als fast</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ey halywater on him cast</L>
<L>&YOGH;it spak &thorn;e child when spreynt was &thorn;e holy water</L>
<L N="1831">And sang O alma redemptoris mater</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This abbot which &thorn;at was an holy man</L>
<L>As monkes ben or elles oughten to<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? to <I>later</I>]</NOTE> be</L>
<L>This &yogh;onge childe to coniure he bigan</L>
<L N="1835">And sayde O deere childe I hailse &thorn;e</L>
<L>By vertu of &thorn;e holy trinite</L>
<L>Telle me what is &thorn;y cause for to synge</L>
<L N="1838">Si&thorn;enes &thorn;at &thorn;y &thorn;rote is kutte at my semynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My &thorn;rote is cutte vnto my nekke bon</L>
<L>Sayde &thorn;is childe and as by way of kynde</L>
<L>I schulde haue deyed &yogh;e long tyme agon</L>
<L N="1842">But ihesu crist as &yogh;e in bookes fynde</L>
<L>Wol &thorn;at his glorie laste and be in mynde</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e worschipe of his moder deere /</L>
<L N="1845">&YOGH;et may I synge O alma lowde and cleere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This welle of mercy crystes mooder swete</L>
<L>I loued alwey as after my konnyng</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at I my lyff schulde lete</L>
<L N="1849">To me sche cam and bad me for to synge</L>
<L>This anteme verraily in my mynde deynge<MILESTONE N="214b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>as &yogh;e haue herd and when &thorn;at I hadde songe</L>
<L N="1852">Me &thorn;ought sche leyde a greyn vpon my tonge /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wherfore I synge and synge moot certein</L>
<L>In honour of &thorn;e blisful martir fre</L>
<L>Til of my tonge of taken is &thorn;e greyn</L>
<L N="1856">And after &thorn;at sayde sche &thorn;us to me
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="476"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="189"></L>
<L>My litel childe now wol I fecche &thorn;e</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;y grein is fro &thorn;y tonge y-take</L>
<L N="1859">Be nought a-gast I wol &thorn;e nought forsake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;is holy monk &thorn;is abbot him mene I</L>
<L>his tunge out caught / and took awey &thorn;e greyn</L>
<L>And he &yogh;af up &thorn;e gost ful softely</L>
<L N="1863">And when &thorn;is abbot / hadde &thorn;is wonder seyn</L>
<L>his salte teeres stryked doun as reyn</L>
<L>And gruff he fell al plat vnto &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L N="1866">And stille he lay as he hadde ben y-bounde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &thorn;e couent eek lay vppon &thorn;e pauyment</L>
<L>Wepyng and herying cristes moder deere</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;ay ryse and for ben went</L>
<L N="1870">And toke awey &thorn;is martir fro his bere /</L>
<L>And in a tombe of marbill stones clere</L>
<L>Enclosen &thorn;ey his litel body swete</L>
<L N="1873">Ther he is now god leue vs for to mete</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O &yogh;onge hewe of lincolle slayn also</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; cursed Iewes as it is notable</L>
<L>ffor it nys but a litel while ago</L>
<L N="1877">Preye eek for vs we synful folk vnstable</L>
<L>That of his mercy god so merciable</L>
<L>On vs his grete mercy multiplye</L>
<L>ffor reuerence of his mooder marie AmeN</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit //
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000505.tif" N="477"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="190">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan seyde was &thorn;is tale euery man</L>
<L>As sober was &thorn;at wonder was to se</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at owre Oste Iape &thorn;o bygan</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne at erst he loked vpon me<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Chaucere</NOTE></L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;us what man art &thorn;ou quod he</L>
<L>Thou lokest as &thorn;ou woldest fynde an hare /<MILESTONE N="215a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1887">ffor euer vpon &thorn;e ground I se &thorn;e stare</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Approche ner and loke meryly</L>
<L>Now ware &yogh;ou sires and let &thorn;is man han place</L>
<L>he in &thorn;e waste is schapen as wel as I</L>
<L N="1891">This were a popet in armes to embrace</L>
<L>ffor any womman smal and fair of face</L>
<L>he seme&thorn; eluyssch by his contynaunce</L>
<L N="1894">ffor vnto no wight do&thorn; he dalyaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Say now somwhat se&thorn;ins o&thorn;er folk han sayd</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale of mer&thorn;e and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L>Oste quod I ne be nought yuel a-payde</L>
<L N="1898">ffor o&thorn;er tale certes can I non</L>
<L>But of a Ryme I lerned longe agon</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at is good quod he schuln we here</L>
<L N="1901">Som deynte &thorn;ing me &thorn;inke&thorn; by his cheere.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000506.tif" N="478"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="191">
<HEAD>&para; Here bygynneth &thorn;e tale of Chaucer of sire Thopas<NOTE PLACE="head">[No gaps between the stanzas in the MS.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ca<SUP>m</SUP> xix<SUP>m</SUP></NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Fytte I.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LEstene&thorn; lordes in good entent</L>
