<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000516.tif" N="488"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="201">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; C<SUP>m</SUP>.xx<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE>Here bygynne&thorn; Chauceres tale of Melibe and his wyf Prudence and his doughter Sapience</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[There are no line-numbers or breaks between the paragraphs in the MS. Tyrwhitt's breaks are kept here to prevent slight differences in the Six Texts throwing out many lines.]</P><P>[<I>Corpus MS, on leaf</I> 217, <I>back.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>[2157] A &YOGH;ong man whilom called Melibe mighty &amp; riche bigate vpon his wyf &thorn;at called was Prudence. a doughter which &thorn;at cleped was Sapience</P>
<P>[2158] &para; vpon a day felle &thorn;at he for his disporte is went in to &thorn;e feeldes him to pleye [2159] his wyf and eek his doughter ha&thorn; he lefte wi&thorn;inne his hous of which &thorn;e dores weren faste schette. [2160] ffoure of his olde foos han it aspyed. and setten ladderes to &thorn;e walles of his hous and by &thorn;e wyndowes ben y-entred [2161] &para; and beeten his wyf and wounded his doughter with fyue mortaille woundes in .v. sondry places. [2162] &thorn;is is to say in hire feet in hire hand. in hire eeres in hire nose in hire mou&thorn; &para; and laften hire for deed and wenten here wey</P>
<P>[2163] &para; When Melibeus retourned was a&yogh;ein in-til his hous and sawe al &thorn;is meschief &para; he y-like a mad man rendyng his clo&thorn;es gan to weepe and crye</P>
<P>[2164] &para; Prudence his wyf as ferfor&thorn; as sche dorste bysought him of his weepyng for to stynte [2165] &para; but nou&yogh;t for-&thorn;y he gan to wepe and crye euer lenger &thorn;e more</P>
<P>[2166] &para; This noble wyf prudence remembred hire on &thorn;e sentence of Ovide in his bok &thorn;at cleped is &thorn;e remedy of loue where he sai&thorn; [2167] he is a fool &thorn;at distourbe&thorn; &thorn;e mooder for to wepe in &thorn;e de&thorn; of hire childe til sche haue wepte hire fille as for a certein tyme [2168] Then schal man don his diligence with amyable wordes hire to comforte and to preye hire of 
<PB REF="00000517.tif" N="489"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="202"> hire wepyng for to stynte [2169] &para; ffor which resoun &thorn;is noble prudence suffred hire housbond for to weepe and crye as for a certeyn space [2170] &para; And when sche saugh hire tyme sche seyde him in &thorn;is wyse &para; Allas my lord quod sche why make &yogh;e &yogh;oure self for to be ylike a fool [2171] ffor so&thorn;e it apertyne&thorn; nou&yogh;t to a wise man to maken such a sorwe [2172] &para; &yogh;oure doughter wi&thorn; &thorn;e grace <MILESTONE N="218a" UNIT="folio">of god schal be warisshed and askape [2173] &para; And alle were it so &thorn;at sche right now were deed; &yogh;e oughte nou&yogh;t as for hire de&thorn; &yogh;oure self to destryue [2174] &para; Senek sai&thorn; &thorn;e wiseman schal nou&yogh;t take to gret discomfort for &thorn;e de&thorn; of his children [2175] but certes he schulde suffre it in pacience as wel as he abyde&thorn; &thorn;e de&thorn; of his owen propre persone</P>
<P>[2176] &para; This Melibeus answerde anon and sayde &para; What man quod he schulde of his wepyng stynte &thorn;at ha&thorn; so gret a cause for to weepe [2177] &para; Ihesus crist oure lord himself wepte for &thorn;e de&thorn; of lazarus his freend [2178] &para; Prudens answerde &para; certes wel I woot a-tempre weepyng is nou&yogh;t defendid vnto him &thorn;at sorwful is among folk in sorwe &para; But it is ra&thorn;er y-graunted him to wepe [2179] &para; The apostel Poule. vnto &thorn;e Romayns write&thorn;. Man schal reioyse wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at maken ioye &para; And weepen wi&thorn; suche folk as wepen [2180] &para; But &thorn;ough a-tempre wepynge be y-graunted Outragous weepyng certes is defended [2181] &para; Mesurable wepyng schulde be considered after &thorn;e lore &thorn;at teche&thorn; vs Senek<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Senek/</NOTE> [2182] &para; Whan &thorn;at &thorn;i freend is deed let nought &thorn;in yen to moyste ben of teeres ne to druye &para; Al &thorn;ough &thorn;e teeres comen of &thorn;in eyen let hem nou&yogh;t fallen [2183] &para; And whan &thorn;ou hast forgon &thorn;i frende I rede &thorn;ou do &thorn;y diligence to gete &thorn;e ano&thorn;er. and &thorn;is is more wiser &thorn;an for to wepe for &thorn;yn freend &thorn;e which &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast lore &para; ffor &thorn;er-in is no boote [2184] &para; And &thorn;erfore if &thorn;ou lust gouerne &thorn;e by Sapience; putte awey sorwe of &yogh;oure herte. [2185] &para; Remembre&thorn; &yogh;ou &thorn;at Ihesus Cyrak / sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ihesus Cyrak/</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="490"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="203"> a man &thorn;at is Ioyous and glad in herte hit him con|serue&thorn; florisching in his age &para; But so&thorn;ly sorwful herte make&thorn; his bones dryue [2186] &para; he sai&thorn; eek &thorn;us &para; &thorn;at sorwe in herte sle&thorn; ful many a man [2187] Sa|lamon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> sei&thorn; &thorn;at right as moughtes in &thorn;e schepes flees annoye&thorn; to &thorn;e clo&thorn;es and &thorn;e smale wormes of &thorn;e trees &para; Right so anoye&thorn; sorwe to &thorn;e herte [2188] &para; Wherfore we ou&yogh;t as wel in &thorn;e de&thorn; of oure children as in &thorn;e losse of oure good haue pacience</P>
<P>[2189] &para; Remembre&thorn; &yogh;ow vpon &thorn;e pacient Iob.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Iob</NOTE> whan he hadde lost his children and his temperel sub|stance / In his body endured and suffred many a greuous temptacion &para; &yogh;et sayde he &thorn;us [2190] &para; Oure lord quod he ha&thorn; &yogh;oue it me &para; Oure lord ha&thorn; byreft it me Right so as oure lord ha&thorn; wolde right so be it don. y-blessed be &thorn;e name of oure lord [2191] &para; To &thorn;ese afore &thorn;inges Melibeus answerde to his wyf dame Prudence / Alle &thorn;ine wordes quod he ben so&thorn;e and &thorn;erto pro|ffitable &para; But trewly myn herte is troubled wi&thorn; &thorn;is sorwe so greuously &thorn;at I not what to done [2192] &para; let calle quod Prudence &thorn;in trewe frendes alle and &thorn;in lynage whiche &thorn;at ben wise Telle hem &thorn;yn [caas] <MILESTONE N="218b" UNIT="folio">and herkne what &thorn;ay say in counseillynge and &yogh;ou gouerneth &thorn;er after here sentence [2193] Salomon sai&thorn; werk alle &thorn;ing by counseil<NOTE PLACE="marg">Salomon</NOTE> and &thorn;ou schalt neuer repente &thorn;e</P>
<P>[2194] &para; Thenne by &thorn;e counseil of his wyf dame Pru|dence; Melibeus let callen a gret congregacion of folk [2195]. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> olde and &yogh;onge and some of his olde enemys reconsiled as by here semblant in to his loue and in to his grace [2196] &para; And &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al &thorn;er come somme of his olde neyghebours and &thorn;at deden him reuerence more for drede &thorn;an for loue as it happe&thorn; ofte [2197] &para; Ther come&thorn; also ful many subtile flaterers and wyse aduocatis lerned in &thorn;e lawe</P>
<P>[2198] And whan &thorn;is folk / togidre assembled were; This Melibeus in sorwful wise schewed hem &thorn;is caas 
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="491"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="204"> [2199] &para; And by &thorn;e manere of &thorn;is speche he bar in his herte a cruel yre redy to don venge|aunce vpon his foos And sodeynly desired &thorn;at &thorn;e werre schulde begynne [2200] &para; But na&thorn;eles &yogh;it asked he here counseil vpon &thorn;is matere [2201] A Surgien by licence and assent of suche as were wyse vp ros vn|to Melibeus and sayde as &yogh;e may heere</P>
<P>[2202] Sire quod he as to vs surgiens aperteyne&thorn; to euery wight &thorn;e beste &thorn;at we can were as we ben wi&thorn;holde &para; And to oure paciences &thorn;at we do no damages [2203] &thorn;erfore it happe&thorn; many tymes and ofte &thorn;at when tuo men haue euerich wounded o&thorn;er O same Surgien hele&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e [2204] &para; Wherfore vnto oure art it nys nou&yogh;t pertynent to norische werre ne parties to supporte [2205] &para; But certes as to &thorn;e warisshyng of &yogh;our doughter be it so &thorn;at sche is perilously wounded; we schulde do so ententyfly busynes fro day to night &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e grace of god sche schal be sound and hool as sone as it is possible [2206] &para; Alle men in &thorn;is same wyse answerden and &thorn;e Phisiciens. saue &thorn;at &thorn;ay sayden a fewe wordes more [2207] &thorn;at right as maladies ben heled by &thorn;e contraries Right so schal men warissche werre by vengaunce [2208] his neyghe|burs fulle of enuye his feynede freendes &thorn;at semed reconsiled his flaterers [2209] maden semblaunt of wepyng enpeyred and engregged meche of his matiere in preysynge gretly Melibeus of might of power of riches and of frendes despysynge &thorn;e power of his aduersaries [2210] and sayden outrely &thorn;at he anon schulde awreken him on his enemys and begynne werre</P>
<P>[2211] &para; Vp ros &thorn;anne an aduoket &thorn;at was wys and sayde by leue and by counseil of o&thorn;ere &thorn;at were wyse &para; And sayde [2212] lordynges the neede for &thorn;e which we ben as|sembled in &thorn;is place is a ful heuy &thorn;ing and an heigh matiere [2213] by cause of &thorn;e wrong and of &thorn;e wikkednesse &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben don and eeke by resoun of &thorn;e grete damage / 
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="492"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="205"> in tyme comynge ben possible to <MILESTONE N="219a" UNIT="folio">falle for &thorn;is same cause [2214] and eek by resoun Of &thorn;e grete richesse and power of &thorn;e parties bo&thorn;e [2215] &para; ffor &thorn;e whiche resouns it were a gret perile for to erren in &thorn;is matiere // [2216] wherfore melibeus &thorn;is is oure sentence we counseile &yogh;ou abouen alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at right anon &thorn;ou do &thorn;i diligence in kepyng of &thorn;i propre persone in suche a wyse &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne wante none aspye ne wacche &thorn;i body for to saue [2217] &para; And after &thorn;at we counseile &thorn;at &thorn;ou sette in &thorn;in hous suffisaunt garnysoun &para; So &thorn;at &thorn;ey may as wel &thorn;y body and &thorn;in hous defende [2218] &para; But certes for to meve werre ne sodeinly for to do vengeance &para; We may nou&yogh;t deme in so litel tyme &thorn;at it were profit|able [2219] wherfore we asken leysir and space to haue deliberacion in &thorn;is cas to deme [2220] for &thorn;e commune prouerbe sai&thorn; &thorn;us. he. &thorn;at sone deme&thorn; sone schal repente [2221] &para; And eek men say &thorn;us &thorn;at &thorn;ilke Iuge is wys &thorn;at sone vnderstande&thorn; a matiere and Iuge&thorn; by leysyr [2222] &para; ffor al be it so &thorn;at alle taryynge be anoyful; algates it nys nou&yogh;t to reproue in &yogh;euyng of Iuggementz ne in vengaunce takynge whanne it is suffisaunt and resonable. [2223] and &thorn;at schewed oure lord ihesus crist by en|sample &para; ffor when &thorn;at &thorn;e womman was taken in aduoutrye was brought in his presens to knowe what schal ben don with hire persone &para; Al be it so &thorn;at he wiste wel himself what &thorn;at he wolde answere; &yogh;it ne wolde he nou&yogh;t answere sodeinly but he wolde haue deliberacion and in &thorn;e grounde he wrot twyes [2224] &para; And by &thorn;is cause we axen deliberacion And we schullen &thorn;anne by &thorn;e grace of god counseile &thorn;e &thorn;inge &thorn;at schal be profitable</P>
<P>[2225] &para; Vp sterte &thorn;enne &thorn;e &yogh;onge folk atones; and &thorn;e moste partye of &thorn;at company haue scorned &thorn;is olde wise man and bygonne to make noyse and sayden [2226] right so &para; as whiles &thorn;at yren is hoot men schulden smyte &para; Right so men schulden wreken here wronges whiles 
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="493"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="206"> &thorn;ay ben freissche and newe &para; And with lowde voys &thorn;ey cryden werre werre</P>
<P>[2227] vp ros &thorn;e on of &thorn;e olde wise and with his hande he made a contynaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ey schulde halden hem stille and &yogh;iuen hem audience [2228] &para; lordynges quod he &thorn;er is ful many a man &thorn;at crie&thorn; werre werre &thorn;at wot ful litel what &thorn;at werre amounte&thorn; [2229] &para; werre at his bygynnyng ha&thorn; so gret an enteryng and so large &para; That euery wight may entre when him like&thorn;. and lightly fynde werre [2230] &para; But certes to what ende &thorn;at schal &thorn;er-of bifalle it nys nou&yogh;t lightly to knowe [2231] &para; whan &thorn;at werre is ones bygonne &thorn;er is ful many a childe vnborne of his moder &thorn;at schal sterue &yogh;ong by cause of &thorn;ilke werre O&thorn;er elles lyue in sorwe and deye in wrecchednesse [2232] &para; And &thorn;erfore er &thorn;at eny werre be bygonne men mosten <MILESTONE N="219b" UNIT="folio">han gret counseil and good deliberacion [2233] &para; And when &thorn;is olde man wende to enforcen his tale by reson wel neih alle at ones bygonne for to ryse for to breken his tale / and beden him fuloften of his wordes for to abregge [2234] &para; ffor so&thorn;ly he &thorn;at preche&thorn; to hem &thorn;at luste nought his wordes ne his sermon hem annoye&thorn; [2235] &para; ffor Ihesus Cirak sai&thorn; &thorn;at musyke in wepynge is<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Ihesus Cirak/</NOTE> annoyous &thorn;ing &thorn;us moche is to sayn as moche annoye&thorn; to speke bifore folk to whiche his speche annoye&thorn;; as it is for to syngen byforn him &thorn;at wepe&thorn; [2236] &para; And when &thorn;is wise man saugh &thorn;at him wantede audience; al schamfast he sette him doun a&yogh;ein. [2237] ffor Salomon sei&thorn;. &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Salomon</NOTE> as &thorn;ou mayst haue non audience; enforce &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to speke [2238] &para; I se wel quod &thorn;is wyse man &thorn;at &thorn;e commune prouerbe is so&thorn; &thorn;at good counseil wante&thorn;. whan it is most nede</P>
<P>[2239] &para; &YOGH;it hadde &thorn;is Melibeus in his counseille many folk &thorn;at priuely in his eere counseled him certein &thorn;ing. and counseilled him &thorn;e contrary in general audience</P>
<P>[2240] &para; When Melibeus hadde herd &thorn;at &thorn;e gretteste 
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="494"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="207"> party of his counseil were acorded &thorn;at he schulde make werre; anon he consentede to here counseilyng &para; and fully affermed to here sentence [2241] &para; Thanne dame Prudence whan &thorn;at sche saugh how &thorn;at hire housbonde schope him for to wreke him on his foes and to begynne werre &para; Sche in ful humble wyse whan sche saugh hire tyme / seyde him in &thorn;ise wordes [2242] &para; My lord quod sche I &yogh;ou beseche as hertely as I dar and can &para; Ne haste &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t to faste &para; And afore alle guerdouns &yogh;if me audience [2243] &para; ffor Pieres Alphons. sai&thorn; &para; O who so do&thorn; to &thorn;e good o&thorn;er harme haste &thorn;e nought to quyten hit &para; ffor in &thorn;is wise &thorn;y frend wole abyde and &thorn;in enemy schal &thorn;e lengere lyue in drede [2244] &para; The prouerbe sai&thorn; &thorn;at he haste&thorn; him wel &thorn;at wisly can abyde &para; and in wicked haste is no profyte</P>
<P>[2245] &para; This mely be answerde to his wijf &para; &para; Prudence I purpose nought quod he to werke by &thorn;y counseille for many causes and resons &para; ffor certes euery wight wolde halde me &thorn;enne a fool [2246] &para; This is for to say &para; If I for &thorn;y counseillyng wolde chaunge &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben ordeynt and affermed by so many wyse [2247] &para; Sec|oundly I say &thorn;at alle wommen ben &thorn;ikke and none goode of hem alle ffor of a &thorn;ousend men sai&thorn; Salomon I fand a good man But certes of alle wommen fond I neuer good womman [2248] &para; And also certes if I gouerned me by &thorn;y counseil it schulde seme &thorn;at I hadde &yogh;oue to &thorn;e ouer me &thorn;e maystrie &para; and god forbede &thorn;at it so were [2249] &para; ffor Ihesus Cyrak <MILESTONE N="220a" UNIT="folio">sai&thorn;. &thorn;at if &thorn;in wijf haue maistrie; sche is contrarious to hire housebonde [2250] &para; and Salomon sai&thorn; &para; Neuer in &thorn;y lyf to &thorn;y wyf ne to &thorn;y childe ne to &thorn;y freende ne &yogh;iue no power ouer &thorn;i self &para; ffor bettre it were &thorn;at &thorn;in children asken of &thorn;y persone &thorn;inges &thorn;at hem neede&thorn; &para; &thorn;en &thorn;ou [be] &thorn;i self in &thorn;e handes of &thorn;in children [2251] &para; And also if I wole wirche by &thorn;i counseylyng; certes my counseille moste som tyme be secree til it were tyme &thorn;at it moste be 
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="495"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="208"> knowe and &thorn;is ne may nought be doo [2252. For it is written, '&thorn;e Iangelry of wommen can huyde &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ey wot nou&yogh;t' [2253] Furthermore, the philosopher saith, 'in wikked counseil, wommen venquysshe&thorn; men;' and for these reasons I ought not to make use of thy counsel. (<I>See Prudence's answers to Reasons</I> 4 <I>&amp;</I> 5, <I>below</I>.)]</P>
<P>[2254] &para; When dame Prudence ful debonerly and wi&thorn; alle pacience hadde herde alle &thorn;at hire housbonde liked for to say: Then asked sche of him licence for to speke and sayde in &thorn;is wise [2255] &para; My lord quod sche. as to &yogh;oure ferste resoun it may lightly ben answerde &para; ffor I say &thorn;at it nys foly to chaunge counseille when &thorn;e &thorn;ing is chaunged O&thorn;er elles when &thorn;e &thorn;ing seme&thorn; o&thorn;er weyes &thorn;enne it seme&thorn; aforn [2256] &para; And more ouer I say &thorn;ay &thorn;at &yogh;e haue sworn and behight to parfourme &yogh;oure emprise [<I>et tu la laissoies a faire</I> (Le M&eacute;nagier de Paris, i. 193)] by iuste cause; men schulde nou&yogh;t seyn &thorn;erfore &thorn;at &yogh;e were a lyere ne forsworn [2257] &para; ffor &thorn;e book sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e wise man make&thorn; no lesynge when he torne&thorn; his corage / to &thorn;e bettre [2258] &para; And if it be so &thorn;at &yogh;oure emprise be establissht and ordeyned by gret multitude of folk &para; &yogh;et &thorn;ar &thorn;e nought acomplyse &thorn;ilke ordynaunce but &yogh;ou like [2259] &para; ffor &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of &thorn;inges and for profite ben ra&thorn;er founde. in fewe folk &thorn;at ben wise / and fulle of reson &thorn;en by gret multitude of folk &thorn;er euery man crye&thorn; and clatere&thorn; when him like&thorn; &para; so&thorn;ly such multitude nys nought honeste [2260] and as to &thorn;e secounde reson wher as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at alle wommen ben wikke; Saue &yogh;oure grace ffor certes &yogh;e despyse&thorn; alle wommen in &thorn;is wise. and he &thorn;at alle despise&thorn; all dispyse&thorn; as sei&thorn; &thorn;e book [2261] &para; And Senek sei&thorn; &thorn;at who so wole haue sapi|ence. schal no man dispreyse &para; But he schal gladly teche &thorn;e science &thorn;at he can wi&thorn;outen presumpsioun or pryde [2262] and suche &thorn;inges &thorn;at he nought ne can he schal nou&yogh;t be asshamed to lere him and to enquere of lasse 
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="496"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="209"> folk &thorn;an of himself [2263] &para; And sire &thorn;at &thorn;er ha&thorn; ben ful many a good womman may lightly be proued [2264] &para; certes sire oure lord ihesu crist nolde neuer han descendet to be borne of a womman if alle wommen hadde be wicke [2265] &para; And after &thorn;at for &thorn;e grete bounte &thorn;at is in wommen oure lord Ihesus when he was rysen fro de&thorn; to lyfe appered ra&thorn;er to womman &thorn;an to his apostels [2266] &para; and &thorn;ough &thorn;at Salomon sai&thorn; &thorn;at he ne fond neuer womman good it <MILESTONE N="220b" UNIT="folio">folwe&thorn; nought &thorn;erfore &thorn;at alle wommen ben wikke [2267] &para; For &thorn;ough &thorn;at he ne fonde no good womman Certes many ano&thorn;er man ha&thorn; founden many a womman ful good and trewe [2268] Or elles perauenture &thorn;e entent of Salamon was &thorn;us &thorn;at as in souereyn bounte he fande no womman [2269] This is to say &thorn;at &thorn;er nys no wight &thorn;at ha&thorn; parfyt bounte saue god allone as he himself recorde&thorn; in his euaun|gelist [2270] &para; For &thorn;er nys no creature so good that him ne wante&thorn; som what/ of &thorn;e perfeccion of god &thorn;at is his makere [2271] &para; The &thorn;ridde resoun is &thorn;is &yogh;e say &thorn;at if &yogh;e gouerne &yogh;ou by my counseil hit schulde seme &thorn;at &yogh;e hadde &yogh;oue me &thorn;e maystry And &thorn;e lordschip of &yogh;oure persone // [2272] Sire saue &yogh;oure grace hit nys nought so &para; For if so were &thorn;at no man schulde be counseled but oonly of hem &thorn;at hadde lorschipe and maystrye of his persone men nolde nought be counseiled so ofte. [2273] For so&thorn;ly &thorn;ilke men &thorn;at aske&thorn; counseil of a purpos &para; &yogh;et ha&thorn; he free wille whe&thorn;er he wol do after &thorn;at counsel or no [2274] &para; And as to &yogh;oure four&thorn;e reson &thorn;er as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at &thorn;e Iangelry of wommen can huyde &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ey wot nou&yogh;t &para; As who sai&thorn; &thorn;at a womman can nought huyde what sche wot [2275] &para; Sire &thorn;ese wordes ben vnder|stonde of wommen &thorn;at ben Iangleresses and wicked [2276] of whiche wommen men sayn &thorn;at &thorn;re &thorn;inges dryue&thorn; a man out of his hous. That is to say Smoke droppyng of Rayn and wickidde wyfes [2277] And 
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="497"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="210"> swiche wommen sai&thorn; Salamon &thorn;at he were bettre to dwelle in desert &thorn;an with a womman &thorn;at is ryetous [2278] And sire by &yogh;oure leue &thorn;at am nought I [2279] &para; For &yogh;e haue ful ofte assayed my grete Cilence and my grete pacience and eek how wel &thorn;at he can huyde and hele &thorn;inges &thorn;at men oughten secrely to huyden [2280] &para; and so&thorn; as to &yogh;oure fifte reson wher as &yogh;e say &thorn;at in wikked coun|seil wommen venquysshe&thorn; men &para; God wot &thorn;ilke reson stant heere in no stede [2281] &para; For vnderstandeth now &yogh;e axeth counseil for to do wikkednes [2282] and if &yogh;e wolen werke wikkednesse and &yogh;oure wijf restreyne&thorn; &thorn;ilke wikked purpos and ouercome &yogh;ou by reson and by good counseil; [2283] certes &yogh;oure wyf oughte ra&thorn;er to be preysed &thorn;en to be blamed [2284] &para; This scholde &yogh;e vnder|stande &thorn;e philosophre &thorn;at sai&thorn; In wicked counseil wommen venquysshen here housebondes [2285] &para; and &thorn;ere as &yogh;e blamen alle wommen &amp; here resons; I schal schewe &yogh;ou by many ensamples &thorn;at many wommen han ben ful goode and &yogh;et ben and here counsel holsome and profitable [2286] &para; eeke some men han sayde &thorn;at &thorn;e counselyng of wommen is ey&thorn;er to deere or elles to lytel of pris [2287] &para; But al be it so &thorn;at ful <MILESTONE N="221a" UNIT="folio">many womman is badde and here counseil vile &amp; nou&yogh;t wor&thorn;; &yogh;et han men founde many a good womman and ful discret and wys in counselyng // [2288] lo Iacob &thorn;urgh &thorn;e goode counseil of his moder Rebekka wan &thorn;e benyson of his fader and &thorn;e lordschipe ouer alle his bre&thorn;eren . [2289] Iudith &thorn;urgh hire goode counseil delyuered &thorn;e Cite of Buphelye in which sche dwelte out of &thorn;e lande of Olyuerne &thorn;at hadde it al byseged and wolde han al destruyet it [2290] &para; Abegayle delyuered Nabal hir housbonde fro Dauid &thorn;e king &thorn;at wolde han slayn him and appaysede &thorn;e yre of &thorn;e king by hire witte and by hire goode counseil|yng [2291] &para;&para; Ester by hire counceil enchaunced gretly &thorn;e poeple of god in &thorn;e Regne of Assueres &thorn;e king [2292] and &thorn;e same bounte. in good counseiling of 
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="498"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="211"> many a womman may men telle [2293] &para; And fur&thorn;ermore whan &thorn;at oure lord had created Adam oure forme fader; he sayde in &thorn;is wise / [2294] It nys nought good to be a man allone &para; Make we an helper semblable to him|self. [2295] &para; Here may &yogh;e see &thorn;at if &thorn;at womman were nou&yogh;t good and hire counseil good and profytable; [2296] Oure lord god of heuene ne wolde neuer han y-wrou&yogh;t hem ne called hem &thorn;e helper of man . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap.</NOTE> [2297] &para; And &thorn;er sayde ones a clerk in tuo vers / what is bettre &thorn;an a good Iaspre . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap.</NOTE> wisdom [2298] And what is bettre &thorn;an wisdam womman and what is bettre &thorn;an womman &thorn;at is a good womman no &thorn;ing [2299] &para; And sire by many of o&thorn;er resons may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at many wommen ben goode and eek here counseil good and profitable [2300] &para; And &thorn;erfore sire if &yogh;e wiln truste to my counseil; I schal restore &yogh;ou &yogh;oure doughter hool and sound [2301] &para; And eek &thorn;at I wol to &yogh;ou don so moche &thorn;at &yogh;e schuln haue honour in &thorn;is caas</P>
<P>[2302] &para; When melybe had herde &thorn;e wordes of his wijf Prudence; he sayde &thorn;us [2303] &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes of Salamon is so&thorn; &para; For he sai&thorn; &thorn;at wordes &thorn;at ben' spoken discretly by ordynaunce ben hony combes ffor &thorn;ey &yogh;iuen swetnesse to &thorn;e soule and holsomnes to &thorn;e body [2304] &para; And wyf by cause of &thorn;ine swete wordes and eeke for I haue y-proued and sayd &thorn;in grete sapience and &thorn;in grete trou&thorn;e I wol gouerne me by &thorn;yn counseyl in alle &thorn;ing</P>
<P>[2305] &para; Now sire quod dame Prudence and se&thorn;enes &yogh;e fouche sauf to be gouerned by my counseil; I wol enforme &yogh;ou how &thorn;at &yogh;e schuln gouerne &yogh;oure self in chesyng of &yogh;oure counseilours [2306] &para; &yogh;e schuln ferst fourme alle &yogh;oure wekes mekely byseken to &thorn;e hihe god &thorn;at he wol ben &yogh;our counseilour [2307] And schape&thorn; &yogh;ou to such entent &thorn;at he &yogh;iue &yogh;ou counseil and confort as taughte Thobye<MILESTONE N="221b" UNIT="folio"> to his sone [2308] at alle tymes. thou schalt/ blesse 
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="499"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="212"> god and preyen him to dresse / &thorn;ine weyes. and loke also &thorn;at &thorn;ine counseiles ben in him for euermore [2309] &para; Seint Iame sai&thorn; &para; If any of &yogh;ou haue neede of Sapience; aske it of god [2310] &para; And afterward &thorn;enne schullen &yogh;e take counsel in &yogh;oure self and examyn wel &yogh;oure owne &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of swiche &thorn;inges as &yogh;ou &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at is best for &yogh;oure profyt [2311] &para; And &thorn;enne schulle &yogh;e dryue fro &yogh;oure hertes &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben contrarious to good counseil [2312] &thorn;at is to say. Ire. Coueytise. and hastynes.</P>
<P>[2313] ffirst he &thorn;at aske&thorn; counseil of himself; certes he moste be wi&thorn;outen Ire . . . . .[2314] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> and wra&thorn;&thorn;e in himself he wene&thorn; alwey &thorn;at he may do &thorn;ing &thorn;at he may not do [2315] &para; And secoundly he &thorn;at is Irous and wro&thorn; he . . . . .[2316] <NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> may nought wel counseille [2317] &para; The &thorn;ridde is &thorn;is. &thorn;at he &thorn;at is Irous and wro&thorn; as sai&thorn; Senek ne may nought speke but blameful &thorn;inges [2318] And with &thorn;ilke vicious wordes he stere&thorn; o&thorn;er folk to anger and to Ire [2319] And eek sire &yogh;e moste drede coueytise out of &yogh;oure herte. [2320] ffor &thorn;e apostel sei&thorn; &thorn;at coueytise is &thorn;e roote of alle harmes. [2321] And trusteth right wel &thorn;at a coueytous man ne can nought deme ne &thorn;enke but only to fulfille &thorn;e ende of his coueytise. [2322] and certes &thorn;at ne may neuer be acomplised. ffor euer &thorn;e more habundance &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of richesse; &thorn;e more he desire&thorn; [2323] &para; And sire &yogh;e moste also driue out of &yogh;our hertes hastynes [2324] &para; For certes &yogh;e may nou&yogh;t deme for &thorn;e beste a sodeyn &thorn;ought &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &yogh;oure herte &para; But &yogh;e moste avise &yogh;ou on hit ful ofte [2325] &para; ffor as &yogh;e haue herd here biforn &thorn;e comune proverbe is &thorn;is That he &thorn;at sone deme&thorn; sone repente&thorn; //</P>
<P>[2326] Sire &yogh;e ne be nou&yogh;t alwey in ylike disposicion [2327] ffor certes som &thorn;ing &thorn;at some tyme seme&thorn; to &yogh;ou &thorn;at is good for to do. Ano&thorn;er tyme it seme&thorn; to &yogh;ou &thorn;e contrarie. <NOTE PLACE="marg">[A great bit is now omitted in Corpus.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="500"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="213"></P>
<P>[2328] [When ye han taken counseile in your self And<MILESTONE UNIT="Laud MS 600 folio" N="233a"> han demed bi good deliberacion siche &thorn;ing as you semi&thorn; best [2329] &para; &thorn;anne rede I / you that ye kepe it secre / [2330] bewrie not your counseile to no persone. bot it so be. &thorn;at ye wene sikerli &thorn;at &thorn;urgh your bewrieng / your condicion shal be to you &thorn;e more profitable [2331] &para; For Ihesus Sirac sai&thorn; &para; Nei&thorn;er to &thorn;i foo ne to &thorn;i frende. discouer not &thorn;i secre ne &thorn;i foli. [2332] for &thorn;ai wol yeue you audience and loking and supportacion in &thorn;i presence and scorne in &thorn;i absence. [2333] &para; Ano&thorn;er clerc sai&thorn; &thorn;at scarsli shalt &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">nota</NOTE> finde any persone &thorn;at mai kepe counseil secreli. [2334] &para; The book sai&thorn; while &thorn;ou kepest &thorn;i counsail in &thorn;in hert &thorn;ou kepist it in &thorn;i prison / [2335] and whan &thorn;ou bewriest &thorn;i counsaile to any wight / he holde&thorn; &thorn;e in his snare ./ [2336] And &thorn;erfore you is better hide your counsaile. in your hert / &thorn;an praien him to whom ye haue bewried your counseil &thorn;at he wol kepe it clos and stille. [2337] &para; For Seneca sai&thorn; if so be. &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne maist not. &thorn;in owne counseile hide. How darst &thorn;ou praien any o&thorn;er wight / &thorn;i counseil secreli to kepe. [2338] &para; Bot na&thorn;eles if &thorn;ou wene sicurli / &thorn;at &thorn;i bewriyng of &thorn;i counsaile to a persone wol make &thorn;i condicion to stonde in a better plite. Then shalt &thorn;ou tellen him &thorn;i counseil in &thorn;is wise [2339] &para; First &thorn;ou shalt make no semblant / where &thorn;e were leuer werre or pees. or &thorn;is. or &thorn;at. ne shew him not &thorn;i wille / and &thorn;in entent [2340] &para; For trust wel &thorn;at comunli &thorn;ise counseilours. ben flaterers And [2341] namely &thorn;e counseil|lours of grete lordes. [2342] for &thorn;ei enforcen hem alwei. ra&thorn;er to speke plesant wordes. enclynyng to &thorn;e lordes lust &thorn;an wordes &thorn;at ben trewe. and profitable. [2343]<MILESTONE UNIT="Laud MS 600 folio" N="233b"> &para; And &thorn;erfore men sai &thorn;at &thorn;e riche man ha&thorn; selden good coun|saile / bot he haue it of himself [2344] &para; And aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt considre &thorn;i frendes and &thorn;i enemyes ./ [2345] And as touching &thorn;i frendes. &thorn;ou shalt con|sidre 
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="501"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="214"> whiche of hem beth most fai&thorn;ful and most<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Laud MS 600]</NOTE> wise. and eldest and most approued in counseilyng [2346] and of hem shalt &thorn;ou axe &thorn;i counsaile as &thorn;e caas requireth</P>
<P>[2347] &para; I / sai &thorn;at first ye shul clepe to youre coun|saile / youre frendes &thorn;at ben trewe ./ [2348] For Salamon sai&thorn; / for right as &thorn;e hert of a man deliti&thorn; in sauour. &thorn;at is soote / right so &thorn;e counsaile of your trewe frendes / yeue&thorn; swetnes to &thorn;e soule [2349] &para; He sai&thorn; also &thorn;er mai no&thorn;ing be likned to &thorn;e trewe frende / [2350] &para; For certes gold ne siluer be not so moche wor&thorn;. as &thorn;e good wille of a trewe frende / [2351] and eke he sai&thorn; &thorn;at a trewe frende. is a stronge defence / who &thorn;at it finde&thorn;. certis he finde&thorn; a gret tresour [2352] &para; &thorn;ene shul ye eke considre / if &thorn;at youre trewe frendes ben discrete and wise / for &thorn;e book sai&thorn;. axe &thorn;i counsaile alwai of hem &thorn;at ben wise. [2353] And bi &thorn;is same resoun. shul ye clepe to youre counsaile of youre frendes &thorn;at ben age. siche as haue sai sightes and ben expert in mony &thorn;inges. and ben approued in counseiling. [2354] for &thorn;e book sai&thorn; &thorn;at in olde men is &thorn;e sapience. and in longe time &thorn;e prudence [2355] &para; And tullius sai&thorn; &thorn;at grete &thorn;inges ben not aye accompleed bi streng&thorn;e ne bi delyuernes of bodi. bot bi good counsail. bi auctorite of persones and bi science. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges ben not feble bi age ./ bot certes &thorn;ai enforcen to en|cresen dai by dai. [2356] and &thorn;an shul ye kepe &thorn;is for a general rewle &para; First shul ye clepe to youre counsaile a fewe of your frendes &thorn;at ben especial [2357] &para; For Salamon sai&thorn; mony frendes haue &thorn;ou. bot among a &thorn;ousand chese &thorn;e on to be &thorn;i conseil|lour / [2358] For al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ou first ne telle &thorn;i counseil bot to a fewe. &thorn;ou maist aftirward telle it to moo folk / if it be nede. [2359] bot loke alwey &thorn;at &thorn;i counseilours haue &thorn;i[l]k &thorn;re condiciouns. &thorn;at I / haue said 
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="502"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="215"> before. &thorn;at is to sai &thorn;at &thorn;ei be trewe and olde. and<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Laud MS]</NOTE> of wis experience. [2360] &para; And wirke not alwey in euery nede / bi on counseilour allone. For somtyme behoue&thorn; it be counseilid bi many. [2361] &para; For Salamon sai&thorn;. Saluacion of &thorn;inges is. where as &thorn;er ben many counselers.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Laud MS <I>ex|tract ends</I>]</NOTE></P>
<P>[2362] Now haue I tolde &yogh;ou of which folk<NOTE PLACE="marg">Corpus MS, on leaf 221, back</NOTE> &yogh;e scholde be counseled NOw wol I teche &yogh;ou which counseil &yogh;e owe to eschewe [2363] fferst &yogh;e schuln eschewe &thorn;e counseilyng of fooles. Salomon sai&thorn; take no coun|seil of a fool ffor he wol counseile but after his owne luste and his affections [2364] &para; The book/ sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e proprete of a fool is &thorn;is &para; he trowe&thorn; lightly harme of euery wight and lightly trowe&thorn; a bounte in himself [2365] &para; Thou schalt eke eschewe &thorn;e counseiling of alle flaterers whiche enforcen hem ra&thorn;er to preysen &yogh;oure persone by flaterye &thorn;an for to telle &yogh;ou &thorn;e so&thorn;|fastnesse of &thorn;inges</P>
<P>[2366] &para; Wherfore Tullius sai&thorn; among alle &thorn;e pestilence <MILESTONE N="222a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at ben in frendschipe &thorn;e grettest is flaterie &para; And &thorn;erfore is it more nede &thorn;at &thorn;ou eschewe and drede flaterers &thorn;an any o&thorn;er poeple / [2367] The book sai&thorn; &thorn;ou schalt ra&thorn;er [drede and] fle fro &thorn;e swete wordes of flaterynge &amp; preysyng &thorn;en fro &thorn;e egre wordes of &thorn;y frend &thorn;at sai&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;in so&thorn;es [2368] Salomon sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e wordes of a flaterer is a snare to cacche Innocence [2369] &para; he sai&thorn; also. he &thorn;at speke&thorn; to his frend wordes of swetnes and of plesance; sette&thorn; a nette biforn his feet to cacche him [2370] &para; And &thorn;erfore Tullius sai&thorn; Enclyne nou&yogh;t &thorn;in eeres to flaterers Ne take no counseil of wordes of flaterie / [2371] and Caton sai&thorn; &para; Avise &thorn;e wel and eschewe &thorn;e wordes of swetnes and of plesaunce [2372] &para; And eek &thorn;ou schalt eschewe &thorn;e counsellyng of &thorn;ine olde enemys &thorn;at be reconsiled [2373] The book sai&thorn; &thorn;at no wight retourne&thorn; saufly in to &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="503"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="216"> grace of his olde enemy [2374] &para; And Isope sai&thorn; &para; Ne truste nou&yogh;t to hem to whiche som tyme &thorn;ou hast had werre / or enmyte ne telle hem nou&yogh;t &thorn;i counseille [2375] &para; And Senek telle&thorn; &thorn;e cause why it may nought be saith he &thorn;at where long tyme fuyr ha&thorn; endured &thorn;at &thorn;er dwelle&thorn; som tyme vapour of hete [2376] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Salamon in &thorn;in olde foo truste &thorn;ou neuere [2377] ffor sikerly &thorn;ough &thorn;in enemy be reconsiled and make&thorn; &thorn;e chere of humilite and lowte&thorn; to &thorn;e wi&thorn; his heed ne truste him neuere [2378] ffor certes he make&thorn; &thorn;ilke feyned humilite more for his profyt &thorn;an for eny humilite or for eny loue of &thorn;in persone by . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> such feyned contynance The which victory he might haue by stryf or werre [2379] And Petre Alfouns sai&thorn;. make no felaschipe wi&thorn; &thorn;ine olde enemyes; ffor if &thorn;ou do hem bounte &thorn;ey wollen peruerten hit to wickednesse [2380] And eeke &thorn;ou most eschewe &thorn;e counseilyng of hem &thorn;at ben &thorn;in seruantz and beren the gret reuerence ffor perauenture &thorn;ey seyn it more for drede &thorn;an for loue [2381] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; a Philosophre in &thorn;is wise &para; Ther nys no wight parfytly trewe to him &thorn;at he to sore drede&thorn; [2382] &para; And Tullius sai&thorn; &para; Ther nys no wight so gret of eny emperour &thorn;at longe may endure / but if he haue loue of &thorn;e poeple and drede [2383] &para; Thow schalt eschewe also &thorn;e counseiling of folk &thorn;at ben drunkelewe for &thorn;ey ne can no counselle huyde. [2384] Salamon sai&thorn; &thorn;er nys no pryuyte &thorn;er as regne&thorn; drunkenes [2385] &para; &yogh;e schullen han also in suspecte to &thorn;e counseling of such folk as counseile &yogh;ow a &thorn;ing priuily and counseile &yogh;ou a &thorn;ing &thorn;at is contrarie openly [2386] ffor Cassidory sai&thorn; &thorn;at it is a maner sleighte to hyndre his enemy when <MILESTONE N="222b" UNIT="folio">he schewe&thorn; to don a &thorn;ing openly and werke&thorn; priuily &thorn;e contrarie [2387] &para; Thou schalt haue also in &thorn;in suspecte &thorn;e conselynge of wikked folk . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at is alwey ful 
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="504"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="217"> of fraude [2388] and Dauid sai&thorn; &thorn;at blisful is &thorn;e man &thorn;at ha&thorn; nought folwed &thorn;e counseling of schrewes [2389] &para; Thow schalt also eschewe &thorn;e counseilling of &yogh;ong folk ffor here counseilyng nys nought rype as Salomon sai&thorn;</P>
<P>[2390] &para; Now sire si&thorn;enes I haue schewed &yogh;ou of which folk &yogh;e schuln take counsel and of which folk &yogh;e schuln folwe &thorn;e counsel / [2391] Now wol I teche &yogh;ou how &yogh;e schuln examyn &yogh;oure counsel after the doctrine of Tullius [2392] in &thorn;e examynyng &thorn;enne of &yogh;oure counseilour &yogh;e schuln considere many &thorn;inges [2393] &para; Al&thorn;er first &thorn;ou schalt considere &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest and vpon what &thorn;ing &thorn;ou wolt han counsell &thorn;at verray trou&thorn;e be sayde and conserued &thorn;is is to say telle trewly &thorn;in tale [2394] &para; For he &thorn;at sai&thorn; fals may [not] wel be counseiled in &thorn;at caas of which [he lyeth] [2395] &para; And after &thorn;is &thorn;ou schalt consideren &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at acorden to &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest for to be by &thorn;in counseil|ours if reson acorde&thorn; &thorn;erto [2396] &para; And eek if &thorn;i might may atteyne &thorn;erto &para; And if &thorn;e more part and &thorn;e bettre part of &yogh;oure counseilours acorden &thorn;erto or no. [2397] &thorn;en schalt &thorn;ou considere what &thorn;ing schal folwe of here counseilinge. as hate pees werre grace profyt other damage and many o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2398] And in alle &thorn;inges &thorn;ou schalt chese &thorn;e beste and weyfe alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2399] &para; Thenne schalt &thorn;ou considere of what roote it is engendred &thorn;e matier of &thorn;in counseil and what fruyt it may conceyue and engendre [2400] &thorn;ou schalt eek considre alle &thorn;ese causes for &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ey ben spronge [2401] &para; and whan &yogh;e haue examyned &yogh;oure counseil as I haue sayde and which partie is &thorn;e bettre and more profitable and hast aproued it by many wise folk and olde [2402] &thorn;anne schalt &thorn;ou considere if &thorn;ou mayst performe hit and make of hit a good ende [2403] &para; For certes reson wol nou&yogh;t &thorn;at any man schal begynne a &thorn;ing but if he mighte performe hit as him ow&yogh;te [2404] &para; Ne no wight schulde 
<PB REF="00000533.tif" N="505"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="218"> taken vpon him so heuy a charge &thorn;at he mighte [not] bere it [2405] &para; For &thorn;e prouerbe sai&thorn; he &thorn;at to mochel enbrace&thorn; distreyne&thorn; litel [2406] &para; And Caton sai&thorn; &para; Assay such &thorn;ing as &thorn;ou hast power to done leste &thorn;e charge oppresse &thorn;e to sore &thorn;at &thorn;e bihoue&thorn; to weyue &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bygonne [2407] &para; And if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou be in doute. wher &thorn;ou maist performe a &thorn;ing or non; chese ra&thorn;er for to suffre &thorn;an for to bygynne [2408] &para; And Pieres alphouns saith If &thorn;ou hast might to don a &thorn;ing of which &thorn;ou most repente it is bettre . . . . .[2409] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> halde &thorn;i tunge <MILESTONE N="223a" UNIT="folio">stille &thorn;an for to speke [2410] &para; Then may I vnderstonde by strenger resouns &thorn;at if &thorn;ou hast power to performe a werk of which &thorn;ou schalt repente &thorn;e &para; Thenne is it bettre &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffre &thorn;an bygynne [2411] wel seyn &thorn;ey &thorn;at defenden euery wight to assaye a &thorn;ing of which he is in doute wher he may performe it or non [2412] &para; And after when &yogh;e haue examynd &yogh;oure conseill as I haue sayd biforn and knowe wel &thorn;at &yogh;e may per|forme &yogh;oure emprise; conferme it &thorn;enne sadly til it be at an ende</P>
<P>[2413] &para; Now is it reson and tyme &thorn;at I schewe &yogh;ou whenne and where-fore &thorn;at &yogh;e may chaunge &yogh;oure counsel|ours wi&thorn;outen &yogh;oure reprofe [2414] &para; So&thorn;ly man may chaunge his purpos and his counseill if &thorn;e cause cesseth or whan a newe cause betyde&thorn; [2415] &para; For &thorn;e lawe sei&thorn; vpon &thorn;inges &thorn;at newely betyden bihoue&thorn; newe conseill [2416] &para; And Senek sai&thorn; &para; If &thorn;in counseil come to &thorn;e eeres of &thorn;in enemys; chaunge &thorn;i conseill [2417] [<I>Apr&egrave;s, l'en peut changier son conseil</I>] if so be &thorn;ou fynde &thorn;at by errour or by ony o&thorn;er cause harme or damage may betyde [2418] &para; Also of &thorn;in counsel be dishoneste o&thorn;er elles come of dishoneste cause; chaunge &thorn;in counsel [2419] &para; For &thorn;e lawe sai&thorn;/ &thorn;at alle bihestes &thorn;at ben dishoneste ne ben of no value. 
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="506"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="219"> [2420] and eek if so be &thorn;at it be impossible o&thorn;er may nou&yogh;t gladly be performed o&thorn;er kepte</P>
<P>[2421] And take &thorn;is for a general reule / &thorn;at euery counsel &thorn;at is enformed so strongly &thorn;at it may nought be chaunged for no condicion &thorn;at may betyde; I say &thorn;at ilke consel is wicked.</P>
<P>[2422] &para; Melibeus whan he hadde herd &thorn;e doctrine of his wijf dame prudence; he answerde in &thorn;is wyse. [2423] Dame quod he as &yogh;et vnto &thorn;is tyme &yogh;e han wel taught me as in generalle how I schal gouerne me and in &thorn;e chesyng and in &thorn;e wi&thorn;holdyng of my counseilours. [2424] But now wolde I fayn &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde condescende in special [2425] and telle me how &thorn;at like&thorn; &yogh;ou or how &thorn;at seme&thorn; &yogh;ou by oure counseil|lours &thorn;at we haue chose in &thorn;is present neede</P>
<P>[2426] &para; My lord quod sche I beseche &yogh;ou in al humbles &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde nought wilfully reproeuen a&yogh;ein myn resons ne distempre &yogh;oure herte &thorn;ough I speke &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;ou displese [2427] &para; ffor god woot as in myn entent I speke it as for &thorn;e beste for &yogh;oure honour and for &yogh;our profyt eeke [2428] &para; And so&thorn;ly I hope &thorn;at &yogh;oure be|nignite wol take it in pacience [2429] &para; and truste&thorn; to me wel &thorn;at &yogh;oure counsel in &thorn;is cas ne scholde nou&yogh;t as to speke proprely be called a counselynge but a mocioun or a meuyng of folye [2430] In which counseil &yogh;e haue herde in many a sondry wise</P>
<P>[2431] &para; fferst and for&thorn;ward &yogh;e han herd in &thorn;e assem|blyng of &yogh;our counsellours [2432] &para; ffor ferst &yogh;e schulde haue cleped <MILESTONE N="223b" UNIT="folio">a fewe folk to &yogh;oure counseille &para; And after &thorn;at &yogh;e might haue schewed it to mo folk if it hadde be neede. [2433] But certes sodeinly &yogh;e han cleped to &yogh;oure coun|seil a gret multitude of poeple fulle chargaunt and ful annuyous for to heere [2434] &para; And also &yogh;e haue herde furthere as &yogh;e schulde only haue cleped to &yogh;oure counselle &yogh;oure trewe frendes olde &amp; wise [2435] &para; &yogh;e han cleped also straunge folk &yogh;ong folk fals flaterers and enemys 
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="507"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="220"> reconsiled and folk &thorn;at don &yogh;ou reuerence wi&thorn;outen loue / [2436] and eek also &yogh;e haue herd for &yogh;e han brought wi&thorn; &yogh;ou to &yogh;oure counseil. Ire. coueytise and hastines [2437] &thorn;e whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges ben contrary to euery good counseil and honest &amp; profitable [2438] &thorn;e whiche &thorn;re &thorn;inges &yogh;e han nou&yogh;t anyntesched o&thorn;er destruyed hem ney&thorn;er in &yogh;oure self ne in &yogh;oure / counceillours as &yogh;e aughte [2439] &para; &YOGH;e han herde also for &yogh;e han schewed to &yogh;oure counseillours &yogh;oure talent &yogh;oure affeccion to make werre anon for to do vengeaunce [2440] And &thorn;ey haue aspied by &yogh;oure wordes to what &thorn;ing &yogh;e ben enclyned [2441] &para; and &thorn;erfore haue &thorn;ey ra&thorn;er counseled &yogh;ou to &yogh;oure talent &thorn;an to &yogh;oure profyt [2442] &yogh;e han herde also for seme&thorn; it / suffice&thorn; to han ben coun|celed by &thorn;is counceillours oonly and wi&thorn; litel auyse [2443] where as in so grete and in so heih a neede it ha&thorn; be necessarye mo counselours and mo deliberacions to parforme &yogh;oure emprise [2444] &para; &YOGH;e han herd also for &yogh;e han herd nought &yogh;oure counsel in &thorn;e forseyde manere ne in dewe manere as &thorn;e cas requyre&thorn; [2445] &para; &yogh;e haue herd also for &yogh;e haue maad no dyuysion betwixe . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &yogh;oure trewe frendes and &yogh;oure feyned concelours [2446] &para; Ne &yogh;e haue nou&yogh;t knowe &thorn;e wille of &yogh;oure trewe freendes olde and wise. [2447] but &yogh;e haue cast alle here wordes in an hoche potte and enclyned &yogh;oure herte to &thorn;e more part and to &thorn;e grettere nombre . . . . .[2448] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> of fooles &thorn;enne of wise men. [2449] &para; And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e counselynge &thorn;at ben at congregacions and mul|titudes of folk &thorn;er as men take more reward to &thorn;e nombre &thorn;en to Sapience of persones; [2450] &yogh;e seen wel &thorn;at in suche councelynges fooles haue &thorn;e maystrie [2451] &para; Melybe answerde and sayde a&yogh;ein I graunte wel &thorn;at I haue herd [2452] &para; But &thorn;er as &thorn;ou hast tolde me &thorn;er biforn &thorn;at he nys nought to blame &thorn;at chaunge&thorn; his coun|ceiloures 
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="508"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="221"> for certein caas and for certein and iuste cause [2453] I am al redy to chaunge myne counceilours right as &thorn;ou woldest deuyse [2454] &para; ffor &thorn;e prouerbe saith &thorn;at for to don synne is mannyssch But certes for to perseueren longe in synne is werkes of &thorn;e deuel.</P>
<P>[2455] <MILESTONE N="224a" UNIT="folio">To &thorn;is sentence answered anon dame Pru|dence and sayde. [2456] examyne&thorn; quod sche &yogh;oure con|selle and let vs se &thorn;e which of hem ha&thorn; spoke more resonably and taught &yogh;ou best conseil [2457] &para; And for as moche as &thorn;at examinacion is necessary. let vs begynne at surgiens and at phisiciens &thorn;at first spaken of &thorn;is matiere [2458] &para; I say &thorn;at Phisiciens &amp; surgiens haue sayd &yogh;ou in &yogh;oure consel discretly as hem oughte [2459] &amp; in here speche sethens ful wisly &thorn;at to &thorn;e office of hem apperteyne&thorn; to don to euery wight honour and profyt and nou&yogh;t for to ennoye [2460] and after here crafte to don gret diligence vnto &thorn;e cure of hem whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ey haue in here gouern|aunce [2461] and sir right as &thorn;ey han answered wisly and discretly; [2462] Right so rede I &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben heighly and souereynly guerdount for here noble speche [2463] and eek for &thorn;ey schullen more do &thorn;e ententyf busynes in &thorn;e curacion of &thorn;in doughter deere [2464] &para; ffor al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben &yogh;oure freendes; &thorn;erfore schuln &yogh;e nou&yogh;t suffre &thorn;at &thorn;ey serue &yogh;ou for nought [2465] &para; But &yogh;e aughte &thorn;er after guerdon hem and payen hem here largesse [2466] &para; and as touchynge &thorn;e proporcion which &thorn;at &thorn;e phisiciens encreseden in &thorn;is caas &para; This is to sayn [2467] &thorn;at in maladyes is &thorn;at a contrary is warisshed by ano&thorn;er contrarie [2468] &para; I wolde fayn knowe how &yogh;e vnderstode &thorn;ilke text and what is &yogh;oure sentence [2469] &para; Certes quod Mellibeus I vnderstande it in &thorn;is wise. [2470] Right as &thorn;ey haue done me a contrary; so schuld I don hem ano&thorn;er [2471] &para; ffor right as &thorn;ey haue venged hem vpon me; and don me wrong; Right so wol I venge me vpon hem 
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="509"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="222"> and don hem wrong [2472] and &thorn;enne haue I cured a contrary by ano&thorn;er</P>
<P>[2473] &para; lo lo quod dame prudence how lightly is euery man enclyned to his owne desir to his plesaunce [2474] &para; Certes quod sche &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e phisicien ne schulde nou&yogh;t be vnderstande in &thorn;at wise [2475] ffor certes wikkednesse is nou&yogh;t contrary to wickednes ne vengeance is nou&yogh;t contrary to veng|aunce ne wrong to wrong [<I>mais sont semblables</I>. [2476] <I>Et pour ce, vengence par vengence, ne injure par in|jure, n'est pas cur&eacute;</I> (Men. i. 206-7)] [2477] But euery of hem encrese&thorn; and engregge&thorn; o&thorn;er [2478] &para; But certes &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e phisicien schullen ben vnder|stonde in &thorn;is wise [2479] &para; ffor good and wicked|nesse ben tuo contrarious &para; And pees and werre venge|ance and sufferance discord and acord and many o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2480] &para; But certes wickednesse schal ben y-warisched by goodnes. discord by acord. werre by pees and so for&thorn; and o&thorn;er &thorn;inges [2481] &para; And herto acorde&thorn; seint Poule &thorn;e appostel and in many place [2482] he sai&thorn; &para; Ne &yogh;elde&thorn; nou&yogh;t harm for<MILESTONE N="224b" UNIT="folio"> harm ne wicked speche [<I>pour mesdit</I>] [2483] But do wel to hem &thorn;at don &thorn;e harme and blesse hem &thorn;at sai&thorn; to &thorn;e harme [2484] And many o&thorn;er places he amonyssche&thorn; pees and acord [2485] &para; But now wol I speke of &thorn;e coun|seil which was y-&yogh;oue vnto &yogh;ou by men of lawe &thorn;e wise folk and olde folk [2486] &thorn;at sayden alle by on acorde as &yogh;e haue herde biforn [2487] &para; That ouer alle &thorn;inges &yogh;e schullen don &yogh;oure diligence to kepe &yogh;oure persone and to warmstore &yogh;oure hous [2488] &para; And &thorn;ay sayden also &thorn;at in &thorn;is caas &yogh;e oughten to wirchen ful avisily and wi&thorn; gret deliberacion [2489] &para; And sir as to &thorn;e first poynt &thorn;at touche&thorn; vnto &thorn;e kepyng of &yogh;oure persone [2490] &yogh;e schullen vnderstande &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; werre schal euermore deuoutely and mekely preyen biforn alle &thorn;inges [2491] &thorn;at Ihesus crist of his mercy wole 
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="510"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="223"> haue him in his proteccion and ben his souerein helpynge at his neede [2492] ffor certes in &thorn;is world nys no wight &thorn;at may be counseled ne kepte sufficiauntly wi&thorn;|outen &thorn;e kepyng of oure lord ihesus crist [2493] To &thorn;is sentence accorde&thorn; &thorn;e prophete dauid &thorn;at sai&thorn;. [2494] If god ne kepe &thorn;e cite in ydel wake&thorn; he &thorn;at it kepe&thorn; [2495] &para; Now sir &thorn;enne schulle &yogh;e quyte &thorn;e kepyng of &yogh;oure persone to &yogh;oure trewe frendes &thorn;at ben aproved and y-knowe [2496] and of hem schuln &yogh;e asken helpe &yogh;oure persone for to kepe &para; ffor Caton sai&thorn; &para; If &thorn;ou hast neede of helpe; aske it of &thorn;in frendes [2497] ffor &thorn;er nys non so good a phisicien as &thorn;in trewe freend [2498] and after &thorn;is &thorn;enne schulle &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou fro alle straunge folk and fro lyeres And haue alway in suspecte here companye [2499] &para; ffor pieres alphouns sai&thorn; &para; Ne take no companye by &thorn;e way of straunge man but it so be &thorn;ou haue knowe him of lengere tyme. [2500] and if so be &thorn;at he falle in to &thorn;in company per|aduenture wi&thorn;outen &thorn;in assent [2501] enquere &thorn;enne as subtilly as &thorn;ou canst of his conuersacion and of his lyf byfore and feyne &thorn;y way seynge &thorn;ou woldest go &thorn;ider as &thorn;ou woldest nou&yogh;t go. [2502] and if he bere&thorn; a spere holde &thorn;e on &thorn;e right syde of him . and if he bere&thorn; a swerde holde &thorn;e on &thorn;e left syde of him. [2503] and &thorn;enne schul &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou wisly fro alle such manere of poeple as Ihaue sayde &yogh;ou here bifore and hem and here coun|sel eschewe [2504] And after &thorn;is &thorn;enne schulle &yogh;e kepe &yogh;ou in such manere [2505] &thorn;at for any presumpcioun of &yogh;oure bodily streng&thorn;e &thorn;at &yogh;e ne dispise nought ne accounte nou&yogh;t &thorn;e might of &yogh;oure aduersary so lyte &thorn;at &yogh;e lete &thorn;e kepynge of &yogh;oure persone for &yogh;oure presumpcion [2506] ffor euery wysman drede&thorn; his enemy [2507] &para; And Salamon sai&thorn; wel fool is he &thorn;at of al ha&thorn; drede [2508] &para; ffor <MILESTONE N="225a" UNIT="folio">certes he &thorn;at &thorn;urgh hardynesse of his herte and &thorn;urgh &thorn;e hardynes of himself ha&thorn; so gret presumpcion him schal yuele betyde [2509] &para; Thenne 
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="511"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="224"> schuln &yogh;e euermore encountrewayte enbusschement&yogh; and alle espyaile. [2510] ffor as sai&thorn; &thorn;e wise man . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> [2511] he ne falle&thorn; in to no periles &thorn;at periles eschewe&thorn; [2512] &para; And al be it/ so &thorn;at &thorn;ou seme &thorn;at &thorn;ou be in secre place &yogh;et schalt &thorn;ou alwey don diligence in the kepynge of &thorn;in persone [2513] &thorn;is is to say. Ne be nou&yogh;t necligent to kepe &thorn;in persone nought only fro &thorn;in grettest enemy . but only fro &thorn;in leste enemy [2514] Senek sai&thorn; a man &thorn;at is wel auysed he drede&thorn; his leste enemy [2515] Ovide sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e lytel wesel wol sle &thorn;e grete bole and &thorn;e wilde hert [2516] And &thorn;e prouerbe sai&thorn; &thorn;at a luytel &thorn;orne may greeue a king ful sore &para; And a litel hound wol holde &thorn;e wilde bore [2517] &para; But na&thorn;eles I say nought &thorn;ou schalt be so coward &thorn;at &thorn;ou doute wher as is no drede [2518] &para; The bok sai&thorn; that some men haue gret lust to disceyue but &yogh;it &thorn;ey drede to be de|sceyued [2519] . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE> And kepe &thorn;e fro &thorn;e company of Scorners [2520] &para; ffor &thorn;e book sai&thorn; &thorn;at scorners ne make&thorn; no companye but flee here word as venym</P>
<P>[2521] &para; Now as to &thorn;e secounde poynt where as &yogh;oure wise counceilours counseiled &yogh;ou to warmstore &yogh;oure houses wi&thorn; gret diligence [2522] &para; I wolde fayn knowe how &thorn;at &yogh;e vnderstande &thorn;ilke wordes and what is &yogh;oure sentence.</P>
<P>[2523] Mellibeus answerde and sayde Certes I vnder|stande in &thorn;is wise &thorn;at I schal warmstore myn hous wi&thorn; toures suche as haue castelles and o&thorn;er maner of edifices &amp; armure and archers [2524] betwen which &thorn;ing if I may my persone and myn hous so kepe and defende &thorn;at myn enemys schuln be in drede myn hous for to approche.</P>
<P>[2525] to &thorn;is sentence answerde anon prudence warnysshing quod sche of heihe toures and of heihe edifices appertyne&thorn; somtyme to pryde [2526] And eek men make heihe toures [<I>et les grans &eacute;difices &agrave; grant travail et &agrave; grans</I> 
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="512"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="225"> <I>despens, et quant elles sont faites, elles ne vallent riens se elles ne sont defendues par sages et par bons amis loyaux, et &agrave; grans missions</I> (Le M&eacute;nagier, i. 209)] [2527] &para; And vnderstande wel &thorn;at &thorn;e grettest and &thorn;e strengest garnyson &thorn;at riche man may haue / as wel to kepen his persone and his goodes is [2528] &thorn;at he [be] biloued wi&thorn; his subiectes and with his neihebours [2529] &para; ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Tullius</NOTE> &thorn;us sai&thorn; Tullius That &thorn;er is a maner garnyson &thorn;at no man may venquysschen ne discomfite and &thorn;at is [2530] a lord to be loued of his cite&yogh;eins and of his poeple</P>
<P>[2531] &para; Now sire as to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde poynt where as &yogh;oure olde and wise counseiloures sayden &para; &thorn;at &yogh;ou ne oughte nou&yogh;t sodeinly ne hastely proceden in &thorn;is neede [2532] But &thorn;at &yogh;e oughten purueyen and apparayle &yogh;ou in &thorn;is caas wi&thorn; gret diligence and with gret deliberacion [2533] &para; Trewely I trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ay sayden right wisly and right so&thorn; [2534] &para; ffor Tullius sai&thorn; In euery<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Tullius.</NOTE> neede er &thorn;ou begynne it apparayle &thorn;e with gret diligence. [2535] &thorn;enne say I &thorn;at in vengaunce takyng in werre in <MILESTONE N="225b" UNIT="folio">bataille and in warnestoringe [2536] er &thorn;ou bygynne &para; I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou apparayle &thorn;e &thorn;er to &para; And do it wi&thorn; gret deliberacion [2537] &para; ffor Tullius sai&thorn;. &thorn;at lange apparaylinge biforn &thorn;e bataile<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Tullius.</NOTE> make&thorn; schort victory [2538] &para; And Cassidorus sai&thorn; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cassidorus</NOTE> garnyson is strenger whan it is long tyme avised</P>
<P>[2539] But now lete vs speke of &thorn;e counseil &thorn;at was acorded by oure neyheboures suche as don &yogh;ou reuerence wi&thorn;outen loue [2540] &yogh;oure olde enemys recon|siled &para; &yogh;oure flaterers [2541] &thorn;at counceleden &yogh;ou cer|teyn &thorn;inges priuely and openly counseileden &yogh;ou &thorn;e contrarie [2542] &para; The &yogh;onge folk also &thorn;at counseiled &yogh;ou to vengen &yogh;ou and to maken werre anon. [2543] &para; And certes sire as I haue sayde byforn; &yogh;e haue gretly y-erred to han y-cleped suche maner of folk to &yogh;oure counselle [2544] &para; Whiche counseiloures / ben ynough reproued by &thorn;e resons aforn sayde [2545] &para; But na&thorn;eles let vs now descende to 
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="513"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="226"> &thorn;e special &yogh;e schuln ferst proceden after &thorn;e doctrine of Tullius [2546] &para; Certes the trou&thorn;e of &thorn;is matier ey&thorn;er of &thorn;is counseil nede&thorn; not diligently enqueren [2547] &para; ffor it is wel wiste whiche &thorn;ey ben &thorn;at doon &yogh;ou &thorn;is trespas &amp; vilenye [2548] and how many trespasoures and in what manere &thorn;ey han don to &yogh;ou al &thorn;is wronge and alle &thorn;is vilanye [2549] &para; And after &thorn;is &thorn;anne schullen &yogh;e examine &yogh;e secounde condicion &thorn;e which &thorn;at Tullius addeth in &thorn;is matiere [2550] &para; ffor Tullius putte&thorn; a &thorn;ing which &thorn;at he clepe&thorn; consentynge &thorn;is is to say [2551] who ben &thorn;ay and whiche ben &thorn;ay and how many &thorn;at consenten to &thorn;in counseil in &thorn;in willefulnesse to don hasty vengeance [2552] &para; And let vs concidre also who ben &thorn;ay and how many ben &thorn;ay . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &thorn;at consenten to &yogh;oure aduersaries [2553] And certes as to &thorn;e ferste poynt &para; hit is wel knowen whiche ben &thorn;ay &thorn;at consenten to oure hastyf wilful|nesse [2554] &para; ffor trewely alle &thorn;o &thorn;at counselen &yogh;ou to maken sodeyn werre ne ben nought &yogh;oure frendes [2555] &para; let se now whiche ben &thorn;ey &thorn;at &yogh;e holden so gretly &yogh;oure frendes as to &yogh;oure persone [2556] &para; ffor al be it so &thorn;at &yogh;e ben mighty and ryche; certes &yogh;e ben but allone [2557] &para; ffor certes &yogh;e ne han no childe but a doughter [2558] ne &yogh;e han no bre&thorn;eren ne cosyns germayns ne non o&thorn;er neih kynrede [2559] &para; Wherfore &yogh;oure enemys scholden stinte to plede wi&thorn; &yogh;ou ne to destruye &yogh;oure persone. [2560] &yogh;e knowen also &thorn;at &yogh;oure richesse moot ben dispended in diuerse partyes [2561] &amp; when &thorn;at euery wight ha&thorn; his parte; &thorn;ey woln take but litel rewarde to vengen &thorn;y de&thorn; [2562] &para; But &thorn;in enemys ben &thorn;re and &thorn;ey haue many children bre&thorn;eren cosyns and o&thorn;er neyh kynrede [2563] &para; And &thorn;ough so were &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest slayn of hem two o&thorn;er .iij. &yogh;et dwellen &thorn;ere ynowe to <MILESTONE N="226a" UNIT="folio">awreken here de&thorn; and to slen &thorn;in persone [2564] &para; And &thorn;eih so be &thorn;at &yogh;oure kynrede be more siker and stedefast &thorn;en 
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="514"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="227"> &thorn;e kyn of &yogh;oure aduersary [2565] &para; &yogh;et neuer &thorn;e les &yogh;oure kynrede is but after kynrede &thorn;ey ben but litel sibbe to &yogh;ou [2566] &para; And &thorn;e kyn of &yogh;oure enemys ben neigh sibbe to hem &para; And certes as in &thorn;at he condicion is bettre &thorn;en is &yogh;oures [2567] &para; &thorn;enne let vs consideren also of &thorn;e counseilynge of hem &thorn;at counseleden &yogh;ou to taken sodeyn vengeance whe&thorn;er it acorde to reson or non. [2568] and certes &yogh;e knowen wel nay. [2569] ffor as by right and reson &thorn;er may no man take vengaunce of no wight &para; But &thorn;e Iugge &thorn;at ha&thorn; Iurdixion of hit [2570] whan it is graunted him to take &thorn;ilke vengeaunce hastely or at|temperelly as &thorn;e lawe requyre&thorn; [2571] &para; And &yogh;et more ouer of &thorn;ilke worde &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; consenting; [2572] &thorn;ou schalt consente if &thorn;in mighte &amp; &thorn;in power may consente and suffice to &thorn;in wilfulnesse and to &thorn;in counseiloures [2573] &para; And certes &thorn;ou mayst wel say &thorn;at nay [2574] &para; ffor sikerly as for to speken proprely we may do no &thorn;ing but oonly such &thorn;ing as we may doon rightfully [2575] &para; And certes rightfully ne may &yogh;e take no vengaunce as of &yogh;oure propre auctorie [2576] &para; Then may &yogh;e seen &thorn;at &yogh;oure power ne consente&thorn; nou&yogh;t ne acorde&thorn; nou&yogh;t with &yogh;our willefulnesse [2577] Now lete vs examine &thorn;e &thorn;ridde poynt &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; consequent [2578] Thou schalt vnderstanden &thorn;at &thorn;e vengaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ou purposest for to take is conse|quent [2579] And &thorn;erfore falle&thorn; ano&thorn;er vengaunce. Peril. and werre and o&thorn;re damages withouten nombre of whiche we ben nou&yogh; warre as at &thorn;is tyme [2580] &para; And as touchinge &thorn;e for&thorn;e poynt/. &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; en|gendrynge [2581] &para; &thorn;ou schalt considere &thorn;at &thorn;is wrang which &thorn;at is don to &thorn;e is engendred of &thorn;e hate of &thorn;in enemys [2582] and of &thorn;e vengeance takynge &para; And vpon &thorn;at wolde engendre ano&thorn;er vengeance and mochel sorwe and wastyng of richesse as I sayde er</P>
<P>[2583] &para; Now sir as touchinge to &thorn;e poynt &thorn;at Tullius clepe&thorn; causes which &thorn;at is &thorn;e laste poynt [2584] &para; Thou 
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="515"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="228"> schalt vnderstande &thorn;at &thorn;e wrong &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast receyued ha&thorn; certein causes [2585] whiche &thorn;at clerkes clepen Oriens et Officiens and causa longinqua and causa propinqua &para; This is to sayn &thorn;e ferre cause [<I>et la prou|chaine;</I> [2586] <I>la loingtaine est Dieu qui est cause de toutes causes</I> [2587] <I>la prouchaine est tes trois ennemis</I> (Le M&eacute;n. i. 212)] [2588] accidental was hate [2589] The causes material ben &thorn;e .v. woundes of &thorn;in dou&yogh;ter [2590] &para; The cause formale is &thorn;e maner of here worchinge &thorn;at brou&yogh;ten laddres and clomben in at &thorn;ine wyndowes / [2591] &para; The cause final was for to slee &thorn;in dou&yogh;ter it latted nought in as moche as in hem was [2592] &para; But for to speken of &thorn;e ferre cause as <MILESTONE N="226b" UNIT="folio">what ende &thorn;ey schullen come Or what schal betyden of hem in &thorn;is caas ne can I nou&yogh;t deeme. but by coniectyng and by supposynge [2593] ffor we schuln suppose [<I>qu'ils avendront</I>] to a wicked ende. [2594] by cause &thorn;e book of decrees saith &para; Selden or wi&thorn; gret peyne ben causes brou&yogh;t to an ende when &thorn;ey ben baldly bygonne</P>
<P>[2595] Now sir if men asked me why &thorn;at &yogh;e suffren men to don &yogh;ou &thorn;is vilenye Certes I can not wel answere as for no so&thorn;fastnes [2596] ffor &thorn;e appostel sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e sciences and &thorn;e Iuggementz of oure lord god ben mighty and deepe [2597] &para; Ther may no man comprehende ne serche hem sufficiently [2598] &para; Na&thorn;eles by certeins presumpcions &amp; coniectynges I halde and bileeue [2599] &thorn;at god &thorn;at is ful of Iustice and of rightwisnesse ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;is bytyde by iuste cause resonable</P>
<P>[2600] &para; &thorn;in name is mellibe &thorn;is is to say a man &thorn;at drinke&thorn; hony [2601] &para; Thou hast y-drunke so meche hony of &thorn;e swete temperel richesses and delices &amp; hon|ures of &thorn;is world [2602] &thorn;at &thorn;ou art drunken and hast for&yogh;eten oure lord ihu crist &thorn;in creatour [2603] &para; Thou hast nou&yogh;t don to him such honour as &thorn;e oughte [2604] &para; Ne &thorn;ou hast nou&yogh;t wel take heede to 
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="516"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="229"> &thorn;e wordes of Ovide &thorn;at sai&thorn; [2605] vnder &thorn;e hony of &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;in body is hyd &thorn;e venym &thorn;at slee&thorn; &thorn;e soule [2606] &para; And Salomon sai&thorn; &para; If &thorn;ou hast founden hony ete of hit what suffice&thorn; [2607] &para; ffor if &thorn;ou ete of hit out of mesure / &thorn;ou schalt spewe and be needy and pore [2608] &para; And peraduenture crist hath &thorn;e in spite and ha&thorn; turned away fro &thorn;e his face and his eres of misericorde [2609] and also he ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ben y-punyssht/ in &thorn;e maner &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast y-trespast [2610] &para; Thow hast don synne a&yogh;eins oure lord ihu crist [2611] &para; ffor certes &thorn;e &thorn;re enemys of man|kynde &thorn;at is to say &thorn;e fleissch. &thorn;e ffeend. and &thorn;e worlde [2612] &para; &thorn;ou hast suffred hem to entre in &thorn;in herte wilfully by &thorn;e wyndowes of &thorn;y body [2613] and hast nou&yogh;t defended &thorn;e sufficeantly a&yogh;eins here defautes and here temptacions So &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue wounded &thorn;i soule in fyue place. [2614] &para; this is to sayn &thorn;e deedly synnes &thorn;at ben entrede in to &thorn;in herte by &thorn;ine .v. wittes [2615] And in &thorn;e same manere oure lord ihesu crist ha&thorn; and wolde and ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;at &thorn;ine &thorn;re enemys ben entred in to &thorn;in hous by &thorn;e wyndowes [2616] and han wounded &thorn;ine doughtres in &thorn;e forseyde manere</P>
<P>[2617] &para; Certes quod Mellibe I se wel &thorn;at &thorn;at &yogh;e en|force &yogh;ou mochel by wordes to ouercome me in such a manere &thorn;at I schal now vengen me of myn enemys [2618] Schewynge me &thorn;e periles and &thorn;e eueles &thorn;at mighten ffalle of &thorn;is vengeance [2619] &para; But who so wolde considere in alle vengances <MILESTONE N="227a" UNIT="folio">&thorn;e periles and eueles &thorn;at mighte sewe of vengance takynge; [2620] a man wolde neuere take vengance and &thorn;at were harme; [2621] ffor by &thorn;e veng|aunce takynge ben &thorn;e wickede men disseuered fro &thorn;e goode men [2622] &para; And &thorn;o &thorn;at han wille to don wicked|nesse restreynen here wickede purpos whan &thorn;ey seen &thorn;e punysschyng and &thorn;e chastysing of trespasours</P>
<P>[2623] [And to this answered dame Prudence: 'Certes,' said she, 'I grant you that from vengeance come many 
<PB REF="00000545.tif" N="517"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="230"> benefits as well as many evils: [2624] yet vengeance be|longeth not to "a singuler persone," but only to the judges, and to those who have jurisdiction over evil-doers.'] [2625] &para; And &yogh;it say I more &thorn;at right as a singuler persone synne&thorn; in takinge vengance of ano&thorn;er man; [2626] Right so synne&thorn; &thorn;e Iugge if he take no vengance of hem &thorn;at it han desserued // [2627] ffor Senek sai&thorn; &thorn;us &thorn;at mayster is good &thorn;at reproeue&thorn; schrewes [2628] &para; And as Cassidory sai&thorn;. A man dredeth to don outrages; whan he woot and knowe&thorn; &thorn;at it displese&thorn; &thorn;e Iuge and &thorn;e soueraignes [2629] &para; And ano&thorn;er sai&thorn; &thorn;e Iugge &thorn;at dredeth do don right make&thorn; schrewes [2630] &para; And seint Poul &thorn;e appostel sai&thorn; in his epistle whan he write&thorn; vnto &thorn;e Romayns that &thorn;e Iuges beren nought &thorn;e spere wi&thorn;outen cause. [2631] but &thorn;ay beren it to punysschen &thorn;e schrewes and &thorn;e mysdoers and for to de|fende &thorn;e goode men [2632] &para; If &yogh;e woln &thorn;enne take vengance of &yogh;oure enemys; &yogh;e schuln retourne or haue &yogh;oure recours to &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;e Iurdexion vpon him [2633] &amp; he schal punyssche hem as &thorn;e lawe axe&thorn; and requyre&thorn;</P>
<P>[2634] &para; A quod Mellibe &thorn;is vengance like&thorn; me no&thorn;ing [2635] &para; I be&thorn;inke me now how fortune ha&thorn; norisched me fro my childhode and ha&thorn; holpen me to passe many a straunge pas [2636] &para; Now wol I assayen here trowynge with goddes grace and helpe &thorn;at sche schal helpe me my schame for to venge</P>
<P>[2637] &para; Certes quod Prudence if &yogh;e woln worche by my counseille; &yogh;e schuln nou&yogh;t assaye fortune by no way. [2638] Ne &yogh;e schuln nought lene ne borwe vnto hire after &thorn;e word of Senek [2639] ffor &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben folily doon and &thorn;at ben in hope of ffortune schuln neuere come to a good ende [2640] &para; and as &thorn;e same senek sei&thorn; &para; The more clere and &thorn;e more schynynge &thorn;at fortune is; &thorn;e more brutel and &thorn;e sonnere y-broke sche is [2641] &para; truste&thorn; nou&yogh;t in hire for sche nys no&thorn;ing stedefast ne stable [2642] ffor when &thorn;ou trowest to be most siker or seure of hire 
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="518"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="231"> helpe; sche wol fayle &thorn;e and disceyue &thorn;e [2643] &para; And wher as &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at fortune ha&thorn; norisshed &yogh;ou fro &yogh;oure childhode [2644] I say &yogh;ou &thorn;at in so mochel schuln &yogh;e &thorn;e lasse trusten in hire and in hire witte [2645] &para; ffor Senek sai&thorn; that what man is norisched by fortune; sche make&thorn; him to gret a fool [2646] &para; Now &thorn;enne se&thorn;ens &yogh;e desire and aske vengance &para; And &thorn;e vengance &thorn;at is doon after &thorn;e lawe and biforn &thorn;e Iugge ne like&thorn; <MILESTONE N="227b" UNIT="folio">&yogh;ou nought [2647] and &thorn;e vengance &thorn;at is don in hope of fortune is peril|ous and vncerteyn [2648] &para; Thenne haue &yogh;e non o&thorn;er remedye but for to haue &yogh;oure recours vnto &thorn;e soueraign Iuge &thorn;at venge&thorn; alle vilanyes and wronges [2649] &para; And he schal venge &yogh;ou after &thorn;at &thorn;in self witnesse&thorn; [ . . . . . ] [2650] leue&thorn; &thorn;e vengance to me and I schal don hit</P>
<P>[2651] &para; Mellibe answerde &para; If I ne venge me nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e wrong &thorn;at men han doon to me [2652] &para; I schal sompne or warne hem &thorn;at han don &thorn;is vilanye to me and alle o&thorn;re to don me ano&thorn;er vilanye [2653] &para; ffor it is writen &para; If &thorn;ou take no vengance of an olde vilanye; &thorn;ou somp|nest &thorn;in aduersarie to don &thorn;e a newe vylanye [2654] [<I>Et ainsi, par souffrir l'en me feroit tant de villenies de toutes pars</I>] &thorn;at I mighte ney&thorn;er bere it ne sus|tene [2655] and so schulde I be ouersette and halden ouer lowe [2656] &para; ffor men sayn &para; In mochil suffrynge schullen many &thorn;inges falle vnto &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ou schalt not mowe suffre</P>
<P>[2657] &para; Certes quod Prudence I graunte &thorn;at ouer mochil suffrance / is nought good [2658] &para; But &yogh;et ne folwe&thorn; it nou&yogh;t &thorn;er-of &thorn;at euery persone to whom men don vilanye take of it vengance [2659] ffor &thorn;at apper|tene&thorn; and longe&thorn; al only to &thorn;e Iuges ffor &thorn;ey schuln venge &thorn;e vilenyes and &thorn;e iniuries [2660] and &thorn;erfore &thorn;o tuo auctoritees &thorn;at &yogh;e han sayde aboue ben oonly vnderstanden in &thorn;e Iuges [2661] &para; ffor whan &thorn;ey suffren ouer mochil &thorn;e wronges and vilanyes ben don 
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="519"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="232"> wi&thorn;outen punysschinge [2662] &thorn;ay sompne nou&yogh;t a man only for to do newe wronges but &thorn;ay comaunden it [2663] &para; Also a wise man sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at cor|recte&thorn; nou&yogh;t &thorn;e synnere comaunde&thorn; and bidde&thorn; him to do synne [2664] &para; And &thorn;e souerains and &thorn;e Iuges / mighten in here lande so mochel suffren of &thorn;e schrewes and mysdoers [2665] &thorn;at &thorn;ey schulden by such suffraunce / by proces of tyme wexen of suche power and might &thorn;at &thorn;ey schulde putte oute &thorn;e Iuges and &thorn;e soueraignes from here places [2666] and at &thorn;e laste maken hem leesen here lordschipes</P>
<P>[2667] &para; But let vs now putte &thorn;at &yogh;e han leue to vengen &yogh;ou [2668] &para; If &yogh;e ben nou&yogh;t of might and power as now to vengen &yogh;ou [2669] ffor if &yogh;e woln maken comparison vnto &thorn;e might of &yogh;oure aduersaries &para; &yogh;e schullen fynden in many &thorn;inges &thorn;at I haue schewed &yogh;ou ben &thorn;is &thorn;at here condicion is bettre &thorn;an &yogh;oures [2670] &para; And &thorn;erfore say I &thorn;at it is good as now &thorn;at &yogh;e suffre and be pacient</P>
<P>[2671] &para; ffer&thorn;ermore &yogh;e knowen &thorn;at after &thorn;e commune sawe it is a woodnesse a man to streyne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ (<I>margin</I>) stryue]</NOTE> a&yogh;eins a strenger or a more mighty man &thorn;en is himself [2672] &para; And for to stryue wi&thorn; a man of euene streng&thorn;e &thorn;at is to say <MILESTONE N="228a" UNIT="folio">wi&thorn; a strong man as he is it is peril [2673] &para; And for to stryue wi&thorn; a waykare man it is folye. [2674] and &thorn;erfore schulde a man fle stryuyng/ as mochel as he mighte [2675] &para; As Salomon saith &para; It is a gret worschipe to kepyn him fro noyse and stryf [2676] &para; And if it so bifalle or happe &thorn;at a man of grettere might and streng&thorn;e &thorn;an &thorn;ou art do &thorn;e greuaunce [2677] study and busy &thorn;e ra&thorn;er to stille &thorn;e same greuaunce &thorn;an for to venge &thorn;e [2678] &para; ffor Senek sai&thorn; &thorn;at he putte&thorn; him in gret perile &thorn;at stryue&thorn; wi&thorn; a gretter man &thorn;an he is himself [2679] &para; And Catoun sai&thorn; if a man of heyer astate or degre or more mighty &thorn;en &thorn;ou do &thorn;e annoye or greuance Suffre him [2680] for he &thorn;at ones ha&thorn; greued &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="520"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="233"> may ano&thorn;er tyme releue &thorn;e and helpe &thorn;e [2681] &para; &yogh;it sette I cas &yogh;e han bo&thorn;e might and licence to vengen &yogh;ou [2682] I say &thorn;at &thorn;er ben many &thorn;inges &thorn;at schuln restreynen &yogh;ou of vengannce takinge [2683] and make &yogh;ou for to encline and for to suffre and for to haue pacience in &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at han be don to &yogh;ou [2684] &para; ffirste and for&thorn;ward if &yogh;e woln concider &thorn;e defautes &thorn;at ben in &yogh;oure owne persone [2685] for whiche defautes god ha&thorn; suffred &yogh;ou to haue &thorn;is tribulacion as I haue sayde &yogh;ou here byforn. [2686] &para; ffor &thorn;e Poete sai&thorn; &thorn;at we oughten paciently taken &thorn;e tribu|lacions &thorn;at come&thorn; / to vs when we &thorn;enken and consydren &thorn;at we han disserued to han hem [2687] &para; And seint Gregory sai&thorn; &para; &thorn;at whan a man considere&thorn; wel &thorn;e nombre of his defautes and of his synnes [2688] &thorn;e peynes and &thorn;e tribulacions &thorn;at he suffre&thorn; semen &thorn;e lasse vnto him [2689] &para; And in als mochel as him &thorn;enk|e&thorn; his synnes &thorn;e more heuy and greuous. [2690] &para; In so moche seme&thorn; his peyne &thorn;e lighter and &thorn;e esyer vnto him [2691] &para; Also &yogh;e owen to encline and to bowen &yogh;oure herte to taken &thorn;e pacience of oure lord Ihesu crist as sai&thorn; seint Petre in his Epistles [2692] &para; Ihesu crist he sai&thorn; ha&thorn; suffred for vs and &yogh;euen ensample vnto euery man to folwe and to sewe him [2693] ffor he dede neuer synne ne neuere ne came a vileyns word out of his mou&thorn; [2694] when men cursed him he cursed hem nought &para; And when men beten him he manased hem nought [2695] &para; Also &thorn;e grece pacience whiche seintes &thorn;at ben in paradys. han had in tribulacions &thorn;at &thorn;ey han suffred wi&thor