<P>[2741] &para; Whan Prudence hadde herd hire housbande to auaunten him of his richesse and of his moneye and dispreys|inge of power and his aduersaries &para; &para; Sche spake and sayde on &thorn;is wise [2742] &para; Certis deere sir I graunte &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e ben riche and mighty [2743] &para; And &thorn;at &thorn;e richesses ben goode to hem &thorn;at han wel y-geten hem and &thorn;at wel can vsen hem [2744] &para; ffor right as &thorn;e body of man may nought lyue wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e soule &para; No more may it lyue withouten temperele goodes [2745] and by rich|esse may a man geten him grace [2746] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Pamphilles If eny gaddes doughter he sai&thorn; be riche. Sche may cheese he sai&thorn; of a &thorn;ousand men [which she will for her husband [2747] and of the thousand] &para; oon wol nought forsaken hire ne refusen hire [2748] &para; And &thorn;is Pamphilles saith also &para; If &thorn;ou be ri&yogh;t happy &para; &thorn;at is to say. If &thorn;ou be right riche &thorn;ou schalt fynden a gret nombre of felawes and frendes [2749] &para; And if &thorn;in fortune chaunge&thorn; &thorn;at is if &thorn;ou wexe pore; ffare wel frendschipe and felaschipe [2750] &para; ffor &thorn;ou schalt ben allone wi&thorn;outen any companye but if it be &thorn;e companye of good folk [2751] &para; And &yogh;it sai&thorn; &thorn;is Pamphilles more ouer / &thorn;at &thorn;ey &thorn;at ben &thorn;ralle &amp; bonde of linage schuln ben maad wor&thorn;y and noble by &thorn;e richesses. [2752] &para; And right so as by richesses &thorn;er comen many goodes &para; Right so by pouert come&thorn; many harmes and eueles. [2753] ffor gret pouert con|streigne&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="524"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="237"> <MILESTONE N="229b" UNIT="folio">a man to don many eueles. [2754] And &thorn;er|fore clepe&thorn; Cassidore Pouert. &thorn;e mooder of ruyne [2755] &thorn;at is to say &thorn;e moder of ouer&thorn;rowing or fallyng doun [2756] &para; And &thorn;erfore saith Pieres alphouns &para; On of &thorn;e grettest aduersary of &thorn;is world is [2757] when a freo by kynde or of bir&thorn;e is constreigned by pouert to eten &thorn;e almes of his enemy [2758] &para; And &thorn;e same sai&thorn; Innocent in oon of his bookes. &thorn;at sorwfulle and myshappy is &thorn;e condicion of a pouere begger [2759] &para; ffor if he axe nought his mete he deye&thorn; for hunger [2760] &para; And if he axe he deye&thorn; for schame &para; And algates necessite constreigne&thorn; him to axe [2761] &para; And &thorn;erfore sai&thorn; Salamon &thorn;at bettre is to deye &thorn;an to haue such pouert [2762] &para; &yogh;et sai&thorn; Sala|mon &thorn;at bettre is to deye of bitter de&thorn; &thorn;an for to lyue in suche wyse [2763] &para; By &thorn;ese resons &thorn;at I haue sayde vnto &yogh;ou and by many o&thorn;er resons &thorn;at I kou&thorn;e say [2764] &para; I graunte &yogh;ou &thorn;at richesse ben good to hem &thorn;at geten hem wel and to hem &thorn;at wel vsen &thorn;e richesses [2765] &para; And &thorn;erfore wol I schewe &yogh;ow how &yogh;e schuln haue &yogh;ou [<I>en acquerant Richesses et en amassant icelles</I>
