<P>[2896] &para; Then sayde dame Prudence &para; I make no semblaunt of wra&thorn;&thorn;e / ne of anger but for &yogh;oure owne profyt [2897] &para; ffor Salomon sai&thorn; &para; he is <MILESTONE N="232a" UNIT="folio">more wor&thorn; &thorn;at re|proue&thorn; or chide&thorn; a fool for his folye schewing him semblant of wra&thorn;&thorn;e; [2898] &thorn;an he &thorn;at supporte&thorn; him / . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> in his mysdoynge &amp; laughe&thorn; at his folye [2899] &para; And &thorn;is same Salomon sai&thorn; afterward &thorn;at by &thorn;e sorwful visage of man &thorn;at is to say by sory and heuy contynaunce of a man [2900] &thorn;e folk correcte&thorn; and amende&thorn; him self</P>
