<P>[2942] &para; Certes quod Prudence &para; It is an hard &thorn;ing and right perilous [2943] &thorn;at a man putte him al outrely in &thorn;e arbitracion and Iuggement and in &thorn;e might &amp; power of his enmys [2944] &para; ffor Salamon sai&thorn; &para; leeue&thorn; me and &yogh;eue&thorn; credence to &thorn;at &thorn;at I schal sayn &para; I say yeuere peple and gouernours of holy chirche [2945] to &thorn;in sone to &thorn;in wyf [<I>&agrave; ton fr&egrave;re</I>] and to &thorn;in freende [2946] [<I>ne donne puissance sur toy en toute ta vie</I> [2947] <I>Se il a doncques deffendu que l'en ne donne . . . &agrave; fr&egrave;re ne &agrave; ami</I> (Le M&eacute;nagier, i. 230)] &thorn;e might of his body [2948] &para; By a strenger reson he defende&thorn; and forbede&thorn; a man to &yogh;iue himself vnto his enemy [2949] &para; And na&thorn;e|les I counseile &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e mystruste nou&yogh;t my lord [2950] &para; ffor I wot wel and knowe wel &thorn;at he is debonaire and meke large &amp; courteys [2951] and no &thorn;ing desirous of good ne coueytous to haue richesse [2952] &para; ffor &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing in &thorn;is world &thorn;at he desire&thorn; saue worschipe and honour [2953] &para; ffor&thorn;ermore I knowe wel and I am right seur &thorn;at he schal no&thorn;ing do in &thorn;is neede withouten my counseil [2954] &para; And I schal so worchen in &thorn;is cause by &thorn;e grace of oure lord god &thorn;at &yogh;e schuln ben reconsiled vnto vs</P>
<P>[2955] &para; &thorn;enne sayden &thorn;ey wi&thorn; oo voys &para; Worschipful 
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="534"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="247"> lady we putten vs and oure goodes al fully in &yogh;oure wille and disposicion [2956] and [been] redy to come what [day] &yogh;ou like&thorn; vnto &yogh;oure noblesse to lymyten vs or to assignen vs [2957] for to maken oure obligacion and bond as strong as it like&thorn; vnto &yogh;oure goodnesse [2958] &thorn;at we may fulfille &thorn;e wille of &yogh;ou and of my lord Mellibe</P>
<P>[2959] &para; Whan dame Prudence hadde herd &thorn;e an|sweres of &thorn;ese men; sche bad hem gon ayayn pryuyly [2960] &para; And sche<MILESTONE N="233a" UNIT="folio"> retourned a&yogh;ein to hire lord Mellybe and tolde him how sche fond his aduersaries ful repentaunt [2961] and knowlechinge ful reuerently and lowely here synnes and here trespaces and how &thorn;ey weren redy to suffre alle peyne. [2962] requyrynge and preyng him of mercy and pite</P>
<P>[2963] &para; Thenne sayde Mellibe: he is wel wor&thorn;y to haue pardon and for&yogh;euenesse [<I>qui ne excuse point son p&eacute;chi&eacute;</I>, [2964] <I>mais le recongnoist et s'en repent et demande indulgence;</I> [2965] <I>car S&eacute;n&egrave;que dit l&agrave; est r&eacute;mission</I> (Le M&eacute;nagier, i. 231)] wher as confession is [2966] &para; ffor confession is neighebor to Innocence [2967] &para; And he saith in ano&thorn;er place &para; he &thorn;at ha&thorn; schame for his synne and knowleche&thorn; it . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap</NOTE> &para; And &thorn;erfore I assente and conferme to haue pees [2968] &para; But it is good &thorn;at we do it nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;outen &thorn;e assente and wille of oure freendes</P>
<P>[2969] &para; Then was Prudence right glad and Ioyeful and sayde [2970] &para; Certes sire quod sche &para; &yogh;e han goodly and wel answered [2971] &para; ffor right as by counseil assent and helpynge of &yogh;oure frendes &yogh;e han ben styred to vengen &yogh;ou and make werre; [2972] Right so wi&thorn;|outen here counseil schulle &yogh;e nought acorde &thorn;ough &yogh;e ne haue pees wi&thorn; &yogh;oure aduersaries [2973] &para; ffor &thorn;e lawe saith &para; &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing so good by way of kynde as &thorn;ing to ben vnbounden by hym &thorn;at it was y-bounde</P>
<P>[2974] &para; And &thorn;enne dame Prudence wi&thorn;outen delay or taryinge sent anon messagers for hire kyn and for hire olde frendes whiche &thorn;at were trewe and wyse [2975] 
<PB REF="00000563.tif" N="535"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="248"> &para; and tolde hem by ordre in &thorn;e presence of Mellybe al &thorn;e matiere as it is abouen expressed and declared [2976] &para; and preyden hem &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden yeuen hire a wyse coun|seille &para; what best were to doon in &thorn;is matiere [2977] &para; And whan mellibeus counseil hadde taken here avys and good de|liberacion of &thorn;e forsayde matiere [2978] and hadden examyned it by gret busynesse and gret diligence [2979] &thorn;ey &yogh;euen ful counseil for to haue pees and reste [2980] And &thorn;at Mellibe schulde receyue hit with good herte of his aduersaries to for&yogh;iuenes and mercy</P>
<P>[2981] &para; And whan dame Prudence hadde herde &thorn;e assent of hire lord Mellibe and &thorn;e counseil of hire frendes [2982] acorded wi&thorn; hire wille and entencion [2983] sche was wonderly glad in herte and sayde [2984] &para; Ther is an olde prouerbe quod sche sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e goodnesse &thorn;at &thorn;u mayst do &thorn;is day do it [2985] and abyd it/ nought ne delay it nought til to morwe [2986] &para; And &thorn;erfore I counseile &thorn;at &yogh;e sende &yogh;oure messagers whiche &thorn;at ben discrete and wise [2987] vnto &yogh;oure aduersaries / tellynge hem in &yogh;oure bihalue [2988] if &thorn;ey wolen trete of pees and acorde [2989] &thorn;at &thorn;ey schapen hem wi&thorn;outen delay or taryynge comynge to vs [2990] &para; which &thorn;ing performed was in dede [2991] and whan &thorn;ese trespasoures and repentynge folk of here folyes &thorn;at is to say &thorn;e aduersaries of Mellibe [2992] hadden herde what &thorn;ese messangeres <MILESTONE N="233b" UNIT="folio"> sayden vnto hem; [2993] &thorn;ey weren ful glad and ioyfulle and answerden ful mekely and benygnely [2994] &yogh;eldynge graces and &thorn;ankes to here lord Mellibe and to alle his companye [2995] &para; and schopen hem wi&thorn;outen delay to go wi&thorn; &thorn;e messangeres and obeye to &thorn;e comaundement of here lord Mellibe</P>
<P>[2996] &para; And right anon &thorn;ey token here wey to Mellibe [2997] &para; And toke &thorn;e somme of here trewe wordes and frendes to maken fei&thorn; for hem and for to ben here borwes [2998] &para; And whanne &thorn;ey comen to 
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="536"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="249"> &thorn;e presence of Mellibe &para; he seyde hem &thorn;ese wordes [2999] &para; It stant &thorn;us quod Mellibe and so&thorn; it is &thorn;at &yogh;e [3000] causeles and wi&thorn;outen skile and reson [3001] han don grete Iniuries and wronges to me and to my wyf Dame Prudence and to myn doughter also [3002] &para; ffor &yogh;e han entred in-to myn hous by vyolence [3003] and han doon suche outrage &thorn;at alle men knowen wel &thorn;at &yogh;e han disserued &thorn;e de&thorn; [3004] &para; And &thorn;erfore wil I knowen and wyten of &yogh;ou [3005] whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &yogh;e wollen putte &thorn;e punysschement and chastisyng and &thorn;e vengaunce of &thorn;is outrage in &thorn;e wille of me and my wyf dame Prudence or &yogh;e woln nou&yogh;t</P>
<P>[3006] &para; Thenne &thorn;e wisest of hem &thorn;re answerde for hem alle and sayde [3007] sir quod he we knowen wel &thorn;at we ben vnwor&thorn;y to come to &yogh;oure court of so gret a lord and of so wor&thorn;y as &yogh;e ben [3008] ffor we han so gretly mystaken vs and han offended and agult in such a wise a&yogh;eins &yogh;our heighe lordschipe. [3009] &thorn;at trewly we han deserued &thorn;e deth [3010] &para; But &yogh;it for &thorn;e grete goodnesse and debonairte &thorn;at alle &thorn;e world witnesse&thorn; of &yogh;oure persone [3011] &para; we submitten vs to &thorn;e excellence and benignite of &yogh;oure gracious lordschipe [3012] and ben redy to obeye to alle &yogh;our comaundementz [3013] besechynge &yogh;ou &thorn;at of &yogh;oure mercyable pite. &yogh;e woln considre oure grete repentaunce and lowe submission [3014] and to graunte vs for&yogh;euenesse of oure outragous trespas and offence [3015] &para; ffor wel we knowe &thorn;at &yogh;oure liberalle grace &amp; mercy strecche&thorn; fer&thorn;er in-to good nesse &thorn;an don oure outrageous gultes and trespaces in-to wickednesse. [3016] al be hit. &thorn;at cursedly and damp|nably we han gult a&yogh;eins &yogh;oure heyhe lordschipe</P>
<P>[3017] &para; Thenne Mellibe took him vp fro &thorn;e grounde ful benygnely [3018] and receyued here obligacions and here bandes by here o&thorn;es vppon here plegges and here borwes [3019] and assigned hem a certeyn day to retournen vnto his courtes [3020] &para; ffor to accepte and receyue &thorn;e sentences and 
<PB REF="00000565.tif" N="537"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="250"> &thorn;e Iuggementes &thorn;at Mellibe wolde comande to ben don on hem by &thorn;e causes a-forn sayde / [3021] whiche &thorn;inges ordeyned; euery man retournede <MILESTONE N="234a" UNIT="folio">to his hous</P>
<P>[3022] &para; And when &thorn;at dame Prudence saugh hire tyme sche f[r]eyned and axede hire lord mellibe [3023] what vengance he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to take of his aduersaries</P>
<P>[3024] To which mellibe answerde and sayde &para; Certez quod he I &thorn;enke and purpose fully [3025] to dis|herite hem of al &thorn;at &thorn;ay han &para; And for to putten hem in exile for euere</P>
<P>[3026] &para; Certes quod Dame Prudence &thorn;is were a cruel sentence and mochel a&yogh;eins reson [3027] &para; ffor &yogh;e ben riche ynough and han no neede of o&thorn;er mennes good [3028] and &yogh;e mighte lightly geten &yogh;ou a coueytous name [3029] which is a vicious &thorn;ing and oughte [be] eschewed of euery man [3030] &para; ffor after &thorn;e sawe of &thorn;e appostel Coueitise is roote of alle harmes [3031] &para; And &thorn;erfore it were bettre to lese so mochel good of &yogh;oure owne &thorn;an for to take of here good in &thorn;is manere [3032] &para; ffor better it is to leese good wi&thorn; worschipe &thorn;enne it is good to wynne worschipe wi&thorn; vilanye and schame [3033] &para; And euery man oughte to don his busynesse and to geten him a good name [3034] &para; and &yogh;et schal he nou&yogh;t only kepen him in kepyng of his good name [3035] &para; But he schal also enforcen him alwey to don som &thorn;ing by which he may renouelle his good name [3036] &para; ffor it is write &thorn;at &thorn;e olde goode loos or good name of a man is sone goon and passed when it is nou&yogh;t newed and re|nouelled [3037] &para; And as touchinge &thorn;at &yogh;e sayn &thorn;at &yogh;e woln exile &yogh;oure aduersaries [3038] &thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; me mochil a&yogh;eins reson and out of mesure [3039] &para; Con|sidere&thorn; &thorn;e power &thorn;at &yogh;e han &yogh;ouen &yogh;ou vpon hemself [3040] and it is writen. &thorn;at he is wor&thorn;y to lesen his priuilege &thorn;at misvse&thorn; it &para; The might and &thorn;e power &thorn;at is &yogh;ouen him. [3041] And I sette caas &thorn;at &yogh;e might annoye hem &thorn;at peyne by right and by lawe [3042] which I 
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="538"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="251"> trowe &yogh;e may nou&yogh;t do [3043] I say ne ne mighte nou&yogh;t putte it to execucion perauenture [3044] and &thorn;enne were it likly to retorne to &thorn;e werre as it was byforn [3045] &para; And &thorn;erfore if &yogh;e woln &thorn;at men do &yogh;ou obeis|sance; &yogh;e moste deme more curteisly [3046] &thorn;is is to sayn &yogh;e moste &yogh;iue more esy sentences and Iugementz [3047] &para; for it is writen &thorn;at he &thorn;at most courteisly comaundeth; to him men most obeyen [3048] &para; And &thorn;er|fore I pray &yogh;ou &thorn;at in &thorn;is necessite and in &thorn;is neede; &yogh;e casten &thorn;erfore to ouercome &yogh;oure herte [3049] &para; ffor Senek sai&thorn; &para; he &thorn;at oones ouercome&thorn; his herte; ouercome&thorn; twyes [3050] &para; And Tullius sai&thorn; &para; Ther is no &thorn;ing so comendable in a gret lord [3051] as whan he is debon|aire and meeke and appese&thorn; him meekely [3052] &para; And I pray &yogh;ou &thorn;at &yogh;e woln forbere now to do vengance [3053] in such a manere. &thorn;at &yogh;oure goode name may be kepte and conserued [3054] and &thorn;at man may haue <MILESTONE N="234b" UNIT="folio">cause and matiere to preyse &yogh;ou of pite and of mercy [3055] and &thorn;at &yogh;e han no cause to repente &yogh;ou of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e doon [3056] &para; ffor Senek sei&thorn;; he ouercome&thorn; in euel manere &thorn;at repente&thorn; him of his victory [3057] &para; Wher|fore I pray &yogh;ou let mercy be in &yogh;oure herte [3058] to &thorn;effecte and &thorn;e entent &thorn;at god almighty haue mercy vpon &yogh;ou in his laste Iuggement [3059] [<I>Car saint Jacques dit en son &eacute;pistre: jugement</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Le M&eacute;n. i. 235]</NOTE>] &para; wi&thorn;|outen mercy schal be to him &thorn;at ha&thorn; no mercy of ano&thorn;er wight</P>
<P>[3060] &para; Whan mellibe had herde &thorn;e grete skiles and resons of Dame Prudence and of hire wise informacions and techinges; [3061] his herte gan enclyne to &thorn;e wille of his wyf consyderyng to &thorn;e trewe entent [3062] con|formed him anon &para; And assented fully to worchen after hire counseil. [3063] and &thorn;anke&thorn; god of/ whom procedeth all goodnesse &thorn;at him sente a wyf of so gret discrecion [3064] &para; And when &thorn;e day came &thorn;at his aduer|saries schulde apperen in his presence; [3065] he spake 
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="539"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="252"> to hem ful goodly and sayde to hem in &thorn;is wise/ [3066] &para; Al be it so &thorn;at of &yogh;oure pruyde and by presumpcion and folye &para; and of &yogh;oure necligence and vnkunnynge [3067] &yogh;e han mysborn &yogh;ou and trespassed to me /./ [3068] &yogh;et for as meche as I se and byholde &yogh;oure grete humilite [3069] and &thorn;at &yogh;e ben sory and repentaunt of &yogh;oure gultes; [3070] it constreigneth me to do &yogh;ou grace and mercy [3071] &para; Wherfore I receyue &yogh;ou vnto my grace/ [3072] and for&yogh;iue &yogh;ou outrely alle &thorn;e offenses Iniuries and wronges &thorn;at &yogh;e han doon a&yogh;eins me and myne [3073] to &thorn;is effecte and to &thorn;is ende / &thorn;at god of his endeles mercy [3074] wol at &thorn;e tyme of oure deyinge for&yogh;iuen oure gultes &thorn;at we han trespast vnto him in &thorn;is wrecchede world // [3075] &para; ffor douteles if we ben sory and repentaunt of &thorn;e synnes and gultes &thorn;e whiche we han trespassed in &thorn;e sight of oure lord god; [3076] he is so fre and so mercy|ful [3077] &thorn;at he wol for&yogh;iuen vs oure gultes [3078] and bryngen vs to &thorn;ilke blisse &thorn;at neuer ha&thorn; ende. To which blisse he vs bringe That blood on crosse for vs gan springe Qui cum patre /</P>
<TRAILER>&para; Here ende&thorn; Chaucers tale of Mellibe //</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="540">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="253">
<HEAD>&para; Prologus Monachi<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 234, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan ended was &thorn;e tale of Mellibe</L>
<L N="3080">And of Prudence and hire benignite</L>
<L>Oure hoost sayde as I am fey&thorn;ful man</L>
<L>And By &thorn;e precious corpus Madryan</L>
<L>I hadde leuer &thorn;an a barel ale</L>
<L N="3084">That goode leef my wyf had herd &thorn;is tale</L>
<L>ffor sche nys no &thorn;ing of such pacience</L>
<L>As was &thorn;is Mellibeus wyf Prudence</L>
<L>By goddes bones whan I bete my knaues<MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3088">Sche bringe&thorn; me &thorn;e grete clobbed stanes</L>
<L>And crye&thorn; sle &thorn;e dogges euerychon</L>
<L>And breke bo&thorn;e bak and bon</L>
<L>And if &thorn;at any neyghebour of myne</L>
<L N="3092">Wol nou&yogh;t in chirche to my wif enclyne</L>
<L>Or be so hardy to hire to trespace</L>
<L>Whan sche come&thorn; home sche rumpeth me &thorn;e face</L>
<L>and crye&thorn; false coward wreke &thorn;in wyf</L>
<L N="3096">By corpus bones I wol haue &thorn;y knyf</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt haue my distaf and go spynne</L>
<L>ffro day to night right &thorn;us sche wol begynne</L>
<L>Allas sche sai&thorn; &thorn;at euer I was y-schape</L>
<L N="3100">To wedde a melksop or a coward ape /</L>
<L>That wil ben ouerled wi&thorn; euery wight</L>
<L>Thou darst nou&yogh;t stonde by &thorn;y wyf aright</L>
<L>This is my lyf but if &thorn;at I wolde fight</L>
<L N="3104">And out at &thorn;e dore anon I mot me dight</L>
<L>Or elles I am lost but if &thorn;at I</L>
<L>Be like a wilde leon fool hardy</L>
<L>I wot wel sche wol do me slee som day</L>
<L N="3108">Som neihebore and &thorn;anne I go my way</L>
<L>ffor I am perilous wi&thorn; knyf on honde /</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at I dar hire nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;stonde /
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="541"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="254"></L>
<L>ffor sche is bigge in armes by my fei&thorn;</L>
<L N="3112">That schal he fynde &thorn;at hire mysdo&thorn; or sei&thorn;</L>
<L>But lat vs passe away fro &thorn;is matiere /</L>
<L>My lord sire monk he sai&thorn; be mery of cheere /</L>
<L>ffor ye schul telle a tale trewely</L>
<L N="3116">Lo Rouchestre stant here faste by</L>
<L>Ryd for&thorn; myn owne lord brek nou&yogh;t our game</L>
<L>But by my trou&thorn;e I knowe nou&yogh;t &yogh;oure name /</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er I schal calle &yogh;ou my lord daun Iohn</L>
<L N="3120">Or Daun Thomas or elles Daun Albon</L>
<L>Of what hous be &yogh;e by your fader kyn</L>
<L>I vowe to god &thorn;ou hast a ful fayr skyn</L>
<L>It is a gentil pasture &thorn;er &thorn;ou gost<MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3124">Thou art nou&yogh;t like a penant or a gost</L>
<L>Vppon my fei&thorn; &thorn;ou art som officer</L>
<L>Som wor&thorn;y Sexteyn or som Celerer</L>
<L>ffor by my fader soule as to my dome</L>
<L N="3128">Thou art a maister whan &thorn;ou art at home</L>
<L>No pouer cloysterer ne no pouer novys</L>
<L>But gouernour wyly and wys</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-with-al of brawnes and of bones</L>
<L N="3132">A wel faryng persone for &thorn;e nones</L>
<L>I pray to god &yogh;iue him confusion</L>
<L>That ferst &thorn;e brought in to religion</L>
<L>Thou woldest haue ben a tredefoul aright</L>
<L N="3136">Haddest &thorn;ou as gret leue as &thorn;ou hast might</L>
<L>To perfourme al &thorn;y lust in engendure /</L>
<L>Thou haddest bygeten many a creature</L>
<L>Allas why werest &thorn;ou so wyd a Cope</L>
<L N="3140">God &yogh;if me sorwe and I were a Pope</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t oonly &thorn;ou but euery mighty man</L>
<L>Though he were schore heyhe vpon his pan</L>
<L>Schulde haue a wyf for al &thorn;is world is lorn</L>
<L N="3144">Religion ha&thorn; take vp al &thorn;e corn</L>
<L>Of tredyng and we borelle men ben schrimpes</L>
<L>Of feeble trees &thorn;er come&thorn; wrecched ympes
<PB REF="00000570.tif" N="542"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="255"></L>
<L>This make&thorn; &thorn;at oure heires ben so sclendre</L>
<L N="3148">And feble &thorn;at &thorn;ay may not wel engendre</L>
<L>This make&thorn; &thorn;at oure wyfes wol assay</L>
<L>Religious folk for &thorn;ey may bettre pay</L>
<L>Of venus payement &thorn;en mowen we</L>
<L N="3152">God woot no lussheburghes paye &yogh;e</L>
<L>But be&thorn; nought wro&thorn; my lord &thorn;ough &thorn;at I play</L>
<L>fful ofte in game a so&thorn; I haue herd say</L>
<L>This wor&thorn;y monk took al in pacience</L>
<L N="3156">And sayde I wil do al my diligence</L>
<L>As fer as sowne&thorn; in to honeste</L>
<L>To telle &yogh;ou a tale or tuo or &thorn;re</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ou liste herkne hiderward<MILESTONE N="236a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3160">I wol &yogh;ou seyn &thorn;e lyf of seint Edward</L>
<L>Or elles tregedys first wol I telle</L>
<L>Of whiche I haue an hundred in my selle</L>
<L>Tregedye is for to telle a certein storye</L>
<L N="3164">As olde bookes maken memorie</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at stood in gret prosperite</L>
<L>And is y-falle out of heigh degre</L>
<L>In-to miserie and ende&thorn; wrecchedly</L>
<L N="3168">And &thorn;ey ben vercefyed comenly</L>
<L>Of sixe foote whiche &thorn;at men clepen examytron</L>
<L>In proce eek ben endited many oon</L>
<L>And eek in metre in many a sondry wyse</L>
<L N="3172">Lo &thorn;is aughte &yogh;ou ynough suffyse</L>
<L>Now herkne&thorn; if &yogh;ou liste for to heere</L>
<L>But first I &yogh;ou beseche in &thorn;is mateere /</L>
<L>&thorn;ough I by ordre telle nou&yogh;t &thorn;ese &thorn;inges</L>
<L N="3176">Be it of Popes Emperours or Kynges</L>
<L>And after here ages as men writen fynde</L>
<L>But telle hem some bifore some behinde</L>
<L>As it come&thorn; now to my remembrance</L>
<L>Haue&thorn; me excused of myn ignorance</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prologus monachi
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000571.tif" N="543"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="256">
<HEAD>&para; Here telle&thorn; &thorn;e monk // De casibus virorum illustrium &para; C<SUP>m</SUP>. xxj<SUP>m</SUP>.<NOTE PLACE="head">[No breaks between the stanzas in the MS.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I Wol bewayle in maner of Tregedye</L>
<L>The harme of hem &thorn;at stande&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[stoden, <I>later, in the margin</I>]</NOTE> in heih degre</L>
<L>And fellen so &thorn;at &thorn;er nas no remedye</L>
<L N="3184">To bringen hem out of here aduersite</L>
<L>ffor certein when &thorn;at fortune lust to fle</L>
<L>Ther may no man of hire &thorn;e cours wi&thorn;holde /</L>
<L>[<SUP>2</SUP>Lat nonis truste on blyn[d] prosperite<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>2_2</SUP> later, in margin]</NOTE>]</L>
<L N="3188">Be&thorn; war by &thorn;is ensamples &yogh;ong and olde</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Lucifer.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At lucifer &thorn;ough he an aungel were<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Primo de lucifero</NOTE></L>
<L>And nought a man at him I wol begynne</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;eigh fortune may non aungel dere</L>
<L N="3192">ffrom heih degre &yogh;et felle he for his synne</L>
<L>Doun in-to helle wher as he &yogh;et is Inne</L>
<L>O lucifer brightest of aungeles alle</L>
<L>Now art &thorn;ou Sathanas &thorn;at mayst not twynne<MILESTONE N="236b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3196">Out of miserie which &thorn;ou art y-falle</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Adamo [<I>in margin.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[LO Adam in the felde of/ Damascene.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. MS 1758 folio" N="184a"></L>
<L>With goddis/ owne finger/ wroght/ was/ he.</L>
<L>And not bi getyng/ of/ mannes/ sperme vnclene.</L>
<L N="3200">And welte all Paradis/ sauyng/ oo tre.</L>
<L>Had neuyr/ worldly man so hye degree.</L>
<L>As/ Adam had till he for his/ gouernaunce.</L>
<L>Was/ dryuen out/ of/ his/ hye prosperite.</L>
<L>To labour/ an to helle &amp; to myschaunce.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000572.tif" N="544"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="257">
<HEAD>[Sampson.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lo Sampson which was annunciate</L>
<L>By &thorn;angel long er his natiuite /</L>
<L>And was to god almighty consecrate</L>
<L N="3208">And stood in nobles whiles he mighte se</L>
<L>Was neuer such ano&thorn;er as was he</L>
<L>To speke of streng&thorn;e and &thorn;erto hardynes</L>
<L>But to his wyues tolde he his secre</L>
<L N="3212">Thurgh which he slough himself &thorn;urgh wrecchednes</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sampson &thorn;is noble and mighty champion</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen wepen sauf his handes tweye</L>
<L>he slough and al to-rente &thorn;e leoun</L>
<L N="3216">Toward his weddyng walkyng by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>his false wyf cou&thorn;e him so plese and preye /</L>
<L>Til sche his counseil knewe and sche vntrewe</L>
<L>Vnto his foos his counseil gan bewreye</L>
<L N="3220">And him forsok and took ano&thorn;er newe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An hundred foxes tok Sampson for Ire</L>
<L>And alle here tayles he togyder bond</L>
<L>And sette &thorn;e foxes tayles alle on fuyre</L>
<L N="3224">ffor he in euery tail ha&thorn; putt a brond</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey brent alle &thorn;e cornes in &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>And eek here Olyues and here vynes eeke</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend men eek he slough wi&thorn; his hond</L>
<L N="3228">And hadde no wepne but an asse cheeke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;ey were slayn so &thorn;ursted him &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Was wel neigh lorn for which he gan to preye</L>
<L>That god wolde of his peyne haue som pite<MILESTONE N="237a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3232">And sende him drinke or elles most he deye /</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is asse cheeke &thorn;at was so druye</L>
<L>Out of a wang too&thorn; sprang anon a welle</L>
<L>Of which he drank ynough schortly to seye</L>
<L N="3236">Thus hilpe him god as Iudicium can telle
<PB REF="00000573.tif" N="545"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="258"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By verray force at Gasan on a night</L>
<L>Maugre philistiens of &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>The gates of &thorn;e toun he ha&thorn; vp plight</L>
<L N="3240">And on his bakke y-karyed hem ha&thorn; he</L>
<L>heighe on an hille where as men mighte se</L>
<L>O noble almighty Sampson leef and deere</L>
<L>That strong and noble ha&thorn; be /</L>
<L N="3244">In alle &thorn;is world ne hadde &thorn;er ben &thorn;y peere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Sampson neuer cyder drank ne wyn</L>
<L>Ne on his heed came Rasour non ne scheere</L>
<L>By precepte of &thorn;e messanger deuyn</L>
<L N="3248">ffor alle his streng&thorn;e was in his here</L>
<L>And fully twenty &yogh;eer by &yogh;ere</L>
<L>he hadde of Israel &thorn;e gouernance</L>
<L>But after soone schal he wepe many a teere</L>
<L N="3252">ffor wommen schuln bringe him to meschance</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vnto his lemman Dalida he tolde</L>
<L>That in his heeres alle his streng&thorn;e lay</L>
<L>And falsly to his fomen sche him solde</L>
<L N="3256">And slepyng vpon hire barme vpan a day</L>
<L>Sche made to clippe or schere his here away</L>
<L>And made his foomen alle his crafte aspyen</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at &thorn;ay him fond in such aray</L>
<L N="3260">They bonde him faste and putte out his eyen</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But er his heer was y-clipped or y-schaue</L>
<L>Ther was no bond &thorn;at might him bynde</L>
<L>But now is he in prisoun putte in a Caue</L>
<L N="3264">Where as &thorn;ey made him at &thorn;e querne grynde</L>
<L>O noble Sampson strengest of mankynde</L>
<L>O whilom Iugge in glorie and in richesse</L>
<L>Now maystow wepe with &thorn;in eyen blynde<MILESTONE N="237b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3268">Se&thorn;enes &thorn;ou art fro wele falle in to wrecchidnesse
<PB REF="00000574.tif" N="546"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="259"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The ende of &thorn;is Caytiffe was as I schal seye</L>
<L>his foomen made a feste vp-on a day</L>
<L>And made him as here fool biforn hem pleye</L>
<L N="3272">And &thorn;is was [in] a temple of gret aray</L>
<L>But at &thorn;e laste he made a foul affray</L>
<L>ffor he tuo postes schook and made hem falle /</L>
<L>And doun fel temple and al &thorn;er it lay</L>
<L N="3276">And slough himself and eek his foomen alle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This is to say &thorn;e princes euerichon</L>
<L>And eek a &thorn;ousand bodyes were &thorn;ey slayn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fallyng of &thorn;e grete temple of stoon</L>
<L N="3280">Of Sampson ne wol I no more sayn</L>
<L>Be&thorn; war of &thorn;is ensample olde and playn</L>
<L>That noman telle here counseil to here wyues</L>
<L>Of such &thorn;ing as &thorn;ay wolde haue secre fayn</L>
<L N="3284">If &thorn;at it touche here lymes or here lyues</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Hercules.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of Ercule &thorn;e soueraign conquerour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Ercule</NOTE></L>
<L>Syngen his werkes lewede and heih renoun</L>
<L>ffor in his tyme of streng&thorn;e he bar &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="3288">he slough and rafte &thorn;e skyn fro &thorn;e leoun</L>
<L>he of sent arwes leyde &thorn;e boost a doun</L>
<L>he arpyes slough &thorn;e cruel briddes felle</L>
<L>he golden apples rafte &thorn;e dragoun</L>
<L N="3292">he drough out Serberois &thorn;e hound of helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He slough &thorn;e cruel tyraunt Buserus</L>
<L>And made his hors to frete him fleissh and boon</L>
<L>He slough &thorn;e verray serpent venymous</L>
<L N="3296">Of Achilles tuo hornes brark he oon</L>
<L>And he slough Cacus in a Cave of ston</L>
<L>He slough &thorn;e geaunt Anteus &thorn;e stronge /</L>
<L>He slough &thorn;e grisly boor and &thorn;at anoon</L>
<L N="3300">And bar &thorn;e heed vpon his necke longe
<PB REF="00000575.tif" N="547"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="260"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Was neuer wight si&thorn;en &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L>&thorn;at slough so many monstres as dede he</L>
<L>Thurgh out &thorn;is wilde world his name ran<MILESTONE N="238a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3304">What for his streng&thorn;e and for his bounte</L>
<L>And euery Reeme went he for to see</L>
<L>He was so strong &thorn;at no man might him lette</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e &thorn;e worldes ende saith trophe /</L>
<L N="3308">In stede of boundes he a piler sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A lemman hadde &thorn;is noble Campion</L>
<L>That highte Deianyre freissh as may</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e clerkes maden mencion</L>
<L N="3312">Sche ha&thorn; him sent a scherte freisch and gay</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;is scherte and weylaway</L>
<L>Enuenymed was subtily wi&thorn; alle</L>
<L>That or &thorn;at he had wered it half a day</L>
<L N="3316">It made his boones fro his fleissch to falle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But na&thorn;eles some clerkes hire exusen</L>
<L>By oon &thorn;at highte Nessus &thorn;at it maked</L>
<L>Be as be may I wol hire nought accusen</L>
<L N="3320">But on his bakke &thorn;e scherte he weres al naked</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;at his fleissh was fro &thorn;e venym blaked</L>
<L>And whan he saugh non o&thorn;er remedye</L>
<L>In hote coles he ha&thorn; himself y-raked</L>
<L N="3324">ffor wi&thorn; no venym deyned he to dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus starf &thorn;is wor&thorn;y mighty hercules</L>
<L>Lo who may truste on fortune ony &thorn;rowe</L>
<L>ffor him &thorn;at folwe&thorn; alle &thorn;is world of prees</L>
<L N="3328">Er he be war is ofte y-leyd ful lowe</L>
<L>fful wys is he &thorn;at himself can knowe</L>
<L>Be&thorn; war for when &thorn;at fortune lust to glose /</L>
<L>Than wayte&thorn; sche hire man doun to &thorn;rowe</L>
<L N="3332">By such a way as he wolde lest suppose //
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000576.tif" N="548"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="261">
<HEAD>[Nebuchadnezzar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The mighty trone &thorn;e precious tresor<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Rege Nabu|godonosore</NOTE></L>
<L>The glorious septir and realle mageste</L>
<L>That hadde &thorn;e king Nabugodonosor</L>
<L N="3336">Wi&thorn; tunge vnne&thorn;e may discryued be</L>
<L>he twyes nam Iherusalem &thorn;e cite /</L>
<L>The vessel of &thorn;e temple he wi&thorn; him ladde</L>
<L>&para; At Babiloyne was his souerain see /<MILESTONE N="238b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3340">In which his glorie and his delit he hadde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fayrest children of &thorn;e blood royalle</L>
<L>Of Ierusalem he dede do gylde anon</L>
<L>And maked eche of hem to ben his &thorn;ralle</L>
<L N="3344">Among alle o&thorn;er Daniel was oon</L>
<L>That was &thorn;e wisest childe of euerychon</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;e dremes of &thorn;e king expowned</L>
<L>Wher as in Caldey clerk was &thorn;er non</L>
<L N="3348">That wiste to what fyn his dremes sowned</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This proude king leet make a statue of golde</L>
<L>Sixty cubites longe and seuen in brede</L>
<L>To which Image bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and olde</L>
<L N="3352">Comaunded he to lowte and haue in drede /</L>
<L>Or in a fourneys ful of flammes rede</L>
<L>He schal be brent &thorn;at wolde nought obeye</L>
<L>But neuere wolde assente to &thorn;at dede</L>
<L N="3356">Danyel ne his &yogh;onge felawes tweye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This king of kynges proude and elat</L>
<L>he wende god &thorn;at sitte in mageste</L>
<L>Ne might him nought byreue of his estate</L>
<L N="3360">But sodeinly he lost his dignite</L>
<L>And like a beeste him seemed for to be</L>
<L>And ete hey as an oxe and lay &thorn;er oute</L>
<L>In reyn wi&thorn; wilde bestes walked he</L>
<L N="3364">Til a certein tyme was come aboute
<PB REF="00000577.tif" N="549"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="262"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And ylike an Egles fe&thorn;eres were his heres</L>
<L>And nayles like briddes clawes were /</L>
<L>God releeued him at certeyn &yogh;eeres</L>
<L N="3368">And &yogh;af him witte and &thorn;anne wi&thorn; many a tere</L>
<L>he &thorn;ankede god and euer his lyf in feere</L>
<L>Was he to don amys or more trespas</L>
<L>And or &thorn;at y-leyd was on his beere</L>
<L N="3372">he knew wel &thorn;at god was ful of might and grace</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Belshazzar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his sone which &thorn;at highte Baltyzar<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Baltazar dicti Regis Nabugodo|nosor filio</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at heeld &thorn;e regne after his fader day</L>
<L>he by his fader cou&thorn;e nou&yogh;t be war<MILESTONE N="239a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3376">ffor prowd he was of herte and of array</L>
<L>And eek an ydolatre was he ay</L>
<L>his heihe astate asseured him in pryde</L>
<L>But fortune caste him doun and &thorn;er he lay</L>
<L N="3380">And sodeinly his regne gan deuyde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A feste he made vnto his lordes alle</L>
<L>vpon a tyme he made hem bli&thorn;e be /</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne his officeres gan he calle</L>
<L N="3384">Goode bringeth forth &thorn;e vesselles quod he</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at my fader in his prosperite</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e temple of Ierusalem byrafte</L>
<L>And to oure heihe goddes &thorn;anke we</L>
<L N="3388">Of honour &thorn;at oure eldres wi&thorn; vs lafte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His wyf his lordes and his concubynes</L>
<L>Ay drunken whiles here appetyte laste /</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is noble vesseles sondry wynes /</L>
<L N="3392">And on a wal &thorn;is king his eyhen caste</L>
<L>And saugh an hande armles &thorn;at/ wrot ful faste</L>
<L>ffor feer of which he quook and siked sore</L>
<L>This hande &thorn;at Baltazar made so sore agast</L>
<L N="3396">Wrot mane techel phares and no more
<PB REF="00000578.tif" N="550"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="263"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In al &thorn;at lond magicien was &thorn;er non</L>
<L>That cou&thorn;e expoune what &thorn;is lettre ment</L>
<L>But Daniel expouned it anon</L>
<L N="3400">And sayde king god to &thorn;i fader sent</L>
<L>Glory and honour Regne tresor and rent</L>
<L>And he was prowde and no &thorn;ing god ne dradde /</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore god gret wreche vpon him sent</L>
<L N="3404">And him byrafte &thorn;e regne &thorn;at he hadde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He was out cast of mannes companye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; asses was his habitacion</L>
<L>And eete hey as a beeste in wete and drye</L>
<L N="3408">Til &thorn;at he knew by grace and by resoun</L>
<L>That god of heuen ha&thorn; domynacion</L>
<L>Ouer euery regne and euery creature</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne hadde god of him compassion<MILESTONE N="239b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3412">And him restored his regne and his figure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Eke &thorn;ou &thorn;at art his sone art proud also</L>
<L>And knowest alle &thorn;is &thorn;inges pryuyly</L>
<L>and art rebell to god and art his foo</L>
<L N="3416">Thou drank eeke of his vessels boldely</L>
<L>Thy wyf eek and &thorn;y wenche synfully</L>
<L>Drank of &thorn;e same vessels sondry wynes</L>
<L>And heryed false goddes cursedly</L>
<L N="3420">Ther fore to &thorn;e schapen gret pyne is /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This hand was sent fro god &thorn;at on &thorn;e wal</L>
<L>Wrot mane techel phares truste me</L>
<L>Thin regne is doon &thorn;ou weyest not at al</L>
<L N="3424">Deuyded is &thorn;y regne and it schal be</L>
<L>To Medes and to Perses &yogh;euen quod he</L>
<L>And &thorn;ilke same night &thorn;e king was slawe</L>
<L>And Daryus occupieth his degre</L>
<L N="3428">They he &thorn;erto nad ney&thorn;er right ne lawe
<PB REF="00000579.tif" N="551"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="264"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lordynges her-by ensample may &yogh;e take</L>
<L>How &thorn;at in lordschipe is no sikernesse</L>
<L>ffor whan fortune wole a man forsake</L>
<L N="3432">He bere&thorn; a-wey his regne and his richesse /</L>
<L>And eek his freendes bo&thorn;e more and lesse</L>
<L>And what man ha&thorn; freendes &thorn;urgh fortune</L>
<L>Mishap wole make hem enemys I gesse</L>
<L N="3436">This prouerbe is ful so&thorn; and ful commune</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Zenobia.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Cenobya of Palymere &thorn;e queene<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Cenobia Paly|merie regina</NOTE></L>
<L>As writen Persiens of hire noblesse</L>
<L>So wor&thorn;y was in armes and so keene</L>
<L N="3440">That no wight passed hire in hardynesse /</L>
<L>Ne in lynage ne in o&thorn;er gentillesse /</L>
<L>Of kinges blood of Perce sche descended</L>
<L>I saye &thorn;at sche nad nou&yogh;t most fairnesse</L>
<L N="3444">But of hire schap sche might nought ben amended</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffro hire childhode I fynde &thorn;at sche fledde</L>
<L>Office of wommen and to woode sche wente</L>
<L>And many a wilde hertes blood sche schedde<MILESTONE N="240a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3448">With arwes brode &thorn;at sche to hem sente /</L>
<L>Sche was so swyfte &thorn;at sche anon hem hente</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at sche was elder sche wold kille</L>
<L>Leouns luperdes and beres alto-rent</L>
<L N="3452">And in hire armes welde hem at hire wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sche dorste wilde bestes dennes seeke</L>
<L>And rennen in &thorn;e mounteinz al &thorn;e night</L>
<L>And slepe vnder a bussche and sche cou&thorn;e eeke</L>
<L N="3456">Wrastlen by verray force and verray might</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; any &yogh;ong man were he neuer so wight</L>
<L>Ther mighte no &thorn;ing in hir armes stonde</L>
<L>Sche kepte hir maydenhed fro euery wight</L>
<L N="3460">To no man deyned hire to be bonde /
<PB REF="00000580.tif" N="552"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="265"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But atte laste hir freendes han hire maryed</L>
<L>To Odenake a Prince of &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Al were it so &thorn;at sche hem longe taryed</L>
<L N="3464">And &yogh;e schuln vnderstonde how &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Hadde suche fantasies as hadde sche</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles whan &thorn;ey were knette in feere</L>
<L>They lyueden in ioye and in felicite</L>
<L N="3468">ffor sche of hem hadde o&thorn;er leef and deere /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[Saue oo thyng/ that/ sche wolde neuyr/ assente.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. MS 1753 folio" N="187a">]</L>
<L>By no wey &thorn;at he schulde by hire lye</L>
<L>But ones for it/ was hire pleyne entent</L>
<L N="3472">To haue a childe &thorn;e world to multiplye</L>
<L>And al so sone as sche might aspye</L>
<L>That sche nas nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; childe wi&thorn; &thorn;at dede</L>
<L>Thanne wolde sche suffre him don his fantasye</L>
<L N="3476">Eftsone and nou&yogh;t but ones out of drede /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And if sche were wi&thorn; childe at &thorn;ilke caste</L>
<L>No more schulde he pleye &thorn;ilke game</L>
<L>Til fully fourty dayes were paste</L>
<L N="3480">Thenne wolde sche ones do suffre him &thorn;e same</L>
<L>Al were &thorn;is Odenak wilde or tame</L>
<L>he gat nomore of hire for &thorn;us sche sayde</L>
<L>It was to wyfes lecchery and schame /</L>
<L>In o&thorn;er caas if &thorn;at men with hem playde<MILESTONE N="240b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tuo sones by &thorn;is Odonak had sche</L>
<L>The whiche sche kepte in vertu and lettrure</L>
<L>But now vnto oure tale turne we /</L>
<L N="3488">I saye &thorn;at worschipful creature</L>
<L>And wys &thorn;erwith and large wi&thorn; mesure</L>
<L>So penyble in &thorn;e werre and curteys eeke</L>
<L>No more laboure mighte in werre endure</L>
<L N="3492">Was non &thorn;ey alle &thorn;is world men schulde seke
<PB REF="00000581.tif" N="553"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="266"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hire riche aray mighte nought be told</L>
<L>As wel in vessel as in hir clo&thorn;inge</L>
<L>Sche was al cladde in perrye and in goolde</L>
<L N="3496">And eek sche lefte nought for non huntynge</L>
<L>To haue of sondry tonges folk knowynge</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche leyser hadde and for to entende</L>
<L>To lerne bookes was al hire likynge</L>
<L N="3500">How sche in vertu might hir lyf dispende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[And schortly of/ this/ storie for to entrete.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. MS 1758 folio" N="187b">]</L>
<L>&para; So doughty was hire housebande as sche</L>
<L>That &thorn;ey conquered many regnes grete</L>
<L N="3504">In &thorn;e orient wi&thorn; many a fair Cite</L>
<L>Apportienant vnto &thorn;e mageste</L>
<L>Of Rome and with strong hand heeld hem faste</L>
<L>Ne neuer might here fomen don hem fle</L>
<L N="3508">Ay whiles &thorn;at Oedenak dayes laste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Here batayles who so luste hem for to ride&middot;</L>
<L>Agayn Sapor &thorn;e king and o&thorn;er mo&middot;</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at al &thorn;is proces felle in &middot;dede&middot;</L>
<L N="3512">Why sche conquered and what title had &thorn;erto</L>
<L>And after of hire meschief and hire woo</L>
<L>how &thorn;at sche was beseged and y-take</L>
<L>let him vnto my mayster Petrarke go</L>
<L N="3516">That writ of &thorn;is ynough I vndertake</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan Odenake was deed sche mightily</L>
<L>The regnes huld and wi&thorn; hir propre hand</L>
<L>Agayn hire foos sche faught trewely</L>
<L N="3520">That &thorn;er nas king ne Prince in al &thorn;at land</L>
<L>That he nas gladde if &thorn;at he grace fand<MILESTONE N="241a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sche ne wolde vpon his land werrey</L>
<L>With hire &thorn;ey made alleyance by band</L>
<L N="3524">To ben in pees and lete hir ryde and pley
<PB REF="00000582.tif" N="554"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="267"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Emperour of Rome Claudius</L>
<L>Ne him byforn &thorn;e Romain Galien</L>
<L>Ne dorste neuer be so coragius</L>
<L N="3528">Ne non Ermyne ne non Egipcien</L>
<L>Ne Surrien ne non arabien</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e feeld &thorn;at dorste with hire fight</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;at sche wolde hem wi&thorn; hir handes sleen</L>
<L N="3532">Or with hire meyne putten hem to flight</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[IN kynges/ abite wente hir/ sones/ two .<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. MS 1758 folio" N="187b">]</L>
<L>As Eyres of here regnes alle</L>
<L>And hermanno and Thymalao</L>
<L N="3536">Here names were as Perciens hem calle</L>
<L>But ay fortune ha&thorn; ay in hir hony galle</L>
<L>This mighty queene may no while en-dure</L>
<L>ffortune out of hire regne made hire falle</L>
<L N="3540">To wrecchednes and to mysauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Aurelion whan &thorn;at &thorn;e gouernance</L>
<L>Of Rome cam in-to his handes tweye</L>
<L>he schoop vpon &thorn;is queen to do vengance</L>
<L N="3544">And wi&thorn; his legiouns he took his weye</L>
<L>Toward Cenobye and schortly for to seye</L>
<L>He made hir flee and at &thorn;e last hir bent</L>
<L>And fetered hire and eek hir children tweye</L>
<L N="3548">And wan &thorn;e lond and home to Rome &thorn;ey went</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Among &thorn;ese o&thorn;er &thorn;inges &thorn;at he wan</L>
<L>hire char &thorn;at was wi&thorn; gold wrought and perre</L>
<L>This grete Romayn &thorn;is aurelian</L>
<L N="3552">Ha&thorn; wi&thorn; him ladde for &thorn;at men schulde se</L>
<L>Byforn his tryumphe walke&thorn; sche</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gilte cheynes on hire necke hangyng</L>
<L>Corouned sche was as after hire degre</L>
<L N="3556">And ful of perre charged hire clo&thorn;ing
<PB REF="00000583.tif" N="555"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="268"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Allas fortune sche &thorn;at whilom was</L>
<L>Dredful to kynges and to emperoures&middot;<MILESTONE N="241b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Now gaure&thorn; al &thorn;e poeple on hire allas&middot;</L>
<L N="3560">And sche &thorn;at helmed was in starke stoures&middot;</L>
<L>And wan by force townes strong and toures&middot;</L>
<L>Schal on hire heede were a vytremyte</L>
<L>And sche &thorn;at bar &thorn;e septre ful of floures</L>
<L N="3564">Schal bere a distaff hir costes for to quyte</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Peter the Cruel, of Spain.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>wrongly markt</I> b <I>in margin, by a later corrector, to follow</I> a (De nero &amp;c).</NOTE>&para; O noble o wor&thorn;y petre glorie of Spayne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Petro Spayne</NOTE></L>
<L>Whom fortune helde so heyh in mageste<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Rege</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel oughte men &thorn;in pitous de&thorn; complayne</L>
<L>Thy bastard bro&thorn;er made &thorn;e to fle</L>
<L>And after at a sege by subtilte</L>
<L N="3570">&thorn;ow were betrayed and lad to his tent</L>
<L>Wher as he wi&thorn; his owen hand slough &thorn;e</L>
<L N="3572">Succedyng in &thorn;y regne and in &thorn;in rent'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The feeld of snow wi&thorn; &thorn;e egle blak &thorn;er-Inne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Bertheun Claykyn</NOTE></L>
<L>Caught wi&thorn; &thorn;e lymrodde coloures as &thorn;e gledes<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Olyuer Mawny</NOTE></L>
<L>he brew &thorn;is cursednes and al &thorn;e synne</L>
<L>The wicked neste was werker of &thorn;is needes<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>Bertrand du Guesclin, &amp; his cousin Sir Oliver de Mauny</I>, l. 3579.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Nought Charles Olyuer &thorn;at ay took god heede</L>
<L N="3578">Of trou&thorn;e and honour but of armorekke</L>
<L>Genyloun Olyuer corupte for meede</L>
<L N="3580">Broughtest &thorn;is wor&thorn;i king in such a brekke</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Peter of Cyprus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wor&thorn;y Petre king of Cypre also<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De petro regis</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at alisaundre wan by heigh maystrie<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Cypri</NOTE></L>
<L>fful many an he&thorn;en wroughtest &thorn;ou ful wo</L>
<L N="3584">Of which &thorn;in owen liege had enuye</L>
<L>And for no &thorn;ing but for &thorn;in Chiualrie</L>
<L>They in &thorn;in bedde han slayn &thorn;e by &thorn;e morwe</L>
<L>Thus gan fortune gouerne and gye</L>
<L N="3588">And out of ioye bringe men in-to sorwe
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000584.tif" N="556"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="269">
<HEAD>[Bernabo Visconti, of Milan.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of Melane gret barnabo viscounte<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Barnabo vicecomite</NOTE></L>
<L>God of delite and scourge of lumbardye</L>
<L>Why schulde nou&yogh;t I &thorn;in fortune acounte /<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; Mediolano /</NOTE></L>
<L N="3592">Se&thorn;&thorn;en in estaat &thorn;ou clombe were so hihe</L>
<L>Thin bro&thorn;er sone &thorn;at was &thorn;in double allye</L>
<L>ffor he &thorn;in neuew was and sone in lawe<MILESTONE N="242a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne his prison made &thorn;e to deye</L>
<L N="3596">But why ne how wot I &thorn;at &thorn;ou were slawe //</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Ugolino, Count of Pisa.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of &thorn;e erl hugelyne of Pyse &thorn;e langour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De hugylyno Comite Pisano.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther may no tunge telle for pite</L>
<L>But lytel out of pyse stant a toure</L>
<L N="3600">In which toure in prison putte was he</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; him ben his litel children &thorn;re</L>
<L>The eldest skarsly .v. &yogh;er was of age</L>
<L>allas fortune it was gret cruelte</L>
<L N="3604">Suche briddes for to putte in such a kage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Dampned he was to deyen in &thorn;at prison</L>
<L>ffor Roger which &thorn;at bisschop was of pyse</L>
<L>Hadde on him maade a fals suggestion</L>
<L N="3608">Thurgh which &thorn;e poeple gan on him aryse</L>
<L>And putten him to pryson in swich wyse</L>
<L>As &yogh;e haue herde and mete and drynk he hadde</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3612">And &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al it was ful pore and badde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And on a day bifelle &thorn;at in &thorn;at oure</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his mete was wont to be brought</L>
<L>The Gailler schutte &thorn;e dores of &thorn;e toure</L>
<L N="3616">He herde it wel but he saugh it nought</L>
<L>And in his herte anon &thorn;er felle a &thorn;ought</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ey for hunger wolde don him deyen</L>
<L>Allas quod he allas &thorn;at I was wrought</L>
<L N="3620">&THORN;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;e teeres felle fro his eyen
<PB REF="00000585.tif" N="557"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="270"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; his &yogh;onge sone &thorn;at &thorn;re &yogh;eer was of age</L>
<L>vnto him sayde fader why do &yogh;e wepe</L>
<L>When wil &thorn;e Gaylere bringen oure potage</L>
<L N="3624">Is &thorn;er no morsel bred &thorn;at &yogh;e do kepe</L>
<L>I am so hungry &thorn;at I may nought slepe</L>
<L>Now wolde god &thorn;at I might slepen euer</L>
<L>Thanne schulde non hunger in my wombe crepe</L>
<L N="3628">&thorn;er nys no &thorn;ing sauf bred &thorn;at me were leuer</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus day by day &thorn;is childe gan to crye</L>
<L>Til in his fadres barme a doun it lay</L>
<L>And sayde fare wel fader I mot deye<MILESTONE N="242b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3632">And kissed his fader and deyde &thorn;e same day</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e woful fader ded him say</L>
<L>ffor wo his armes tuo he gan to byte /</L>
<L>And sayde allas fortune and welaway</L>
<L N="3636">Thyn fals wheel my wo I may al wyte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; His children wende &thorn;at it for hunger was</L>
<L>&thorn;at he his armes gnowe and nought for wo</L>
<L>And sayde fader do nou&yogh;t so allas</L>
<L N="3640">But ra&thorn;er ete &thorn;e fleissch vpon ous tuo</L>
<L>Oure fleissch &thorn;ou &yogh;af vs take oure flessch vs fro</L>
<L>And ete ynough right &thorn;us to him &thorn;ay sayde /</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at wi&thorn;inne a day or tuo</L>
<L N="3644">They leyde hem doun right in his lappe and deyde /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Himself dispeyred eek for hunger starf</L>
<L>Thus ended is &thorn;e mighty erl of Pyse</L>
<L>ffro heih estate fortune fro him karf</L>
<L N="3648">Of &thorn;is tregetrye it ought ynough suffise /</L>
<L>Who so wol heere it in a lenger wise</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; &thorn;e grete poete of ytayle /</L>
<L>That highte daunte for he can it deuyse</L>
<L N="3652">ffro poynt to poynt nou&yogh;t o word wol he fayle
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000586.tif" N="558"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="271">
<HEAD>[Nero.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>wrongly markt</I> .a. <I>by a later corrector, to go before Peter of Spain.</I>]</NOTE>&para; Al &thorn;ough &thorn;at Nero was as vicious<NOTE PLACE="marg">De nero</NOTE></L>
<L>As eny feend &thorn;at li&thorn; ful lowe adoun</L>
<L>&YOGH;et he as telle&thorn; vs Swetheneus</L>
<L N="3656">This wilde world ha&thorn; in Subieccioun</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e Est and west and Septemptrioun</L>
<L>Of Rubies Saphires and of perlis white</L>
<L>Were alle his clo&thorn;es brouded vp and doun</L>
<L N="3660">ffor he in gemmes grete gan delyte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; More delicate more pompous of array</L>
<L>More proud was neuer emperour &thorn;an he</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilke clo&thorn; &thorn;at he had wered a day</L>
<L N="3664">After &thorn;at tyme he nolde it neuer se</L>
<L>Nettes of golde &thorn;red hadde he gret plente</L>
<L>To fissche in Tybre when him leste to pleye</L>
<L>his lustes were as lawe in his degre<MILESTONE N="243a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3668">ffor fortune as his freende wolde him obeye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He Rome brente for his delicacye</L>
<L>The senatoures he slough vpon a day</L>
<L>To heere how &thorn;at men wolde weepe and crye</L>
<L N="3672">And slough his bro&thorn;er and by his suster lay</L>
<L>His mooder made he in pitous aray</L>
<L>ffor he hire wombe slitte to byholde</L>
<L>Where he consceyued was so weylaway</L>
<L N="3676">&THORN;at he so litel of his moder tolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; No teere out of his eyhen for &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>Ne came but sayde a fair womman was sche</L>
<L>Gret wonder is &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e or might</L>
<L N="3680">Be domesman of hire ded beute</L>
<L>The wyn to brynge &thorn;o comanded he</L>
<L>And drank anon. non o&thorn;er wo he made /</L>
<L>Whan might is ioygned vnto cruelte</L>
<L N="3684">Allas to deepe wole &thorn;e venym wade
<PB REF="00000587.tif" N="559"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="272"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In &yogh;ou&thorn;e a mayster hadde &thorn;is emperour</L>
<L>To teche him lettrure and curtesye</L>
<L>ffor of moralite he was &thorn;e flour</L>
<L N="3688">As in his tyme but if bookes lye</L>
<L>And whiles his mayster hadde of him maystrye</L>
<L>He made him so konnyng and so souple /</L>
<L>That longe tyme it was or tyrannye</L>
<L N="3692">Or any vice dorste in him vncouple</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This Seneka of which I deuyse</L>
<L>By cause nero hadde of him such drede</L>
<L>ffor he for vices wolde him chastise</L>
<L N="3696">Discretly as by word and nought by drede</L>
<L>Sire wolde he sayn an Emperour moot neede</L>
<L>Be vertuous and hate tyrauntrye</L>
<L>ffor which he him in bathe made to blede</L>
<L N="3700">In bo&thorn;e his armes til he moste dye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This nero hadde eek of a costummance</L>
<L>In &yogh;ou&thorn;e a&yogh;eins his mayster for to ryse</L>
<L>Which aftirward him &thorn;ought a gret greuaunce<MILESTONE N="243b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3704">Therfore he made him deye in &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles &thorn;is Seneke &thorn;e wise /</L>
<L>Chees in a bathe to deye in &thorn;is manere /</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;er &thorn;an han ano&thorn;er tormentrye</L>
<L N="3708">And &thorn;us ha&thorn; Nero slayn his mayster deere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now felle it so &thorn;at fortune lust no lenger</L>
<L>&thorn;e heihe pryde of nero to cherissche</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough he were strong &yogh;et was sche strenger</L>
<L N="3712">Sche &thorn;oughte &thorn;us by god I am to nyse</L>
<L>To setten a man &thorn;at is fulfilde of vice</L>
<L>In heigh degre and emperour him calle</L>
<L>By god out of his sete I wol him tryce</L>
<L N="3716">When he lest wene&thorn; sonnest schal he falle
<PB REF="00000588.tif" N="560"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="273"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The poeple ros vpon him on a night</L>
<L>ffor his defaute and whan he it aspyed</L>
<L>Out of his dores anon he ha&thorn; him dight</L>
<L N="3720">Allone and &thorn;er he wende han ben allyed</L>
<L>he knokked faste and ay &thorn;e more he cryed</L>
<L>&thorn;e faster schutten &thorn;ey &thorn;e dores alle</L>
<L>Tho wiste he wel he hadde himself begyled</L>
<L N="3724">And went his way no lenger dorste he calle /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The poeple cryed and rombled vp and doun</L>
<L>&thorn;at wi&thorn; his eeres herde he how &thorn;ey sayde</L>
<L>Wher is &thorn;is false tyraunt &thorn;is Neroun</L>
<L N="3728">ffor fere almost out of his witte a brayde</L>
<L>And to his goddes pitously he sayde</L>
<L>ffor socour but it mighte nought betyde</L>
<L>ffor drede of &thorn;is him &thorn;oughte &thorn;at he deyde</L>
<L N="3732">and ran in to a gardyn him to huyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And in &thorn;is gardyn fond he cherles tweye</L>
<L>And saten by a fuyre ful grete and rede</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e cherles twey he gan to preye</L>
<L N="3736">To slen him and to gurden of his hede</L>
<L>That to his body whan &thorn;at he were dede</L>
<L>Were no despite y-done for his deffame /</L>
<L>Himself he slough he cou&thorn;e no better reed<MILESTONE N="244a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3740">Of which fortune lough and hadde a game</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Holofernes.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Was neuer Capitayn vnder a king<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Olipherno</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at regnes mo putte in subieccioun</L>
<L>Ne strenger was in feeld of alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="3744">As in his tyme ne gretter of Renoun</L>
<L>Ne more pompous in heigh presumpcioun</L>
<L>Then Olyferne which fortune ay keste /</L>
<L>So likerously and ladde him vp and doun</L>
<L N="3748">Til &thorn;at he hed was er &thorn;at he wiste /
<PB REF="00000589.tif" N="561"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="274"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Nought oonly &thorn;at &thorn;is world had of him awe /</L>
<L>ffor lesyng of Richesse and liberte</L>
<L>But he made euery man reneye his lawe /</L>
<L N="3752">Nabugodonosor was lord sayde</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;er god schulde honoured be</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins his heste no wight dar trespace /</L>
<L>Saue in Bethulya a strang Cite</L>
<L N="3756">Where Elyachim a prest was of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But take keepe of &thorn;e de&thorn; of Olypherne</L>
<L>Amydde his hoste he drunke lay a nyght</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;inne his tente large as is a berne /</L>
<L N="3760">And &yogh;et for alle his pompe and alle his might</L>
<L>Iudith a womman as he lay vpright</L>
<L>Slepyng his heed of smot and fro his tent /</L>
<L>fful pryuyly sche stal fro euery wight</L>
<L N="3764">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Antiochus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What neede&thorn; it of king antiochus<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De antiochio illustri.</NOTE></L>
<L>To telle his heihe and real mageste</L>
<L>his heighe pruyde his werkes venymous</L>
<L N="3768">ffor such ano&thorn;er nas neuer non as he</L>
<L>Rede&thorn; which &thorn;at he was in Machabe</L>
<L>And rede&thorn; &thorn;e proude wordes &thorn;at he sayde</L>
<L>And why he felle fro his prosperite</L>
<L N="3772">And in an hulle how wrecchedly he deyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; ffortune him hadde enhaunced so in pruyde</L>
<L>&thorn;at verrayly he wende he mighte atteyne</L>
<L N="3775">vnto &thorn;e sterres vpon euery syde</L>
<L>And in a balaunce to weye vche mountayne /<MILESTONE N="244b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e floodes of &thorn;e see restreyne</L>
<L>And goddes poeple hadde he most in hate</L>
<L>Hem wolde he sle in torment and peyne /</L>
<L N="3780">Wenyng &thorn;at god ne might his pruyde abate
<PB REF="00000590.tif" N="562"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="275"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And for &thorn;at Nichamour and Thymothee</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Iewes were venquyscht mightily</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Iewes swich an hate hadde he</L>
<L N="3784">That he hadde greythed his chaar ful hastily</L>
<L>And swor and sayde ful dispitously</L>
<L>vnto Ierusalem he wolde eft sone /</L>
<L>To wreke his Ire on hit ful cruelly</L>
<L N="3788">But of his purpos he was lette ful sone /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; God for his manace him so sore smot/</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; inuisible wounde ay vncurable/</L>
<L>That in his guttes karf so and bote</L>
<L N="3792">That his peynes were importable</L>
<L>And certeynly &thorn;e wreche was resonable</L>
<L>ffor many mannes guttes dede he payne</L>
<L>But fro his pourpos cursed and dampnable</L>
<L N="3796">ffor alle his smerte he nolde him nought restreyne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But bad anon apparaylen his Oste</L>
<L>And sodeinly er he was of hit/ ware</L>
<L>God daunted alle his pruyde and alle his boste</L>
<L N="3800">ffor he so sore felle out of his chare</L>
<L>That hurt his lymes and his skyn totare</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he ne mighte go ne ryde</L>
<L>But in a Chayer men aboute him bare</L>
<L N="3804">Al forbrused bo&thorn;e bak and syde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The wreche of god him smot so cruelly</L>
<L>That in his body wickede wormes crepte</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al he stank so orribly</L>
<L N="3808">That non of alle his meigne &thorn;at him kepte /</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er so &thorn;at he wook or elles slepte /</L>
<L>Ne mighte nought/ &thorn;e stynk of him endure</L>
<L>In &thorn;is meschief he weyled and eek wepte /</L>
<L N="3812">And knewe god lord of euery creature<MILESTONE N="245a" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000591.tif" N="563"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="276"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To alle his host and to himself also</L>
<L>fful wlatsom was &thorn;e stynke of &thorn;is Careyne</L>
<L>No man ne mighte him bere to ne fro</L>
<L N="3816">And in his stynke and in his horible peyne</L>
<L>He starf ful wrecchedly in a mounteyne</L>
<L>Thus ha&thorn; &thorn;is robbour and &thorn;is homicide</L>
<L>That many a man made to weepe and pleyne</L>
<L N="3820">Such guerdon as bilonge&thorn; vnto pruyde /</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Alexander the Great.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The story of alisaundre is so commune<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De alexandro magno philippi Regis Macedonie filio.</NOTE></L>
<L>That euery wight &thorn;at ha&thorn; discrecioun</L>
<L>ha&thorn; herd somwhat or al of his fortune</L>
<L N="3824">This wilde world as in conclusioun</L>
<L>He wan by streng&thorn;e or for his heigh renoun</L>
<L>They weren glad for pees vnto him sende</L>
<L>The pruyde of man and beste he leyde a doun</L>
<L N="3828">Wher so he cam vnto &thorn;e worldes ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Comparison might neuer &yogh;it/ be maked</L>
<L>Betwix him and ano&thorn;er conquerour</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;is worlde for drede of him ha&thorn; quaked</L>
<L N="3832">he was of knighthede and of fredam flour</L>
<L>ffortune him made &thorn;e heier of hure honour</L>
<L>Saue wyn and wommen no &thorn;ing might aswage /</L>
<L>His heihe entent in armes and labour</L>
<L N="3836">So was he fulle of louynge corage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; What pite were it to him &thorn;ey I &yogh;ou tolde</L>
<L>Of darius and an .C. &thorn;ousand mo</L>
<L>Of kinges princes dukes eerles bolde</L>
<L N="3840">Which he conquered and brou&yogh;t hem in-to woo</L>
<L>I say as fer as man may ryde or goo</L>
<L>&THORN;e worlde was his what schulde I more deuyse</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ough I write or tolde &yogh;ou euermo</L>
<L N="3844">Of his knighthode he mighte nought suffise
<PB REF="00000592.tif" N="564"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="277"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Twelf &yogh;eer he regned as sai&thorn; Machabe</L>
<L>Philippes sone of Macedo he was /</L>
<L>That first was king of Grece &thorn;e Contre /</L>
<L N="3848">O wor&thorn;y gentil alisandre allas<MILESTONE N="245b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at euer schulde falle such a caas</L>
<L>Enpoysoned of &thorn;in folk &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>&thorn;yn. S fortune ha&thorn; torned in-to an aas</L>
<L N="3852">And &yogh;et for &thorn;e ne weep sche neuer a tere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who schal men &yogh;eue teeres to compleyne</L>
<L>The de&thorn; of gentilesse and of fraunchise</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;e world weeldid in his demeygne /</L>
<L N="3856">And &yogh;et him &thorn;oughte it might not suffise /</L>
<L>So ful was his corage of heigh emprise</L>
<L>Allas who schal me helpe to endite</L>
<L>ffals fortune and poyson to despise</L>
<L N="3860">&thorn;e whiche tuo of al &thorn;is wo I wite</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Julius C&aelig;sar.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; By wisedom manhede and by labour<NOTE PLACE="marg">&para; De Iulio Cesare.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffro humbleheed and fro Royal mageste</L>
<L>vp ros he Iulius &thorn;e Conquerour</L>
<L N="3864">That alle &thorn;e Occident by land and fee</L>
<L>By streng&thorn;e of hand or elles by tretee</L>
<L>And vnto Rome made hem tributarie</L>
<L>And se&thorn;enes of Rome &thorn;emperour was he</L>
<L N="3868">Til &thorn;at fortune wax his aduersarie</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O mighty Cesar &thorn;at in Tessalye</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens Pompeus fader &thorn;in in lawe</L>
<L>That of &thorn;e Orient hadde al &thorn;e chiualrye</L>
<L N="3872">as ferre as &thorn;at &thorn;e day begynne&thorn; dawe</L>
<L>&thorn;ou &thorn;orugh &thorn;in knighthode &thorn;ou hast hem take and slawe /</L>
<L>Saue fewe folk &thorn;at wi&thorn; Pompeus fledde /</L>
<L>&thorn;urgh which &thorn;ou puttest al &thorn;e Orient in awe</L>
<L N="3876">Thanke fortune &thorn;at so wel &thorn;e spedde
<PB REF="00000593.tif" N="565"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="278"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But now a litel while I wol bewayle /</L>
<L>&thorn;is Pompeus &thorn;is noble gouernour</L>
<L>Of Rome which &thorn;at fleigh at &thorn;is batayle</L>
<L N="3880">I say on of his men a fals traytour</L>
<L>His heed of smoot/ to wynne him fauour</L>
<L>Of Iulius and him &thorn;e heed broughte</L>
<L>Allas Pompeye of &thorn;e Orient conquerour</L>
<L N="3884">That fortune vnto such a finye broughte<MILESTONE N="246a" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To Rome a&yogh;ein repayre&thorn; Iulius</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his triumphe laureate ful hey&yogh;e</L>
<L>But on a tyme Brutus Cassius</L>
<L N="3888">That euer had of his heigh estaat enuye</L>
<L>fful priuily had maad conspiracie</L>
<L>A&yogh;eins &thorn;is Iulius in subtil wise</L>
<L>And caste &thorn;e place in which he schulde deye</L>
<L N="3892">Wi&thorn; boydekynnes as I schal &yogh;ou deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;is Iulius to &thorn;e Capithole went</L>
<L>vppon a day as he was wont to goon</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Capitolye anon him hent</L>
<L N="3896">This false brutus on his foule foon</L>
<L>And stiked him wi&thorn; boydekynnes anon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; many a wounde and &thorn;us &thorn;ey leet/ him lye</L>
<L>But neuer gronte he at no stroke but oon</L>
<L N="3900">Or elles at tuo but if his story lye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; So manly was &thorn;is Iulius of herte</L>
<L>And so wel loued estaatly honeste</L>
<L>That &thorn;ough his dedly woundes so sore smerte</L>
<L N="3904">His mantel ouer his hepes caste he</L>
<L>ffor noman schulde seen his priuyte</L>
<L>And as he lay as deyinge in a traunce</L>
<L>And wiste verrily &thorn;at deed was he</L>
<L N="3908">Of honeste &yogh;et hadde he remembrance
<PB REF="00000594.tif" N="566"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="279"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lucane to &thorn;is story I recomende</L>
<L>And to Sweton and to Valerius also</L>
<L>That of &thorn;is story write&thorn; word and ende</L>
<L N="3912">how &thorn;at &thorn;ese grete conqueroures tuo</L>
<L>ffortune was ferst freend and si&thorn;en a foo</L>
<L>No man ne truste vpon his fauour longe</L>
<L>But haue hire in awayte for eueremo</L>
<L N="3916">Witnesse on alle &thorn;ise conqueroures stronge</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Cresus.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This riche Cresus whilom king of lyde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cresus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of whiche Cresus Cyquus sore him dradde</L>
<L N="3919">&YOGH;et was he caught amyddes alle his pryde</L>
<L>And to be brent men to &thorn;e fuyre him ladde<MILESTONE N="246b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But such a reyn doun fro &thorn;e walken schadde</L>
<L>&thorn;at slough &thorn;e fuyr and made him to askape</L>
<L>But to be war &yogh;et no grace he hadde</L>
<L N="3924">Til fortune on &thorn;e galwes made him gape</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whan he askaped was he can not stynte</L>
<L>ffor to begynne a newe reyne a&yogh;ein</L>
<L>he wende wel for &thorn;at fortune him sente</L>
<L N="3928">Such happe &thorn;at he escaped &thorn;urgh &thorn;e rayn</L>
<L>That of his foos he mighte not be slayn</L>
<L>And swich a swefne vppan a night he mette</L>
<L>Of which he was so proud and eek so fayn</L>
<L N="3932">That in vengaunce he alle his herte sette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vpon a tree he was as &thorn;at him &thorn;oughte</L>
<L>There Iubiter him wisshe bo&thorn;e halse and syde</L>
<L>And Phebus eek a fair towayle him broughte</L>
<L N="3936">To druye him wi&thorn; and &thorn;erfore wax his pryde</L>
<L>And to his doughter &thorn;at stood him besyde</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at he knew in heigh sentence abounde</L>
<L>He bad hire telle him what it signefyed</L>
<L N="3940">And sche his dreemes bygan right &thorn;us expounde
<PB REF="00000595.tif" N="567"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="280"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The tree quod sche &thorn;e galwes is to mene</L>
<L>And Iubiter bitokne&thorn; snow and rayn</L>
<L>And Phebus wi&thorn; his towayle so clene</L>
<L N="3944">Tho be &thorn;e sonne stremes for to sayn</L>
<L>Thou schalt an honged be fader certayn</L>
<L>Reyn schal &thorn;e waissche and sonne schal &thorn;e druye</L>
<L>&thorn;us warned him ful platte and ful playn</L>
<L N="3948">His doughter &thorn;at called was Phanye /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An honged was Cresus &thorn;e proude king</L>
<L>His roial trone might him nought auayle</L>
<L>Tegedie is non o&thorn;er maner &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="3952">Ne can synnynge crye ne by-wayle</L>
<L>But &thorn;at fortune alway wol assayle /</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; vnwar strook &thorn;e regnes that ben proude</L>
<L>ffor whan men truste&thorn; hire &thorn;an wol sche fayle</L>
<L N="3956">And couere hire brighte face wi&thorn; a cloude<MILESTONE N="247a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit/
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000596.tif" N="568"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="281">
<HEAD>&para; Here begynne&thorn; &thorn;e prologe of &thorn;e nonne prestes tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 247</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HO quod &thorn;e knight goode sire nomore of &thorn;is</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e han sayde is right ynough ywis</L>
<L>And meche more for litel heuynesse</L>
<L N="3960">Is right ynough to meche folk as I gesse /<NOTE PLACE="marg">[no gap in the Corpus MS]</NOTE></L>
<L>[I sey for me . it is a grete disease<MILESTONE UNIT="Reg. 17 D. xv folio" N="273b"></L>
<L>Where as men han bien . in grete welth and ease</L>
<L>To here of theyr sodayn falle alas</L>
<L N="3964">And the contrary is Ioy . and grete solas</L>
<L>And whan a man hath bien in pouer estate</L>
<L>And clymbith vp . and wexith fortunate</L>
<L>And ther abydith &middot; in prosperite<MILESTONE UNIT="Reg. 17 D. xv folio" N="274a"></L>
<L N="3968">Swiche thyng is gladsom . as it thynkyth me</L>
<L>And of swiche thynges . were goodely for to telle</L>
<L>Ya quod oure host . be seynt poulis belle</L>
<L>Ye say right soth . this monk be clappid lowde</L>
<L N="3972">He spak how fortune . was couered with a clowde</L>
<L>I not neuer what . and als of a tregedye</L>
<L>Right now ye herd . and parde no remedye</L>
<L>Is it for to be-wailen . and compleyn</L>
<L N="3976">That . that is don . and als it is a peyn</L>
<L>As ye have sayd . to here of hevynesse</L>
<L>Sir monke nomore of this . so god yow blisse</L>
<L>Yowre tale anoyeth . al this company</L>
<L>Swiche thyng is nat worth a boterflye]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>MS Reg.</B> <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>&yogh;oure tales don vs no desport ne game</L>
<L>Wherfore sir monk Doun Pieres by &yogh;our name</L>
<L>I pray &yogh;ou hertely telle vs som what elles</L>
<L N="3984">ffor siker nere clynkyng of &yogh;oure belles /
<PB REF="00000597.tif" N="569"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="282"></L>
<L>&thorn;at on &yogh;oure brydel hange&thorn; on euery syde /</L>
<L>By heuene king &thorn;at for vs alle dyde</L>
<L>I schal for &thorn;is falle doun for slepe /</L>
<L N="3988">Al &thorn;ough &thorn;e slough hadde neuer ben so depe</L>
<L>&thorn;an hadde &yogh;oure tale be told in vayn</L>
<L>ffor certeinly as &thorn;ese clerkes sayn</L>
<L>Wher as a man may han non audience</L>
<L N="3992">Nought helpe&thorn; it to tellen his sentence</L>
<L>And wel I woot &thorn;e substance is in me /</L>
<L>If eny &thorn;ing schal wel reported be</L>
<L>Sire say somwhat of huntyng I &yogh;ou pray</L>
<L N="3996">Nay quod &thorn;e monk I haue no lust to play</L>
<L>Now lete ano&thorn;er telle as I haue tolde</L>
<L>&thorn;anne spak oure Ost wi&thorn; ruyde speche and bolde</L>
<L>And sayde vnto &thorn;e nonnes prest anon</L>
<L N="4000">Come ner sire prest com hider sir Iohn</L>
<L>Telle vs such &thorn;ing as may oure hertes glade</L>
<L>Be mery &thorn;ough &thorn;ou ryde vpon a Iade /</L>
<L>What &thorn;ough &thorn;in hors be hagged foul or lene</L>
<L N="4004">If he wol serue &thorn;e rekke &thorn;e nought a bene</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;in herte be mery euermo</L>
<L>&yogh;is Ost quod he so mote I ryde or go</L>
<L>But I be mery I-wys I wil be blamed</L>
<L N="4008">And right anon he ha&thorn; his tale tamed</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he seyde to vs euerychon</L>
<L>This swete prest &thorn;is goode man sir Iohn .</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prologus
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000598.tif" N="570"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="283">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ca<SUP>m</SUP> xxij<SUP>m</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; Here begynne&thorn; &thorn;e nonnes prestes tale of &thorn;e kokke &amp; his vij. hennes</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Pouere wydewe somdel stope in age<MILESTONE N="247b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4012">Was whilom dwellyng in a narwe cotage</L>
<L>Besydes a groue standyng in a dale</L>
<L>This wydewe of which I telle &yogh;ou my tale</L>
<L>Se&thorn;ins &thorn;ilke day &thorn;at sche was last/ a wyf</L>
<L N="4016">In pacience ladde a ful simple lyf</L>
<L>ffor litel was hire catelle and hire rent</L>
