<L>Lo suche it is for to be recheles /</L>
<L>and necligent and truste&thorn; on flaterye</L>
<L N="4628">But &yogh;e &thorn;at halden &thorn;is tale a folye</L>
<L>As of a fox and of a cok and an hen</L>
<L>Take&thorn; &thorn;e moralite goode men<MILESTONE N="256a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor seint poule sai&thorn; / alle &thorn;at writen is</L>
<L N="4632">To oure doctrine / it is y-writen y-wis</L>
<L>Take&thorn; &thorn;e fruit/ and lete&thorn; &thorn;e chaff be stille</L>
<L>Now goode god if &thorn;at it be &thorn;in wille /</L>
<L>As sei&thorn; my lord so make vs alle goode men</L>
<L N="4636">And bringe vs alle to his heihe blisse ameN</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here ende&thorn; &thorn;e Nonne prestes tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="H" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000616.tif" N="588">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="576">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>H.</B> FRAGMENT IX.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; <B>1.</B> THE MANCIPLE'S HEAD-LINK.</HEAD>
<HEAD>CORPUS MS.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Here folwe&thorn; &thorn;e Prologe of &thorn;e man| &para; ciples tale<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 256</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ca<SUP>m</SUP> xxiij<SUP>m</SUP></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WOt &yogh;e not wher &thorn;er stant/ a litel toun</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at is cleped Bobbe vp and doun</L>
<L>vnder &thorn;e Blee in Caunterbery way</L>
<L N="4">Ther gan oure Oste for to Iape and play</L>
<L>And sayde syres what donne is in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Is no man for preyer ne for huyre</L>
<L>That wole awake oure felawe be-hynde /</L>
<L N="8">A &thorn;eef might him ful lightly robbe and bynde</L>
<L>Se how he nappe&thorn; se for goddes bones</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wol falle fro his hors at ones</L>
<L>Is &thorn;at a Cook of london wi&thorn; meschance</L>
<L N="12">Do him come forth he knowe&thorn; his pen&amacr;nce</L>
<L>ffor he schal telle a tale by my fey</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ough it be nought wor&thorn; a botel hey</L>
<L>Awake &thorn;ou Cook quod he god &yogh;iue &thorn;e sorwe</L>
<L N="16">What eyle&thorn; &thorn;e to slepe by &thorn;e morwe</L>
<L>hast &thorn;ou had fleen al night or art &thorn;ou drunke</L>
<L>Or hast &thorn;ou wi&thorn; som quene al night y-swunke</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst nought holden vp &thorn;in heed</L>
<L N="20">This Cook &thorn;at was ful pale and no &thorn;ing reed</L>
<L>Seyde oure Ost so god my soule blesse</L>
<L>As &thorn;er is falle on me such heuynesse</L>
<L>Not I nou&yogh;t why me were leuer to slepe</L>
<L N="24">Then &thorn;e beste galon of wyn in Chepe
<PB REF="00000617.tif" N="589"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="577"></L>
<L N="25">Wel quod &thorn;e maunciple if it &thorn;e may don ese</L>
<L>To &thorn;e sir Cook and to no wight displese</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at heer ryde&thorn; in &thorn;is companye /</L>
<L N="28">And &thorn;at oure host wole of his curtesye</L>
<L>I wole as now excuse &thorn;e of &thorn;in tale<MILESTONE N="256b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor in good fei&thorn; &thorn;i visage is ful pale</L>
<L>Thin eyen dasewen so&thorn;ly as me &thorn;inke&thorn;</L>
<L N="32">And wel I woot &thorn;i bre&thorn; ful soure stinke&thorn;</L>
<L>That schewe&thorn; wel &thorn;ou art nought wel disposed</L>
<L>Of me certeyn &thorn;ou schalt nought ben y-glosed</L>
<L>Se how he goneth lo his drunken wight</L>
<L N="36">As &thorn;ough he wolde vs swolwe anon right</L>
<L>hald clos &thorn;in mou&thorn; man by &thorn;yn fader kyn</L>
<L>The deuyl of helle sette his foot &thorn;erin</L>
<L>This cursed breth wol infecte vs alle</L>
<L N="40">ffy stynkynge swyn fy foule mote &thorn;e falle</L>
<L>Take&thorn; heede sires of &thorn;is lusty man</L>
<L>Now sweete sire wole &yogh;e iuste at &thorn;e van</L>
<L>Ther-to me &thorn;enke&thorn; &yogh;e ben wel y-schape</L>
<L N="44">I trowe &thorn;at &yogh;e haue drunken wyn ape</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is whan men pleye wi&thorn; a straw /</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his speche &thorn;e Cooke wax al wraw</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e maunciple bygan he nodde faste</L>
<L N="48">ffor lakke of speche and doun &thorn;e hors him caste</L>
<L>Wher as he lay til &thorn;at men him vp took</L>
<L>This was a fayr Chiuacheef of a cook</L>
<L>Allas he ne hadde holde him by his ladel</L>
<L N="52">And er &thorn;at he a&yogh;ein were in his sadel</L>
<L>Ther was a gret schowuyng bo&thorn;e to and fro</L>
<L>To lifte him vp and mochil care and woo</L>
<L>So vnweldy was &thorn;is sely pallede goste</L>
<L N="56">And to &thorn;e maunciple &thorn;enne spak oure Oste</L>
<L>By cause &thorn;at drynke ha&thorn; dominacion</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is man by my Sauacion</L>
<L>I trowe he lewedly wolde telle his tale</L>
<L N="60">ffor were it wyn or olde or moysty ale
<PB REF="00000618.tif" N="590"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="578"></L>
<L N="61">That he ha&thorn; drunke he speke&thorn; so in his nose /</L>
<L>And fnese&thorn; faste and eek he ha&thorn; &thorn;e pose</L>
<L>he hath also to don more &thorn;an ynough</L>
<L N="64">To kepe him and his capel out of &thorn;e slough</L>
<L>And if he falle fro his capil eft sone /<MILESTONE N="257a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thenne schulle we alle haue ynough to doone</L>
<L>In liftyng vp his heuy drunken cors</L>
<L N="68">Telle on &thorn;in tale of him make I no fors</L>
<L>But &yogh;it maunciple in fei&thorn; &thorn;ou art to nyce</L>
<L>Thus openly to reproue him of his vice</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er day he wole perauenture</L>
<L N="72">Reclayme &thorn;e and bringen &thorn;e to lure</L>
<L>I mene he speke wole of smale &thorn;inges</L>
<L>And for to pynchen at &thorn;ine rekenynges</L>
<L>That were not honeste if it come to pref</L>
<L N="76">No quod &thorn;e maunciple &thorn;at were a gret meschief</L>
<L>So might he bringe me in to &thorn;e snare</L>
<L>Yet hadde I leuer payen for &thorn;e mare</L>
<L>Which he ryt on &thorn;an he schulde wi&thorn; me stryue</L>
<L N="80">I wol not wra&thorn;&thorn;e him so mote I &thorn;ryue</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;at I spak I seyde it in my bourde</L>
<L>And wite &yogh;e wel I haue heer in my gourde</L>
<L>A draught of wyn ye of a rype grape</L>
<L N="84">And right anon &yogh;e schullen seen a good Iape</L>
<L>This Cook schal drynke &thorn;er-of if I may</L>
<L>vp peyne of my lyf he wol not say nay</L>
<L>And certeinly to tellen as it/ was</L>
<L N="88">Of &thorn;is vessell &thorn;e Cook drank faste allas</L>
<L>What neede&thorn; it he drank ynough aforn</L>
<L>And whan he hadde pouped in his horn</L>
<L>To &thorn;e maunciple he took &thorn;e gourde again</L>
<L N="92">And of &thorn;at drynke &thorn;e cook was wonder fayn</L>
<L>And &thorn;anked him in such wise as he cowde</L>
<L>Then gan oure Oste to lawhe wonder lowde</L>
<L>And sayde I se wel it is necessarie</L>
<L N="96">Where &thorn;at we goon good drink wi&thorn; vs to carie
<PB REF="00000619.tif" N="591"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="579"></L>
<L N="97">ffor &thorn;at wol tourne rancour and disese</L>
<L>To acord and loue and many a word to peese</L>
<L>O Bachus y-blessed be &thorn;y name</L>
<L N="100">&thorn;at so canst torne ernest in to game</L>
<L>Worschipe and &thorn;onke be to &thorn;y deite<MILESTONE N="257b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at matiere ne gete &yogh;e nomore of me</L>
<L>Tel on &thorn;i tale &thorn;ou manciple I &thorn;e preye</L>
<L>Wel sire quod he now kerkne&thorn; what I seye</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit prologus
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000620.tif" N="592"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="580">
<HEAD>Incipit fabula<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>on leaf</I> 257, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan phebus dwelde heer in &thorn;is er&thorn;e adoun</L>
<L N="106">As olde booke maken mencioun</L>
<L>he was &thorn;e moste lusty bachiler</L>
<L>Of/ alle &thorn;e world and eek &thorn;e best archeer</L>
<L>he slough Phyton &thorn;e serpent/ as he lay</L>
<L>Slepyng agayn &thorn;e sonne vpon a day</L>
<L>And many ano&thorn;er noble wor&thorn;y dede /</L>
<L N="112">He wi&thorn; his bowe brought as men nowe rede</L>
<L>Pleyen he cou&thorn;e of euery menstralcye</L>
<L>And syngen &thorn;at it was a melodye</L>
<L>To heeren of his cleere voys &thorn;e soun</L>
<L N="116">Certes &thorn;e king of Thebes amphyoun</L>
<L>That wi&thorn; his syngyng walled &thorn;at Cite</L>
<L>Cowde neuer syngen half so wel as he</L>
<L>Therto he was &thorn;e semlyeste man</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;at is or was si&thorn;en &thorn;e world bygan</L>
<L>What neede&thorn; it his fetures to discryue</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;is world was non so fair on lyue</L>
<L>he was &thorn;er-wi&thorn; fulfild of gentilnesse</L>
<L N="124">Of honour and of parfyte wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>This Phebus &thorn;at was flour of Bachelrye</L>
<L>As wel in freedam as in Chiualrie</L>
<L>ffor disporte in signe eek of victorie</L>
<L N="128">Of Phyton so as telle&thorn; vs &thorn;e storye</L>
<L>Was wor&thorn;y to beren in his hond a bowe /</L>
<L>Now hadde &thorn;is Phebus in his hous a crowe</L>
<L>Which in a cage he fostred many a day</L>
<L N="132">And taught it speke as &thorn;at men teche a Iay
<PB REF="00000621.tif" N="593"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="581"></L>
<L N="133">Whit was &thorn;is Crowe as is a snow whit swan</L>
<L>And countrefeted &thorn;e speche of euery man</L>
<L>he cowde when he schulde telle a tale</L>
<L N="136">Ther-wi&thorn; in al &thorn;e world no nightyngale</L>
<L>Ne cou&thorn;e by an hundred &thorn;ousend deel<MILESTONE N="258a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Syngen so wonderly meryly and weel</L>
<L>Now hadde &thorn;is Phebus in his hous a wyf</L>
<L N="140">Which &thorn;at he loued more &thorn;an his owne lyf</L>
<L>And night and day dyd euer his diligence</L>
<L>Hir for to plese and don hire reuerence</L>
<L>Saue oonly if &thorn;e so&thorn; &thorn;at I schal sayn</L>
<L N="144">Gelous he was and wolde haue kept hire fayn</L>
<L>ffor him were lo&thorn; by-Iaped for to be</L>
<L>And so euery wight in such degre</L>
<L>But al for nou&yogh;t for it auayle&thorn; nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="148">A good wyff &thorn;at is clene of werk and &thorn;ought</L>
<L>Schulde nought be kepte in non awayte certain</L>
<L>And trewely &thorn;e labour is in vayn</L>
<L>To kepe a schrewe for it wol nou&yogh;t be</L>
<L N="152">This halde I for a verray nycete</L>
<L>To spille labour for to keepe wyues</L>
<L>Thus writen olde Clerkes in here lyues</L>
<L>But now to purpos as I first bigan</L>
<L N="156">This wor&thorn;y Phebus do&thorn; al &thorn;at he can</L>
<L>To plesen hyre wenyng by such plesance</L>
<L>And for his manhode and his gouernance</L>
<L>That no man schulde haue put him fro hir grace</L>
<L N="160">But god it woot/ &thorn;er may no man enbrace</L>
<L>As to distreyne a &thorn;ing which &thorn;at nature</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; naturelly sette in a creature</L>
<L>Take eny bryd and put it in a kage</L>
<L N="164">And do al &thorn;in entent and &thorn;y corage</L>
<L>To fostre it tendrely wi&thorn; mete and drinke</L>
<L>Of alle deyntees &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst by&thorn;inke</L>
<L>And keepe it/ also clenly as &thorn;ou may</L>
<L N="168">Al &thorn;ough his cage of golde be neuer so gay
<PB REF="00000622.tif" N="594"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="582"></L>
<L N="169">&yogh;et ha&thorn; &thorn;is bridde by .xx. &thorn;ousand folde</L>
<L>Leuer in a fforest &thorn;at is wilde and colde</L>
<L>Gon ete wormes and such wrecchedenesse</L>
<L N="172">ffor euer &thorn;is bridde wol doon his busynesse</L>
<L>To eskape out of his cage when he may<MILESTONE N="258b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>his liberte &thorn;e bridde desire&thorn; ay</L>
<L>Let take a catte and fostre him wel wi&thorn; melk</L>
<L N="176">An tendre fleissch and make his couche of selk</L>
<L>And let him seen a mous go by &thorn;e walle</L>
<L>And anon he weyue&thorn; milke fleissche and alle</L>
<L>And euery deynte &thorn;at is in &thorn;at hous</L>
<L N="180">Such appetyt ha&thorn; sche to ete a mous</L>
<L>Lo he[<I>re</I>] ha&thorn; luste his dampnacion</L>
<L>And appetyt flemyth discrecion</L>
<L>As &thorn;e wolf ha&thorn; also a vyleyns kynde</L>
<L N="184">The lewedeste wolf &thorn;at sche may fynde</L>
<L>Of lest of reputacion &thorn;at wol sche take</L>
<L>In tyme whan hire luste to haue a make</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ise ensamples speke I by &thorn;ese men</L>
<L N="188">That ben vntrewe and no&thorn;ing by wommen</L>
<L>ffor men han euere a likerous appetyt</L>
<L>On lowere &thorn;ing to parforme here delyt</L>
<L>Then on here wyfes ben &thorn;ay neuer so fayre</L>
<L N="192">Ne neuer so trewe ne so debonaire</L>
<L>ffleissche is so newefongul wi&thorn; meschance</L>
<L>That we ne konne in no &thorn;ing han plesance</L>
<L>That sowne&thorn; in to vertu eny while</L>
<L N="196">This Phebus which &thorn;at &thorn;ought vpon no gile</L>
<L>Desceyued was for alle his Iolite</L>
<L>ffor vnder him ano&thorn;er hadde sche</L>
<L>A man of litel reputacion</L>
<L N="200">Nought wor&thorn; to Phebus in comparison</L>
<L>The more harm it is it happe&thorn; ofte so</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;er come&thorn; mochil harme and wo</L>
<L>And so bifelle whan Phebus was absent</L>
<L N="204">His wif anon ha&thorn; for hir lemman sent
<PB REF="00000623.tif" N="595"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="583"></L>
<L N="205">Hire lemman certes &thorn;is is a kauissch speche</L>
<L>ffor&yogh;iue&thorn; it me and &thorn;at I &yogh;ou beseche</L>
<L>The wyse Plato sai&thorn; as &yogh;e may rede</L>
<L N="208">&thorn;e worde moot need acorde wi&thorn; &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>&yogh;if men schal telle proprely a &thorn;ing<MILESTONE N="259a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The word moot/ cosyn be to &thorn;e workyng</L>
<L>I am a boystous man riht &thorn;us say I</L>
<L N="212">Ther is no difference trewely</L>
<L>Betwix a wyf &thorn;at is of heih degre</L>
<L>If of hire body dishoneste sche be</L>
<L>And a pouere wenche othir &thorn;an &thorn;is</L>
<L N="216">If it so be &thorn;ey werke bo&thorn;e amys</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;e gentil is in staat aboue</L>
<L>Sche schal be cleped his lady as in loue</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at o&thorn;er is a pouer womman</L>
<L N="220">Sche schal be cleped his wenche or his lemman</L>
<L>And god it woot myn owne deere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>Men leyn &thorn;at oon as lowe as li&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Right so betwixe a titles tyraunt</L>
<L N="224">And an outlawe or a &thorn;eef erraunt</L>
<L>The same I say &thorn;er is no difference /</L>
<L>To alisaundre was tolde &thorn;is sentence /</L>
<L>That for &thorn;e tyraunt is of grettere might</L>
<L N="228">By force of meyne for to sleen doun right</L>
<L>And brenne hous and home and make al playn</L>
<L>Lo &thorn;erfore is he cleped a Capitayn</L>
<L>&para; And for &thorn;e outlawe ha&thorn; but smal meigne</L>
<L N="232">And may not doon so gret an harm as he</L>
<L>Ne bringe a Contre to so gret mescheef</L>
<L>Men clepen him an outlawe or a &thorn;eef</L>
<L>But for I am a man not texted wel</L>
<L N="236">I wol not telle of Tytus neuer a deel</L>
<L>I wol go to my tale as I began</L>
<L>Whan Phebus [wyf] hadde sent for hire lemman</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ey wroughten alle here lust volage</L>
<L N="240">This white crowe &thorn;at heng ay in &thorn;e kage
<PB REF="00000624.tif" N="596"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="584"></L>
<L N="241">Bihelde hire werk and seyde neuer a word</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at home was come Phebus &thorn;e lord</L>
<L>This crowe sange cokkow cokkow cokkow</L>
<L N="244">What bryd quo&thorn; Phebus what song syngest &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Ne were &thorn;ou wont so meryly to synge<MILESTONE N="259b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at to myn herte it was a reioisschinge</L>
<L>To here &thorn;i voys allas what song is &thorn;is</L>
<L N="248">By god quod he I synge nought amys</L>
<L>Phebus quod he for al &thorn;i wor&thorn;inesse</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;y beaute and &thorn;yn gentilnesse</L>
<L>ffor alle &thorn;i song and al &thorn;i menstralcye</L>
<L N="252">ffor al &thorn;i waytyng blered is &thorn;in ye</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; on of litel reputacion</L>
<L>Nought wor&thorn; to &thorn;e as in comparison</L>
<L>&thorn;e mountance of a gnatte so mote I &thorn;riue</L>
<L N="256">ffor on &thorn;y bed &thorn;y wyff / I say him swyue</L>
<L>What wole &yogh;e more &thorn;e crowe anon him tolde</L>
<L>By sadde tokenes and by wordes bolde</L>
<L>How &thorn;at his wyf hadde doon hire leccherie</L>
<L N="260">him to gret schame and to gret vilanye</L>
<L>And tolde him ofte he say it wi&thorn; his eyen</L>
<L>&thorn;is Phebus gan awayward for to wryen</L>
<L>him &thorn;ought his sorwful herte brast a tuo /</L>
<L N="264">His bowe he bente and sette &thorn;er-Inne a floo</L>
<L>And in his Ire &thorn;an ha&thorn; he his wif y-slayn</L>
<L>This is &thorn;effecte &thorn;er is nomore to sayn</L>
<L>ffor sorwe of which he brak his mynstralcye</L>
<L N="268">Bo&thorn;e harpe and lewte gyterne and Sawterye</L>
<L>And eek he brak his arwes and his bowe</L>
<L>And after &thorn;at &thorn;us spak he to &thorn;e crowe</L>
<L>Traytour quod he wi&thorn; tonge of Scorpion</L>
<L N="272">Thou hast me brought to my confusion</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at I was wrought why nere I ded</L>
<L>O deere wyf o gemme of lustyhed</L>
<L>That were to me so sadde and eek so trewe</L>
<L N="276">Now lyes &thorn;ou deed wi&thorn; face pale of hewe /
<PB REF="00000625.tif" N="597"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="585"></L>
<L N="277">fful gulteles &thorn;at durst I swere ywys</L>
<L>O rakel hound to don so foule amys</L>
<L>O trouble witte .O. Ire recheles</L>
<L N="280">That vnauysed smytest gulteles /</L>
<L>O wan-truste ful of fals suspecion<MILESTONE N="260a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Where was &thorn;y witte and &thorn;i discrecion</L>
<L>O euery man be war of rekelnesse</L>
<L N="284">Ne trowe no&thorn;ing wi&thorn;outen strong witnesse</L>
<L>Smyt nou&yogh;t to sone er &thorn;at &thorn;ou wite why</L>
<L>And be auysed wel and soburly</L>
<L>Or &yogh;e doon eny execucion</L>
<L N="288">Vpon &yogh;oure Ire for suspecion</L>
<L>Allas a &thorn;ousand folk han rakel Ire</L>
<L>ffully fordoon or brought hem in &thorn;e myre</L>
<L>Allas for sorwe I wil my selue slee</L>
<L N="292">And to &thorn;e crowe O false &thorn;eef sayde he</L>
<L>I wol &thorn;e quyte anon &thorn;y false tale</L>
<L>&thorn;ou songe whilom lyk a nightyngale</L>
<L>Now schalt &thorn;ou false &thorn;eef &thorn;i song forgon</L>
<L N="296">Eeke &thorn;in white fe&thorn;eres euerichon</L>
<L>Ne neuer in alle &thorn;i lyue schalt &thorn;ou speke</L>
<L>Thus schal men on a traitour ben awreke</L>
<L>Thou and &thorn;in hospreinge euere schuln be blake</L>
<L N="300">Ne neuere swete noyse schul &yogh;e make /</L>
<L>But euer crye agayn tempest and reyn</L>
<L>In toknyng &thorn;at &thorn;urgh &thorn;e my wyf was slayn</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e crowe he sterte and &thorn;at anon</L>
<L N="304">And pulled his white fe&thorn;eres euerychon</L>
<L>and made him blak and reft him alle his song</L>
<L>And eek his speche and out at &thorn;e dore him slong</L>
<L>vnto &thorn;e deuel which I him betake /</L>
<L N="308">And for &thorn;is caas ben alle crowes blake</L>
<L>Lordynges by &thorn;is ensample I &yogh;ou preye</L>
<L>Be&thorn; war and take&thorn; keepe what &thorn;at &yogh;e seye</L>
<L>Ne telle&thorn; neuer no man in &yogh;our lyff/</L>
<L N="312">how &thorn;at ano&thorn;er man ha&thorn; dight his wyf
<PB REF="00000626.tif" N="598"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="586"></L>
<L N="313">He wole &yogh;ow haten mortelly certein</L>
<L>Daun Salomon as wise clerkes sein</L>
<L>Teche&thorn; a man to kepe his tonge wel</L>
<L N="316">But as I sayde I am nought text wel</L>
<L>But na&thorn;eles &thorn;us taughte me my dame<MILESTONE N="260b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My sone &thorn;enk on &thorn;e crowe a goddes name</L>
<L>My sone keepe wel &thorn;i tonge and kepe &thorn;y frende</L>
<L N="320">A wikked tonge is worse &thorn;an a feende</L>
<L>My sone ffrom a feend men may hem blesse</L>
<L>My sone god of his endeles goodnesse /</L>
<L>Walled a tonge wi&thorn; tee&thorn; and lippes eeke</L>
<L N="324">ffor man schulde him auyse what he speeke</L>
<L>My sone ful ofte for to mochel speche</L>
<L>ha&thorn; many a man be spilt as clerkes teche</L>
<L>But for litel speche auysily</L>
<L N="328">Is no man schent to speke generally</L>
<L>My sone &thorn;y tonge schuldest &thorn;ou restreigne</L>
<L>At alle tyme but whan &thorn;ou dost &thorn;y peyne</L>
<L>To speke of god in honour and preyere</L>
<L N="332">The ferste vertu sone if &thorn;ou wolt lere</L>
<L>Is to restreyne and kepe wel &thorn;i tunge</L>
<L>&thorn;us lernen children whanne &thorn;ey ben &yogh;onge</L>
<L>My sone of mochel spekyng euel auysed</L>
<L N="336">Ther lasse spekyng hadde ynough suffised</L>
<L>Come&thorn; mochil harm &thorn;us was me told and taught</L>
<L>In mochil speche synne wante&thorn; naught</L>
<L>Wostow wher-of a rakil tonge serue&thorn;</L>
<L N="340">Right as a swerd forkutte&thorn; and forkerue&thorn;</L>
<L>An arm a tuo my deere sone right so</L>
<L>A tunge kutte&thorn; frendschipe al a tuo</L>
<L>A ianglere is to god abhominable /</L>
<L N="344">Rede Salamon so wys and honorable /</L>
<L>Rede Dauyd and his psalmys red senekke</L>
<L>My sone speek nought but wi&thorn; &thorn;in heed &thorn;ou bekke</L>
<L>Dissimule as &thorn;ou were defe if &thorn;at &thorn;ou heere</L>
<L N="348">A Iangler speke of perilous mateere /
<PB REF="00000627.tif" N="599"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="587"></L>
<L N="349">&thorn;e flemyng sai&thorn; and lerne it if &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>&thorn;at lytel Iangelynge cause&thorn; mechel reste</L>
<L>My sone if &thorn;ou no wickede word hast seyd</L>
<L N="352">&thorn;e &thorn;ar nou&yogh;t drede for to be bywreyd</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at ha&thorn; myssayd I dar wel sayn<MILESTONE N="261a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he may by no way clepe his word agayn</L>
<L>Thing &thorn;at is sayde is sayde and for&thorn; it go&thorn;</L>
<L N="356">Though him repente or be him neuer so lo&thorn;</L>
<L>he is his &thorn;ralle to whom &thorn;at he ha&thorn; sayd</L>
<L>A tale of which he is now yuele payd</L>
<L>My sone be war and be nou&yogh;t auctour newe</L>
<L N="360">Of tydynges whe&thorn;er &thorn;ay ben fals or trewe</L>
<L>Wher so &thorn;ou come amonges heihe or lowe</L>
<L>Kepe wel &thorn;y tunge and &thorn;enk vpon &thorn;e crowe</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula mancipii
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
